{"title_page": "Sean Hannity", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American television host, conservative political commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sean Hannity\n| nickname    = \n| image       = Sean Hannity by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg\n| caption     = Hannity in 2016\n| birth_name  = Sean Patrick Hannity<ref name=middle>{{cite web|url=http://www.hannity.com/article/about-sean-hannity/14852|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105234529/http://www.hannity.com/article/about-sean-hannity/14852|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 5, 2012|title=About Sean Hannity|last=Hannity|first=Sean Patrick|date=December 26, 2011|publisher=Hannity.com|accessdate=September 15, 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1961|12|30}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| residence   = [[Centre Island, New York]], U.S.<ref>[https://variety.com/2014/dirt/real-estalker/is-sean-hannity-saying-bye-bye-to-new-york-1201237414/ Is Sean Hannity Saying Bye-Bye To New York | Variety] Retrieved September 5, 2014.</ref>\n| nationality = American\n| education   = [[New York University]]<br />[[University of California, Santa Barbara|UC Santa Barbara]]<br />[[Adelphi University]]<br />(no degrees awarded)\n| occupation  = Radio host, television host, political commentator, author\n| employer    = [[Premiere Networks]], [[Fox News Channel]]\n| known_for   = [[Conservative]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.salon.com/2013/06/19/sean_hannity_im_not_a_republican | title = Sean Hannity: \"I'm not a Republican\" | publisher = salon.com| date = 2013-06-19 }}</ref> [[Political commentator|political commentary]]\n| net_worth   = \n| party       = [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative]]\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Jill Rhodes|1993}}\n| partner     = \n| children    = 2\n| relatives   = \n| website     = {{URL|hannity.com}}\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n\n'''Sean Patrick Hannity''' (born December 30, 1961) is an American [[talk show]] host and conservative [[political commentator]]. Hannity is the host of ''[[The Sean Hannity Show]]'', a [[radio syndication|nationally syndicated]] talk radio show. He also hosts a commentary program, ''[[Hannity]]'', on [[Fox News]].\n\nHannity worked as a general contractor and volunteered as a talk show host at [[UC Santa Barbara]] in 1989. He later joined [[WVNN (AM)|WVNN]] in [[Athens, Alabama]] and shortly afterward, [[WGST]] in [[Atlanta]]. After leaving WGST, he worked at [[WABC (AM)|WABC]] in New York until 2013. Since 2014, Hannity has worked at [[WOR (AM)|WOR]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1996, Hannity and [[Alan Colmes]] co-hosted ''[[Hannity & Colmes]]'' on [[Fox News|Fox]].  After Colmes announced his departure in January 2008, Hannity merged the ''Hannity & Colmes'' show into ''[[Hannity]]''. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nHannity has received several awards and honors, including an honorary degree from [[Liberty University]]. He has written three books: ''[[Let Freedom Ring: Winning the War of Liberty over Liberalism]]''; ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism]]''; and ''[[Conservative Victory: Defeating Obama's Radical Agenda]]''.\n\nHannity has promoted [[conspiracy theories]], such as [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|Birtherism]], claims that the [[murder of Seth Rich]] was part of a conspiracy, and falsehoods about [[Hillary Clinton]]'s health. Hannity was an early supporter of [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]. Since Trump's election, Hannity has often acted as a mouthpiece for Trump's messaging, criticizing the media, attacking the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|special counsel inquiry]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/fox-news-hannity-carlson-ingraham-attack-mueller-hes-sleazy-and-dishonest-1439017|title=Fox News' Hannity, Carlson, Ingraham attack Mueller: He's a \"sleazy and dishonest\" \"mean girl\" who's \"full of crap\"|last=EDT|first=Christina Zhao On 5/30/19 at 1:37 AM|date=2019-05-30|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> and discouraging social distancing amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/us/politics/michael-savage-trump-coronavirus.html|title=Why Michael Savage Is Blasting Hannity and the Right-Wing Media on the Virus|date=2020-04-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He reportedly speaks to the president on the phone most weeknights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5|title=Trump reportedly talks to Sean Hannity most nights before bed|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|website=Business Insider}}</ref> Hannity has spoken at the president's lectern during a Trump rally and White House advisors have characterized him as the \"shadow\" chief-of-staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hannitys-rising-role-in-trumps-world-he-basically-has-a-desk-in-the-place/2018/04/17/e2483018-4260-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html|title=Hannity's rising role in Trump's world: 'He basically has a desk in the place'|website=Washington Post|accessdate=August 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2013/06/19/sean_hannity_im_not_a_republican/|title=Sean Hannity: \"I'm not a Republican\"|date=2013-06-19|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> According to ''[[Forbes]]'', by 2018 Hannity had become one of the most-watched hosts in cable news and most-listened-to hosts in talk radio due to his closeness and access to President Donald Trump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5|title=Trump reportedly talks to Sean Hannity most nights before bed|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHannity was born in New York City, New York, the son of Lillian (Flynn) and Hugh Hannity.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=njdbBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT33|title=Let Freedom Ring|work=google.ca|isbn=9780060514556|last1=Hannity|first1=Sean|date=2002-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2018/nov/06/sean-hannity/hannity-vows-not-appear-onstage-trump-rally-then-h/|title=PolitiFact - Sean Hannity vows not to appear onstage at Trump rally, then he does|last=Washington|first=District of Columbia 1100 Connecticut Ave NW Suite 1300B|last2=Dc 20036|website=@politifact|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Lillian worked as a stenographer and a corrections officer at a county jail and Hugh was a family-court officer.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|title=How Far Will Sean Hannity Go?|last=Shaer|first=Matthew|date=November 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 29, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129003856/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|url-status=live|archive-date=November 29, 2017}}</ref> He is the youngest of four siblings.<ref name=\":24\" /> All his grandparents immigrated to the United States from [[Ireland]]. He grew up in [[Franklin Square, New York]].<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nHannity attended Sacred Heart Seminary in [[Hempstead (village), New York|Hempstead, New York]], during his middle school years and [[St. Pius X Preparatory Seminary]] high school in [[Uniondale, New York]].<ref>Hannity, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Bco44op7ArEC Let Freedom Ring]'', p. 49.</ref> He attended [[New York University]], [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UC Santa Barbara]], and [[Adelphi University]], but did not graduate.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1572959/Sean-Hannity|title=Sean Hannity|work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"rightfielder\">{{cite news | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/99494805.html?dids=99494805:99494805&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jan+14%2C+2002&author=Howard+Kurtz&pub=The+Washington+Post&edition=&startpage=C.01&desc=Radio%27s+New+Right-Fielder%3B+For+Conservative+Hannity%2C+Liberal+Praise | title=Radio's New Right-Fielder |work=Washington Post | date=January 14, 2002 | first=Howard | last=Kurtz|accessdate = November 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Interview of the Vice President Dick Cheney by Sean Hannity.jpg|thumb|left|Interviewing Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] in 2006]]\n[[File:Vice President Pence at CPAC (49596293561).jpg|thumb|left|Interviewing Vice President [[Mike Pence]] in 2020]]\nIn 1982, Hannity started a house-painting business and a few years later, worked as a building contractor in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref name=Lipton /> He hosted his first talk radio show in 1989 at the volunteer college station at [[UC Santa Barbara]], [[KCSB-FM]], while working as a general contractor. The show aired for 40 hours of air time.<ref name=\"wdbo_bio\">{{cite web |url=http://wdbo.com/hannity/biography.html |title=Hannity Bio |accessdate=October 13, 2008 |publisher=[[The Sean Hannity Show]] at [[WDBO (AM)|WDBO]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sean Hannity: Construction Worker, Union Member, Sack of Sh*t. |url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2012/12/19/1171909/-Sean-Hannity-Construction-Worker-Union-Member-Sack-of-Sh-t |website=dailykos.com |publisher=Kos Media, LLC |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Regarding his first show, he said, \"I wasn't good at it. I was terrible.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Hannitization' Of America |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/05/21/sunday/main619045.shtml |publisher=CBS News |date=May 23, 2004 |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Radio ===\nHannity's weekly show on KCSB was canceled after less than a year after a controversy. During two shows, gay and lesbian rights were discussed in what was considered to be a contentious manner. (See [[#LGBT rights|LGBT issues]] below.) The university board that governed the station later reversed its decision after a campaign conducted on Hannity's behalf by the Santa Barbara chapter of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] argued that the station had discriminated against Hannity's First Amendment rights. When the station refused to issue Hannity a public apology and more airtime, he did not return to KCSB.<ref name=\"www.fair.org\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Rendall |title=An Aggressive Conservative vs. a 'Liberal to be Determined' |url=http://fair.org/home/an-aggressive-conservative-vs-a-quotliberal-to-be-determinedquot/ |work=Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting |date=November\u2013December 2003 |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":6\"/>\n\nAfter leaving KCSB, Hannity placed an ad in radio publications, presenting himself as \"the most talked about college radio host in America.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Radio station [[WVNN (AM)|WVNN]] in [[Athens, Alabama]] (part of the [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]] media market), then hired him to be the afternoon talk show host.<ref name=\"wdbo_bio\"/> From Huntsville, he moved to [[WGST]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]] in 1992, filling the slot vacated by [[Neal Boortz]], who had moved to competing station [[WSB (AM)|WSB]]. In September 1996, Fox News co-founder [[Roger Ailes]] hired the then relatively unknown Hannity to host a television program under the working title ''Hannity and LTBD'' (\"liberal to be determined\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alan.com/staff/alan.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061109203543/http://www.alan.com/staff/alan.htm|title=Alan Colmes|archivedate=November 9, 2006|work=alan.com}}</ref> [[Alan Colmes]] was then hired to co-host and the show debuted as ''[[Hannity & Colmes]]''.\n\nLater that year, Hannity left WGST for New York, where WABC had him substitute for their afternoon [[drive time]] host during Christmas week. In January 1997, WABC put Hannity on the air full-time, giving him the late-night time slot. WABC then moved Hannity to the same drive-time slot he had filled temporarily a little more than a year earlier. Hannity was on WABC's afternoon time slot from January 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wabcradio.com/showdj.asp?DJID=1725 |title=Sean Hannity is a multi-media superstar, spending four hours a day every day reaching out to millions of Americans on radio, television and internet |accessdate=October 13, 2008 |publisher=[[WABC (AM)|WABC]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012131347/http://www.wabcradio.com/showdj.asp?DJID=1725 |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn their 2007 book ''Common Ground: How to Stop the Partisan War That Is Destroying America'', conservative [[Cal Thomas]] and liberal [[Bob Beckel]] describe Hannity as a leader of the pack among broadcasting political polarizers, which following [[James Q. Wilson]] they define as those who have \"an intense commitment to a candidate, a culture, or an ideology that sets people in one group definitively apart from people in another, rival group.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Cal |last=Thomas |authorlink=Cal Thomas |author2=Bob Beckel |title=Common Ground: How to Stop the Partisan War That Is Destroying America |publisher=William Morrow |location=New York |year=2007 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/commongroundhowt00calt_0/page/3 3\u20136] |isbn=978-0-06-123634-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/commongroundhowt00calt_0/page/3 }}</ref> The WABC slot continued until the end of 2013. Since January 2014, Hannity has hosted the 3\u20136 p.m. time slot on WOR in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/wor-ends-era-new-york-radio-article-1.1542179|title=WOR ends an era in New York radio and officially kicks off the new coming war with rival WABC|first=David|last=Hinckley|publisher=New York Daily News|date=December 6, 2013|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Sean Hannity by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|right|thumb|Speaking at the 2015 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in February 2015]]\n\nHannity's radio program is a conservative political talk show that features Hannity's opinions and ideology related to current issues and politicians. ''The Sean Hannity Show'' began national syndication on September 10, 2001, on over 500 stations nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/090806.pdf |title=Canon Communications LLC: Home |publisher=Affiliates.abcradionetworks.com |accessdate=August 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326002949/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/090806.pdf |archivedate=March 26, 2009 }}</ref> In 2004, Hannity signed a $25-million five-year contract extension with ABC Radio (now [[Citadel Media]]) to continue the show until 2009.<ref name=\"contract\">{{cite web |url=http://wsgw.com/skin/blurb.php?sectionId=182&contentId=116798 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811021712/http://wsgw.com/skin/blurb.php?sectionId=182&contentId=116798 |archivedate=August 11, 2007 |title=Sean Hannity Profile |publisher=WSGW |year=2006 |accessdate=November 5, 2008}}</ref> The program was made available via [[American Forces Network|Armed Forces Radio Network]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/010306.pdf |title=Canon Communications LLC: Home |publisher=Affiliates.abcradionetworks.com |accessdate=August 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326002948/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/010306.pdf |archivedate=March 26, 2009 }}</ref> In June 2007, ABC Radio was sold to [[Citadel Communications]]<ref>{{cite press release |title=Disney and Citadel Announce Completion of ABC Radio Merger |publisher=The Walt Disney Company |date=June 12, 2007 |url=http://corporate.disney.go.com/news/corporate/2007/2007_0613_abcradiomerger.html |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref> and in the summer of 2008, Hannity was signed for a $100- million five-year contract.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Sean Hannity Gets $100 Million Deal |publisher=Huff Post Media |date=July 21, 2008 |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/07/21/sean-hannity-gets-100-mil_n_114026.html |accessdate=May 9, 2012}}</ref> As of March 2018, the program is heard by over 13.5 million listeners a week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talkers.com/top-talk-audiences/ |title=The Top Talk Radio Audiences | date= March 2018 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 |publisher=Talkers Magazine }}</ref> Hannity was ranked No.{{nbsp}}2 in ''Talker Magazine''<nowiki/>'s 2017 Heavy Hundred<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.talkers.com/2017-talkers-heavy-hundred-1-25/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926170941/http://www.talkers.com/2017-talkers-heavy-hundred-1-25/ | archive-date=September 26, 2017 | title=2017 TALKERS Heavy Hundred 1-25 | work=Talkers Magazine | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all | date=2017-05-22 }}</ref> and was listed as No.{{nbsp}}72 on ''Forbes''<nowiki/>' \"Celebrity 100\" list in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/person/h/sean-hannity.html|title=Sean Hannity {{!}} Fox News|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, [[Clear Channel Communications]] signed a groupwide three-year extension with Hannity on over 80 stations.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Clear Channel Radio Renews Sean Hannity Through 2010 |publisher=[[Clear Channel Communications]] |date=September 28, 2006 |url=http://www.clearchannel.com/Radio/PressRelease.aspx?PressReleaseID=1768 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004045741/http://www.clearchannel.com/Radio/PressRelease.aspx?PressReleaseID=1768 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 4, 2006 |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}\n</ref> The largest stations in the group deal included [[KTRH]] Houston, [[KFYI]] Phoenix, [[WPGB]] Pittsburgh, [[WKRC (AM)|WKRC]] Cincinnati, [[WOOD (AM)|WOOD]] Grand Rapids, [[WFLA (AM)|WFLA]] Tampa, [[WOAI (AM)|WOAI]] San Antonio, [[WLAC]] Nashville, and [[WREC]] Memphis.\n\nHannity signed a long-term contract to remain with Premiere Networks in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Byers|first=Dylan|title=Hannity signs 'long-term' contract|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/09/hannity-signs-longterm-premiere-contract-172472.html?hp=l7|publisher=Politico|accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of 2014, Hannity signed contracts to air on several [[Salem Communications]] stations including [[WDTK]] Detroit, [[WIND (AM)|WIND]] Chicago, [[WQOF|WWRC]] Washington, D.C., and [[KSKY]] Dallas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boyce|first=Phil|title=Sean Hannity Moves to WDTK-AM 1400 in Detroit|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/sean-hannity-moves-to-wdtk-am-1400-in-detroit-2014-01-14|publisher=MarketWatch|accessdate=January 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n{{See also|Hannity & Colmes|Hannity's America|Hannity}}\n\nHannity was a co-host of ''Hannity & Colmes'', an American political \"point-counterpoint\"-style television program on the Fox News Channel featuring Hannity and [[Alan Colmes]] as co-hosts. Hannity presented the conservative point of view with Colmes providing the liberal viewpoint.\n\nHannity said if the Catholic Church were to [[excommunication|excommunicate]] him over his support for contraception he would join [[Jerry Falwell]]'s [[Thomas Road Baptist Church]].<ref>Royal, Robert. \"Sean and Rudy's excellent adventures in moral theology.\" ''National Catholic Reporter''; March 30, 2007, Vol. 43 Issue 22, p. 19-19, 2/3p.</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Hannity began a new Sunday night television show on Fox News, ''[[Hannity's America]]''.\n\nIn November 2008, Colmes announced his departure from ''Hannity & Colmes''. After the show's final broadcast on January 9, 2009, Hannity took over the time slot with his own new show, ''[[Hannity]]'', which has a format similar to ''Hannity's America''.\n\n=== Books ===\nHannity is the author of three books. ''[[Let Freedom Ring: Winning the War of Liberty over Liberalism]]'' was published in 2002, and ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism]]'' was published in 2004 through [[ReganBooks]]. Both these books reached the nonfiction ''New York Times'' bestseller list, the second of which stayed there for five weeks.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">''Contemporary Authors Online'', Thomson Gale, 2005.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/abcradio/seanhannitybio.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=August 7, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807124253/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/abcradio/seanhannitybio.pdf|archivedate=August 7, 2007}}</ref> Hannity has said he is too busy to write many books,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> and dictated a lot of his own two books into a tape recorder while driving in to do his radio show.<ref>{{cite news |last=Poniewozik |first=James |author2=Sean Hannity |date=November 5, 2002 |title=10 Questions for Sean Hannity |work=Time |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1101021111-386927,00.html |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHannity wrote his third book, ''[[Conservative Victory: Defeating Obama's Radical Agenda]]'', which was released by [[HarperCollins]] in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2010/02/sean-hannity-to-write-book-on-defeating-obama-democrats/1 | work=USA Today | title=Sean Hannity writes book on defeating Obama, Democrats | date=February 16, 2010 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> The book became Hannity's third ''New York Times'' Bestseller.<ref name=\"NYT 2010\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/books/bestseller/bestpapernonfiction.html?ref=bestseller|title=NYT Best Sellers \u2013 Paperback Nonfiction|date=April 15, 2010|work=NY Times|accessdate=April 18, 2010|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler}}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|FreedomConcerts}}\n\n=== Freedom Concerts ===\nFrom 2003 until 2010, Hannity hosted [[country music]]-themed \"Freedom Concerts\" to raise money for charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/hannity-bringing-freedom-concert-back-flags-article-1.560657 |title=Hannity Bringing 'Freedom' Concert to Six Flags |date=July 20, 2006 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |accessdate=August 23, 2009 }}</ref> In 2010, conservative blogger [[Debbie Schlussel]] wrote that only a small percentage of the money raised by the concerts goes to the target charity, [[Oliver North#Freedom Alliance|Freedom Alliance]].<ref name=TheWeek100401>{{cite web | url=https://theweek.com/articles/495654/sean-hannitys-charity-scam | title=Sean Hannity's charity 'scam' | work=[[The Week]] | date=April 1, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> The [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] (CREW) filed complaints with the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) and the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS), also in 2010. The FTC complaint alleges that Hannity was \"falsely promoting that all concert proceeds would be donated to a scholarship fund for the children of those killed or wounded in war.\"<ref name=Dimascio>{{cite web | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2010/03/crew-flags-hannity-concert-series-035160 | title=CREW flags Hannity concert series | work=[[Politico]] | date=March 29, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Dimascio | first=Jen}}</ref> The complaint filed with the IRS claims that Freedom Alliance has violated its [[501(c)3]] charity status.<ref name=Sheppard>{{cite web | url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/03/crew-sean-hannity-freedom-concert-freedom-alliance/ | title=Hannity's Charity Under Fire | work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | date=March 29, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Sheppard | first=Kate}}</ref><ref name=Scallon>{{cite web | url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/2010/03/20/freedom-scam/ | title=Freedom Scam? | work=[[The American Conservative]] | date=March 20, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Scallon | first=Sean}}</ref> The concerts stopped around the same year.<ref name=Fahrenthold>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/06/01/hannity-defended-trumps-handling-of-donations-to-veterans-groups-he-didnt-mention-his-personal-ties-to-one-of-them/?noredirect=on | title=Hannity defended Trump's handling of donations to veterans groups. He didn't mention his personal ties to one of them. | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=June 1, 2016 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Fahrenthold | first=David}}</ref>\n\n=== Other activities ===\nHannity [[Executive producer|executive produced]] and appeared in the 2017 film ''[[Let There Be Light (2017 film)|Let There Be Light]]'', which also stars [[Kevin Sorbo]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-let-there-be-light-review-20171026-story.html |title= Review: Sean Hannity and Kevin Sorbo join forces in the Christian reckoning drama 'Let There Be Light' |author= Gary Goldstein |date= October 26, 2017 |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate= October 27, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2018 Hannity owned at least 877 residential properties, which were bought for nearly $89 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/media/2018/apr/22/michael-cohen-sean-hannity-property-real-estate-ben-carson-hud|title=Michael Cohen case shines light on Sean Hannity's property empire|last=Swaine|first=Jon|date=April 23, 2018|work=the Guardian|access-date=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gstalter |first1=Morgan |title=Sean Hannity linked to shell companies that spent $90M on property: report |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/384366-hannity-hud-shell-companies-report |website=thehill.com |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> He purchased some of the homes with the help of loans from [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD)]] and most are in working class neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matt Pearce |first1=Jenny Jarvie and |title=In Georgia, Sean Hannity is just another landlord hiking the rent |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-hannity-landlord-20180427-story.html |website=www.latimes.com |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> His [[property management|property manager]]s have taken an aggressive management approach with a much higher than average eviction rate. The ''[[Washington Post]]'' reported that his property management team has used eviction proceedings both to remove tenants and to generate revenue. His property managers have claimed that Sean Hannity has no active role in the management of the more than 1,000 properties he has a stake in.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shawn Boburg |first1=Aaron C. Davis and |title=At Sean Hannity properties in working-class areas, an aggressive approach to rent collection |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/at-hannitys-properties-in-low-income-areas-an-aggressive-approach-to-rent-collection/2018/05/10/964be4a2-4eea-11e8-84a0-458a1aa9ac0a_story.html |website=www.washingtonpost.com |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political commentary, controversies, and criticism ==\nAccording to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Hannity \"repeatedly embraces storylines that prove to be inaccurate\" and takes positions that change over time.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/the-making-of-sean-hannity-how-a-long-island-kid-learned-to-channel-red-state-rage/2017/10/09/540cfc38-8821-11e7-961d-2f373b3977ee_story.html|title=The making of Sean Hannity: How a Long Island kid learned to channel red-state rage|last=Fisher|first=Marc|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=October 12, 2017|date=October 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012202547/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/the-making-of-sean-hannity-how-a-long-island-kid-learned-to-channel-red-state-rage/2017/10/09/540cfc38-8821-11e7-961d-2f373b3977ee_story.html|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In the opinion of ''[[The New York Times]]'', Hannity is \"barreling headfirst into the murky territory between opinion and out-and-out conspiracy theorism.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> Hannity often promotes [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] without explicitly endorsing them, unlike [[Alex Jones]]; ''The New York Times'' wrote that this \"has the effect of nourishing the more wild-eyed beliefs of his fans while providing Hannity a degree of plausible deniability.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' wrote in 2019 that Hannity had \"[spewed] baseless conspiracy theories with impunity.\"<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/03/11/the-making-of-the-fox-news-white-house|title=The Making of the Fox News White House|last=Mayer|first=Jane|date=2019-03-04|access-date=2019-03-04|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Bush years, Hannity \"loyally supported the president's policies.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> During the Obama administration, Hannity \"leaned more heavily on stories he believed were being given short shrift by the 'liberal media' \u2014 stories about where Obama was born, and who deserved blame for the attack on the U.S. compound in Benghazi, Libya.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> In 2017, ''The Washington Post'' wrote that \"what Hannity has stood for \u2014 at least for the past couple of years \u2014 is Trump.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Birtherism ===\nAlthough Hannity said he believed President Obama was born in the United States, [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|to answer queries on Obama's citizenship]] he repeatedly called on Obama to release his birth certificate.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/top-republican-try-to-scotch-birther-theories/2011/04/19/AFsrhU8D_story.html|title=Top Republicans try to scotch birther theories|website=Washington Post|access-date=February 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222194249/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/top-republican-try-to-scotch-birther-theories/2011/04/19/AFsrhU8D_story.html|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/28/business/media/28birth.html|title='Birthers' Fanned Flames of Conspiracy for Years|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=April 27, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=February 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405122718/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/28/business/media/28birth.html|archive-date=2017-04-05|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity described the circumstances regarding Obama's birth certificate as \"odd\".<ref name=\":29\" /> Hannity also defended and promoted those who questioned Obama's citizenship of the United States, such as Donald Trump. Hannity invited Trump to his show at the same time that Trump was a leader in the birther movement; during an interview with Hannity, Trump said Obama \"could have easily have come from Kenya, or someplace.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> To which Hannity responded, \"The issue could go away in a minute. Just show the certificate.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> After Obama in 2008 produced what the state of Hawaii certified as a legitimate birth certificate, Hannity kept calling on Obama to release his birth certificate, asking, if there was a birth certificate, why did he not \"just produce it and we move on?\"<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/02/us/02iht-letter02.html|title=A Lie Is Born, and We All Know Where|last=News|first=Albert R. Hunt {{!}} Bloomberg|date=May 1, 2011|access-date=February 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331|newspaper=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222113610/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/02/us/02iht-letter02.html|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2016, Hannity offered to purchase a one-way ticket to Kenya for Obama, harking back to the controversy.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hannity-obama-kenya-birthers-230317|title=Hannity offers to pay for Obama to go to Kenya|access-date=February 21, 2017|newspaper=POLITICO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222111657/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hannity-obama-kenya-birthers-230317|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 presidential campaign ===\n==== Candidacy of Donald Trump ====\n[[File:Donald Trump & Sean Hannity (16677778952).jpg|thumb|Hannity with [[Donald Trump]] in 2015]]\n\nHannity is known for his pro-Trump coverage.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/09/fox-news-trump-presidency-244712 |title= Fox, facing new competitors, clings tighter to Trump |work= Politico |access-date= November 9, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171109114104/https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/09/fox-news-trump-presidency-244712 |archive-date= 2017-11-09 |url-status= live }}</ref> According to ''The Washington Post'', \"Hannity's comeback coincided with his early, eager embrace of his fellow New Yorker\"{{nbsp}}... Trump attacked the Gold Star father, and Hannity stood by him. Trump went after a federal judge of Mexican descent, and Hannity backed him. After the [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape|''Access Hollywood'' tape]] emerged of Trump making lewd comments about inappropriate sexual behaviour towards women, Hannity continued to defend him: '[[King David]] had 500 concubines, for crying out loud'.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> After the inauguration, the first interview the new president gave to a cable news channel was conducted by Hannity.<ref name=\":6\" /> Hannity additionally defended the Trump administration's false claim that Trump's inauguration crowd was the biggest ever.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHannity has been criticized as being overly favorable to the candidacy of [[Donald Trump]], and granting Trump more airtime than other presidential candidates during the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries|2016 primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |title=How Sean Hannity Became Influential In Conservative Media And Politics |url=https://www.tpr.org/post/how-sean-hannity-became-influential-conservative-media-and-politics |website=tpr.org |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> Hannity, for instance, let Trump promote the false claim that [[Rafael Cruz]], father of Trump's rival presidential candidate [[Ted Cruz]], was involved in the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|John F. Kennedy assassination]].<ref name=\":6\" /> He admitted to favouring [[Republican Party (U.S.)|Republican]] candidates, though without indicating a preference for Donald Trump over Ted Cruz.<ref name=\"Byers2016\">{{Citation|last=Byers|first=Dylan | date = May 2, 2016 | url = http://money.cnn.com/2016/05/02/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-profile/ | title = Sean Hannity embraces Donald Trump, without apology | work = CNN | access-date = 2019-02-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180716025338/https://money.cnn.com/2016/05/02/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-profile/ | archive-date = 2018-07-16 | url-status = live }}.</ref> According to [[Dylan Byers]] of [[CNN]], Hannity during interviews \"frequently cites areas where he agrees with Trump, or where he thinks Trump was right about something, then asks him to expand on it\", and \"often ignores or defends Trump from criticism.\"<ref name=\"Byers2016\" />\n\nTensions between Cruz and Hannity appeared to reach a boiling point during a contentious April 2016 radio interview, during which Cruz implied Hannity was a \"hard-core Donald Trump supporter\" and Hannity responded by accusing Cruz of \"throw[ing] this in my face\" every time he asked a \"legitimate question\".<ref>{{Citation | date = April 19, 2016 | url = http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/19/ted-cruz-and-sean-hannity-finally-duke-it-out.html | title = Ted Cruz and Sean Hannity Finally Duke It Out | newspaper = The Daily Beast | last1 = Kirell | first1 = Andrew | access-date = 2019-02-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161222144129/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/19/ted-cruz-and-sean-hannity-finally-duke-it-out.html | archive-date = 2016-12-22 | url-status = live }}.</ref> [[Jim Rutenberg]] commented in August 2016 that Hannity is \"not only Mr. Trump's biggest media booster; he also veers into the role of adviser,\" citing sources who said Hannity spent months offering suggestions to Trump and his campaign on strategy and messaging. Hannity responded to the report by saying, \"I'm not hiding the fact that I want Donald Trump to be the next President of the United States.{{nbsp}}... I never claimed to be a journalist.\"<ref name=\"NYT08212016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/22/business/media/sean-hannity-turns-adviser-in-the-service-of-donald-trump.html |title= Sean Hannity Turns Adviser in the Service of Donald Trump |last= Rutenberg |first= Jim |date= August 21, 2016 |work= The NY times |access-date= 2019-02-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190114150953/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/22/business/media/sean-hannity-turns-adviser-in-the-service-of-donald-trump.html |archive-date= 2019-01-14 |url-status= live }}</ref> (In an article published in December 2017, Hannity said \"I'm a journalist. But I'm an [[advocacy journalism|advocacy journalist]], or an opinion journalist.\")<ref name=\":24\"/> Hannity has feuded with several conservatives who oppose Trump, including ''[[National Review]]''{{'}}s [[Jonah Goldberg]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Gass|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-twitter-war-227819|title=Hannity and National Review's Jonah Goldberg get into epic Twitter battle|work=Politico|date=September 7, 2016|accessdate=September 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005180905/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-twitter-war-227819|archive-date=2016-10-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Oliver |last= Darcy |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-trump-2016-9 |title= Sean Hannity and National Review's Jonah Goldberg get into heated Twitter fight over Donald Trump |work= Business Insider |date= September 7, 2016 |accessdate= September 29, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160909160730/http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-trump-2016-9 |archive-date= 2016-09-09 |url-status= live }}</ref> ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' foreign affairs columnist [[Bret Stephens]],<ref>{{cite web |first= Nick |last= Gass |url= http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/sean-hannity-bret-stephens-feud-226714 |title= Hannity to WSJ editor: If Clinton wins, 'I will hold a--holes like you accountable' |work= [[Politico]] |date= August 5, 2016 |accessdate= September 29, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041003/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/sean-hannity-bret-stephens-feud-226714 |archive-date= 2016-09-28 |url-status= live }}</ref> and ''National Review'' editor [[Rich Lowry]].<ref>{{cite web |first= Paulina |last= Firozi |url= http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/295312-hannity-feuds-with-national-review-editor-on-twitter |title= Hannity feuds with National Review editor on Twitter |work= The Hill |date= September 10, 2016 |accessdate= September 29, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160918070533/http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/295312-hannity-feuds-with-national-review-editor-on-twitter |archive-date= 2016-09-18 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==== Conspiracy theories about Hillary Clinton ====\nDuring the 2016 presidential election, Hannity periodically promoted conspiracy theories regarding [[Hillary Clinton]] and the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\">{{Cite web|author=David Weigel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/11/in-prime-time-sean-hannity-carries-out-a-clinton-medical-investigation/|title=In prime time, Sean Hannity carries out a Clinton medical 'investigation'|website=Washington Post|date=August 11, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209235320/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/11/in-prime-time-sean-hannity-carries-out-a-clinton-medical-investigation/|archive-date=2019-02-09|url-status=live|author-link=David Weigel}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|author=Rebecca Morin|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/hannity-responds-to-stelter-criticism-on-twitter-226773|title=Hannity, Stelter swap criticism over conspiracy theories|date=August 7, 2016|newspaper=Politico|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109204838/https://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/hannity-responds-to-stelter-criticism-on-twitter-226773|archive-date=2018-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/8/18/12505078/hillary-clinton-health-stroke-conspiracy-fake|title=Here's how we know the bonkers conspiracy theory about Hillary Clinton's health is catching on|last=Golshan|first=Tara|date=August 18, 2016|website=Vox|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106112555/https://www.vox.com/2016/8/18/12505078/hillary-clinton-health-stroke-conspiracy-fake|archive-date=2019-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/20/the-seth-rich-conspiracy-shows-how-fake-news-still-works/|title=Analysis {{!}} The Seth Rich conspiracy shows how fake news still works|work=[[Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=May 20, 2017|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520234833/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/20/the-seth-rich-conspiracy-shows-how-fake-news-still-works/|archive-date=2017-05-20|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity repeatedly claimed that Clinton had very serious medical problems and that the media was covering them up.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /><ref>{{Cite web|first=Susan|last=Milligan|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-08-15/hillarys-health-conspiracy-or-concern|title=Hillary's Health: Conspiracy or Concern?|work=U.S. News & World Report|date=August 15, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229204101/https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-08-15/hillarys-health-conspiracy-or-concern|archive-date=2018-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Brian|last=Stelter|title=Sean Hannity peddling debunked Clinton story|url=http://edition.cnn.com/videos/tv/2016/08/14/hannity-pushes-debunked-clinton-theory.cnn|work=Reliable Sources with Brian Stelter|publisher=CNN|date=August 14, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925121620/https://edition.cnn.com/videos/tv/2016/08/14/hannity-pushes-debunked-clinton-theory.cnn|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref> He misrepresented photos of Clinton to give the impression that she had secret medical problems.<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /><ref name=\":52\" /> He shared a photo from the fringe news site [[The Gateway Pundit|Gateway Pundit]] and falsely claimed that it showed her Secret Service agent holding a diazepam pen intended to treat seizures, when he in fact was holding a small flashlight.<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /> He booked doctors on his show to discuss Clinton's health; although these people had never personally examined Clinton, they made alarmist statements about her state of health which turned out to be false.<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /><ref name=\":52\" /> At one point, Hannity promoted an unsubstantiated report that Clinton had been drunk at a rally; at another point, he suggested that Clinton was drunk and that her campaign needed to \"sober her up\".<ref>{{Cite news|first=Oliver|last=Darcy|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-hillary-clinton-conspiracy-drunk-2016-10?r=US&IR=T|title=Sean Hannity promotes conspiracy theory Clinton was drunk at rally, then claims he didn't mean to do so|work=Business Insider|date=October 31, 2016|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224222329/https://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-hillary-clinton-conspiracy-drunk-2016-10?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2018-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Murder of Seth Rich conspiracy theories ====\nIn May 2017, Hannity became a prominent promoter of the conspiracy theory that Hillary Clinton and the Democratic Party had a [[Murder of Seth Rich|DNC staffer killed]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/fox-news-conspiracy-theory-wikileaks-seth-rich_us_591b493ee4b07d5f6ba6d027|title=Fox Pushes WikiLeaks Murder Conspiracy From Man Who Warned Of Armed Lesbian Pedophiles|last=Waldron|first=Travis|date=May 16, 2017|work=Huffington Post|access-date=May 16, 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517054751/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/fox-news-conspiracy-theory-wikileaks-seth-rich_us_591b493ee4b07d5f6ba6d027|archive-date=2017-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forward.com/fast-forward/372104/sean-hannity-im-looking-into-seth-richs-suspicious-death/|title=Sean Hannity: I'm 'Looking Into' Seth Rich's 'Suspicious' Death|work=The Forward|access-date=May 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516235150/http://forward.com/fast-forward/372104/sean-hannity-im-looking-into-seth-richs-suspicious-death/|archive-date=2017-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/charliewarzel/how-the-pro-trump-media-responds-to-a-crisis-in-just-4-steps|title=How The Pro-Trump Media Responds To A Crisis In Just 4 Steps|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=May 17, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517052108/https://www.buzzfeed.com/charliewarzel/how-the-pro-trump-media-responds-to-a-crisis-in-just-4-steps|archive-date=2017-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-1.789915|title=Explained // 'Alt-right' Using Cruel Seth Rich Conspiracy Theory to Deflect From Trump's Russia Scandal|last=Sommer|first=Allison Kaplan|date=May 17, 2017|work=Haaretz|access-date=May 17, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517173820/http://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-1.789915|archive-date=2017-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/22/the-seth-rich-conspiracys-biggest-myths-explained/|title=Analysis {{!}} The Seth Rich conspiracy's biggest myths, explained|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523013951/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/22/the-seth-rich-conspiracys-biggest-myths-explained/|archive-date=2017-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Shortly afterward, he faced backlash from both left- and right-wing sources and lost several advertisers, including [[Crowne Plaza Hotels]], [[Cars.com]], Leesa Mattress, [[USAA]], [[Peloton]] and [[Casper Sleep]] deciding to pull their marketing from his program on Fox News.<ref name=\"baggaglio\">{{citation|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hannity-advertisers-fox-20170525-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 25, 2017|title=Sean Hannity goes on vacation as advertisers drop out of his show|last=Battaglio|first=Stephen|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907022655/http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hannity-advertisers-fox-20170525-story.html|archive-date=2018-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"paulbond\">{{citation|first=Paul|last=Bond|date=May 25, 2017|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/more-advertisers-pressuring-fox-news-sean-hannity-1007805|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|title=Several advertisers have pulled TV spots over the 'Hannity' host's reporting on Seth Rich, while conservatives are mounting a counter-boycott.|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613183900/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/more-advertisers-pressuring-fox-news-sean-hannity-1007805|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Friedersdorf, Conor. [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/05/sean-hannity/528144/ \"How Conservatives Awoke to the Dangers of Sean Hannity.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114012501/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/05/sean-hannity/528144/ |date=2019-01-14 }} ''The Atlantic''. May 30, 2017.</ref> However, USAA decided to return to the show shortly after following a negative outcry against its decision to pull out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2017/05/30/usaa-says-reinstate-ads-fox-news-channels-hannity/102325194/|title=USAA says it will reinstate ads on Fox News Channel's 'Hannity'|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716000023/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2017/05/30/usaa-says-reinstate-ads-fox-news-channels-hannity/102325194/|archive-date=2018-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Conservative magazine ''[[National Review]]'' compared the story to a flat earth video, called it a \"disgrace\" that Hannity and other conspiracy theorists were hyping the story, and called for them to stop.<ref>{{cite news|last1=French|first1=David|title=The Seth Rich Conspiracy Theory Is Shameful Nonsense|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/447903/sean-hannitys-seth-rich-conspiracy-theory-disgrace|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=National Review|date=May 24, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717085214/http://www.nationalreview.com/article/447903/sean-hannitys-seth-rich-conspiracy-theory-disgrace|archive-date=2017-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Seth Rich's parents filed a lawsuit against Fox News for pushing conspiracy theories about their son's death. The suit alleges that the network \"intentionally exploited\" the tragedy for political purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/seth-rich-parents-sue-fox-news-over-retracted-story-they-say-treated-him-like-a-political-football/2018/03/14/647f5da2-27ab-11e8-b79d-f3d931db7f68_story.html|title=Seth Rich parents sue Fox News over retracted story they say treated him like 'a political football'|last=https://www.facebook.com/paul.farhi|website=Washington Post|accessdate=August 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826115319/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/seth-rich-parents-sue-fox-news-over-retracted-story-they-say-treated-him-like-a-political-football/2018/03/14/647f5da2-27ab-11e8-b79d-f3d931db7f68_story.html|archive-date=2018-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Claims about election fraud ====\nHannity came under criticism during the 2016 presidential election for false claims about [[election rigging]] during interviews. Hannity responded to this by citing [[Mitt Romney]]'s failure in the [[2012 United States presidential election]] to obtain any votes in 59 of 1,687 [[Philadelphia]] voting districts as proof of election rigging. However, [[FactCheck.org|Factcheck.org]] and [[PolitiFact.com|PolitiFact]] found that it was not unusual at all for this to occur, as those [[electoral district]]s are heavily African-American. Philadelphia elections inspector Ryan Godfrey also refuted Hannity's claim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2013/01/voting-conspiracies/|title=Voting Conspiracies|website=www.factcheck.org|language=en-US|access-date=February 23, 2017|date=2013-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404085919/http://www.factcheck.org/2013/01/voting-conspiracies/|archive-date=2017-04-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/pennsylvania/statements/2016/aug/12/viral-image/internet-philly-rigged-2012-presidential-election-|title=Internet: Philly rigged the 2012 presidential election. Experts: Still no|work=@politifact|access-date=March 26, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224211904/http://www.politifact.com/pennsylvania/statements/2016/aug/12/viral-image/internet-philly-rigged-2012-presidential-election-/|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== WikiLeaks ===\nIn 2010, Sean Hannity said [[WikiLeaks]] founder [[Julian Assange]] was waging a \"war\" on the United States, and that Wikileaks put American lives in \"jeopardy\" and \"danger\" around the world. He also criticized the [[Obama administration]] for failing to apprehend Assange.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Wilstein|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/07/sean-hannity-suddenly-loves-julian-assange-now-that-he-s-anti-hillary.html|title=Sean Hannity Suddenly Loves Julian Assange Now That He's Anti-Hillary|date=September 7, 2016|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224053419/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/07/sean-hannity-suddenly-loves-julian-assange-now-that-he-s-anti-hillary.html|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/04/how-some-republicans-learned-to-stop-worrying-and-love-julian-assange/|title=How some Republicans learned to stop worrying and love Julian Assange|website=Washington Post|access-date=January 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105180131/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/04/how-some-republicans-learned-to-stop-worrying-and-love-julian-assange/|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, after Wikileaks published [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak|leaked emails from the Democratic National Committee]], Hannity praised Assange for showing \"how corrupt, dishonest and phony our government is\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\" /><ref>{{cite news|first=Jamiles|last=Lartey|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/news-blog/2016/oct/22/wikileaks-clinton-leaks-julian-assange-sean-hannity-david-duke|title=WikiLeaks praised by Sean Hannity and David Duke after Clinton revelations|date=October 22, 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=February 23, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222115214/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/news-blog/2016/oct/22/wikileaks-clinton-leaks-julian-assange-sean-hannity-david-duke|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> He told Assange in a September 2016 interview, \"I do hope you get free one day. I wish you the best.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/la-na-trailguide-updates-hannity-hopes-for-wikileaks-founder-s-1473255689-htmlstory.html|title=Campaign 2016 updates: Donald Trump indicates allowing those in the country illegally to stay if they join military|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=February 23, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224052516/http://www.latimes.com/la-na-trailguide-updates-hannity-hopes-for-wikileaks-founder-s-1473255689-htmlstory.html|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> The following month,<!-- October 2016 --> Hannity claimed that [[WikiLeaks]] has revealed \"everything that conspiracy theorists have said over the years\" about Hillary Clinton is true.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Tim|last=Hains|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2016/10/12/hannity_wikileaks_proves_everything_that_conspiracy_theorists_said_was_true.html|title=Hannity: WikiLeaks Has Proven That \"Everything The Conspiracy Theorists Said\" Was True|website=[[RealClearPolitics]]|date=October 12, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917222936/https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2016/10/12/hannity_wikileaks_proves_everything_that_conspiracy_theorists_said_was_true.html|archive-date=2018-09-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Hannity retweeted a WikiLeaks tweet linking to an article by the Gateway Pundit site, claiming that [[John McCain]] was a \"[[globalism|globalist]] war criminal\". McCain's spokeswoman called Hannity out on it, asking him to \"correct the record.\" Hannity later deleted the tweet.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite news|first=Jordain|last=Carney|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/320832-mccain-spokeswoman-hannity-should-correct-the-record-after-tweet|title=McCain spokeswoman: Hannity should 'correct the record' after 'fake news' tweet|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=February 23, 2017|access-date=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224112057/http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/320832-mccain-spokeswoman-hannity-should-correct-the-record-after-tweet|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, Hannity made an offer to Assange to guest host his Fox News TV show.<ref>{{cite web|first=Oliver|last=Darcy|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/31/media/julian-assange-guest-host-hannity-radio-show/index.html|title=Julian Assange exploring ways to guest host Hannity's radio program after invite|website=CNNMoney|date=May 31, 2017|access-date=June 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602020850/http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/31/media/julian-assange-guest-host-hannity-radio-show/index.html|archive-date=2017-06-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with Donald Trump and Michael Cohen ===\nHannity developed a close relationship with Trump during the election and has become even closer during his presidency.<ref name=\":29\" /> The two men speak on the phone multiple times a week, discussing Hannity's weekday show, the special counsel investigation, even evaluating White House staff.<ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hannitys-rising-role-in-trumps-world-he-basically-has-a-desk-in-the-place/2018/04/17/e2483018-4260-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html|title=Hannity's rising role in Trump's world: 'He basically has a desk in the place'|last=Costa|first=Robert|date=April 17, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 28, 2018|last2=Ellison|first2=Sarah|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dawsey|first3=Josh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427210202/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hannitys-rising-role-in-trumps-world-he-basically-has-a-desk-in-the-place/2018/04/17/e2483018-4260-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html|title=The Strange Cocoon of Trump and Hannity, Two Friends Who Like to Talk Before Bed|last=Nuzzi|first=Olivia|work=Daily Intelligencer|access-date=May 14, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514014528/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT101017\">{{Cite news | first1 = Noah | last1 = Bierman | first2 = Cathleen | last2 = Decker | first3 = Brian | last3 = Bennett | url = https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-trump-kelly-20171010-story.html | title = Trump unleashes himself from would-be handlers, lashing out mornings, nights and weekends | newspaper = Los Angeles Times | date = October 10, 2017 | access-date = February 20, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181214014010/https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-trump-kelly-20171010-story.html | archive-date = December 14, 2018 | url-status = live }}.</ref> Hannity shares, ''[[The Economist]]'' asserts, \"Mr Trump's love of conspiracy theories and hatred of snooty elites\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21740777-michael-cohen-has-all-best-clients-sean-hannity-shares-lot-donald-trump|title=Sean Hannity shares a lot with Donald Trump, including an attorney|date=April 19, 2018|work=The Economist|accessdate=April 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421001923/https://economist.com/news/united-states/21740777-michael-cohen-has-all-best-clients-sean-hannity-shares-lot-donald-trump|archive-date=2018-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref> They speak so often that one Trump adviser has said that Hannity \"basically has a desk in the place\".<ref name=\":27\" /> On the air, Hannity echoes Trump's attacks on the media and [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]].<ref name=\"Lima\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/hannity-michael-cohen-fbi-raid-526860|title=Fox's Hannity, named as a client of Michael Cohen, spent days attacking FBI raid|last=Lima|first=Cristiano|date=April 16, 2018|work=Politico|accessdate=April 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094345/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/hannity-michael-cohen-fbi-raid-526860|archive-date=2018-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Trump sometimes quotes Hannity to others or promotes the show to his Twitter followers.<ref name=\":27\" /> Hannity has encouraged Trump to shut down the government to get funding for a border wall, as well as his declaration of a national emergency over the US-Mexico border.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nAccording to reports by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, Hannity frequently talks to Trump by telephone after Hannity's weekday broadcasts,<ref name=\"LAT101017\" /><ref name=Nuzzi>{{cite web | url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html | title=Donald Trump and Sean Hannity Like to Talk Before Bedtime | work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] | date=May 14, 2018 | accessdate=May 14, 2018 | last=Nuzzi | first=Olivia | last2=Darrow | first2=Joe | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514014528/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html | archive-date=2018-05-14 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Cranley>{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5 | title=Trump reportedly talks to Sean Hannity most nights before bed | work=[[Business Insider]] | date=May 14, 2018 | accessdate=May 14, 2018 | last=Cranley | first=Ellen | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514193211/http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5 | archive-date=2018-05-14 | url-status=live }}</ref> and Hannity is one of several dozen cleared callers whose calls to the White House public switchboard can be connected directly to the president.<ref name=Nuzzi/>\n\nHannity stirred controversy in April 2018 when it was revealed that he shared a lawyer, [[Michael Cohen]], with President Trump. In a breach of [[journalism ethics|journalistic ethics]], Hannity had failed to disclose that Cohen was his lawyer while at the same time taking to the Fox airwaves to defend Cohen and criticize those who investigated him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/business/media/sean-hannity-fox-news.html|title=No Disclosure? No Problem. Sean Hannity Gets a Pass at Fox News.|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=April 17, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 28, 2018|last2=Koblin|first2=John|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427010532/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/business/media/sean-hannity-fox-news.html|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/17/sean-hannity-fox-news-full-support-michael-cohen-528948|title=Cohen controversy tests Hannity's Teflon Sean reputation|work=POLITICO|access-date=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429092537/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/17/sean-hannity-fox-news-full-support-michael-cohen-528948|archive-date=2018-04-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/sean-hannity-cohen-attorney-trump-527897|title=Hannity's ethics under fire|work=POLITICO|access-date=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427165830/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/sean-hannity-cohen-attorney-trump-527897|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/17/watchdogs-attack-sean-hannity-for-hiding-link-to-trump-lawyer-cohen.html|title=Fox News gives Sean Hannity 'full support' as critics slam him for hiding link to Trump lawyer|last=Breuninger|first=Kevin|date=April 17, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429092044/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/17/watchdogs-attack-sean-hannity-for-hiding-link-to-trump-lawyer-cohen.html|archive-date=2018-04-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2018, federal agents from the [[U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York|U.S. Attorney's office]] served a search warrant on the office and residence of [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]], Trump's personal attorney.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren |last2=Walcott |first2=John |title=FBI raids offices, home of Trump's personal lawyer: sources |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |website=Reuters |accessdate=April 10, 2018 |date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410012921/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |archive-date=2018-04-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the air, Hannity defended Cohen and criticized the federal action, calling it \"highly questionable\" and \"an unprecedented abuse of power\".<ref name=\"Winter\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|title=Fox News host Sean Hannity revealed as Michael Cohen's mystery client|last1=Winter|first1=Tom|last2=Edelman|first2=Adam|date=April 16, 2018|work=NBC News|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416122620/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 16, 2018, in a court hearing, Cohen's lawyers told the judge that Cohen had ten clients in 2017-2018 but did \"traditional legal tasks\" for only three: Trump, [[Elliott Broidy]], and a \"prominent person\" who did not wish to be named for fear of being \"embarrassed\".<ref name = Miller/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pierson|first1=Brendan|last2=Freifeld|first2=Karen|last3=Stempel|first3=Jonathan|title=Fox's Hannity revealed as mystery client of Trump's personal lawyer|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-cohen/foxs-hannity-revealed-as-mystery-client-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-idUSKBN1HN12G|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418020458/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-cohen/foxs-hannity-revealed-as-mystery-client-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-idUSKBN1HN12G|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Feuer|first1=Alan|last2=Grynbaum|first2=Michael|last3=Koblin|first3=John|title=Sean Hannity Is Named as Client of Michael Cohen, Trump's Lawyer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/16/business/media/sean-hannity-michael-cohen-client.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417195139/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/16/business/media/sean-hannity-michael-cohen-client.html|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal judge ordered the revelation of the third client, whom Cohen's lawyers named as Hannity.<ref name = Miller/> Although Hannity has covered Cohen on his show, he did not disclose that he had consulted with Cohen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2018/04/fox-news-sean-hannity-downplay-michael-cohen-relationship/|title=Fox News and Sean Hannity Downplay Host's Relationship With Attorney Michael Cohen|last=Richardson|first=Davis|date=April 16, 2018|work=The Observer|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105818/http://observer.com/2018/04/fox-news-sean-hannity-downplay-michael-cohen-relationship/|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFox News released a statement on April 16, 2018, attributed to Hannity: \"Michael Cohen has never represented me in any matter. I never retained him, received an invoice, or paid legal fees. I have occasionally had brief discussions with him about legal questions about which I wanted his input and perspective. I assumed those conversations were confidential, but to be absolutely clear they never involved any matter between me and a third party.\"<ref name=cohenfox>{{cite web|last1=Borchers|first1=Callum|title=The gaping hole in Sean Hannity's story about being Michael Cohen's client|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/16/the-gaping-hole-in-sean-hannitys-story-about-being-michael-cohens-client/?noredirect=on|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423033629/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/16/the-gaping-hole-in-sean-hannitys-story-about-being-michael-cohens-client/?noredirect=on|archive-date=2018-04-23|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, [[NBC News]] quoted Hannity as saying: \"We definitely had [[attorney-client privilege]] because I asked him for that\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Edelman|first1=Adam|last2=Winter|first2=Tom|title=Fox News host Sean Hannity revealed as Michael Cohen's mystery client|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416234249/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> while Hannity said on his radio show that he \"might have handed him ten bucks\" for the attorney-client privilege.<ref name=cohenfox/><ref name=Miller>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Hayley|last2=Blumberg|first2=Antonia|title=Identity Of Michael Cohen's 'Mystery' Client Revealed As Sean Hannity|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/michael-cohen-sean-hannity_us_5ad4ef98e4b016a07e9f6410|work=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416231924/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/michael-cohen-sean-hannity_us_5ad4ef98e4b016a07e9f6410|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Lastly, Hannity tweeted that his discussions with Cohen were \"almost exclusively\" about [[real estate]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Samuels|first1=Brett|title=Hannity downplays connection to Trump's personal lawyer|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/383417-hannity-downplays-connection-to-trumps-personal-lawyer|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031520/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/383417-hannity-downplays-connection-to-trumps-personal-lawyer|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, news reports revealed that Hannity had shared another lawyer with Trump, [[Jay Sekulow]]. Sekulow had written a [[cease-and-desist letter]] to [[KFAQ]] on Hannity's behalf in May 2017, and later represented Trump in connection with the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gray|first1=Rosie|title=Sean Hannity's Ties to Two More Trump-Connected Lawyers|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/sean-hannity/558272/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417235448/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/sean-hannity/558272/|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Report: Sean Hannity used two other Trump-connected lawyers|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/report-sean-hannity-used-two-other-trump-connected-lawyers/|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418032454/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/report-sean-hannity-used-two-other-trump-connected-lawyers/|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Hannity allowed Sekulow and [[Rudy Giuliani]], another personal lawyer for Trump, to host Hannity's radio show; the duo proceeded to defend Trump and promote arguments made by the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boboltz |first1=Sara |title=Sean Hannity Just Let Trump's Lawyers Host His Radio Show |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sean-hannity-is-letting-trumps-lawyers-host-his-radio-show_us_5b6d9441e4b0ae32af978334 |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |accessdate=August 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824224858/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sean-hannity-is-letting-trumps-lawyers-host-his-radio-show_us_5b6d9441e4b0ae32af978334 |archive-date=2018-08-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|The New Yorker]]'', Hannity has reversed on the issue of negotiations with North Korea: during Obama's presidency, Hannity called negotiations with [[North Korea]] \"disturbing\", whereas he called Trump's negotiations with North Korea a \"huge foreign-policy win.\"<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nIn June 2019, Hannity expressed outrage at Speaker of the House [[Nancy Pelosi]]'s comment that she would like to see Trump \"in prison\". Hannity declared: \"Based on no actual crimes, she wants a political opponent locked up in prison? That happens in [[banana republic]]s \u2014 beyond despicable behavior.\" Aaron Rupar of ''[[Vox (news site)|Vox]]'' criticized Hannity for \"obvious hypocrisy\", noting that Hannity himself had said in January 2018 regarding Hillary Clinton: \"I think Hillary should be in jail. Lock her up.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rupar |first1=Aaron |title=Hannity: \"Hillary should be in jail.\" Also Hannity: Locking up Trump would be \"beyond despicable.\" |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/6/7/18656356/hannity-lock-them-up-pelosi-trump |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> Aaron Blake of ''The Washington Post'' described Hannity's comment as \"a pretty obvious bit of [[gaslighting]]\", noting Hannity's loyalty to Trump, whose campaign rallies have featured chants of \"Lock her up\", and also Hannity's comments that Trump was free to investigate Clinton.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Parsing Sean Hannity's incredible flip-flop on jailing political opponents |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/06/07/parsing-sean-hannitys-incredible-flip-flop-jailing-political-opponents |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism of FBI, DOJ, and special counsel ===\nDuring President Trump's administration, Hannity has repeatedly been highly critical of the FBI, DOJ, Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]], and others investigating [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 election]].<ref name=newsweekporter>{{cite journal|url=http://www.newsweek.com/watergate-reporter-carl-bernstein-thinks-fox-news-helping-trump-administration-743904|title=Watergate Reporter Carl Bernstein Thinks Fox News Is Helping the Trump Administration Cover Up Its Russia Ties|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=December 11, 2017|first=Tom|last=Porter|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023095822/https://www.newsweek.com/watergate-reporter-carl-bernstein-thinks-fox-news-helping-trump-administration-743904|archive-date=2018-10-23|url-status=live}}</ref> According to a review by ''[[Media Matters for America|Media Matters]]'' of all transcripts from the 254 episodes of Hannity's show from Mueller's appointment (May 17, 2017) to May 16, 2018, Hannity had 487 segments substantially devoted to Mueller (approximately two per episode), opened his program with Mueller 152 times (approximately three times per week), and the content of his show was highly critical of the probe and the media's coverage of the probe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/05/23/study-sean-hannity-spent-last-year-laying-groundwork-authoritarian-response-russia-probe/220281|title=Study: Sean Hannity spent the last year laying the groundwork for an authoritarian response to the Russia probe|date=May 22, 2018|work=Media Matters for America|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523153737/https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/05/23/study-sean-hannity-spent-last-year-laying-groundwork-authoritarian-response-russia-probe/220281|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref> He has called the Russia inquiry a \"witch hunt\", an \"utter disgrace\", and \"a direct threat to you, the American people, and our American republic.\"<ref name=newsweekporter/> Hannity has expressed skepticism of the U.S. intelligence community's view that Russia hacked the [[Democratic National Convention]]'s emails during the 2016 election and has promoted various conspiracy theories. In March 2017 he publicized a theory, first proposed at the Wikileaks Twitter account, that the CIA could have done the hacking while making it look like Russia did it.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-cia-hacked-2017-3?r=US&IR=T|title=Conservative media figures are embracing a wild WikiLeaks conspiracy theory that the CIA hacked the DNC, and then framed Russia|work=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=March 11, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108034506/http://uk.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-cia-hacked-2017-3?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2017-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> In August he suggested that [[Seth Rich]] may have been the leaker.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/seth-rich-russia-and-2016-election-648312|title=Link between Russia and 2016 election may be Seth Rich murder, Republican lobbyist tells Robert Mueller|last=Nazaryan|first=Alexander|date=August 19, 2017|work=Newsweek|accessdate=April 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421233212/http://www.newsweek.com/seth-rich-russia-and-2016-election-648312|archive-date=2018-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHannity has described the Mueller investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election, as well as [[James Comey]]'s tenure as FBI Director, as \"one giant incestuous circle of corruption.\"<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|first=Mark|last=Mazzetti|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/us/politics/memo-trump-nunes.html|title=How Trump's Allies Fanned an Ember of Controversy Into Flames of Outrage|date=February 2, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 3, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203043405/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/us/politics/memo-trump-nunes.html|archive-date=2018-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2018, Hannity ran a segment where he claimed there were \"criminal\" connections between [[Bill Clinton|Bill]] and [[Hillary Clinton]], Mueller, and Comey.<ref name=\":25\" /> Hannity asserted that there were three connected \"Deep State crime families\" actively \"trying to take down the president.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-promotes-conspiratorial-hannity-episode-calling-mueller-head-of-deep-state-crime-families-2|title=Trump Promotes Conspiratorial 'Hannity' Episode Calling Mueller Part of 'Deep State Crime Families'|date=April 12, 2018|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=April 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413035126/https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-promotes-conspiratorial-hannity-episode-calling-mueller-head-of-deep-state-crime-families-2|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":25\" /> A guest on the segment, attorney [[Joseph diGenova]], called Mueller's team \"legal terrorists\" and referred to Comey as a \"dirty cop\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/joseph-digenova-trump-fox-news-sessions-should-fire-rosenstein-2018-4?r=US&IR=T|title=Former federal prosecutor Joseph diGenova calls for Rosenstein's firing on Fox News after Trump tells people to tune in to the 'big show'|work=Business Insider|access-date=April 12, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412212145/http://uk.businessinsider.com/joseph-digenova-trump-fox-news-sessions-should-fire-rosenstein-2018-4?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2018-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHannity also claimed that Mueller had been involved in the corrupt dealings of several FBI agents in connection with [[Boston, Massachusetts]] [[crime boss]] [[Whitey Bulger]].<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/opinion/robert-mueller-smearing-complicit.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Smearing Robert Mueller|date=April 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 19, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419004452/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/opinion/robert-mueller-smearing-complicit.html|archive-date=2018-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal judge who presided over a lawsuit concerning the corrupt dealings said Hannity's claims were unsubstantiated and that Mueller was never accused of any wrongdoing nor even mentioned during the proceedings.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nIn June 2018, after reports that Mueller's probe had asked witnesses to turn their personal phones over to investigators for examination, Hannity sarcastically suggested on air to the witnesses that they \"follow Hillary Clinton's lead\" and destroy their personal phones so they cannot be examined.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/391115-hannity-advises-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-smash-their-phones-to-little-itsy|title=Fox's Hannity advises witnesses in Mueller probe smash their phones to 'little itsy bitsy pieces'|last=Greenwood|first=Max|date=June 6, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=June 7, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180607035847/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/391115-hannity-advises-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-smash-their-phones-to-little-itsy|archive-date=2018-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/sean-hannity-to-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-bash-your-phones-into-pieces|title=Sean Hannity to Witnesses in Mueller Probe: 'Bash' Your Phones Into Pieces|date=June 7, 2018|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=June 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180607035909/https://www.thedailybeast.com/sean-hannity-to-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-bash-your-phones-into-pieces|archive-date=2018-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, after Mueller gave a statement saying the Special Counsel investigation did not exonerate Trump of crimes, Hannity said Mueller was \"basically full of crap\" and did not know the law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fox-news-mueller-hannity-carlson-ingraham_n_5cef781ce4b0888f89d0e91d|title=Fox News Hosts Freak Out Over 'Mean Girl' Robert Mueller: 'Full Of Crap'|last=Moran|first=Lee|date=2019-05-30|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Uranium One ===\nFrom 2015 into 2018, Fox News broadcast extensive coverage of an alleged scandal surrounding the sale of [[Uranium One]] to Russian interests, which Hannity characterized as \"one of the biggest scandals in American history.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/10/25/hannity-uranium-one-deal-was-biggest-scandal-american-history-nda-lifted-informant|title=Hannity: Uranium One Deal 'One of the Biggest Scandals in American History'|date=October 26, 2017|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074024/http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/10/25/hannity-uranium-one-deal-was-biggest-scandal-american-history-nda-lifted-informant|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref> The Fox News coverage extended throughout the programming day, with particular emphasis by Hannity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2017/11/09/study-fox-spent-nearly-12-hours-pushing-uranium-one-pseudoscandal-over-last-three-weeks/218475|title=Study: Fox spent nearly 12 hours pushing the Uranium One pseudoscandal over the last three weeks|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803044454/https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2017/11/09/study-fox-spent-nearly-12-hours-pushing-uranium-one-pseudoscandal-over-last-three-weeks/218475|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref> The network promoted a narrative asserting that, as Secretary of State, Hillary Clinton personally approved the Uranium One sale in exchange for $145 million in bribes paid to the [[Clinton Foundation]]. Donald Trump repeated these allegations as a candidate and as president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factba.se/search#%22uranium+one%22|title=Donald Trump Complete - Search Tweets, Speeches, Policies - Factbase|last=Factbase|website=Factbase|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809150520/https://factba.se/search#%22uranium+one%22#%22uranium+one%22|archive-date=2018-08-09|url-status=live}}</ref> No evidence of wrongdoing by Clinton had been found after three years of allegations, an FBI investigation, and the 2017 appointment of a Federal attorney to evaluate the investigation. In November 2017, Fox News host [[Shepard Smith]] concisely debunked the alleged scandal, including stating that Clinton did not personally approve the sale, infuriating viewers who suggested he should work for CNN or MSNBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/11/15/fox-news-shepherd-smith-debunks-his-networks-hillary-clinton-scandal-story-infuriates-viewers/|title=Fox News's Shepard Smith debunks his network's favorite Hillary Clinton 'scandal,' infuriates viewers|website=Washington Post|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806134030/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/11/15/fox-news-shepherd-smith-debunks-his-networks-hillary-clinton-scandal-story-infuriates-viewers/|archive-date=2018-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7A9EV64aX_Q|title=Fox News Reports: Sean Hannity Is a Liar|last=fb|date=November 15, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=August 3, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> Hannity later called Smith \"clueless,\" while Smith stated, \"I get it, that some of our opinion programming is there strictly to be entertaining. I get that. I don't work there. I wouldn't work there.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/shepard-smith-fox-news-trump-sean-hannity-20180316.html|title=Fox News fight: Shepard Smith, Sean Hannity trade insults|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803044423/http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/shepard-smith-fox-news-trump-sean-hannity-20180316.html|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/shepard-smith-calls-out-fox-news-opinion-programming-those-shows-exist-strictly-to-be-entertaining/|title=Shepard Smith on Fox News 'Opinion Programming': Shows Exist 'Strictly to Be Entertaining'|website=www.mediaite.com|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074031/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/shepard-smith-calls-out-fox-news-opinion-programming-those-shows-exist-strictly-to-be-entertaining/|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA two-year Justice Department investigation initiated after Donald Trump became president found no evidence to justify pursuing a criminal investigation.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/justice-dept-winds-down-clinton-related-inquiry-once-championed-by-trump-it-found-nothing-of-consequence/2020/01/09/ca83932e-32f9-11ea-a053-dc6d944ba776_story.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/09/politics/clinton-justice-department-investigation/index.html|title=Justice inquiry into Hillary Clinton's business dealings languishes|author1=Evan Perez |author2=David Shortell|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n=== Deep state ===\nHannity has advocated [[QAnon]], the \"[[Deep state in the United States|deep state]]\" theory proposing a network of government officials are working to hinder the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Coaston|first=Jane|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/8/1/17253444/qanon-trump-conspiracy-theory-reddit|title=#QAnon, the scarily popular pro-Trump conspiracy theory, explained|work=Vox|date=August 2, 2018|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref> He has described the deep state as a \"Shadow Government\" and \"Deep state swamp of Obama holdovers and DC lifers\".<ref>{{Cite web|first=Hunter|last=Schwarz|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/07/politics/deep-state/index.html|title=What's a 'Deep State' and why is it a new buzzword for the online right?|website=[[CNN]]|date=March 7, 2017|access-date=March 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314091502/http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/07/politics/deep-state/index.html|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|first=Chris|last=Graham|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/11/deep-state-shadowy-network-obama-holdovers-undermining-donald/|title=What is 'deep state' and is a shadowy network of Obama holdovers undermining Donald Trump?|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=March 11, 2017|access-date=March 14, 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314025019/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/11/deep-state-shadowy-network-obama-holdovers-undermining-donald/|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2017, he called for a \"purge\" of Obama-era bureaucrats and appointees in government.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Mark|last=Hensch|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/323458-spicer-wont-reject-deep-state-against-trump|title=Spicer won't reject idea that 'deep state' opposes Trump|date=March 10, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=March 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313232436/http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/323458-spicer-wont-reject-deep-state-against-trump|archive-date=2017-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref> In an op-ed for ''The Wall Street Journal'', conservative columnist [[Bret Stephens]] disputed Sean Hannity's deep state allegations, saying they were an example of the \"paranoid style in politics\".<ref>{{Cite news|first=Bret|last=Stephens|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/deep-states-and-demagogues-1489446006|title=Deep States and Demagogues|date=March 13, 2017|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=March 14, 2017|issn=0099-9660|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314002054/https://www.wsj.com/articles/deep-states-and-demagogues-1489446006|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that month, Hannity said NBC News was part of the deep state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tax-story-puts-spotlight-on-msnbcs-rachel-maddow/2017/03/14/4702121a-092f-11e7-bd19-fd3afa0f7e2a_story.html|title=Tax story puts spotlight on MSNBC's Rachel Maddow|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315180557/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tax-story-puts-spotlight-on-msnbcs-rachel-maddow/2017/03/14/4702121a-092f-11e7-bd19-fd3afa0f7e2a_story.html|archive-date=2017-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, he reiterated that deep state/intelligence operatives were trying to destroy the Trump presidency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-supporters-idUSKCN18E36Q|title=For Trump's defenders, White House turmoil is politics as usual|date=May 18, 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=May 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518232147/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-supporters-idUSKCN18E36Q|archive-date=2017-05-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Hannity attacked Special Counsel Robert Mueller, saying his career was \"anything but impeccable.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/379475-hannity-rips-muellers-career-anything-but-impeccable|title=Hannity rips Mueller's career: 'Anything but impeccable'|last=Manchester|first=Julia|date=March 21, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321174903/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/379475-hannity-rips-muellers-career-anything-but-impeccable|archive-date=2018-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity asserted that Mueller was friends with former FBI Director James Comey and current Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]], and that he \"cannot be expected to honestly investigate scandals that his friends are directly involved in.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/379470-hannity-mueller-cant-honestly-investigate-scandals-that-comey-rosenstein-are|title=Hannity: Mueller can't 'honestly investigate scandals' that Comey, Rosenstein are 'directly involved in'|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=March 21, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321164758/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/379470-hannity-mueller-cant-honestly-investigate-scandals-that-comey-rosenstein-are|archive-date=2018-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> He said these individuals were involved in \"one massive, huge, deep-state conflict of interest after another. Now they're protecting themselves. They're trying to preserve their own power.\"<ref name=\":25\" />\n\n=== Comments on sexual harassment ===\nIn 2016, Hannity vociferously defended Roger Ailes when he was accused by multiple women of sexual harassment.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\"Alderman\">{{cite news|last1=Alderman|first1=Julie|last2=Radtke|first2=Dina|last3=Lawrence|first3=Andrew|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/11/22/sean-hannity-continues-to-defend-sexual-abusers_partner/|title=Sean Hannity's long-standing defense of sexual abusers|work=Salon|agency=Media Matters for America|date=November 23, 2017|access-date=November 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109070737/https://www.salon.com/2017/11/22/sean-hannity-continues-to-defend-sexual-abusers_partner/|archive-date=2018-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, Hannity paid a tribute to Ailes after he died.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sean-hannity-has-message-for-roger-ailes-enemies/|title=Sean Hannity has message for Roger Ailes' enemies|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065103/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sean-hannity-has-message-for-roger-ailes-enemies/|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity called him \"a second father\" and said to Ailes's \"enemies\" that he was \"preparing to kick your {{As written|a**}} in the next life\".<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIn April 2017, Hannity came to the defense of Fox News co-president [[Bill Shine]] after it was reported that Shine's job was at risk.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/27/business/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-bill-shine.html|title=Sean Hannity Defends Executive as Fox News Turmoil Continues|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=April 27, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 12, 2017|last2=Steel|first2=Emily|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065121/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/27/business/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-bill-shine.html|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-04-28/sean-hannity-defends-boss-says-ouster-would-be-end-of-fox-news|title=Sean Hannity Defends Boss, Says Ouster Would Be End of Fox News|date=April 28, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065136/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-04-28/sean-hannity-defends-boss-says-ouster-would-be-end-of-fox-news|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> At least four lawsuits alleged that Shine had ignored, enabled or concealed Roger Ailes' alleged sexual harassment.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/may/25/sean-hannity-fox-news-media-matters-seth-rich|title=Sean Hannity targets media watchdog amid questions over future at Fox News|last=Gabbatt|first=Adam|date=May 25, 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 13, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013172248/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/may/25/sean-hannity-fox-news-media-matters-seth-rich|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, several months after [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] was fired from Fox News in the wake of a number of women's alleging that he had sexually harassed them, Hannity hosted O'Reilly on his show.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/352439-hannity-to-host-oreilly-tuesday-for-second-interview-in-eight-days|title=Hannity to host O'Reilly Tuesday on Fox News|last=Lejeune|first=Tristan|date=September 26, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065440/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/352439-hannity-to-host-oreilly-tuesday-for-second-interview-in-eight-days|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/26/media/oreilly-hannity-fox-news-interview/index.html|title=Bill O'Reilly appears on Fox News for first time since his ouster|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011230546/http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/26/media/oreilly-hannity-fox-news-interview/index.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/09/27/bill-oreilly-returns-to-fox-as-sean-hannitys-guest/106036888/|title=Bill O'Reilly returns to Fox as Sean Hannity's guest|work=USA TODAY|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013070622/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/09/27/bill-oreilly-returns-to-fox-as-sean-hannitys-guest/106036888/|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Some Fox News employees criticized the decision.<ref name=\":16\" /> In the interview, O'Reilly attacked liberal media watchdog groups and said he should have fought harder when those groups targeted his advertisers.<ref name=\":16\" /> According to CNN, during the interview, Hannity found kinship with O'Reilly as he appeared \"to feel that he and O'Reilly have both become victims of liberals looking to silence them.\"<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nHannity came under criticism in October 2017 when he attacked Democrats after it became known that a large number of women had accused [[Harvey Weinstein]], the Hollywood producer and donor to Democratic causes, of sexual harassment.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-harvey-weinstein-bill-oreilly-2017-10?IR=T|title=Sean Hannity goes on 10-minute rant about left's 'hypocrisy' on Harvey Weinstein, two weeks after having Bill O'Reilly on his show|work=Business Insider|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012201648/http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-harvey-weinstein-bill-oreilly-2017-10?IR=T|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> Critics noted that Hannity had weeks earlier defended and hosted his coworker Bill O'Reilly who was fired following a number of sexual harassment allegations.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-and-friends-hypocrites-slam-late-night-hosts-weinstein-silence|title='Fox & Friends' Hypocrites Slam Late-Night Hosts' Weinstein Silence|last=Wilstein|first=Matt|date=October 9, 2017|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011205846/https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-and-friends-hypocrites-slam-late-night-hosts-weinstein-silence|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nIn the radio show for KCSB, which was the subject of controversy in 1989, Hannity made anti-gay comments.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|first=Emily|last=Shugarman|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/sean-hannity-gay-people-aids-lgbt-homosexuality-sewer-comments-college-radio-a7995696.html|title=Sean Hannity once compared homosexuality to 'playing in a sewer'|work=[[The Independent]]|date=October 11, 2017|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012002053/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/sean-hannity-gay-people-aids-lgbt-homosexuality-sewer-comments-college-radio-a7995696.html|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"PinkNews 2017\" /> He called AIDS a \"gay disease\" and said the media was hiding salient information from the public.<ref name=\":6\"/><ref name=\"PinkNews 2017\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/10/11/fox-news-host-sean-hannity-called-aids-a-gay-disease-and-lashed-out-at-gay-brainwashing/|title=Fox News host Sean Hannity called AIDS a 'gay disease' and lashed out at gay 'brainwashing'|work=PinkNews|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011231213/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/10/11/fox-news-host-sean-hannity-called-aids-a-gay-disease-and-lashed-out-at-gay-brainwashing/|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref> Two editions featured anti-gay activist Gene Antonio, a Lutheran minister,<ref>{{cite news|last=Shaer|first=Matthew|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|title=How Far Will Sean Hannity Go?|work=The New York Times|date=November 28, 2017|access-date=November 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129003856/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|archive-date=2017-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref> discussing his book ''The AIDS Coverup: The Real and Alarming Facts about AIDS''. In the book, Antonio claims that AIDS can be spread by people sneezing in close proximity to each other. Hannity encouraged Antonio when he said that AIDS spread when gay men consumed each other's [[feces]],<ref name=\":6\" /> said that homosexuality was a \"lower form of behavior\", compared homosexual sex lives to \"playing in a sewer\" and gay people of being \"filled with hatred and bigotry\".<ref name=\":7\" /> When a lesbian, another broadcaster at the station, called into the show, Hannity said \"I feel sorry for your child\".<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{cite book |first=Jeff |last=Cohen |authorlink=Jeff Cohen (media critic) |title=Cable News Confidential: My Misadventures in Corporate Media |publisher=[[Polipoint Press]] |location=Sausalito, California |date=2006 |url=https://archive.org/details/cablenewsconfide00cohe |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/cablenewsconfide00cohe/page/85 85] |isbn=978-0-9760621-6-5}}</ref> Hannity was quoted at the time as saying that \"anyone listening to this show that believes homosexuality is a normal lifestyle has been brainwashed\".<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Marshall|first=Colin|url=https://www.independent.com/news/2009/nov/23/let-freeform-ring/|title=Let Freeform Ring: A Brief History of KCSB, Part VI|work=Santa Barbara Independent|date=November 23, 2009|access-date=November 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109205455/http://www.independent.com/news/2009/nov/23/let-freeform-ring/|archive-date=2018-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The ACLU opposed his firing and petitioned the station to reverse their decision. Hannity demanded a formal apology and double the airtime. While the station did offer to allow Hannity to return, they would not meet Hannity's additional demands and he declined to return.\n\nIn 2017, Hannity said he regretted the comments and that they were \"ignorant and embarrassing\".<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|last=Cuccinello|first=Hayley C.|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hayleycuccinello/2018/07/16/sean-hannity-celebrity-100/#50cbee972d93|title=Trump Bump: How Sean Hannity Earned $36 Million This Year|work=Forbes|access-date=July 16, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Immigration ===\nHannity opposed amnesty, then he said in 2012 that he had evolved on the issue and favored a \"pathway to citizenship\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2012/11/hannity-ive-evolved-on-immigration-and-support-a-pathway-to-citizenship-149078|title=Hannity: I've 'evolved' on immigration and support a 'pathway to citizenship'|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095450/https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2012/11/hannity-ive-evolved-on-immigration-and-support-a-pathway-to-citizenship-149078|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Later, he opposed that idea.<ref name=\":6\" /> By 2018, he was described as an immigration hardliner by CNN, ''The Washington Post'', and ''New York'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/02/politics/donald-trump-weekend-immigration/index.html|title=At Mar-a-Lago, Trump hears from immigration hardliners|last=Producer|first=Kevin Liptak, CNN White House|work=CNN|access-date=May 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523011605/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/02/politics/donald-trump-weekend-immigration/index.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/04/white-house-pursues-new-immigration-push-after-trump-tweets.html|title=White House Unveils New Immigration Push, Tries to Make Sense of Trump's Tweets|last=Hartmann|first=Margaret|work=Daily Intelligencer|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095510/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/04/white-house-pursues-new-immigration-push-after-trump-tweets.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-heats-up-rhetoric-on-border-immigration-as-some-supporters-grow-impatient/2018/04/02/88d5353e-3690-11e8-acd5-35eac230e514_story.html|title=Trump heats up rhetoric on border, immigration as some supporters grow impatient|last=Nakamura|first=David|date=April 3, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523011054/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-heats-up-rhetoric-on-border-immigration-as-some-supporters-grow-impatient/2018/04/02/88d5353e-3690-11e8-acd5-35eac230e514_story.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2018, President Trump suggested that he might shut down the government to force Congress to fund his border wall, boasting that Sean Hannity agreed with the action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/02/president-trump-sean-hannity-government-shutdown-border-money/894974002/|title=President Trump boasts of Sean Hannity's approval of government shutdown plan|work=USA TODAY|access-date=August 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Islam ===\nHannity has warned of [[sharia law]] coming to the United States.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2011/04/paul-to-hannity-stop-with-your-sharia-053693|title=Paul to Hannity: Stop with your Sharia|work=POLITICO|access-date=October 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017093438/http://www.politico.com/story/2011/04/paul-to-hannity-stop-with-your-sharia-053693|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity opposed the building of [[Park51]], a mosque two blocks from the [[World Trade Center site]].<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nHannity promoted the idea of \"Islamic training camps right here in America\", which were based on an unsubstantiated \"documentary\" by the Christian Action Network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/11/05/the-conspiracy-theories-animating-the-right|title=The Conspiracy Theories Animating the Right|last=Clift|first=Eleanor|date=November 5, 2015|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Hannity was critical of [[Keith Ellison]], the first Muslim elected to U.S. Congress, being sworn into office with an oath on a [[Quran]]. Hannity equated the Quran with ''[[Mein Kampf]]'', asking a guest on his show whether he would have allowed Ellison \"to choose, you know, [[Hitler]]'s Mein Kampf, which is the [[Nazi]] bible?\"<ref>{{Cite book|first=Randy|last=Bobbitt|url=https://archive.org/details/usagainstthempol0000bobb|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/usagainstthempol0000bobb/page/59 59]|quote=hannity ellison Mein Kampf.|title=Us against Them: The Political Culture of Talk Radio|date=May 25, 2010|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=9781461634652|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Brian|last=Lambert|url=https://www.minnpost.com/glean/2013/03/minnesota-winters-warming-faster-any-other-state|title=Minnesota winters warming faster than in any other state|work=[[MinnPost]]|date=March 1, 2013|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017043007/https://www.minnpost.com/glean/2013/03/minnesota-winters-warming-faster-any-other-state|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Torture ===\nIn 2009, Hannity said he supported [[enhanced interrogation]], a euphemism for torture. He also volunteered to be [[waterboarded]] for charity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Linkins|first1=Jason|title=Hannity Offers To Be Waterboarded For Charity (By Charles Grodin!)|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/22/hannity-offers-to-be-wate_n_190354.html|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227194400/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/22/hannity-offers-to-be-wate_n_190354.html|archive-date=2018-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hannity, Grodin Go One-on-One on Waterboarding, Obama's Agenda|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2009/04/23/hannity-grodin-go-one-on-one-on-waterboarding-obama-agenda.html|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413185817/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2009/04/23/hannity-grodin-go-one-on-one-on-waterboarding-obama-agenda.html|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, [[Keith Olbermann]] pledged to donate $1,000 for every second of waterboarding Hannity underwent. In 2017, Hannity continued to advocate for waterboarding, raising the example of using it against a kidnapper.<ref>{{cite web|last1=de Moraes|first1=Lisa|title=Sean Hannity & Donald Trump Wonder How David Muir Would Feel About Waterboarding If His Child Was Kidnapped|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/donald-trump-sean-hannity-waterboarding-david-muir-kidnap-child-1201895285/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413185912/http://deadline.com/2017/01/donald-trump-sean-hannity-waterboarding-david-muir-kidnap-child-1201895285/|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity has not been waterboarded as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Simon|first1=Maloy|title=Torture fan Sean Hannity still hasn't been waterboarded like he promised|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/03/16/Torture-fan-Sean-Hannity-still-hasnt-been-waterboarded-like-he-promised/219665|journal=[[Media Matters for America|Media Matters]]|date=March 16, 2018|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212070508/https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/03/16/Torture-fan-Sean-Hannity-still-hasnt-been-waterboarded-like-he-promised/219665|archive-date=2019-02-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate change ===\nHannity rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. In 2001, he described it as \"phony science from the left.\"<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=McKnight|first=David|date=December 1, 2010|title=A change in the climate? The journalism of opinion at News Corporation|journal=Journalism|language=en|volume=11|issue=6|pages=693\u2013706|doi=10.1177/1464884910379704|issn=1464-8849}}</ref> In 2004, he falsely claimed that scientists couldn't agree on whether global warming was \"scientific fact or fiction\".<ref name=\":18\" /> In 2010, Hannity falsely stated that so-called [[Climatic Research Unit email controversy|\"Climategate\"]] \u2013 the leaking of e-mails written by climate scientists that climate change skeptics said demonstrated scientific misconduct, but which all subsequent inquiries found to show no evidence of misconduct or wrongdoing \u2013 was a scandal that \"exposed global warming as a myth cooked up by alarmists.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-11/news/ct-oped-0711-page-20100711_1_climate-change-scientific-journals-scientists|title=Climate change heats up again|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017044436/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-11/news/ct-oped-0711-page-20100711_1_climate-change-scientific-journals-scientists|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity frequently invites critics of climate science onto his shows.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RsYr_iQUs6QC&pg=PA144&dq=hannity+%22climate+change%22#v=onepage&q=hannity&f=false|title=The Oxford Handbook of Climate Change and Society|last=Dryzek|first=John S.|last2=Norgaard|first2=Richard B.|last3=Schlosberg|first3=David|date=August 18, 2011|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780199566600|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Death panels ===\nHannity promoted the falsehood that the [[Affordable Care Act]] would create so-called \"[[death panel]]s\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2010/05/health-care_reform|title=Epistemic closure and political disinformation|work=The Economist|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816034937/https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2010/05/health-care_reform|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Nyhan|first=Brendan|date=April 27, 2010|title=Why the \"Death Panel\" Myth Wouldn't Die: Misinformation in the Health Care Reform Debate|journal=The Forum|language=en|volume=8|issue=1|doi=10.2202/1540-8884.1354|issn=1540-8884|citeseerx=10.1.1.692.9614|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meirick|first=Patrick C.|date=January 10, 2013|title=Motivated Misperception? Party, Education, Partisan News, and Belief in \"Death Panels\"|journal=Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly|language=en|volume=90|issue=1|pages=39\u201357|doi=10.1177/1077699012468696|hdl=11244/25317|url=https://shareok.org/bitstream/11244/25317/1/10.1177.1077699012468696.pdf}}</ref> According to a study by [[Dartmouth College]] political scientist [[Brendan Nyhan]], Hannity's show, along with the [[Laura Ingraham|Laura Ingraham Show]], were the first major conservative media personalities to latch onto the false claim of [[Betsy McCaughey]] a former lieutenant governor of New York, that the Affordable Care Act contained death panels.<ref name=\":19\" /> When [[Sarah Palin]] stirred controversy by promoting the death panels myth, and argued her case in a Facebook post, Hannity defended her and said, \"I agree with everything that she wrote.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite journal|last=Bard|first=Mitchell T.|date=September 1, 2016|title=The Role of Differing Host Styles in Fox News' Prime Time Coverage of Health Care Reform in August 2009|journal=Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly|language=en|volume=93|issue=3|pages=659\u2013676|doi=10.1177/1077699016628817|issn=1077-6990}}</ref> Hannity also claimed that he found the specific pages in the Affordable Care Act containing provisions on death panels.<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nA 2016 study found that Hannity promoted a number of falsehoods about the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\":20\" /> For instance, Hannity falsely alleged several times that Democratic [[Senate Finance Committee]] Chairman [[Max Baucus]] had said [[Social Security]] could be \"insolvent in two years\" due to the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\":20\" /> According to the study, Hannity, unlike other Fox News hosts such as Bill O'Reilly and [[Greta Van Susteren]], \"took a more direct approach, aggressively supporting Republicans and conservatives and attacking Democrats and liberals, endorsing the more spurious claims long after they were proven incorrect, and putting advocacy above accurate reporting, to further the network's themes opposing reform.\"<ref name=\":20\" />\n\n=== Roy Moore interview and Twitter controversy ===\nIn November 2017, Hannity interviewed the Alabama senate candidate [[Roy Moore]], who was facing accusations of sexual assault and harassment of teenage girls while he was in his thirties. Hannity said Moore \"deserves the presumption of innocence\" and that \"none of us know the truth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5021237/sean-hannity-boycott-keurig-roy-moore/|title=Here's Why Sean Hannity Fans Are Smashing Their Keurig Coffee Machines to Pieces|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622155422/http://time.com/5021237/sean-hannity-boycott-keurig-roy-moore/|archive-date=2018-06-22|url-status=live}}</ref> After a media campaign from [[Media Matters for America]], which had collected statements he made,<ref name=\"Alderman\" /> and promoted a boycott of Hannity since May 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/research/2017/05/23/these-are-sean-hannitys-advertisers/216607|title=These are Sean Hannity's advertisers|date=May 23, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017|publisher=Media Matters for America|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930212949/https://www.mediamatters.org/research/2017/05/23/these-are-sean-hannitys-advertisers/216607|archive-date=2017-09-30|url-status=live}}</ref> several major companies pulled their advertising from Hannity's show. Notably, [[Keurig Dr Pepper|Keurig]] tweeted that it would comply with the boycott organized by Media Matters; this tweet was widely shared and prompted a counter-boycott from fans of Hannity, who tweeted clips of themselves destroying their own [[Keurig|Keurig coffee machines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/reddi-wip-and-hebrew-national-cut-advertising-from-sean-hannitys-show-2017-11?r=UK&IR=T|title=Hebrew National and Reddi-wip announced they pulled advertising from Sean Hannity's show \u2014 but they say it has nothing to do with the recent Keurig-smashing backlash|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217201949/https://www.businessinsider.com/reddi-wip-and-hebrew-national-cut-advertising-from-sean-hannitys-show-2017-11?r=UK&IR=T|archive-date=2018-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":28\" /> After a contentious week, the [[CEO]] of Keurig stated in a publicized memo that the announcement of a boycott on social media was \"outside of company protocols\". He clarified that Keurig had engaged in a \"pause\" in advertisement on Hannity's show, which he claimed to be routine and subject to future review. Hannity later responded by thanking Keurig for \"standing by [him]\", and pledged to give out 500 Keurig machines.<ref>{{cite web|first=Erik|last=Wemple|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/11/13/keurig-ceo-tweet-regarding-hannity-created-an-unacceptable-situation/|title=Keurig CEO: Tweet regarding 'Hannity' created an 'unacceptable situation'|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113210532/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/11/13/keurig-ceo-tweet-regarding-hannity-created-an-unacceptable-situation/|archive-date=2017-11-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Adam Clark|last=Estes|url=https://gizmodo.com/sean-hannity-settles-keurig-controversy-in-dumbest-way-1820446440/|title=Sean Hannity Settles Keurig Controversy in Dumbest Way Possible|work=[[Gizmodo]]|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Jake Tapper ===\nIn November 2017, Fox News distorted a statement by [[Jake Tapper]] to make it appear as if he had said that \"Allahu Akbar\" can be used under the most \"beautiful circumstances\" in the immediate aftermath of the [[2017 New York City truck attack]] wherein a terrorist shouted \"Allahu Akbar\".<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/jake-tapper-fox-news-lying-allahu-akbar-beautiful-2017-11?r=US&IR=T|title=Jake Tapper slams Fox News for misrepresenting comments about New York City terror attack|work=Business Insider|access-date=November 2, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003601/http://uk.businessinsider.com/jake-tapper-fox-news-lying-allahu-akbar-beautiful-2017-11?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Fox News omitted that Tapper had said that the use of \"Allahu Akbar\" in the terrorist attack was not one of these beautiful circumstances.<ref name=\":21\" /> A headline on FoxNews.com was preceded by a tag reading \"OUTRAGEOUS\".<ref name=\":21\" /> The Fox News Twitter account distorted the statement even more, saying \"Jake Tapper Says 'Allahu Akbar' Is 'Beautiful' Right After NYC Terror Attack\" in a tweet that was later deleted.<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nEven after the Fox News Twitter account had deleted the tweet on Tapper's out-of-context comments, Hannity repeated the out-of-context comments to his viewers, calling Tapper \"liberal fake news CNN's fake Jake Tapper\" and mocking his ratings.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/358382-tapper-hits-fox-hannity-over-allahu-akbar-comments-after-ny-terror-attack|title=Tapper hits Fox, Hannity over 'Allahu Akbar' comments after NY terror attack|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=November 2, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102162728/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/358382-tapper-hits-fox-hannity-over-allahu-akbar-comments-after-ny-terror-attack|archive-date=2017-11-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":222\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/cnn-jake-tapper-allahu-akbar-fox-news-nyc-attack-sean-hannity-20171102.html|title=Jake Tapper feuds with Fox News, Sean Hannity over 'Allahu Akbar' comments|work=Philly.com|access-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102214409/http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/cnn-jake-tapper-allahu-akbar-fox-news-nyc-attack-sean-hannity-20171102.html|archive-date=2017-11-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Appearance at November 2018 Trump rally ===\nOn November 4, 2018, Trump's website, DonaldJTrump.com, announced in a press release that Hannity would make a \"special guest appearance\" with Trump at a midterm campaign rally the following night in Cape Girardeau, Missouri.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/04/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-rally-fox-news/index.html|title='Special Guest' Sean Hannity to appear at Trump rally|first=Brian|last=Stelter|website=[[CNN]]|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106012236/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/04/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-rally-fox-news/index.html|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The following morning, Hannity tweeted \"To be clear, I will not be on stage campaigning with the President.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/seanhannity/status/1059476042975535104|title=Sean Hannity on Twitter|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106045357/https://twitter.com/seanhannity/status/1059476042975535104|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity spoke at the president's lectern on stage at the rally, immediately mocking the \"fake news\" at the back of the auditorium, Fox News reporters among them. Several Fox News employees expressed outrage at Hannity's actions, with one stating, \"a new line was crossed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/06/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-jeanine-pirro-trump-rally/index.html|title='It disturbs me to my core': Fox News staffers express outrage over Hannity's rally appearance|first=Oliver Darcy, CNN|last=Business|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106185550/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/06/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-jeanine-pirro-trump-rally/index.html|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity later asserted that his action was not pre-planned, and Fox News stated it \"does not condone any talent participating in campaign events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/fox-news-responds-hannity-at-trump-rally-we-do-not-condone-this-unfortunate-distraction/|title=Fox News Responds to Hannity at Trump Rally: We Do 'Not Condone' This 'Unfortunate Distraction'|website=www.mediaite.com|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107054236/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/fox-news-responds-hannity-at-trump-rally-we-do-not-condone-this-unfortunate-distraction/|archive-date=2018-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Fox News host [[Jeanine Pirro]] also appeared on stage with Trump at the rally. The Trump press release was later removed from Trump's website.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>https://www.donaldjtrump.com/rallies/nov-girardeau-2018/</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\nIn 2009, Hannity said of the Iraq War, \"we were victorious in spite of the Democrats' efforts and attempts at preventing victory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2010/03/revisionism-iraq-invasion-a-great-idea-after-all/346364/|title=Revisionism: Iraq Invasion a Great Idea, After All|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=March 12, 2010|website=[[The Atlantic]]|language=en-US|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Hannity called on Trump to \"bomb the hell of out Iran\" after Iran shot down a U.S. drone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/hannity-warns-iran-youre-going-to-get-the-living-crap-bombed-out-of-you|title=Hannity Warns Iran: 'You're Going to Get the Living Crap Bombed Out of You'|last=Baragona|first=Justin|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 21, 2019|access-date=July 1, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Ukraine ===\n\nIn February 2020, [[The Daily Beast]] acquired a leaked document entitled \"Ukraine, Disinformation, & the Trump Administration\" produced by a Fox News research team. The document warned of \"disinformation\" being pushed by frequent ''Hannity'' guests, including [[Rudy Giuliani]], [[John Solomon (political commentator)|John Solomon]], [[Victoria Toensing]] and [[Joe diGenova]]. Among other criticisms, the analysis noted that on his show Hannity discussed with Toensing and diGenova an affidavit from former Ukrainian prosecutor general [[Viktor Shokin]] that accused [[Joe Biden]] of getting him fired to end an investigation into [[Burisma Holdings]], which employed Biden's son. The affidavit was drafted at the request of attorneys for Ukrainian oligarch [[Dmitry Firtash]],<ref>https://time.com/5699201/exclusive-how-a-ukrainian-oligarch-wanted-by-u-s-authorities-helped-giuliani-attack-biden/</ref> but neither Hannity nor his guests disclosed to viewers that Toensing and diGenova were among Firtash's attorneys.<ref>https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-news-internal-document-bashes-john-solomon-joe-digenova-and-rudy-giuliani-for-spreading-disinformation?ref=author</ref>\n\n=== Coronavirus outbreak ===\nIn February 2020, amid the spread of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]] to the United States, Hannity said that \"many on the left are now all rooting for corona to wreak havoc in the United States. Why? To score cheap, repulsive political points.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/business/media/coronavirus-right-wing-media.html|title=Right-Wing Media Says Virus Fears Were Whipped Up to Hurt Trump|date=2020-03-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-09|last2=Abrams|first2=Rachel|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In March 2020, he characterized the virus as a \"hoax\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/business/coronavirus-fox-news-lachlan-murdoch.html|title=Rupert Murdoch Put His Son in Charge of Fox. It Was a Dangerous Mistake.|date=2020-03-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and said that it \"may be true\" that the coronavirus outbreak was a \"fraud\" perpetrated by the \"deep state.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/us/politics/coronavirus-conservative-media.html|title=If Sean Hannity Thinks Coronavirus Panic Is a \u2018Hoax,\u2019 How Many Millions of His Listeners Do Too?|date=2020-03-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-12|last2=Grynbaum|first2=Michael M.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/sean-hannity-it-may-be-true-deep-state-using-coronavirus-manipulate-markets|title=Sean Hannity: The \u201cdeep state\u201d may be using coronavirus to manipulate markets, suppress dissent and push mandated medicines|last=Staff|first=Media Matters|website=Media Matters for America|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Later in March, as the coronavirus outbreak turned into a pandemic and President Trump declared a national emergency, Hannity started to take the virus more seriously.<ref name=\":30\" /> Hannity falsely claimed that his show had taken the coronavirus pandemic seriously all along.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/us/politics/hannity-limbaugh-trump-coronavirus.html|title=Alarm, Denial, Blame: The Pro-Trump Media\u2019s Coronavirus Distortion|date=2020-04-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/20/21186727/hannity-coronavirus-coverage-fox-news|title=Hannity claims he\u2019s \"never called the virus a hoax\" 9 days after decrying Democrats\u2019 \"new hoax\"|last=Rupar|first=Aaron|date=2020-03-20|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHannity has been married to Jill Rhodes since 1993. They have two children and live on [[Long Island]], New York.<ref name=Lipton>{{cite web|last=Lipton |first=Michael A. |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20136407,00.html |title=The (Far) Right Stuff |publisher=People.com |accessdate=September 2, 2013}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated that Hannity's annual income was $36 million.<ref name=\":28\" /> In 2014 he said he has carried a weapon \"more than half my adult life\".<ref>{{cite news |last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/piers-morgan-sean-hannity-gun-control-debate-847112/ |title=Piers Morgan Resurfaces On Cable News, Talking Guns With FNC's Sean Hannity |work=Deadline Hollywood |publisher=Penske Business Media |date=October 6, 2014 |accessdate=October 7, 2014 }}{{better source|date=October 2019}}</ref> Hannity left the [[Catholic Church]] citing \u201ctoo much institutionalized corruption.\u201d However, he has said that as he has aged his Christian faith has \"gotten stronger\" and that he needs and wants God in his life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sean Hannity says faith is 'stronger' than ever after leaving Catholic Church over 'institutionalized corruption' |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/sean-hannity-says-faith-is-stronger-than-ever-after-leaving-catholic-church-over-institutionalized-corruption.html |website=www.christianpost.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\n=== Awards and honors ===\n* Hannity received a [[Marconi Award]] in 2003 and 2007 as the Network Syndicated Personality of the Year from the [[National Association of Broadcasters]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Sean Hannity Wins 2007 Marconi Award |publisher=[[Citadel Media]] |date=September 28, 2007 |url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2007releases/092807.pdf |accessdate=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029031453/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2007releases/092807.pdf |archivedate=October 29, 2008 }}</ref>\n* In 2009, ''[[Talkers Magazine]]'' listed Hannity as #2 on their list of the 100 most important radio talk show hosts in America (with [[Rush Limbaugh]] listed as #1).<ref name=\"Talkers\">{{cite web|url=http://talkers.com/online/?p=267 |title=Heavy Hundred |date=July\u2013August 2009 |publisher=Talkers Magazine |page=267 |accessdate=August 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903062331/http://talkers.com/online/?p=267 |archivedate=September 3, 2010 }}</ref> The same magazine gave Hannity his Freedom of Speech Award in 2003.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_Nov_29/ai_n15882509 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120716032330/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_Nov_29/ai_n15882509 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 16, 2012 |title=Sean Hannity and Michael Medved Shows Come to News Talk 590 KTIE-AM |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=November 29, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>\n* In 2005, Jerry Falwell, chancellor of the evangelical [[Liberty University]], awarded Hannity an honorary degree.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jared |last=Pierce |title=Hannity to speak at Liberty |url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/communications/champion/index.cfm?PID=10609&CAID=217 |work=The Liberty Champion |date=April 17, 2007 |accessdate=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219025025/http://www.liberty.edu/academics/communications/champion/index.cfm?PID=10609&CAID=217 |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n* Hannity was inducted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]] in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/sean-hannity-gets-inducted-into-the-national-radio-hall-of-fame/347308|title=Sean Hannity Gets Inducted Into the National Radio Hall of Fame|last=Katz|first=A. J.|website=TVNewser|date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Hannity, Sean (2002). ''[[Let Freedom Ring: Winning the War of Liberty over Liberalism]]'', [[ReganBooks]], {{ISBN|0-06-051455-8}}.\n* Hannity, Sean (2004). ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism]]'', ReganBooks, {{ISBN|0-06-058251-0}}.\n* Hannity, Sean (2010). ''[[Conservative Victory: Defeating Obama's Radical Agenda]]'', [[HarperCollins|Harper Paperbacks]], {{ISBN|0-06-200305-4}}.\n\n== See also ==\n*''[[The Sean Hannity Show]]''\n*[[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hannity.com}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Sean Hannity}}\n\n{{Sean Hannity}}\n{{Fox News Personalities}}\n{{Conservatism US footer}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Conservatism|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hannity, Sean}}\n[[Category:Sean Hannity| ]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Adelphi University alumni]]\n[[Category:American broadcast news analysts]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American conservative talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of New York State politicians]]\n[[Category:Environmental skepticism]]\n[[Category:Far-right politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Centre Island, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Franklin Square, New York]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American television host, conservative political commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sean Hannity\n| nickname    = \n| image       = Sean Hannity by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg\n| caption     = Hannity in 2016\n| birth_name  = Sean Patrick Hannity<ref name=middle>{{cite web|url=http://www.hannity.com/article/about-sean-hannity/14852|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105234529/http://www.hannity.com/article/about-sean-hannity/14852|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 5, 2012|title=About Sean Hannity|last=Hannity|first=Sean Patrick|date=December 26, 2011|publisher=Hannity.com|accessdate=September 15, 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1961|12|30}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| residence   = [[Centre Island, New York]], U.S.<ref>[https://variety.com/2014/dirt/real-estalker/is-sean-hannity-saying-bye-bye-to-new-york-1201237414/ Is Sean Hannity Saying Bye-Bye To New York | Variety] Retrieved September 5, 2014.</ref>\n| nationality = American\n| education   = [[New York University]]<br />[[University of California, Santa Barbara|UC Santa Barbara]]<br />[[Adelphi University]]<br />(no degrees awarded)\n| occupation  = Radio host, television host, political commentator, author\n| employer    = [[Premiere Networks]], [[Fox News Channel]]\n| known_for   = [[Conservative]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.salon.com/2013/06/19/sean_hannity_im_not_a_republican | title = Sean Hannity: \"I'm not a Republican\" | publisher = salon.com| date = 2013-06-19 }}</ref> [[Political commentator|political commentary]]\n| net_worth   = \n| party       = [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative]]\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Jill Rhodes|1993}}\n| partner     = \n| children    = 2\n| relatives   = \n| website     = {{URL|hannity.com}}\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n\n'''Sean Patrick Hannity''' (born December 30, 1961) is an American [[talk show]] host and conservative [[political commentator]]. Hannity is the host of ''[[The Sean Hannity Show]]'', a [[radio syndication|nationally syndicated]] talk radio show. He also hosts a commentary program, ''[[Hannity]]'', on [[Fox News]].\n\nHannity worked as a general contractor and volunteered as a talk show host at [[UC Santa Barbara]] in 1989. He later joined [[WVNN (AM)|WVNN]] in [[Athens, Alabama]] and shortly afterward, [[WGST]] in [[Atlanta]]. After leaving WGST, he worked at [[WABC (AM)|WABC]] in New York until 2013. Since 2014, Hannity has worked at [[WOR (AM)|WOR]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1996, Hannity and [[Alan Colmes]] co-hosted ''[[Hannity & Colmes]]'' on [[Fox News|Fox]].  After Colmes announced his departure in January 2008, Hannity merged the ''Hannity & Colmes'' show into ''[[Hannity]]''. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nHannity has received several awards and honors, including an honorary degree from [[Liberty University]]. He has written three books: ''[[Let Freedom Ring: Winning the War of Liberty over Liberalism]]''; ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism]]''; and ''[[Conservative Victory: Defeating Obama's Radical Agenda]]''.\n\nHannity has promoted [[conspiracy theories]], such as [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|Birtherism]], claims that the [[murder of Seth Rich]] was part of a conspiracy, and falsehoods about [[Hillary Clinton]]'s health. Hannity was an early supporter of [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]. Since Trump's election, Hannity has often acted as a mouthpiece for Trump's messaging, criticizing the media, attacking the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|special counsel inquiry]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/fox-news-hannity-carlson-ingraham-attack-mueller-hes-sleazy-and-dishonest-1439017|title=Fox News' Hannity, Carlson, Ingraham attack Mueller: He's a \"sleazy and dishonest\" \"mean girl\" who's \"full of crap\"|last=EDT|first=Christina Zhao On 5/30/19 at 1:37 AM|date=2019-05-30|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> and discouraging social distancing amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/us/politics/michael-savage-trump-coronavirus.html|title=Why Michael Savage Is Blasting Hannity and the Right-Wing Media on the Virus|date=2020-04-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He reportedly speaks to the president on the phone most weeknights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5|title=Trump reportedly talks to Sean Hannity most nights before bed|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|website=Business Insider}}</ref> Hannity has spoken at the president's lectern during a Trump rally and White House advisors have characterized him as the \"shadow\" chief-of-staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hannitys-rising-role-in-trumps-world-he-basically-has-a-desk-in-the-place/2018/04/17/e2483018-4260-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html|title=Hannity's rising role in Trump's world: 'He basically has a desk in the place'|website=Washington Post|accessdate=August 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2013/06/19/sean_hannity_im_not_a_republican/|title=Sean Hannity: \"I'm not a Republican\"|date=2013-06-19|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> According to ''[[Forbes]]'', by 2018 Hannity had become one of the most-watched hosts in cable news and most-listened-to hosts in talk radio due to his closeness and access to President Donald Trump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5|title=Trump reportedly talks to Sean Hannity most nights before bed|last=Cranley|first=Ellen|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHannity was born in New York City, New York, the son of Lillian (Flynn) and Hugh Hannity.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=njdbBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT33|title=Let Freedom Ring|work=google.ca|isbn=9780060514556|last1=Hannity|first1=Sean|date=2002-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2018/nov/06/sean-hannity/hannity-vows-not-appear-onstage-trump-rally-then-h/|title=PolitiFact - Sean Hannity vows not to appear onstage at Trump rally, then he does|last=Washington|first=District of Columbia 1100 Connecticut Ave NW Suite 1300B|last2=Dc 20036|website=@politifact|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Lillian worked as a stenographer and a corrections officer at a county jail and Hugh was a family-court officer.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|title=How Far Will Sean Hannity Go?|last=Shaer|first=Matthew|date=November 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 29, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129003856/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|url-status=live|archive-date=November 29, 2017}}</ref> He is the youngest of four siblings.<ref name=\":24\" /> All his grandparents immigrated to the United States from [[Ireland]]. He grew up in [[Franklin Square, New York]].<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nHannity attended Sacred Heart Seminary in [[Hempstead (village), New York|Hempstead, New York]], during his middle school years and [[St. Pius X Preparatory Seminary]] high school in [[Uniondale, New York]].<ref>Hannity, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Bco44op7ArEC Let Freedom Ring]'', p. 49.</ref> He attended [[New York University]], [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UC Santa Barbara]], and [[Adelphi University]], but did not graduate.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1572959/Sean-Hannity|title=Sean Hannity|work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"rightfielder\">{{cite news | url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/99494805.html?dids=99494805:99494805&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jan+14%2C+2002&author=Howard+Kurtz&pub=The+Washington+Post&edition=&startpage=C.01&desc=Radio%27s+New+Right-Fielder%3B+For+Conservative+Hannity%2C+Liberal+Praise | title=Radio's New Right-Fielder |work=Washington Post | date=January 14, 2002 | first=Howard | last=Kurtz|accessdate = November 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Interview of the Vice President Dick Cheney by Sean Hannity.jpg|thumb|left|Interviewing Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] in 2006]]\n[[File:Vice President Pence at CPAC (49596293561).jpg|thumb|left|Interviewing Vice President [[Mike Pence]] in 2020]]\nIn 1982, Hannity started a house-painting business and a few years later, worked as a building contractor in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref name=Lipton /> He hosted his first talk radio show in 1989 at the volunteer college station at [[UC Santa Barbara]], [[KCSB-FM]], while working as a general contractor. The show aired for 40 hours of air time.<ref name=\"wdbo_bio\">{{cite web |url=http://wdbo.com/hannity/biography.html |title=Hannity Bio |accessdate=October 13, 2008 |publisher=[[The Sean Hannity Show]] at [[WDBO (AM)|WDBO]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sean Hannity: Construction Worker, Union Member, Sack of Sh*t. |url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2012/12/19/1171909/-Sean-Hannity-Construction-Worker-Union-Member-Sack-of-Sh-t |website=dailykos.com |publisher=Kos Media, LLC |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Regarding his first show, he said, \"I wasn't good at it. I was terrible.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='Hannitization' Of America |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/05/21/sunday/main619045.shtml |publisher=CBS News |date=May 23, 2004 |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Radio ===\nHannity's weekly show on KCSB was canceled after less than a year after a controversy. During two shows, gay and lesbian rights were discussed in what was considered to be a contentious manner. (See [[#LGBT rights|LGBT issues]] below.) The university board that governed the station later reversed its decision after a campaign conducted on Hannity's behalf by the Santa Barbara chapter of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] argued that the station had discriminated against Hannity's First Amendment rights. When the station refused to issue Hannity a public apology and more airtime, he did not return to KCSB.<ref name=\"www.fair.org\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Rendall |title=An Aggressive Conservative vs. a 'Liberal to be Determined' |url=http://fair.org/home/an-aggressive-conservative-vs-a-quotliberal-to-be-determinedquot/ |work=Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting |date=November\u2013December 2003 |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":6\"/>\n\nAfter leaving KCSB, Hannity placed an ad in radio publications, presenting himself as \"the most talked about college radio host in America.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Radio station [[WVNN (AM)|WVNN]] in [[Athens, Alabama]] (part of the [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]] media market), then hired him to be the afternoon talk show host.<ref name=\"wdbo_bio\"/> From Huntsville, he moved to [[WGST]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]] in 1992, filling the slot vacated by [[Neal Boortz]], who had moved to competing station [[WSB (AM)|WSB]]. In September 1996, Fox News co-founder [[Roger Ailes]] hired the then relatively unknown Hannity to host a television program under the working title ''Hannity and LTBD'' (\"liberal to be determined\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alan.com/staff/alan.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061109203543/http://www.alan.com/staff/alan.htm|title=Alan Colmes|archivedate=November 9, 2006|work=alan.com}}</ref> [[Alan Colmes]] was then hired to co-host and the show debuted as ''[[Hannity & Colmes]]''.\n\nLater that year, Hannity left WGST for New York, where WABC had him substitute for their afternoon [[drive time]] host during Christmas week. In January 1997, WABC put Hannity on the air full-time, giving him the late-night time slot. WABC then moved Hannity to the same drive-time slot he had filled temporarily a little more than a year earlier. Hannity was on WABC's afternoon time slot from January 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wabcradio.com/showdj.asp?DJID=1725 |title=Sean Hannity is a multi-media superstar, spending four hours a day every day reaching out to millions of Americans on radio, television and internet |accessdate=October 13, 2008 |publisher=[[WABC (AM)|WABC]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012131347/http://www.wabcradio.com/showdj.asp?DJID=1725 |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn their 2007 book ''Common Ground: How to Stop the Partisan War That Is Destroying America'', conservative [[Cal Thomas]] and liberal [[Bob Beckel]] describe Hannity as a leader of the pack among broadcasting political polarizers, which following [[James Q. Wilson]] they define as those who have \"an intense commitment to a candidate, a culture, or an ideology that sets people in one group definitively apart from people in another, rival group.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Cal |last=Thomas |authorlink=Cal Thomas |author2=Bob Beckel |title=Common Ground: How to Stop the Partisan War That Is Destroying America |publisher=William Morrow |location=New York |year=2007 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/commongroundhowt00calt_0/page/3 3\u20136] |isbn=978-0-06-123634-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/commongroundhowt00calt_0/page/3 }}</ref> The WABC slot continued until the end of 2013. Since January 2014, Hannity has hosted the 3\u20136 p.m. time slot on WOR in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/wor-ends-era-new-york-radio-article-1.1542179|title=WOR ends an era in New York radio and officially kicks off the new coming war with rival WABC|first=David|last=Hinckley|publisher=New York Daily News|date=December 6, 2013|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Sean Hannity by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|right|thumb|Speaking at the 2015 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in February 2015]]\n\nHannity's radio program is a conservative political talk show that features Hannity's opinions and ideology related to current issues and politicians. ''The Sean Hannity Show'' began national syndication on September 10, 2001, on over 500 stations nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/090806.pdf |title=Canon Communications LLC: Home |publisher=Affiliates.abcradionetworks.com |accessdate=August 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326002949/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/090806.pdf |archivedate=March 26, 2009 }}</ref> In 2004, Hannity signed a $25-million five-year contract extension with ABC Radio (now [[Citadel Media]]) to continue the show until 2009.<ref name=\"contract\">{{cite web |url=http://wsgw.com/skin/blurb.php?sectionId=182&contentId=116798 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811021712/http://wsgw.com/skin/blurb.php?sectionId=182&contentId=116798 |archivedate=August 11, 2007 |title=Sean Hannity Profile |publisher=WSGW |year=2006 |accessdate=November 5, 2008}}</ref> The program was made available via [[American Forces Network|Armed Forces Radio Network]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/010306.pdf |title=Canon Communications LLC: Home |publisher=Affiliates.abcradionetworks.com |accessdate=August 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326002948/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2006releases/010306.pdf |archivedate=March 26, 2009 }}</ref> In June 2007, ABC Radio was sold to [[Citadel Communications]]<ref>{{cite press release |title=Disney and Citadel Announce Completion of ABC Radio Merger |publisher=The Walt Disney Company |date=June 12, 2007 |url=http://corporate.disney.go.com/news/corporate/2007/2007_0613_abcradiomerger.html |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref> and in the summer of 2008, Hannity was signed for a $100- million five-year contract.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Sean Hannity Gets $100 Million Deal |publisher=Huff Post Media |date=July 21, 2008 |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/07/21/sean-hannity-gets-100-mil_n_114026.html |accessdate=May 9, 2012}}</ref> As of March 2018, the program is heard by over 13.5 million listeners a week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talkers.com/top-talk-audiences/ |title=The Top Talk Radio Audiences | date= March 2018 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 |publisher=Talkers Magazine }}</ref> Hannity was ranked No.{{nbsp}}2 in ''Talker Magazine''<nowiki/>'s 2017 Heavy Hundred<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.talkers.com/2017-talkers-heavy-hundred-1-25/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926170941/http://www.talkers.com/2017-talkers-heavy-hundred-1-25/ | archive-date=September 26, 2017 | title=2017 TALKERS Heavy Hundred 1-25 | work=Talkers Magazine | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all | date=2017-05-22 }}</ref> and was listed as No.{{nbsp}}72 on ''Forbes''<nowiki/>' \"Celebrity 100\" list in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/person/h/sean-hannity.html|title=Sean Hannity {{!}} Fox News|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, [[Clear Channel Communications]] signed a groupwide three-year extension with Hannity on over 80 stations.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Clear Channel Radio Renews Sean Hannity Through 2010 |publisher=[[Clear Channel Communications]] |date=September 28, 2006 |url=http://www.clearchannel.com/Radio/PressRelease.aspx?PressReleaseID=1768 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004045741/http://www.clearchannel.com/Radio/PressRelease.aspx?PressReleaseID=1768 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 4, 2006 |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}\n</ref> The largest stations in the group deal included [[KTRH]] Houston, [[KFYI]] Phoenix, [[WPGB]] Pittsburgh, [[WKRC (AM)|WKRC]] Cincinnati, [[WOOD (AM)|WOOD]] Grand Rapids, [[WFLA (AM)|WFLA]] Tampa, [[WOAI (AM)|WOAI]] San Antonio, [[WLAC]] Nashville, and [[WREC]] Memphis.\n\nHannity signed a long-term contract to remain with Premiere Networks in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Byers|first=Dylan|title=Hannity signs 'long-term' contract|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/09/hannity-signs-longterm-premiere-contract-172472.html?hp=l7|publisher=Politico|accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of 2014, Hannity signed contracts to air on several [[Salem Communications]] stations including [[WDTK]] Detroit, [[WIND (AM)|WIND]] Chicago, [[WQOF|WWRC]] Washington, D.C., and [[KSKY]] Dallas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boyce|first=Phil|title=Sean Hannity Moves to WDTK-AM 1400 in Detroit|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/sean-hannity-moves-to-wdtk-am-1400-in-detroit-2014-01-14|publisher=MarketWatch|accessdate=January 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n{{See also|Hannity & Colmes|Hannity's America|Hannity}}\n\nHannity was a co-host of ''Hannity & Colmes'', an American political \"point-counterpoint\"-style television program on the Fox News Channel featuring Hannity and [[Alan Colmes]] as co-hosts. Hannity presented the conservative point of view with Colmes providing the liberal viewpoint.\n\nHannity said if the Catholic Church were to [[excommunication|excommunicate]] him over his support for contraception he would join [[Jerry Falwell]]'s [[Thomas Road Baptist Church]].<ref>Royal, Robert. \"Sean and Rudy's excellent adventures in moral theology.\" ''National Catholic Reporter''; March 30, 2007, Vol. 43 Issue 22, p. 19-19, 2/3p.</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Hannity began a new Sunday night television show on Fox News, ''[[Hannity's America]]''.\n\nIn November 2008, Colmes announced his departure from ''Hannity & Colmes''. After the show's final broadcast on January 9, 2009, Hannity took over the time slot with his own new show, ''[[Hannity]]'', which has a format similar to ''Hannity's America''.\n\n=== Books ===\nHannity is the author of three books. ''[[Let Freedom Ring: Winning the War of Liberty over Liberalism]]'' was published in 2002, and ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism]]'' was published in 2004 through [[ReganBooks]]. Both these books reached the nonfiction ''New York Times'' bestseller list, the second of which stayed there for five weeks.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">''Contemporary Authors Online'', Thomson Gale, 2005.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/abcradio/seanhannitybio.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=August 7, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807124253/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/abcradio/seanhannitybio.pdf|archivedate=August 7, 2007}}</ref> Hannity has said he is too busy to write many books,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> and dictated a lot of his own two books into a tape recorder while driving in to do his radio show.<ref>{{cite news |last=Poniewozik |first=James |author2=Sean Hannity |date=November 5, 2002 |title=10 Questions for Sean Hannity |work=Time |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1101021111-386927,00.html |accessdate=October 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHannity wrote his third book, ''[[Conservative Victory: Defeating Obama's Radical Agenda]]'', which was released by [[HarperCollins]] in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2010/02/sean-hannity-to-write-book-on-defeating-obama-democrats/1 | work=USA Today | title=Sean Hannity writes book on defeating Obama, Democrats | date=February 16, 2010 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> The book became Hannity's third ''New York Times'' Bestseller.<ref name=\"NYT 2010\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/books/bestseller/bestpapernonfiction.html?ref=bestseller|title=NYT Best Sellers \u2013 Paperback Nonfiction|date=April 15, 2010|work=NY Times|accessdate=April 18, 2010|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler}}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|FreedomConcerts}}\n\n=== Freedom Concerts ===\nFrom 2003 until 2010, Hannity hosted [[country music]]-themed \"Freedom Concerts\" to raise money for charity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/hannity-bringing-freedom-concert-back-flags-article-1.560657 |title=Hannity Bringing 'Freedom' Concert to Six Flags |date=July 20, 2006 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |accessdate=August 23, 2009 }}</ref> In 2010, conservative blogger [[Debbie Schlussel]] wrote that only a small percentage of the money raised by the concerts goes to the target charity, [[Oliver North#Freedom Alliance|Freedom Alliance]].<ref name=TheWeek100401>{{cite web | url=https://theweek.com/articles/495654/sean-hannitys-charity-scam | title=Sean Hannity's charity 'scam' | work=[[The Week]] | date=April 1, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> The [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] (CREW) filed complaints with the [[Federal Trade Commission]] (FTC) and the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS), also in 2010. The FTC complaint alleges that Hannity was \"falsely promoting that all concert proceeds would be donated to a scholarship fund for the children of those killed or wounded in war.\"<ref name=Dimascio>{{cite web | url=https://www.politico.com/story/2010/03/crew-flags-hannity-concert-series-035160 | title=CREW flags Hannity concert series | work=[[Politico]] | date=March 29, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Dimascio | first=Jen}}</ref> The complaint filed with the IRS claims that Freedom Alliance has violated its [[501(c)3]] charity status.<ref name=Sheppard>{{cite web | url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/03/crew-sean-hannity-freedom-concert-freedom-alliance/ | title=Hannity's Charity Under Fire | work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | date=March 29, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Sheppard | first=Kate}}</ref><ref name=Scallon>{{cite web | url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/2010/03/20/freedom-scam/ | title=Freedom Scam? | work=[[The American Conservative]] | date=March 20, 2010 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Scallon | first=Sean}}</ref> The concerts stopped around the same year.<ref name=Fahrenthold>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/06/01/hannity-defended-trumps-handling-of-donations-to-veterans-groups-he-didnt-mention-his-personal-ties-to-one-of-them/?noredirect=on | title=Hannity defended Trump's handling of donations to veterans groups. He didn't mention his personal ties to one of them. | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=June 1, 2016 | accessdate=April 23, 2018 | last=Fahrenthold | first=David}}</ref>\n\n=== Other activities ===\nHannity [[Executive producer|executive produced]] and appeared in the 2017 film ''[[Let There Be Light (2017 film)|Let There Be Light]]'', which also stars [[Kevin Sorbo]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-let-there-be-light-review-20171026-story.html |title= Review: Sean Hannity and Kevin Sorbo join forces in the Christian reckoning drama 'Let There Be Light' |author= Gary Goldstein |date= October 26, 2017 |work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate= October 27, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2018 Hannity owned at least 877 residential properties, which were bought for nearly $89 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/media/2018/apr/22/michael-cohen-sean-hannity-property-real-estate-ben-carson-hud|title=Michael Cohen case shines light on Sean Hannity's property empire|last=Swaine|first=Jon|date=April 23, 2018|work=the Guardian|access-date=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gstalter |first1=Morgan |title=Sean Hannity linked to shell companies that spent $90M on property: report |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/384366-hannity-hud-shell-companies-report |website=thehill.com |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> He purchased some of the homes with the help of loans from [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD)]] and most are in working class neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matt Pearce |first1=Jenny Jarvie and |title=In Georgia, Sean Hannity is just another landlord hiking the rent |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-hannity-landlord-20180427-story.html |website=www.latimes.com |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref> His [[property management|property manager]]s have taken an aggressive management approach with a much higher than average eviction rate. The ''[[Washington Post]]'' reported that his property management team has used eviction proceedings both to remove tenants and to generate revenue. His property managers have claimed that Sean Hannity has no active role in the management of the more than 1,000 properties he has a stake in.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shawn Boburg |first1=Aaron C. Davis and |title=At Sean Hannity properties in working-class areas, an aggressive approach to rent collection |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/at-hannitys-properties-in-low-income-areas-an-aggressive-approach-to-rent-collection/2018/05/10/964be4a2-4eea-11e8-84a0-458a1aa9ac0a_story.html |website=www.washingtonpost.com |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political commentary, controversies, and criticism ==\nAccording to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Hannity \"repeatedly embraces storylines that prove to be inaccurate\" and takes positions that change over time.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/the-making-of-sean-hannity-how-a-long-island-kid-learned-to-channel-red-state-rage/2017/10/09/540cfc38-8821-11e7-961d-2f373b3977ee_story.html|title=The making of Sean Hannity: How a Long Island kid learned to channel red-state rage|last=Fisher|first=Marc|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=October 12, 2017|date=October 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012202547/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/the-making-of-sean-hannity-how-a-long-island-kid-learned-to-channel-red-state-rage/2017/10/09/540cfc38-8821-11e7-961d-2f373b3977ee_story.html|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In the opinion of ''[[The New York Times]]'', Hannity is \"barreling headfirst into the murky territory between opinion and out-and-out conspiracy theorism.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> Hannity often promotes [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] without explicitly endorsing them, unlike [[Alex Jones]]; ''The New York Times'' wrote that this \"has the effect of nourishing the more wild-eyed beliefs of his fans while providing Hannity a degree of plausible deniability.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' wrote in 2019 that Hannity had \"[spewed] baseless conspiracy theories with impunity.\"<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/03/11/the-making-of-the-fox-news-white-house|title=The Making of the Fox News White House|last=Mayer|first=Jane|date=2019-03-04|access-date=2019-03-04|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Bush years, Hannity \"loyally supported the president's policies.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> During the Obama administration, Hannity \"leaned more heavily on stories he believed were being given short shrift by the 'liberal media' \u2014 stories about where Obama was born, and who deserved blame for the attack on the U.S. compound in Benghazi, Libya.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> In 2017, ''The Washington Post'' wrote that \"what Hannity has stood for \u2014 at least for the past couple of years \u2014 is Trump.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Birtherism ===\nAlthough Hannity said he believed President Obama was born in the United States, [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|to answer queries on Obama's citizenship]] he repeatedly called on Obama to release his birth certificate.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/top-republican-try-to-scotch-birther-theories/2011/04/19/AFsrhU8D_story.html|title=Top Republicans try to scotch birther theories|website=Washington Post|access-date=February 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222194249/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/top-republican-try-to-scotch-birther-theories/2011/04/19/AFsrhU8D_story.html|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/28/business/media/28birth.html|title='Birthers' Fanned Flames of Conspiracy for Years|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=April 27, 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=February 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170405122718/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/28/business/media/28birth.html|archive-date=2017-04-05|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity described the circumstances regarding Obama's birth certificate as \"odd\".<ref name=\":29\" /> Hannity also defended and promoted those who questioned Obama's citizenship of the United States, such as Donald Trump. Hannity invited Trump to his show at the same time that Trump was a leader in the birther movement; during an interview with Hannity, Trump said Obama \"could have easily have come from Kenya, or someplace.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> To which Hannity responded, \"The issue could go away in a minute. Just show the certificate.\"<ref name=\":24\" /> After Obama in 2008 produced what the state of Hawaii certified as a legitimate birth certificate, Hannity kept calling on Obama to release his birth certificate, asking, if there was a birth certificate, why did he not \"just produce it and we move on?\"<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/02/us/02iht-letter02.html|title=A Lie Is Born, and We All Know Where|last=News|first=Albert R. Hunt {{!}} Bloomberg|date=May 1, 2011|access-date=February 21, 2017|issn=0362-4331|newspaper=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222113610/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/02/us/02iht-letter02.html|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2016, Hannity offered to purchase a one-way ticket to Kenya for Obama, harking back to the controversy.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hannity-obama-kenya-birthers-230317|title=Hannity offers to pay for Obama to go to Kenya|access-date=February 21, 2017|newspaper=POLITICO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222111657/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hannity-obama-kenya-birthers-230317|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 presidential campaign ===\n==== Candidacy of Donald Trump ====\n[[File:Donald Trump & Sean Hannity (16677778952).jpg|thumb|Hannity with [[Donald Trump]] in 2015]]\n\nHannity is known for his pro-Trump coverage.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/09/fox-news-trump-presidency-244712 |title= Fox, facing new competitors, clings tighter to Trump |work= Politico |access-date= November 9, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171109114104/https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/09/fox-news-trump-presidency-244712 |archive-date= 2017-11-09 |url-status= live }}</ref> According to ''The Washington Post'', \"Hannity's comeback coincided with his early, eager embrace of his fellow New Yorker\"{{nbsp}}... Trump attacked the Gold Star father, and Hannity stood by him. Trump went after a federal judge of Mexican descent, and Hannity backed him. After the [[Donald Trump Access Hollywood tape|''Access Hollywood'' tape]] emerged of Trump making lewd comments about inappropriate sexual behaviour towards women, Hannity continued to defend him: '[[King David]] had 500 concubines, for crying out loud'.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> After the inauguration, the first interview the new president gave to a cable news channel was conducted by Hannity.<ref name=\":6\" /> Hannity additionally defended the Trump administration's false claim that Trump's inauguration crowd was the biggest ever.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHannity has been criticized as being overly favorable to the candidacy of [[Donald Trump]], and granting Trump more airtime than other presidential candidates during the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries|2016 primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |title=How Sean Hannity Became Influential In Conservative Media And Politics |url=https://www.tpr.org/post/how-sean-hannity-became-influential-conservative-media-and-politics |website=tpr.org |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> Hannity, for instance, let Trump promote the false claim that [[Rafael Cruz]], father of Trump's rival presidential candidate [[Ted Cruz]], was involved in the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|John F. Kennedy assassination]].<ref name=\":6\" /> He admitted to favouring [[Republican Party (U.S.)|Republican]] candidates, though without indicating a preference for Donald Trump over Ted Cruz.<ref name=\"Byers2016\">{{Citation|last=Byers|first=Dylan | date = May 2, 2016 | url = http://money.cnn.com/2016/05/02/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-profile/ | title = Sean Hannity embraces Donald Trump, without apology | work = CNN | access-date = 2019-02-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180716025338/https://money.cnn.com/2016/05/02/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-profile/ | archive-date = 2018-07-16 | url-status = live }}.</ref> According to [[Dylan Byers]] of [[CNN]], Hannity during interviews \"frequently cites areas where he agrees with Trump, or where he thinks Trump was right about something, then asks him to expand on it\", and \"often ignores or defends Trump from criticism.\"<ref name=\"Byers2016\" />\n\nTensions between Cruz and Hannity appeared to reach a boiling point during a contentious April 2016 radio interview, during which Cruz implied Hannity was a \"hard-core Donald Trump supporter\" and Hannity responded by accusing Cruz of \"throw[ing] this in my face\" every time he asked a \"legitimate question\".<ref>{{Citation | date = April 19, 2016 | url = http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/19/ted-cruz-and-sean-hannity-finally-duke-it-out.html | title = Ted Cruz and Sean Hannity Finally Duke It Out | newspaper = The Daily Beast | last1 = Kirell | first1 = Andrew | access-date = 2019-02-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161222144129/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/19/ted-cruz-and-sean-hannity-finally-duke-it-out.html | archive-date = 2016-12-22 | url-status = live }}.</ref> [[Jim Rutenberg]] commented in August 2016 that Hannity is \"not only Mr. Trump's biggest media booster; he also veers into the role of adviser,\" citing sources who said Hannity spent months offering suggestions to Trump and his campaign on strategy and messaging. Hannity responded to the report by saying, \"I'm not hiding the fact that I want Donald Trump to be the next President of the United States.{{nbsp}}... I never claimed to be a journalist.\"<ref name=\"NYT08212016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/22/business/media/sean-hannity-turns-adviser-in-the-service-of-donald-trump.html |title= Sean Hannity Turns Adviser in the Service of Donald Trump |last= Rutenberg |first= Jim |date= August 21, 2016 |work= The NY times |access-date= 2019-02-20 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190114150953/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/22/business/media/sean-hannity-turns-adviser-in-the-service-of-donald-trump.html |archive-date= 2019-01-14 |url-status= live }}</ref> (In an article published in December 2017, Hannity said \"I'm a journalist. But I'm an [[advocacy journalism|advocacy journalist]], or an opinion journalist.\")<ref name=\":24\"/> Hannity has feuded with several conservatives who oppose Trump, including ''[[National Review]]''{{'}}s [[Jonah Goldberg]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Gass|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-twitter-war-227819|title=Hannity and National Review's Jonah Goldberg get into epic Twitter battle|work=Politico|date=September 7, 2016|accessdate=September 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005180905/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/09/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-twitter-war-227819|archive-date=2016-10-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Oliver |last= Darcy |url= http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-trump-2016-9 |title= Sean Hannity and National Review's Jonah Goldberg get into heated Twitter fight over Donald Trump |work= Business Insider |date= September 7, 2016 |accessdate= September 29, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160909160730/http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-jonah-goldberg-trump-2016-9 |archive-date= 2016-09-09 |url-status= live }}</ref> ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' foreign affairs columnist [[Bret Stephens]],<ref>{{cite web |first= Nick |last= Gass |url= http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/sean-hannity-bret-stephens-feud-226714 |title= Hannity to WSJ editor: If Clinton wins, 'I will hold a--holes like you accountable' |work= [[Politico]] |date= August 5, 2016 |accessdate= September 29, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041003/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/sean-hannity-bret-stephens-feud-226714 |archive-date= 2016-09-28 |url-status= live }}</ref> and ''National Review'' editor [[Rich Lowry]].<ref>{{cite web |first= Paulina |last= Firozi |url= http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/295312-hannity-feuds-with-national-review-editor-on-twitter |title= Hannity feuds with National Review editor on Twitter |work= The Hill |date= September 10, 2016 |accessdate= September 29, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160918070533/http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/295312-hannity-feuds-with-national-review-editor-on-twitter |archive-date= 2016-09-18 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==== Conspiracy theories about Hillary Clinton ====\nDuring the 2016 presidential election, Hannity periodically promoted conspiracy theories regarding [[Hillary Clinton]] and the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\">{{Cite web|author=David Weigel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/11/in-prime-time-sean-hannity-carries-out-a-clinton-medical-investigation/|title=In prime time, Sean Hannity carries out a Clinton medical 'investigation'|website=Washington Post|date=August 11, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209235320/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/11/in-prime-time-sean-hannity-carries-out-a-clinton-medical-investigation/|archive-date=2019-02-09|url-status=live|author-link=David Weigel}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|author=Rebecca Morin|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/hannity-responds-to-stelter-criticism-on-twitter-226773|title=Hannity, Stelter swap criticism over conspiracy theories|date=August 7, 2016|newspaper=Politico|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109204838/https://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/hannity-responds-to-stelter-criticism-on-twitter-226773|archive-date=2018-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/8/18/12505078/hillary-clinton-health-stroke-conspiracy-fake|title=Here's how we know the bonkers conspiracy theory about Hillary Clinton's health is catching on|last=Golshan|first=Tara|date=August 18, 2016|website=Vox|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106112555/https://www.vox.com/2016/8/18/12505078/hillary-clinton-health-stroke-conspiracy-fake|archive-date=2019-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/20/the-seth-rich-conspiracy-shows-how-fake-news-still-works/|title=Analysis {{!}} The Seth Rich conspiracy shows how fake news still works|work=[[Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=May 20, 2017|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520234833/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/20/the-seth-rich-conspiracy-shows-how-fake-news-still-works/|archive-date=2017-05-20|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity repeatedly claimed that Clinton had very serious medical problems and that the media was covering them up.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /><ref>{{Cite web|first=Susan|last=Milligan|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-08-15/hillarys-health-conspiracy-or-concern|title=Hillary's Health: Conspiracy or Concern?|work=U.S. News & World Report|date=August 15, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229204101/https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-08-15/hillarys-health-conspiracy-or-concern|archive-date=2018-12-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Brian|last=Stelter|title=Sean Hannity peddling debunked Clinton story|url=http://edition.cnn.com/videos/tv/2016/08/14/hannity-pushes-debunked-clinton-theory.cnn|work=Reliable Sources with Brian Stelter|publisher=CNN|date=August 14, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925121620/https://edition.cnn.com/videos/tv/2016/08/14/hannity-pushes-debunked-clinton-theory.cnn|archive-date=2018-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref> He misrepresented photos of Clinton to give the impression that she had secret medical problems.<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /><ref name=\":52\" /> He shared a photo from the fringe news site [[The Gateway Pundit|Gateway Pundit]] and falsely claimed that it showed her Secret Service agent holding a diazepam pen intended to treat seizures, when he in fact was holding a small flashlight.<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /> He booked doctors on his show to discuss Clinton's health; although these people had never personally examined Clinton, they made alarmist statements about her state of health which turned out to be false.<ref name=\"WeigelPrimeTime\" /><ref name=\":52\" /> At one point, Hannity promoted an unsubstantiated report that Clinton had been drunk at a rally; at another point, he suggested that Clinton was drunk and that her campaign needed to \"sober her up\".<ref>{{Cite news|first=Oliver|last=Darcy|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-hillary-clinton-conspiracy-drunk-2016-10?r=US&IR=T|title=Sean Hannity promotes conspiracy theory Clinton was drunk at rally, then claims he didn't mean to do so|work=Business Insider|date=October 31, 2016|language=en|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224222329/https://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-hillary-clinton-conspiracy-drunk-2016-10?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2018-12-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Murder of Seth Rich conspiracy theories ====\nIn May 2017, Hannity became a prominent promoter of the conspiracy theory that Hillary Clinton and the Democratic Party had a [[Murder of Seth Rich|DNC staffer killed]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/fox-news-conspiracy-theory-wikileaks-seth-rich_us_591b493ee4b07d5f6ba6d027|title=Fox Pushes WikiLeaks Murder Conspiracy From Man Who Warned Of Armed Lesbian Pedophiles|last=Waldron|first=Travis|date=May 16, 2017|work=Huffington Post|access-date=May 16, 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517054751/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/fox-news-conspiracy-theory-wikileaks-seth-rich_us_591b493ee4b07d5f6ba6d027|archive-date=2017-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forward.com/fast-forward/372104/sean-hannity-im-looking-into-seth-richs-suspicious-death/|title=Sean Hannity: I'm 'Looking Into' Seth Rich's 'Suspicious' Death|work=The Forward|access-date=May 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516235150/http://forward.com/fast-forward/372104/sean-hannity-im-looking-into-seth-richs-suspicious-death/|archive-date=2017-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/charliewarzel/how-the-pro-trump-media-responds-to-a-crisis-in-just-4-steps|title=How The Pro-Trump Media Responds To A Crisis In Just 4 Steps|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=May 17, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517052108/https://www.buzzfeed.com/charliewarzel/how-the-pro-trump-media-responds-to-a-crisis-in-just-4-steps|archive-date=2017-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-1.789915|title=Explained // 'Alt-right' Using Cruel Seth Rich Conspiracy Theory to Deflect From Trump's Russia Scandal|last=Sommer|first=Allison Kaplan|date=May 17, 2017|work=Haaretz|access-date=May 17, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517173820/http://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-1.789915|archive-date=2017-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/22/the-seth-rich-conspiracys-biggest-myths-explained/|title=Analysis {{!}} The Seth Rich conspiracy's biggest myths, explained|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523013951/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/05/22/the-seth-rich-conspiracys-biggest-myths-explained/|archive-date=2017-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Shortly afterward, he faced backlash from both left- and right-wing sources and lost several advertisers, including [[Crowne Plaza Hotels]], [[Cars.com]], Leesa Mattress, [[USAA]], [[Peloton]] and [[Casper Sleep]] deciding to pull their marketing from his program on Fox News.<ref name=\"baggaglio\">{{citation|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hannity-advertisers-fox-20170525-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 25, 2017|title=Sean Hannity goes on vacation as advertisers drop out of his show|last=Battaglio|first=Stephen|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907022655/http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hannity-advertisers-fox-20170525-story.html|archive-date=2018-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"paulbond\">{{citation|first=Paul|last=Bond|date=May 25, 2017|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/more-advertisers-pressuring-fox-news-sean-hannity-1007805|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|title=Several advertisers have pulled TV spots over the 'Hannity' host's reporting on Seth Rich, while conservatives are mounting a counter-boycott.|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613183900/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/more-advertisers-pressuring-fox-news-sean-hannity-1007805|archive-date=2018-06-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Friedersdorf, Conor. [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/05/sean-hannity/528144/ \"How Conservatives Awoke to the Dangers of Sean Hannity.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114012501/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/05/sean-hannity/528144/ |date=2019-01-14 }} ''The Atlantic''. May 30, 2017.</ref> However, USAA decided to return to the show shortly after following a negative outcry against its decision to pull out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2017/05/30/usaa-says-reinstate-ads-fox-news-channels-hannity/102325194/|title=USAA says it will reinstate ads on Fox News Channel's 'Hannity'|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716000023/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2017/05/30/usaa-says-reinstate-ads-fox-news-channels-hannity/102325194/|archive-date=2018-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Conservative magazine ''[[National Review]]'' compared the story to a flat earth video, called it a \"disgrace\" that Hannity and other conspiracy theorists were hyping the story, and called for them to stop.<ref>{{cite news|last1=French|first1=David|title=The Seth Rich Conspiracy Theory Is Shameful Nonsense|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/447903/sean-hannitys-seth-rich-conspiracy-theory-disgrace|accessdate=July 26, 2017|work=National Review|date=May 24, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717085214/http://www.nationalreview.com/article/447903/sean-hannitys-seth-rich-conspiracy-theory-disgrace|archive-date=2017-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Seth Rich's parents filed a lawsuit against Fox News for pushing conspiracy theories about their son's death. The suit alleges that the network \"intentionally exploited\" the tragedy for political purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/seth-rich-parents-sue-fox-news-over-retracted-story-they-say-treated-him-like-a-political-football/2018/03/14/647f5da2-27ab-11e8-b79d-f3d931db7f68_story.html|title=Seth Rich parents sue Fox News over retracted story they say treated him like 'a political football'|last=https://www.facebook.com/paul.farhi|website=Washington Post|accessdate=August 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826115319/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/seth-rich-parents-sue-fox-news-over-retracted-story-they-say-treated-him-like-a-political-football/2018/03/14/647f5da2-27ab-11e8-b79d-f3d931db7f68_story.html|archive-date=2018-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Claims about election fraud ====\nHannity came under criticism during the 2016 presidential election for false claims about [[election rigging]] during interviews. Hannity responded to this by citing [[Mitt Romney]]'s failure in the [[2012 United States presidential election]] to obtain any votes in 59 of 1,687 [[Philadelphia]] voting districts as proof of election rigging. However, [[FactCheck.org|Factcheck.org]] and [[PolitiFact.com|PolitiFact]] found that it was not unusual at all for this to occur, as those [[electoral district]]s are heavily African-American. Philadelphia elections inspector Ryan Godfrey also refuted Hannity's claim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2013/01/voting-conspiracies/|title=Voting Conspiracies|website=www.factcheck.org|language=en-US|access-date=February 23, 2017|date=2013-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404085919/http://www.factcheck.org/2013/01/voting-conspiracies/|archive-date=2017-04-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/pennsylvania/statements/2016/aug/12/viral-image/internet-philly-rigged-2012-presidential-election-|title=Internet: Philly rigged the 2012 presidential election. Experts: Still no|work=@politifact|access-date=March 26, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224211904/http://www.politifact.com/pennsylvania/statements/2016/aug/12/viral-image/internet-philly-rigged-2012-presidential-election-/|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== WikiLeaks ===\nIn 2010, Sean Hannity said [[WikiLeaks]] founder [[Julian Assange]] was waging a \"war\" on the United States, and that Wikileaks put American lives in \"jeopardy\" and \"danger\" around the world. He also criticized the [[Obama administration]] for failing to apprehend Assange.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Wilstein|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/07/sean-hannity-suddenly-loves-julian-assange-now-that-he-s-anti-hillary.html|title=Sean Hannity Suddenly Loves Julian Assange Now That He's Anti-Hillary|date=September 7, 2016|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|access-date=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224053419/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/09/07/sean-hannity-suddenly-loves-julian-assange-now-that-he-s-anti-hillary.html|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/04/how-some-republicans-learned-to-stop-worrying-and-love-julian-assange/|title=How some Republicans learned to stop worrying and love Julian Assange|website=Washington Post|access-date=January 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105180131/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/04/how-some-republicans-learned-to-stop-worrying-and-love-julian-assange/|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, after Wikileaks published [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak|leaked emails from the Democratic National Committee]], Hannity praised Assange for showing \"how corrupt, dishonest and phony our government is\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost.com\" /><ref>{{cite news|first=Jamiles|last=Lartey|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/news-blog/2016/oct/22/wikileaks-clinton-leaks-julian-assange-sean-hannity-david-duke|title=WikiLeaks praised by Sean Hannity and David Duke after Clinton revelations|date=October 22, 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=February 23, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222115214/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/news-blog/2016/oct/22/wikileaks-clinton-leaks-julian-assange-sean-hannity-david-duke|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> He told Assange in a September 2016 interview, \"I do hope you get free one day. I wish you the best.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/la-na-trailguide-updates-hannity-hopes-for-wikileaks-founder-s-1473255689-htmlstory.html|title=Campaign 2016 updates: Donald Trump indicates allowing those in the country illegally to stay if they join military|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=February 23, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224052516/http://www.latimes.com/la-na-trailguide-updates-hannity-hopes-for-wikileaks-founder-s-1473255689-htmlstory.html|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> The following month,<!-- October 2016 --> Hannity claimed that [[WikiLeaks]] has revealed \"everything that conspiracy theorists have said over the years\" about Hillary Clinton is true.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Tim|last=Hains|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2016/10/12/hannity_wikileaks_proves_everything_that_conspiracy_theorists_said_was_true.html|title=Hannity: WikiLeaks Has Proven That \"Everything The Conspiracy Theorists Said\" Was True|website=[[RealClearPolitics]]|date=October 12, 2016|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917222936/https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2016/10/12/hannity_wikileaks_proves_everything_that_conspiracy_theorists_said_was_true.html|archive-date=2018-09-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Hannity retweeted a WikiLeaks tweet linking to an article by the Gateway Pundit site, claiming that [[John McCain]] was a \"[[globalism|globalist]] war criminal\". McCain's spokeswoman called Hannity out on it, asking him to \"correct the record.\" Hannity later deleted the tweet.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite news|first=Jordain|last=Carney|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/320832-mccain-spokeswoman-hannity-should-correct-the-record-after-tweet|title=McCain spokeswoman: Hannity should 'correct the record' after 'fake news' tweet|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=February 23, 2017|access-date=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224112057/http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/320832-mccain-spokeswoman-hannity-should-correct-the-record-after-tweet|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, Hannity made an offer to Assange to guest host his Fox News TV show.<ref>{{cite web|first=Oliver|last=Darcy|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/31/media/julian-assange-guest-host-hannity-radio-show/index.html|title=Julian Assange exploring ways to guest host Hannity's radio program after invite|website=CNNMoney|date=May 31, 2017|access-date=June 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602020850/http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/31/media/julian-assange-guest-host-hannity-radio-show/index.html|archive-date=2017-06-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Relationship with Donald Trump and Michael Cohen ===\nHannity developed a close relationship with Trump during the election and has become even closer during his presidency.<ref name=\":29\" /> The two men speak on the phone multiple times a week, discussing Hannity's weekday show, the special counsel investigation, even evaluating White House staff.<ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hannitys-rising-role-in-trumps-world-he-basically-has-a-desk-in-the-place/2018/04/17/e2483018-4260-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html|title=Hannity's rising role in Trump's world: 'He basically has a desk in the place'|last=Costa|first=Robert|date=April 17, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 28, 2018|last2=Ellison|first2=Sarah|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dawsey|first3=Josh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427210202/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hannitys-rising-role-in-trumps-world-he-basically-has-a-desk-in-the-place/2018/04/17/e2483018-4260-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html|title=The Strange Cocoon of Trump and Hannity, Two Friends Who Like to Talk Before Bed|last=Nuzzi|first=Olivia|work=Daily Intelligencer|access-date=May 14, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514014528/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"LAT101017\">{{Cite news | first1 = Noah | last1 = Bierman | first2 = Cathleen | last2 = Decker | first3 = Brian | last3 = Bennett | url = https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-trump-kelly-20171010-story.html | title = Trump unleashes himself from would-be handlers, lashing out mornings, nights and weekends | newspaper = Los Angeles Times | date = October 10, 2017 | access-date = February 20, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181214014010/https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-trump-kelly-20171010-story.html | archive-date = December 14, 2018 | url-status = live }}.</ref> Hannity shares, ''[[The Economist]]'' asserts, \"Mr Trump's love of conspiracy theories and hatred of snooty elites\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21740777-michael-cohen-has-all-best-clients-sean-hannity-shares-lot-donald-trump|title=Sean Hannity shares a lot with Donald Trump, including an attorney|date=April 19, 2018|work=The Economist|accessdate=April 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421001923/https://economist.com/news/united-states/21740777-michael-cohen-has-all-best-clients-sean-hannity-shares-lot-donald-trump|archive-date=2018-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref> They speak so often that one Trump adviser has said that Hannity \"basically has a desk in the place\".<ref name=\":27\" /> On the air, Hannity echoes Trump's attacks on the media and [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]] into [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]].<ref name=\"Lima\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/hannity-michael-cohen-fbi-raid-526860|title=Fox's Hannity, named as a client of Michael Cohen, spent days attacking FBI raid|last=Lima|first=Cristiano|date=April 16, 2018|work=Politico|accessdate=April 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421094345/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/hannity-michael-cohen-fbi-raid-526860|archive-date=2018-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Trump sometimes quotes Hannity to others or promotes the show to his Twitter followers.<ref name=\":27\" /> Hannity has encouraged Trump to shut down the government to get funding for a border wall, as well as his declaration of a national emergency over the US-Mexico border.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nAccording to reports by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, Hannity frequently talks to Trump by telephone after Hannity's weekday broadcasts,<ref name=\"LAT101017\" /><ref name=Nuzzi>{{cite web | url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html | title=Donald Trump and Sean Hannity Like to Talk Before Bedtime | work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] | date=May 14, 2018 | accessdate=May 14, 2018 | last=Nuzzi | first=Olivia | last2=Darrow | first2=Joe | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514014528/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/sean-hannity-donald-trump-late-night-calls.html | archive-date=2018-05-14 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Cranley>{{cite web | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5 | title=Trump reportedly talks to Sean Hannity most nights before bed | work=[[Business Insider]] | date=May 14, 2018 | accessdate=May 14, 2018 | last=Cranley | first=Ellen | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514193211/http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-sean-hannity-talk-before-bed-2018-5 | archive-date=2018-05-14 | url-status=live }}</ref> and Hannity is one of several dozen cleared callers whose calls to the White House public switchboard can be connected directly to the president.<ref name=Nuzzi/>\n\nHannity stirred controversy in April 2018 when it was revealed that he shared a lawyer, [[Michael Cohen]], with President Trump. In a breach of [[journalism ethics|journalistic ethics]], Hannity had failed to disclose that Cohen was his lawyer while at the same time taking to the Fox airwaves to defend Cohen and criticize those who investigated him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/business/media/sean-hannity-fox-news.html|title=No Disclosure? No Problem. Sean Hannity Gets a Pass at Fox News.|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=April 17, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 28, 2018|last2=Koblin|first2=John|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427010532/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/business/media/sean-hannity-fox-news.html|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/17/sean-hannity-fox-news-full-support-michael-cohen-528948|title=Cohen controversy tests Hannity's Teflon Sean reputation|work=POLITICO|access-date=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429092537/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/17/sean-hannity-fox-news-full-support-michael-cohen-528948|archive-date=2018-04-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/sean-hannity-cohen-attorney-trump-527897|title=Hannity's ethics under fire|work=POLITICO|access-date=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427165830/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/16/sean-hannity-cohen-attorney-trump-527897|archive-date=2018-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/17/watchdogs-attack-sean-hannity-for-hiding-link-to-trump-lawyer-cohen.html|title=Fox News gives Sean Hannity 'full support' as critics slam him for hiding link to Trump lawyer|last=Breuninger|first=Kevin|date=April 17, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429092044/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/17/watchdogs-attack-sean-hannity-for-hiding-link-to-trump-lawyer-cohen.html|archive-date=2018-04-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2018, federal agents from the [[U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York|U.S. Attorney's office]] served a search warrant on the office and residence of [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]], Trump's personal attorney.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strobel |first1=Warren |last2=Walcott |first2=John |title=FBI raids offices, home of Trump's personal lawyer: sources |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |website=Reuters |accessdate=April 10, 2018 |date=April 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410012921/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-cohen-raid/fbi-raids-offices-home-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-sources-idUSKBN1HG336 |archive-date=2018-04-10 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the air, Hannity defended Cohen and criticized the federal action, calling it \"highly questionable\" and \"an unprecedented abuse of power\".<ref name=\"Winter\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|title=Fox News host Sean Hannity revealed as Michael Cohen's mystery client|last1=Winter|first1=Tom|last2=Edelman|first2=Adam|date=April 16, 2018|work=NBC News|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416122620/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 16, 2018, in a court hearing, Cohen's lawyers told the judge that Cohen had ten clients in 2017-2018 but did \"traditional legal tasks\" for only three: Trump, [[Elliott Broidy]], and a \"prominent person\" who did not wish to be named for fear of being \"embarrassed\".<ref name = Miller/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pierson|first1=Brendan|last2=Freifeld|first2=Karen|last3=Stempel|first3=Jonathan|title=Fox's Hannity revealed as mystery client of Trump's personal lawyer|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-cohen/foxs-hannity-revealed-as-mystery-client-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-idUSKBN1HN12G|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418020458/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-cohen/foxs-hannity-revealed-as-mystery-client-of-trumps-personal-lawyer-idUSKBN1HN12G|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Feuer|first1=Alan|last2=Grynbaum|first2=Michael|last3=Koblin|first3=John|title=Sean Hannity Is Named as Client of Michael Cohen, Trump's Lawyer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/16/business/media/sean-hannity-michael-cohen-client.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417195139/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/16/business/media/sean-hannity-michael-cohen-client.html|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal judge ordered the revelation of the third client, whom Cohen's lawyers named as Hannity.<ref name = Miller/> Although Hannity has covered Cohen on his show, he did not disclose that he had consulted with Cohen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2018/04/fox-news-sean-hannity-downplay-michael-cohen-relationship/|title=Fox News and Sean Hannity Downplay Host's Relationship With Attorney Michael Cohen|last=Richardson|first=Davis|date=April 16, 2018|work=The Observer|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105818/http://observer.com/2018/04/fox-news-sean-hannity-downplay-michael-cohen-relationship/|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFox News released a statement on April 16, 2018, attributed to Hannity: \"Michael Cohen has never represented me in any matter. I never retained him, received an invoice, or paid legal fees. I have occasionally had brief discussions with him about legal questions about which I wanted his input and perspective. I assumed those conversations were confidential, but to be absolutely clear they never involved any matter between me and a third party.\"<ref name=cohenfox>{{cite web|last1=Borchers|first1=Callum|title=The gaping hole in Sean Hannity's story about being Michael Cohen's client|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/16/the-gaping-hole-in-sean-hannitys-story-about-being-michael-cohens-client/?noredirect=on|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423033629/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/04/16/the-gaping-hole-in-sean-hannitys-story-about-being-michael-cohens-client/?noredirect=on|archive-date=2018-04-23|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, [[NBC News]] quoted Hannity as saying: \"We definitely had [[attorney-client privilege]] because I asked him for that\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Edelman|first1=Adam|last2=Winter|first2=Tom|title=Fox News host Sean Hannity revealed as Michael Cohen's mystery client|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416234249/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-wants-review-some-materials-seized-cohen-fbi-raid-n866226|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> while Hannity said on his radio show that he \"might have handed him ten bucks\" for the attorney-client privilege.<ref name=cohenfox/><ref name=Miller>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Hayley|last2=Blumberg|first2=Antonia|title=Identity Of Michael Cohen's 'Mystery' Client Revealed As Sean Hannity|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/michael-cohen-sean-hannity_us_5ad4ef98e4b016a07e9f6410|work=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416231924/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/michael-cohen-sean-hannity_us_5ad4ef98e4b016a07e9f6410|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Lastly, Hannity tweeted that his discussions with Cohen were \"almost exclusively\" about [[real estate]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Samuels|first1=Brett|title=Hannity downplays connection to Trump's personal lawyer|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/383417-hannity-downplays-connection-to-trumps-personal-lawyer|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031520/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/383417-hannity-downplays-connection-to-trumps-personal-lawyer|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe following day, news reports revealed that Hannity had shared another lawyer with Trump, [[Jay Sekulow]]. Sekulow had written a [[cease-and-desist letter]] to [[KFAQ]] on Hannity's behalf in May 2017, and later represented Trump in connection with the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gray|first1=Rosie|title=Sean Hannity's Ties to Two More Trump-Connected Lawyers|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/sean-hannity/558272/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417235448/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/sean-hannity/558272/|archive-date=2018-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Report: Sean Hannity used two other Trump-connected lawyers|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/report-sean-hannity-used-two-other-trump-connected-lawyers/|publisher=[[CBS News]]|accessdate=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418032454/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/report-sean-hannity-used-two-other-trump-connected-lawyers/|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Hannity allowed Sekulow and [[Rudy Giuliani]], another personal lawyer for Trump, to host Hannity's radio show; the duo proceeded to defend Trump and promote arguments made by the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boboltz |first1=Sara |title=Sean Hannity Just Let Trump's Lawyers Host His Radio Show |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sean-hannity-is-letting-trumps-lawyers-host-his-radio-show_us_5b6d9441e4b0ae32af978334 |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |accessdate=August 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824224858/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sean-hannity-is-letting-trumps-lawyers-host-his-radio-show_us_5b6d9441e4b0ae32af978334 |archive-date=2018-08-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|The New Yorker]]'', Hannity has reversed on the issue of negotiations with North Korea: during Obama's presidency, Hannity called negotiations with [[North Korea]] \"disturbing\", whereas he called Trump's negotiations with North Korea a \"huge foreign-policy win.\"<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nIn June 2019, Hannity expressed outrage at Speaker of the House [[Nancy Pelosi]]'s comment that she would like to see Trump \"in prison\". Hannity declared: \"Based on no actual crimes, she wants a political opponent locked up in prison? That happens in [[banana republic]]s \u2014 beyond despicable behavior.\" Aaron Rupar of ''[[Vox (news site)|Vox]]'' criticized Hannity for \"obvious hypocrisy\", noting that Hannity himself had said in January 2018 regarding Hillary Clinton: \"I think Hillary should be in jail. Lock her up.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rupar |first1=Aaron |title=Hannity: \"Hillary should be in jail.\" Also Hannity: Locking up Trump would be \"beyond despicable.\" |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/6/7/18656356/hannity-lock-them-up-pelosi-trump |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref> Aaron Blake of ''The Washington Post'' described Hannity's comment as \"a pretty obvious bit of [[gaslighting]]\", noting Hannity's loyalty to Trump, whose campaign rallies have featured chants of \"Lock her up\", and also Hannity's comments that Trump was free to investigate Clinton.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |title=Parsing Sean Hannity's incredible flip-flop on jailing political opponents |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/06/07/parsing-sean-hannitys-incredible-flip-flop-jailing-political-opponents |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism of FBI, DOJ, and special counsel ===\nDuring President Trump's administration, Hannity has repeatedly been highly critical of the FBI, DOJ, Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]], and others investigating [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 election]].<ref name=newsweekporter>{{cite journal|url=http://www.newsweek.com/watergate-reporter-carl-bernstein-thinks-fox-news-helping-trump-administration-743904|title=Watergate Reporter Carl Bernstein Thinks Fox News Is Helping the Trump Administration Cover Up Its Russia Ties|journal=[[Newsweek]]|date=December 11, 2017|first=Tom|last=Porter|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023095822/https://www.newsweek.com/watergate-reporter-carl-bernstein-thinks-fox-news-helping-trump-administration-743904|archive-date=2018-10-23|url-status=live}}</ref> According to a review by ''[[Media Matters for America|Media Matters]]'' of all transcripts from the 254 episodes of Hannity's show from Mueller's appointment (May 17, 2017) to May 16, 2018, Hannity had 487 segments substantially devoted to Mueller (approximately two per episode), opened his program with Mueller 152 times (approximately three times per week), and the content of his show was highly critical of the probe and the media's coverage of the probe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/05/23/study-sean-hannity-spent-last-year-laying-groundwork-authoritarian-response-russia-probe/220281|title=Study: Sean Hannity spent the last year laying the groundwork for an authoritarian response to the Russia probe|date=May 22, 2018|work=Media Matters for America|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523153737/https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/05/23/study-sean-hannity-spent-last-year-laying-groundwork-authoritarian-response-russia-probe/220281|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref> He has called the Russia inquiry a \"witch hunt\", an \"utter disgrace\", and \"a direct threat to you, the American people, and our American republic.\"<ref name=newsweekporter/> Hannity has expressed skepticism of the U.S. intelligence community's view that Russia hacked the [[Democratic National Convention]]'s emails during the 2016 election and has promoted various conspiracy theories. In March 2017 he publicized a theory, first proposed at the Wikileaks Twitter account, that the CIA could have done the hacking while making it look like Russia did it.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-cia-hacked-2017-3?r=US&IR=T|title=Conservative media figures are embracing a wild WikiLeaks conspiracy theory that the CIA hacked the DNC, and then framed Russia|work=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=March 11, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108034506/http://uk.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-cia-hacked-2017-3?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2017-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> In August he suggested that [[Seth Rich]] may have been the leaker.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/seth-rich-russia-and-2016-election-648312|title=Link between Russia and 2016 election may be Seth Rich murder, Republican lobbyist tells Robert Mueller|last=Nazaryan|first=Alexander|date=August 19, 2017|work=Newsweek|accessdate=April 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421233212/http://www.newsweek.com/seth-rich-russia-and-2016-election-648312|archive-date=2018-04-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHannity has described the Mueller investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election, as well as [[James Comey]]'s tenure as FBI Director, as \"one giant incestuous circle of corruption.\"<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|first=Mark|last=Mazzetti|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/us/politics/memo-trump-nunes.html|title=How Trump's Allies Fanned an Ember of Controversy Into Flames of Outrage|date=February 2, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 3, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203043405/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/us/politics/memo-trump-nunes.html|archive-date=2018-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2018, Hannity ran a segment where he claimed there were \"criminal\" connections between [[Bill Clinton|Bill]] and [[Hillary Clinton]], Mueller, and Comey.<ref name=\":25\" /> Hannity asserted that there were three connected \"Deep State crime families\" actively \"trying to take down the president.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-promotes-conspiratorial-hannity-episode-calling-mueller-head-of-deep-state-crime-families-2|title=Trump Promotes Conspiratorial 'Hannity' Episode Calling Mueller Part of 'Deep State Crime Families'|date=April 12, 2018|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=April 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413035126/https://www.thedailybeast.com/trump-promotes-conspiratorial-hannity-episode-calling-mueller-head-of-deep-state-crime-families-2|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":25\" /> A guest on the segment, attorney [[Joseph diGenova]], called Mueller's team \"legal terrorists\" and referred to Comey as a \"dirty cop\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/joseph-digenova-trump-fox-news-sessions-should-fire-rosenstein-2018-4?r=US&IR=T|title=Former federal prosecutor Joseph diGenova calls for Rosenstein's firing on Fox News after Trump tells people to tune in to the 'big show'|work=Business Insider|access-date=April 12, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412212145/http://uk.businessinsider.com/joseph-digenova-trump-fox-news-sessions-should-fire-rosenstein-2018-4?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2018-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHannity also claimed that Mueller had been involved in the corrupt dealings of several FBI agents in connection with [[Boston, Massachusetts]] [[crime boss]] [[Whitey Bulger]].<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/opinion/robert-mueller-smearing-complicit.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Smearing Robert Mueller|date=April 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 19, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419004452/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/opinion/robert-mueller-smearing-complicit.html|archive-date=2018-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref> The federal judge who presided over a lawsuit concerning the corrupt dealings said Hannity's claims were unsubstantiated and that Mueller was never accused of any wrongdoing nor even mentioned during the proceedings.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nIn June 2018, after reports that Mueller's probe had asked witnesses to turn their personal phones over to investigators for examination, Hannity sarcastically suggested on air to the witnesses that they \"follow Hillary Clinton's lead\" and destroy their personal phones so they cannot be examined.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/391115-hannity-advises-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-smash-their-phones-to-little-itsy|title=Fox's Hannity advises witnesses in Mueller probe smash their phones to 'little itsy bitsy pieces'|last=Greenwood|first=Max|date=June 6, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=June 7, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180607035847/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/391115-hannity-advises-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-smash-their-phones-to-little-itsy|archive-date=2018-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/sean-hannity-to-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-bash-your-phones-into-pieces|title=Sean Hannity to Witnesses in Mueller Probe: 'Bash' Your Phones Into Pieces|date=June 7, 2018|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=June 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180607035909/https://www.thedailybeast.com/sean-hannity-to-witnesses-in-mueller-probe-bash-your-phones-into-pieces|archive-date=2018-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, after Mueller gave a statement saying the Special Counsel investigation did not exonerate Trump of crimes, Hannity said Mueller was \"basically full of crap\" and did not know the law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fox-news-mueller-hannity-carlson-ingraham_n_5cef781ce4b0888f89d0e91d|title=Fox News Hosts Freak Out Over 'Mean Girl' Robert Mueller: 'Full Of Crap'|last=Moran|first=Lee|date=2019-05-30|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Uranium One ===\nFrom 2015 into 2018, Fox News broadcast extensive coverage of an alleged scandal surrounding the sale of [[Uranium One]] to Russian interests, which Hannity characterized as \"one of the biggest scandals in American history.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/10/25/hannity-uranium-one-deal-was-biggest-scandal-american-history-nda-lifted-informant|title=Hannity: Uranium One Deal 'One of the Biggest Scandals in American History'|date=October 26, 2017|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074024/http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/10/25/hannity-uranium-one-deal-was-biggest-scandal-american-history-nda-lifted-informant|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref> The Fox News coverage extended throughout the programming day, with particular emphasis by Hannity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2017/11/09/study-fox-spent-nearly-12-hours-pushing-uranium-one-pseudoscandal-over-last-three-weeks/218475|title=Study: Fox spent nearly 12 hours pushing the Uranium One pseudoscandal over the last three weeks|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803044454/https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2017/11/09/study-fox-spent-nearly-12-hours-pushing-uranium-one-pseudoscandal-over-last-three-weeks/218475|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref> The network promoted a narrative asserting that, as Secretary of State, Hillary Clinton personally approved the Uranium One sale in exchange for $145 million in bribes paid to the [[Clinton Foundation]]. Donald Trump repeated these allegations as a candidate and as president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factba.se/search#%22uranium+one%22|title=Donald Trump Complete - Search Tweets, Speeches, Policies - Factbase|last=Factbase|website=Factbase|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809150520/https://factba.se/search#%22uranium+one%22#%22uranium+one%22|archive-date=2018-08-09|url-status=live}}</ref> No evidence of wrongdoing by Clinton had been found after three years of allegations, an FBI investigation, and the 2017 appointment of a Federal attorney to evaluate the investigation. In November 2017, Fox News host [[Shepard Smith]] concisely debunked the alleged scandal, including stating that Clinton did not personally approve the sale, infuriating viewers who suggested he should work for CNN or MSNBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/11/15/fox-news-shepherd-smith-debunks-his-networks-hillary-clinton-scandal-story-infuriates-viewers/|title=Fox News's Shepard Smith debunks his network's favorite Hillary Clinton 'scandal,' infuriates viewers|website=Washington Post|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806134030/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/11/15/fox-news-shepherd-smith-debunks-his-networks-hillary-clinton-scandal-story-infuriates-viewers/|archive-date=2018-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7A9EV64aX_Q|title=Fox News Reports: Sean Hannity Is a Liar|last=fb|date=November 15, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=August 3, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> Hannity later called Smith \"clueless,\" while Smith stated, \"I get it, that some of our opinion programming is there strictly to be entertaining. I get that. I don't work there. I wouldn't work there.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/shepard-smith-fox-news-trump-sean-hannity-20180316.html|title=Fox News fight: Shepard Smith, Sean Hannity trade insults|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803044423/http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/shepard-smith-fox-news-trump-sean-hannity-20180316.html|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/shepard-smith-calls-out-fox-news-opinion-programming-those-shows-exist-strictly-to-be-entertaining/|title=Shepard Smith on Fox News 'Opinion Programming': Shows Exist 'Strictly to Be Entertaining'|website=www.mediaite.com|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074031/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/shepard-smith-calls-out-fox-news-opinion-programming-those-shows-exist-strictly-to-be-entertaining/|archive-date=2018-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA two-year Justice Department investigation initiated after Donald Trump became president found no evidence to justify pursuing a criminal investigation.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/justice-dept-winds-down-clinton-related-inquiry-once-championed-by-trump-it-found-nothing-of-consequence/2020/01/09/ca83932e-32f9-11ea-a053-dc6d944ba776_story.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/09/politics/clinton-justice-department-investigation/index.html|title=Justice inquiry into Hillary Clinton's business dealings languishes|author1=Evan Perez |author2=David Shortell|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n=== Deep state ===\nHannity has advocated [[QAnon]], the \"[[Deep state in the United States|deep state]]\" theory proposing a network of government officials are working to hinder the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Coaston|first=Jane|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/8/1/17253444/qanon-trump-conspiracy-theory-reddit|title=#QAnon, the scarily popular pro-Trump conspiracy theory, explained|work=Vox|date=August 2, 2018|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref> He has described the deep state as a \"Shadow Government\" and \"Deep state swamp of Obama holdovers and DC lifers\".<ref>{{Cite web|first=Hunter|last=Schwarz|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/07/politics/deep-state/index.html|title=What's a 'Deep State' and why is it a new buzzword for the online right?|website=[[CNN]]|date=March 7, 2017|access-date=March 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314091502/http://www.cnn.com/2017/03/07/politics/deep-state/index.html|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|first=Chris|last=Graham|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/11/deep-state-shadowy-network-obama-holdovers-undermining-donald/|title=What is 'deep state' and is a shadowy network of Obama holdovers undermining Donald Trump?|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=March 11, 2017|access-date=March 14, 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314025019/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/11/deep-state-shadowy-network-obama-holdovers-undermining-donald/|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2017, he called for a \"purge\" of Obama-era bureaucrats and appointees in government.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Mark|last=Hensch|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/323458-spicer-wont-reject-deep-state-against-trump|title=Spicer won't reject idea that 'deep state' opposes Trump|date=March 10, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=March 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313232436/http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/323458-spicer-wont-reject-deep-state-against-trump|archive-date=2017-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref> In an op-ed for ''The Wall Street Journal'', conservative columnist [[Bret Stephens]] disputed Sean Hannity's deep state allegations, saying they were an example of the \"paranoid style in politics\".<ref>{{Cite news|first=Bret|last=Stephens|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/deep-states-and-demagogues-1489446006|title=Deep States and Demagogues|date=March 13, 2017|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=March 14, 2017|issn=0099-9660|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314002054/https://www.wsj.com/articles/deep-states-and-demagogues-1489446006|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that month, Hannity said NBC News was part of the deep state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tax-story-puts-spotlight-on-msnbcs-rachel-maddow/2017/03/14/4702121a-092f-11e7-bd19-fd3afa0f7e2a_story.html|title=Tax story puts spotlight on MSNBC's Rachel Maddow|website=Washington Post|access-date=March 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315180557/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/tax-story-puts-spotlight-on-msnbcs-rachel-maddow/2017/03/14/4702121a-092f-11e7-bd19-fd3afa0f7e2a_story.html|archive-date=2017-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, he reiterated that deep state/intelligence operatives were trying to destroy the Trump presidency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-supporters-idUSKCN18E36Q|title=For Trump's defenders, White House turmoil is politics as usual|date=May 18, 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=May 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518232147/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-supporters-idUSKCN18E36Q|archive-date=2017-05-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Hannity attacked Special Counsel Robert Mueller, saying his career was \"anything but impeccable.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/379475-hannity-rips-muellers-career-anything-but-impeccable|title=Hannity rips Mueller's career: 'Anything but impeccable'|last=Manchester|first=Julia|date=March 21, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321174903/http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/379475-hannity-rips-muellers-career-anything-but-impeccable|archive-date=2018-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity asserted that Mueller was friends with former FBI Director James Comey and current Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]], and that he \"cannot be expected to honestly investigate scandals that his friends are directly involved in.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/379470-hannity-mueller-cant-honestly-investigate-scandals-that-comey-rosenstein-are|title=Hannity: Mueller can't 'honestly investigate scandals' that Comey, Rosenstein are 'directly involved in'|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=March 21, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321164758/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/379470-hannity-mueller-cant-honestly-investigate-scandals-that-comey-rosenstein-are|archive-date=2018-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> He said these individuals were involved in \"one massive, huge, deep-state conflict of interest after another. Now they're protecting themselves. They're trying to preserve their own power.\"<ref name=\":25\" />\n\n=== Comments on sexual harassment ===\nIn 2016, Hannity vociferously defended Roger Ailes when he was accused by multiple women of sexual harassment.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\"Alderman\">{{cite news|last1=Alderman|first1=Julie|last2=Radtke|first2=Dina|last3=Lawrence|first3=Andrew|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/11/22/sean-hannity-continues-to-defend-sexual-abusers_partner/|title=Sean Hannity's long-standing defense of sexual abusers|work=Salon|agency=Media Matters for America|date=November 23, 2017|access-date=November 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109070737/https://www.salon.com/2017/11/22/sean-hannity-continues-to-defend-sexual-abusers_partner/|archive-date=2018-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2017, Hannity paid a tribute to Ailes after he died.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sean-hannity-has-message-for-roger-ailes-enemies/|title=Sean Hannity has message for Roger Ailes' enemies|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065103/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sean-hannity-has-message-for-roger-ailes-enemies/|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity called him \"a second father\" and said to Ailes's \"enemies\" that he was \"preparing to kick your {{As written|a**}} in the next life\".<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIn April 2017, Hannity came to the defense of Fox News co-president [[Bill Shine]] after it was reported that Shine's job was at risk.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/27/business/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-bill-shine.html|title=Sean Hannity Defends Executive as Fox News Turmoil Continues|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=April 27, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 12, 2017|last2=Steel|first2=Emily|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065121/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/27/business/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-bill-shine.html|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-04-28/sean-hannity-defends-boss-says-ouster-would-be-end-of-fox-news|title=Sean Hannity Defends Boss, Says Ouster Would Be End of Fox News|date=April 28, 2017|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065136/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-04-28/sean-hannity-defends-boss-says-ouster-would-be-end-of-fox-news|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> At least four lawsuits alleged that Shine had ignored, enabled or concealed Roger Ailes' alleged sexual harassment.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/may/25/sean-hannity-fox-news-media-matters-seth-rich|title=Sean Hannity targets media watchdog amid questions over future at Fox News|last=Gabbatt|first=Adam|date=May 25, 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 13, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013172248/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/may/25/sean-hannity-fox-news-media-matters-seth-rich|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, several months after [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] was fired from Fox News in the wake of a number of women's alleging that he had sexually harassed them, Hannity hosted O'Reilly on his show.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/352439-hannity-to-host-oreilly-tuesday-for-second-interview-in-eight-days|title=Hannity to host O'Reilly Tuesday on Fox News|last=Lejeune|first=Tristan|date=September 26, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065440/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/352439-hannity-to-host-oreilly-tuesday-for-second-interview-in-eight-days|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/26/media/oreilly-hannity-fox-news-interview/index.html|title=Bill O'Reilly appears on Fox News for first time since his ouster|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011230546/http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/26/media/oreilly-hannity-fox-news-interview/index.html|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/09/27/bill-oreilly-returns-to-fox-as-sean-hannitys-guest/106036888/|title=Bill O'Reilly returns to Fox as Sean Hannity's guest|work=USA TODAY|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013070622/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/09/27/bill-oreilly-returns-to-fox-as-sean-hannitys-guest/106036888/|archive-date=2017-10-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Some Fox News employees criticized the decision.<ref name=\":16\" /> In the interview, O'Reilly attacked liberal media watchdog groups and said he should have fought harder when those groups targeted his advertisers.<ref name=\":16\" /> According to CNN, during the interview, Hannity found kinship with O'Reilly as he appeared \"to feel that he and O'Reilly have both become victims of liberals looking to silence them.\"<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nHannity came under criticism in October 2017 when he attacked Democrats after it became known that a large number of women had accused [[Harvey Weinstein]], the Hollywood producer and donor to Democratic causes, of sexual harassment.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-harvey-weinstein-bill-oreilly-2017-10?IR=T|title=Sean Hannity goes on 10-minute rant about left's 'hypocrisy' on Harvey Weinstein, two weeks after having Bill O'Reilly on his show|work=Business Insider|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012201648/http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-harvey-weinstein-bill-oreilly-2017-10?IR=T|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref> Critics noted that Hannity had weeks earlier defended and hosted his coworker Bill O'Reilly who was fired following a number of sexual harassment allegations.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-and-friends-hypocrites-slam-late-night-hosts-weinstein-silence|title='Fox & Friends' Hypocrites Slam Late-Night Hosts' Weinstein Silence|last=Wilstein|first=Matt|date=October 9, 2017|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011205846/https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-and-friends-hypocrites-slam-late-night-hosts-weinstein-silence|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nIn the radio show for KCSB, which was the subject of controversy in 1989, Hannity made anti-gay comments.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|first=Emily|last=Shugarman|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/sean-hannity-gay-people-aids-lgbt-homosexuality-sewer-comments-college-radio-a7995696.html|title=Sean Hannity once compared homosexuality to 'playing in a sewer'|work=[[The Independent]]|date=October 11, 2017|access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012002053/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/sean-hannity-gay-people-aids-lgbt-homosexuality-sewer-comments-college-radio-a7995696.html|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"PinkNews 2017\" /> He called AIDS a \"gay disease\" and said the media was hiding salient information from the public.<ref name=\":6\"/><ref name=\"PinkNews 2017\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/10/11/fox-news-host-sean-hannity-called-aids-a-gay-disease-and-lashed-out-at-gay-brainwashing/|title=Fox News host Sean Hannity called AIDS a 'gay disease' and lashed out at gay 'brainwashing'|work=PinkNews|access-date=October 12, 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011231213/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2017/10/11/fox-news-host-sean-hannity-called-aids-a-gay-disease-and-lashed-out-at-gay-brainwashing/|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=live}}</ref> Two editions featured anti-gay activist Gene Antonio, a Lutheran minister,<ref>{{cite news|last=Shaer|first=Matthew|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|title=How Far Will Sean Hannity Go?|work=The New York Times|date=November 28, 2017|access-date=November 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129003856/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/28/magazine/how-far-will-sean-hannity-go.html|archive-date=2017-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref> discussing his book ''The AIDS Coverup: The Real and Alarming Facts about AIDS''. In the book, Antonio claims that AIDS can be spread by people sneezing in close proximity to each other. Hannity encouraged Antonio when he said that AIDS spread when gay men consumed each other's [[feces]],<ref name=\":6\" /> said that homosexuality was a \"lower form of behavior\", compared homosexual sex lives to \"playing in a sewer\" and gay people of being \"filled with hatred and bigotry\".<ref name=\":7\" /> When a lesbian, another broadcaster at the station, called into the show, Hannity said \"I feel sorry for your child\".<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{cite book |first=Jeff |last=Cohen |authorlink=Jeff Cohen (media critic) |title=Cable News Confidential: My Misadventures in Corporate Media |publisher=[[Polipoint Press]] |location=Sausalito, California |date=2006 |url=https://archive.org/details/cablenewsconfide00cohe |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/cablenewsconfide00cohe/page/85 85] |isbn=978-0-9760621-6-5}}</ref> Hannity was quoted at the time as saying that \"anyone listening to this show that believes homosexuality is a normal lifestyle has been brainwashed\".<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Marshall|first=Colin|url=https://www.independent.com/news/2009/nov/23/let-freeform-ring/|title=Let Freeform Ring: A Brief History of KCSB, Part VI|work=Santa Barbara Independent|date=November 23, 2009|access-date=November 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109205455/http://www.independent.com/news/2009/nov/23/let-freeform-ring/|archive-date=2018-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The ACLU opposed his firing and petitioned the station to reverse their decision. Hannity demanded a formal apology and double the airtime. While the station did offer to allow Hannity to return, they would not meet Hannity's additional demands and he declined to return.\n\nIn 2017, Hannity said he regretted the comments and that they were \"ignorant and embarrassing\".<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|last=Cuccinello|first=Hayley C.|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hayleycuccinello/2018/07/16/sean-hannity-celebrity-100/#50cbee972d93|title=Trump Bump: How Sean Hannity Earned $36 Million This Year|work=Forbes|access-date=July 16, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Immigration ===\nHannity opposed amnesty, then he said in 2012 that he had evolved on the issue and favored a \"pathway to citizenship\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2012/11/hannity-ive-evolved-on-immigration-and-support-a-pathway-to-citizenship-149078|title=Hannity: I've 'evolved' on immigration and support a 'pathway to citizenship'|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095450/https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2012/11/hannity-ive-evolved-on-immigration-and-support-a-pathway-to-citizenship-149078|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /> Later, he opposed that idea.<ref name=\":6\" /> By 2018, he was described as an immigration hardliner by CNN, ''The Washington Post'', and ''New York'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/02/politics/donald-trump-weekend-immigration/index.html|title=At Mar-a-Lago, Trump hears from immigration hardliners|last=Producer|first=Kevin Liptak, CNN White House|work=CNN|access-date=May 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523011605/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/04/02/politics/donald-trump-weekend-immigration/index.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/04/white-house-pursues-new-immigration-push-after-trump-tweets.html|title=White House Unveils New Immigration Push, Tries to Make Sense of Trump's Tweets|last=Hartmann|first=Margaret|work=Daily Intelligencer|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523095510/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/04/white-house-pursues-new-immigration-push-after-trump-tweets.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-heats-up-rhetoric-on-border-immigration-as-some-supporters-grow-impatient/2018/04/02/88d5353e-3690-11e8-acd5-35eac230e514_story.html|title=Trump heats up rhetoric on border, immigration as some supporters grow impatient|last=Nakamura|first=David|date=April 3, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523011054/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-heats-up-rhetoric-on-border-immigration-as-some-supporters-grow-impatient/2018/04/02/88d5353e-3690-11e8-acd5-35eac230e514_story.html|archive-date=2018-05-23|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2018, President Trump suggested that he might shut down the government to force Congress to fund his border wall, boasting that Sean Hannity agreed with the action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/02/president-trump-sean-hannity-government-shutdown-border-money/894974002/|title=President Trump boasts of Sean Hannity's approval of government shutdown plan|work=USA TODAY|access-date=August 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Islam ===\nHannity has warned of [[sharia law]] coming to the United States.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2011/04/paul-to-hannity-stop-with-your-sharia-053693|title=Paul to Hannity: Stop with your Sharia|work=POLITICO|access-date=October 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017093438/http://www.politico.com/story/2011/04/paul-to-hannity-stop-with-your-sharia-053693|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity opposed the building of [[Park51]], a mosque two blocks from the [[World Trade Center site]].<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nHannity promoted the idea of \"Islamic training camps right here in America\", which were based on an unsubstantiated \"documentary\" by the Christian Action Network.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/11/05/the-conspiracy-theories-animating-the-right|title=The Conspiracy Theories Animating the Right|last=Clift|first=Eleanor|date=November 5, 2015|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Hannity was critical of [[Keith Ellison]], the first Muslim elected to U.S. Congress, being sworn into office with an oath on a [[Quran]]. Hannity equated the Quran with ''[[Mein Kampf]]'', asking a guest on his show whether he would have allowed Ellison \"to choose, you know, [[Hitler]]'s Mein Kampf, which is the [[Nazi]] bible?\"<ref>{{Cite book|first=Randy|last=Bobbitt|url=https://archive.org/details/usagainstthempol0000bobb|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/usagainstthempol0000bobb/page/59 59]|quote=hannity ellison Mein Kampf.|title=Us against Them: The Political Culture of Talk Radio|date=May 25, 2010|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=9781461634652|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Brian|last=Lambert|url=https://www.minnpost.com/glean/2013/03/minnesota-winters-warming-faster-any-other-state|title=Minnesota winters warming faster than in any other state|work=[[MinnPost]]|date=March 1, 2013|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017043007/https://www.minnpost.com/glean/2013/03/minnesota-winters-warming-faster-any-other-state|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Torture ===\nIn 2009, Hannity said he supported [[enhanced interrogation]], a euphemism for torture. He also volunteered to be [[waterboarded]] for charity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Linkins|first1=Jason|title=Hannity Offers To Be Waterboarded For Charity (By Charles Grodin!)|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/22/hannity-offers-to-be-wate_n_190354.html|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227194400/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/22/hannity-offers-to-be-wate_n_190354.html|archive-date=2018-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hannity, Grodin Go One-on-One on Waterboarding, Obama's Agenda|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2009/04/23/hannity-grodin-go-one-on-one-on-waterboarding-obama-agenda.html|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413185817/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2009/04/23/hannity-grodin-go-one-on-one-on-waterboarding-obama-agenda.html|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, [[Keith Olbermann]] pledged to donate $1,000 for every second of waterboarding Hannity underwent. In 2017, Hannity continued to advocate for waterboarding, raising the example of using it against a kidnapper.<ref>{{cite web|last1=de Moraes|first1=Lisa|title=Sean Hannity & Donald Trump Wonder How David Muir Would Feel About Waterboarding If His Child Was Kidnapped|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/donald-trump-sean-hannity-waterboarding-david-muir-kidnap-child-1201895285/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413185912/http://deadline.com/2017/01/donald-trump-sean-hannity-waterboarding-david-muir-kidnap-child-1201895285/|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity has not been waterboarded as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Simon|first1=Maloy|title=Torture fan Sean Hannity still hasn't been waterboarded like he promised|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/03/16/Torture-fan-Sean-Hannity-still-hasnt-been-waterboarded-like-he-promised/219665|journal=[[Media Matters for America|Media Matters]]|date=March 16, 2018|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212070508/https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2018/03/16/Torture-fan-Sean-Hannity-still-hasnt-been-waterboarded-like-he-promised/219665|archive-date=2019-02-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate change ===\nHannity rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. In 2001, he described it as \"phony science from the left.\"<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=McKnight|first=David|date=December 1, 2010|title=A change in the climate? The journalism of opinion at News Corporation|journal=Journalism|language=en|volume=11|issue=6|pages=693\u2013706|doi=10.1177/1464884910379704|issn=1464-8849}}</ref> In 2004, he falsely claimed that scientists couldn't agree on whether global warming was \"scientific fact or fiction\".<ref name=\":18\" /> In 2010, Hannity falsely stated that so-called [[Climatic Research Unit email controversy|\"Climategate\"]] \u2013 the leaking of e-mails written by climate scientists that climate change skeptics said demonstrated scientific misconduct, but which all subsequent inquiries found to show no evidence of misconduct or wrongdoing \u2013 was a scandal that \"exposed global warming as a myth cooked up by alarmists.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-11/news/ct-oped-0711-page-20100711_1_climate-change-scientific-journals-scientists|title=Climate change heats up again|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017044436/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-11/news/ct-oped-0711-page-20100711_1_climate-change-scientific-journals-scientists|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity frequently invites critics of climate science onto his shows.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RsYr_iQUs6QC&pg=PA144&dq=hannity+%22climate+change%22#v=onepage&q=hannity&f=false|title=The Oxford Handbook of Climate Change and Society|last=Dryzek|first=John S.|last2=Norgaard|first2=Richard B.|last3=Schlosberg|first3=David|date=August 18, 2011|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=9780199566600|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Death panels ===\nHannity promoted the falsehood that the [[Affordable Care Act]] would create so-called \"[[death panel]]s\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2010/05/health-care_reform|title=Epistemic closure and political disinformation|work=The Economist|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816034937/https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2010/05/health-care_reform|archive-date=2017-08-16|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Nyhan|first=Brendan|date=April 27, 2010|title=Why the \"Death Panel\" Myth Wouldn't Die: Misinformation in the Health Care Reform Debate|journal=The Forum|language=en|volume=8|issue=1|doi=10.2202/1540-8884.1354|issn=1540-8884|citeseerx=10.1.1.692.9614|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meirick|first=Patrick C.|date=January 10, 2013|title=Motivated Misperception? Party, Education, Partisan News, and Belief in \"Death Panels\"|journal=Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly|language=en|volume=90|issue=1|pages=39\u201357|doi=10.1177/1077699012468696|hdl=11244/25317|url=https://shareok.org/bitstream/11244/25317/1/10.1177.1077699012468696.pdf}}</ref> According to a study by [[Dartmouth College]] political scientist [[Brendan Nyhan]], Hannity's show, along with the [[Laura Ingraham|Laura Ingraham Show]], were the first major conservative media personalities to latch onto the false claim of [[Betsy McCaughey]] a former lieutenant governor of New York, that the Affordable Care Act contained death panels.<ref name=\":19\" /> When [[Sarah Palin]] stirred controversy by promoting the death panels myth, and argued her case in a Facebook post, Hannity defended her and said, \"I agree with everything that she wrote.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite journal|last=Bard|first=Mitchell T.|date=September 1, 2016|title=The Role of Differing Host Styles in Fox News' Prime Time Coverage of Health Care Reform in August 2009|journal=Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly|language=en|volume=93|issue=3|pages=659\u2013676|doi=10.1177/1077699016628817|issn=1077-6990}}</ref> Hannity also claimed that he found the specific pages in the Affordable Care Act containing provisions on death panels.<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nA 2016 study found that Hannity promoted a number of falsehoods about the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\":20\" /> For instance, Hannity falsely alleged several times that Democratic [[Senate Finance Committee]] Chairman [[Max Baucus]] had said [[Social Security]] could be \"insolvent in two years\" due to the Affordable Care Act.<ref name=\":20\" /> According to the study, Hannity, unlike other Fox News hosts such as Bill O'Reilly and [[Greta Van Susteren]], \"took a more direct approach, aggressively supporting Republicans and conservatives and attacking Democrats and liberals, endorsing the more spurious claims long after they were proven incorrect, and putting advocacy above accurate reporting, to further the network's themes opposing reform.\"<ref name=\":20\" />\n\n=== Roy Moore interview and Twitter controversy ===\nIn November 2017, Hannity interviewed the Alabama senate candidate [[Roy Moore]], who was facing accusations of sexual assault and harassment of teenage girls while he was in his thirties. Hannity said Moore \"deserves the presumption of innocence\" and that \"none of us know the truth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5021237/sean-hannity-boycott-keurig-roy-moore/|title=Here's Why Sean Hannity Fans Are Smashing Their Keurig Coffee Machines to Pieces|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622155422/http://time.com/5021237/sean-hannity-boycott-keurig-roy-moore/|archive-date=2018-06-22|url-status=live}}</ref> After a media campaign from [[Media Matters for America]], which had collected statements he made,<ref name=\"Alderman\" /> and promoted a boycott of Hannity since May 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/research/2017/05/23/these-are-sean-hannitys-advertisers/216607|title=These are Sean Hannity's advertisers|date=May 23, 2017|accessdate=November 17, 2017|publisher=Media Matters for America|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930212949/https://www.mediamatters.org/research/2017/05/23/these-are-sean-hannitys-advertisers/216607|archive-date=2017-09-30|url-status=live}}</ref> several major companies pulled their advertising from Hannity's show. Notably, [[Keurig Dr Pepper|Keurig]] tweeted that it would comply with the boycott organized by Media Matters; this tweet was widely shared and prompted a counter-boycott from fans of Hannity, who tweeted clips of themselves destroying their own [[Keurig|Keurig coffee machines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/reddi-wip-and-hebrew-national-cut-advertising-from-sean-hannitys-show-2017-11?r=UK&IR=T|title=Hebrew National and Reddi-wip announced they pulled advertising from Sean Hannity's show \u2014 but they say it has nothing to do with the recent Keurig-smashing backlash|access-date=2019-02-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217201949/https://www.businessinsider.com/reddi-wip-and-hebrew-national-cut-advertising-from-sean-hannitys-show-2017-11?r=UK&IR=T|archive-date=2018-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":28\" /> After a contentious week, the [[CEO]] of Keurig stated in a publicized memo that the announcement of a boycott on social media was \"outside of company protocols\". He clarified that Keurig had engaged in a \"pause\" in advertisement on Hannity's show, which he claimed to be routine and subject to future review. Hannity later responded by thanking Keurig for \"standing by [him]\", and pledged to give out 500 Keurig machines.<ref>{{cite web|first=Erik|last=Wemple|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/11/13/keurig-ceo-tweet-regarding-hannity-created-an-unacceptable-situation/|title=Keurig CEO: Tweet regarding 'Hannity' created an 'unacceptable situation'|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|location=Washington DC|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113210532/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/11/13/keurig-ceo-tweet-regarding-hannity-created-an-unacceptable-situation/|archive-date=2017-11-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Adam Clark|last=Estes|url=https://gizmodo.com/sean-hannity-settles-keurig-controversy-in-dumbest-way-1820446440/|title=Sean Hannity Settles Keurig Controversy in Dumbest Way Possible|work=[[Gizmodo]]|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Jake Tapper ===\nIn November 2017, Fox News distorted a statement by [[Jake Tapper]] to make it appear as if he had said that \"Allahu Akbar\" can be used under the most \"beautiful circumstances\" in the immediate aftermath of the [[2017 New York City truck attack]] wherein a terrorist shouted \"Allahu Akbar\".<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/jake-tapper-fox-news-lying-allahu-akbar-beautiful-2017-11?r=US&IR=T|title=Jake Tapper slams Fox News for misrepresenting comments about New York City terror attack|work=Business Insider|access-date=November 2, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003601/http://uk.businessinsider.com/jake-tapper-fox-news-lying-allahu-akbar-beautiful-2017-11?r=US&IR=T|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Fox News omitted that Tapper had said that the use of \"Allahu Akbar\" in the terrorist attack was not one of these beautiful circumstances.<ref name=\":21\" /> A headline on FoxNews.com was preceded by a tag reading \"OUTRAGEOUS\".<ref name=\":21\" /> The Fox News Twitter account distorted the statement even more, saying \"Jake Tapper Says 'Allahu Akbar' Is 'Beautiful' Right After NYC Terror Attack\" in a tweet that was later deleted.<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nEven after the Fox News Twitter account had deleted the tweet on Tapper's out-of-context comments, Hannity repeated the out-of-context comments to his viewers, calling Tapper \"liberal fake news CNN's fake Jake Tapper\" and mocking his ratings.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/358382-tapper-hits-fox-hannity-over-allahu-akbar-comments-after-ny-terror-attack|title=Tapper hits Fox, Hannity over 'Allahu Akbar' comments after NY terror attack|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=November 2, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102162728/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/358382-tapper-hits-fox-hannity-over-allahu-akbar-comments-after-ny-terror-attack|archive-date=2017-11-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":222\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/cnn-jake-tapper-allahu-akbar-fox-news-nyc-attack-sean-hannity-20171102.html|title=Jake Tapper feuds with Fox News, Sean Hannity over 'Allahu Akbar' comments|work=Philly.com|access-date=November 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102214409/http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/cnn-jake-tapper-allahu-akbar-fox-news-nyc-attack-sean-hannity-20171102.html|archive-date=2017-11-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Appearance at November 2018 Trump rally ===\nOn November 4, 2018, Trump's website, DonaldJTrump.com, announced in a press release that Hannity would make a \"special guest appearance\" with Trump at a midterm campaign rally the following night in Cape Girardeau, Missouri.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/04/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-rally-fox-news/index.html|title='Special Guest' Sean Hannity to appear at Trump rally|first=Brian|last=Stelter|website=[[CNN]]|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106012236/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/04/media/sean-hannity-donald-trump-rally-fox-news/index.html|archive-date=November 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The following morning, Hannity tweeted \"To be clear, I will not be on stage campaigning with the President.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/seanhannity/status/1059476042975535104|title=Sean Hannity on Twitter|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106045357/https://twitter.com/seanhannity/status/1059476042975535104|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity spoke at the president's lectern on stage at the rally, immediately mocking the \"fake news\" at the back of the auditorium, Fox News reporters among them. Several Fox News employees expressed outrage at Hannity's actions, with one stating, \"a new line was crossed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/06/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-jeanine-pirro-trump-rally/index.html|title='It disturbs me to my core': Fox News staffers express outrage over Hannity's rally appearance|first=Oliver Darcy, CNN|last=Business|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106185550/https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/06/media/fox-news-sean-hannity-jeanine-pirro-trump-rally/index.html|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=live}}</ref> Hannity later asserted that his action was not pre-planned, and Fox News stated it \"does not condone any talent participating in campaign events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/fox-news-responds-hannity-at-trump-rally-we-do-not-condone-this-unfortunate-distraction/|title=Fox News Responds to Hannity at Trump Rally: We Do 'Not Condone' This 'Unfortunate Distraction'|website=www.mediaite.com|accessdate=November 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107054236/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/fox-news-responds-hannity-at-trump-rally-we-do-not-condone-this-unfortunate-distraction/|archive-date=2018-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Fox News host [[Jeanine Pirro]] also appeared on stage with Trump at the rally. The Trump press release was later removed from Trump's website.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>https://www.donaldjtrump.com/rallies/nov-girardeau-2018/</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\nIn 2009, Hannity said of the Iraq War, \"we were victorious in spite of the Democrats' efforts and attempts at preventing victory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2010/03/revisionism-iraq-invasion-a-great-idea-after-all/346364/|title=Revisionism: Iraq Invasion a Great Idea, After All|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=March 12, 2010|website=[[The Atlantic]]|language=en-US|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Hannity called on Trump to \"bomb the hell of out Iran\" after Iran shot down a U.S. drone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/hannity-warns-iran-youre-going-to-get-the-living-crap-bombed-out-of-you|title=Hannity Warns Iran: 'You're Going to Get the Living Crap Bombed Out of You'|last=Baragona|first=Justin|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 21, 2019|access-date=July 1, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Ukraine ===\n\nIn February 2020, [[The Daily Beast]] acquired a leaked document entitled \"Ukraine, Disinformation, & the Trump Administration\" produced by a Fox News research team. The document warned of \"disinformation\" being pushed by frequent ''Hannity'' guests, including [[Rudy Giuliani]], [[John Solomon (political commentator)|John Solomon]], [[Victoria Toensing]] and [[Joe diGenova]]. Among other criticisms, the analysis noted that on his show Hannity discussed with Toensing and diGenova an affidavit from former Ukrainian prosecutor general [[Viktor Shokin]] that accused [[Joe Biden]] of getting him fired to end an investigation into [[Burisma Holdings]], which employed Biden's son. The affidavit was drafted at the request of attorneys for Ukrainian oligarch [[Dmitry Firtash]],<ref>https://time.com/5699201/exclusive-how-a-ukrainian-oligarch-wanted-by-u-s-authorities-helped-giuliani-attack-biden/</ref> but neither Hannity nor his guests disclosed to viewers that Toensing and diGenova were among Firtash's attorneys.<ref>https://www.thedailybeast.com/fox-news-internal-document-bashes-john-solomon-joe-digenova-and-rudy-giuliani-for-spreading-disinformation?ref=author</ref>\n\n=== Coronavirus outbreak ===\nIn February 2020, amid the spread of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]] to the United States, Hannity said that \"many on the left are now all rooting for corona to wreak havoc in the United States. Why? To score cheap, repulsive political points.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/business/media/coronavirus-right-wing-media.html|title=Right-Wing Media Says Virus Fears Were Whipped Up to Hurt Trump|date=2020-03-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-09|last2=Abrams|first2=Rachel|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In March 2020, he characterized the virus as a \"hoax\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/business/coronavirus-fox-news-lachlan-murdoch.html|title=Rupert Murdoch Put His Son in Charge of Fox. It Was a Dangerous Mistake.|date=2020-03-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and said that it \"may be true\" that the coronavirus outbreak was a \"fraud\" perpetrated by the \"deep state.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/us/politics/coronavirus-conservative-media.html|title=If Sean Hannity Thinks Coronavirus Panic Is a \u2018Hoax,\u2019 How Many Millions of His Listeners Do Too?|date=2020-03-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-12|last2=Grynbaum|first2=Michael M.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/coronavirus-covid-19/sean-hannity-it-may-be-true-deep-state-using-coronavirus-manipulate-markets|title=Sean Hannity: The \u201cdeep state\u201d may be using coronavirus to manipulate markets, suppress dissent and push mandated medicines|last=Staff|first=Media Matters|website=Media Matters for America|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Later in March, as the coronavirus outbreak turned into a pandemic and President Trump declared a national emergency, Hannity started to take the virus more seriously.<ref name=\":30\" /> Hannity falsely claimed that his show had taken the coronavirus pandemic seriously all along.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/us/politics/hannity-limbaugh-trump-coronavirus.html|title=Alarm, Denial, Blame: The Pro-Trump Media\u2019s Coronavirus Distortion|date=2020-04-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/20/21186727/hannity-coronavirus-coverage-fox-news|title=Hannity claims he\u2019s \"never called the virus a hoax\" 9 days after decrying Democrats\u2019 \"new hoax\"|last=Rupar|first=Aaron|date=2020-03-20|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHannity has been married to Jill Rhodes since 1993. They have two children and live on [[Long Island]], New York.<ref name=Lipton>{{cite web|last=Lipton |first=Michael A. |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20136407,00.html |title=The (Far) Right Stuff |publisher=People.com |accessdate=September 2, 2013}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated that Hannity's annual income was $36 million.<ref name=\":28\" /> In 2014 he said he has carried a weapon \"more than half my adult life\".<ref>{{cite news |last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/piers-morgan-sean-hannity-gun-control-debate-847112/ |title=Piers Morgan Resurfaces On Cable News, Talking Guns With FNC's Sean Hannity |work=Deadline Hollywood |publisher=Penske Business Media |date=October 6, 2014 |accessdate=October 7, 2014 }}{{better source|date=October 2019}}</ref> Hannity left the [[Catholic Church]] citing \u201ctoo much institutionalized corruption.\u201d However, he has said that as he as aged his Christian faith has \"gotten stronger\" and that he needs and wants God in his life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sean Hannity says faith is 'stronger' than ever after leaving Catholic Church over 'institutionalized corruption' |url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/sean-hannity-says-faith-is-stronger-than-ever-after-leaving-catholic-church-over-institutionalized-corruption.html |website=www.christianpost.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n\n=== Awards and honors ===\n* Hannity received a [[Marconi Award]] in 2003 and 2007 as the Network Syndicated Personality of the Year from the [[National Association of Broadcasters]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Sean Hannity Wins 2007 Marconi Award |publisher=[[Citadel Media]] |date=September 28, 2007 |url=http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2007releases/092807.pdf |accessdate=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029031453/http://affiliates.abcradionetworks.com/press/2007releases/092807.pdf |archivedate=October 29, 2008 }}</ref>\n* In 2009, ''[[Talkers Magazine]]'' listed Hannity as #2 on their list of the 100 most important radio talk show hosts in America (with [[Rush Limbaugh]] listed as #1).<ref name=\"Talkers\">{{cite web|url=http://talkers.com/online/?p=267 |title=Heavy Hundred |date=July\u2013August 2009 |publisher=Talkers Magazine |page=267 |accessdate=August 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903062331/http://talkers.com/online/?p=267 |archivedate=September 3, 2010 }}</ref> The same magazine gave Hannity his Freedom of Speech Award in 2003.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_Nov_29/ai_n15882509 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120716032330/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_Nov_29/ai_n15882509 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 16, 2012 |title=Sean Hannity and Michael Medved Shows Come to News Talk 590 KTIE-AM |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |date=November 29, 2005 |accessdate=October 16, 2008}}</ref>\n* In 2005, Jerry Falwell, chancellor of the evangelical [[Liberty University]], awarded Hannity an honorary degree.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jared |last=Pierce |title=Hannity to speak at Liberty |url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/communications/champion/index.cfm?PID=10609&CAID=217 |work=The Liberty Champion |date=April 17, 2007 |accessdate=October 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219025025/http://www.liberty.edu/academics/communications/champion/index.cfm?PID=10609&CAID=217 |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n* Hannity was inducted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]] in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/sean-hannity-gets-inducted-into-the-national-radio-hall-of-fame/347308|title=Sean Hannity Gets Inducted Into the National Radio Hall of Fame|last=Katz|first=A. J.|website=TVNewser|date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Hannity, Sean (2002). ''[[Let Freedom Ring: Winning the War of Liberty over Liberalism]]'', [[ReganBooks]], {{ISBN|0-06-051455-8}}.\n* Hannity, Sean (2004). ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism]]'', ReganBooks, {{ISBN|0-06-058251-0}}.\n* Hannity, Sean (2010). ''[[Conservative Victory: Defeating Obama's Radical Agenda]]'', [[HarperCollins|Harper Paperbacks]], {{ISBN|0-06-200305-4}}.\n\n== See also ==\n*''[[The Sean Hannity Show]]''\n*[[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.hannity.com}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Sean Hannity}}\n\n{{Sean Hannity}}\n{{Fox News Personalities}}\n{{Conservatism US footer}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Conservatism|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hannity, Sean}}\n[[Category:Sean Hannity| ]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Adelphi University alumni]]\n[[Category:American broadcast news analysts]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American conservative talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of New York State politicians]]\n[[Category:Environmental skepticism]]\n[[Category:Far-right politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Centre Island, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Franklin Square, New York]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Iamreallygoodatcheckers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sean_Hannity"}
{"title_page": "Mike Dodd (soccer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Mike Dodd\n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        = \n|fullname       = Michael Dodd \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|4|24}}\n|birth_place    = [[North Vancouver (city)|North Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n|height         = \n|position       = [[Midfielder]]\n|youthyears1    = 1989\u20131990\n|youthclubs1    = [[Capilano College]]\n|years1         = 1991\u20131993\n|clubs1         = [[Winnipeg Fury]]\n|caps1          = \n|goals1         =\n|years2         = 1993\n|clubs2         = \u2192 [[Vancouver 86ers]] (loan)\n|caps2          = 3\n|goals2         = 0\n|years3         = 1994\u20131998\n|clubs3         = [[Vancouver 86ers]]\n|caps3          = 31\n|goals3         = 2\n|totalcaps      = \n|totalgoals     = \n|nationalyears1 = 1991\u20131992\n|nationalteam1  = [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada U23]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 10\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Mike Dodd''' (born April 24, 1971) is a Canadian former [[soccer player]]. \n\n== Career ==\nDodd began playing at the [[College soccer|college level]] in 1989 with [[Capilano College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://athletics.capilanou.ca/sports/msoc/1989-90/roster|title=1989 Capilano Men's Soccer Roster|website=Capilano University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> In 1991, he was drafted by the [[Vancouver 86ers]] of the [[Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992)|Canadian Soccer League]] (CSL), but was loaned to the [[Winnipeg Fury]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasljerseys.com/ASL/Rosters/Fury_Rosters.htm|title=Winnipeg Fury Rosters|website=www.nasljerseys.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/winnipeg-free-press-jul-07-1991-p-20/|title=Changes in works for Fury|last=Paraskevas|first=Joe|date=July 7, 1991|website=NewspaperArchive.com|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|page=20|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> In 1992, he signed a contract with Winnipeg and secured the Mita Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/winnipeg-free-press-jan-28-1992-p-38/|title=Fury ecstatic with drafting|last=Prest|first=Ashley|date=January 28, 1992|website=NewspaperArchive.com|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|page=38|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> After the demise of the CSL the Fury joined the [[Canadian National Soccer League]], and he re-signed with Winnipeg.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/winnipeg-free-press-may-21-1993-p-30/|title=Fury expect high-scoring tilt|last=McDonald|first=Marvin|date=May 21, 1993|website=NewspaperArchive.com|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|page=30|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> During the 1993 season he was temporarily loaned to the Vancouver 86ers of the [[American Professional Soccer League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/495211886/?terms=mike+dodd|title=Reinforcements arrive to help fill up 86ers' roster|last=|first=|date=August 12, 1993|website=Newspapers.com|publisher=Vancouver Sun|page=46|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soccerstats.us/bios/mike-dodd/|title=Mike Dodd {{!}} SoccerStats.us|website=soccerstats.us|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\nIn 1994, he permanently signed with Vancouver, and played with them until the [[1998 USISL A-League]] season.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lodes|first=Kirk J.|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=IEtLjtqaCTgC&pg=PA1086&lpg=PA1086&dq=mike+dodd+vancouver&source=bl&ots=t-w0ZiqIu8&sig=ACfU3U1PP5NJksDkvkuDyfPVgG5fb-O-SA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiq-bjli-voAhWFVs0KHcEaBOw4ChDoATACegQICxAn#v=onepage&q=mike%20dodd%20vancouver&f=false|title=The American Soccer Guide|date=2008|publisher=Kirk Lodes|isbn=978-1-930852-09-9|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/327842877/?terms=mike+dodd+Vancouver+86ers|title=Stats Review|last=|first=|date=September 7, 1994|website=Newspapers.com|publisher=Richmond Review|page=37|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> In 1998, he was inducted into the [[Manitoba Sports Hall of Fame and Museum]] as a member of the 1992 Winnipeg Fury team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://honouredmembers.sportmanitoba.ca/inductee.php?id=391&criteria_sort=name|title=Honoured Members Database {{!}} Manitoba Sports Hall of Fame|website=honouredmembers.sportmanitoba.ca|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n== International career  ==\nHe made his debut for the [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team]] on May 5, 1991 against [[Trinidad and Tobago national under-23 football team|Trinidad and Tobago]] in a [[1992 CONCACAF Men's Pre-Olympic Tournament|Olympic qualifier match]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/?pid=989&t=profile&|title=Canada Soccer|website=www.canadasoccer.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992)|Canadian Soccer League]]: 1'''\n:: 1992\n\n== References ==\n<references /> \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dodd, Mike}}\n\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Fury players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Whitecaps (1986\u20132010) players]]\n[[Category:Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992) players]]\n[[Category:Canadian National Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:American Professional Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:USISL A-League players]]\n[[Category:Soccer people from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:People from North Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from North Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Mike Dodd\n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        = \n|fullname       = Michael Dodd \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|4|24}}\n|birth_place    = [[North Vancouver (city)|North Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n|height         = \n|position       = [[Midfielder]]\n|youthyears1    = 1989\u20131990\n|youthclubs1    = [[Capilano College]]\n|years1         = 1991\u20131993\n|clubs1         = [[Winnipeg Fury]]\n|caps1          = \n|goals1         =\n|years2         = 1993\n|clubs2         = \u2192 [[Vancouver 86ers]] (loan)\n|caps2          = 3\n|goals2         = 0\n|years3         = 1994\u20131998\n|clubs3         = [[Vancouver 86ers]]\n|caps3          = 31\n|goals3         = 2\n|totalcaps      = \n|totalgoals     = \n|nationalyears1 = 1991\u20131992\n|nationalteam1  = [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada U23]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 10\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Mike Dodd''' (born April 24, 1971) is an Canadian former [[soccer player]]. \n\n== Career ==\nDodd began playing at the [[College soccer|college level]] in 1989 with [[Capilano College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://athletics.capilanou.ca/sports/msoc/1989-90/roster|title=1989 Capilano Men's Soccer Roster|website=Capilano University|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> In 1991, he was drafted by the [[Vancouver 86ers]] of the [[Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992)|Canadian Soccer League]] (CSL), but was loaned to the [[Winnipeg Fury]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasljerseys.com/ASL/Rosters/Fury_Rosters.htm|title=Winnipeg Fury Rosters|website=www.nasljerseys.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/winnipeg-free-press-jul-07-1991-p-20/|title=Changes in works for Fury|last=Paraskevas|first=Joe|date=July 7, 1991|website=NewspaperArchive.com|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|page=20|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> In 1992, he signed a contract with Winnipeg and secured the Mita Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/winnipeg-free-press-jan-28-1992-p-38/|title=Fury ecstatic with drafting|last=Prest|first=Ashley|date=January 28, 1992|website=NewspaperArchive.com|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|page=38|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> After the demise of the CSL the Fury joined the [[Canadian National Soccer League]], and he re-signed with Winnipeg.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/winnipeg-free-press-may-21-1993-p-30/|title=Fury expect high-scoring tilt|last=McDonald|first=Marvin|date=May 21, 1993|website=NewspaperArchive.com|publisher=Winnipeg Free Press|page=30|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> During the 1993 season he was temporarily loaned to the Vancouver 86ers of the [[American Professional Soccer League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/495211886/?terms=mike+dodd|title=Reinforcements arrive to help fill up 86ers' roster|last=|first=|date=August 12, 1993|website=Newspapers.com|publisher=Vancouver Sun|page=46|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soccerstats.us/bios/mike-dodd/|title=Mike Dodd {{!}} SoccerStats.us|website=soccerstats.us|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\nIn 1994, he permanently signed with Vancouver, and played with them until the [[1998 USISL A-League]] season.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lodes|first=Kirk J.|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=IEtLjtqaCTgC&pg=PA1086&lpg=PA1086&dq=mike+dodd+vancouver&source=bl&ots=t-w0ZiqIu8&sig=ACfU3U1PP5NJksDkvkuDyfPVgG5fb-O-SA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiq-bjli-voAhWFVs0KHcEaBOw4ChDoATACegQICxAn#v=onepage&q=mike%20dodd%20vancouver&f=false|title=The American Soccer Guide|date=2008|publisher=Kirk Lodes|isbn=978-1-930852-09-9|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/327842877/?terms=mike+dodd+Vancouver+86ers|title=Stats Review|last=|first=|date=September 7, 1994|website=Newspapers.com|publisher=Richmond Review|page=37|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> In 1998, he was inducted into the [[Manitoba Sports Hall of Fame and Museum]] as a member of the 1992 Winnipeg Fury team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://honouredmembers.sportmanitoba.ca/inductee.php?id=391&criteria_sort=name|title=Honoured Members Database {{!}} Manitoba Sports Hall of Fame|website=honouredmembers.sportmanitoba.ca|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n== International career  ==\nHe made his debut for the [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team]] on May 5, 1991 against [[Trinidad and Tobago national under-23 football team|Trinidad and Tobago]] in a [[1992 CONCACAF Men's Pre-Olympic Tournament|Olympic qualifier match]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/?pid=989&t=profile&|title=Canada Soccer|website=www.canadasoccer.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992)|Canadian Soccer League]]: 1'''\n:: 1992\n\n== References ==\n<references /> \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dodd, Mike}}\n\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Fury players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Whitecaps (1986\u20132010) players]]\n[[Category:Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992) players]]\n[[Category:Canadian National Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:American Professional Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:USISL A-League players]]\n[[Category:Soccer people from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:People from North Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from North Vancouver]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Dodd_(soccer)"}
{"title_page": "Port Pirie", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Port Pirie (disambiguation){{!}}Port Pirie}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = city\n|name          = Port Pirie\n|state         = sa\n|image         = Port Pirie1.JPG\n|caption       = The lead smelter and grain silos at the wharf of Port Pirie\n|pop           = 14188\n|pop_year      = 2018\n|pop_footnotes = <ref name=ABSSUA>{{cite web|title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2017-18: Population Estimates by Significant Urban Area, 2008 to 2018|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3218.02017-18|website=Australian Bureau of Statistics|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=25 October 2019}} Estimated resident population, 30 June 2018.</ref>\n|poprank       =\n|postcode      = 5540\n|density       =\n|est           = 1845\n|elevation     = 4\n|coordinates   = {{coord|33|11|9|S|138|1|1|E|display=inline,title}}\n|area          =\n|timezone      = [[Australian Central Standard Time|ACST]]\n|utc           = +9:30\n|timezone-dst  = [[Australian Central Daylight Time|ACDT]]\n|utc-dst       = +10:30\n|lga           = Port Pirie Regional Council\n|stategov      = [[Electoral district of Frome|Frome]]\n|fedgov        = [[Division of Grey|Grey]]\n|dist1         = 223\n|location1     = Adelaide\n}}\n\n'''Port Pirie''' is a city  and [[seaport]] on the east coast of the [[Spencer Gulf]] in [[South Australia]], {{convert|223|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}<ref>UBD South Australia and Northern Territory Country Road Atlas, 6th Edition, 2005. Universal Publishers Pty Ltd. {{ISBN|0 7319 1606 9}}</ref> north of the state capital, [[Adelaide]]. The settlement was founded in 1845 and at June 2018 had an estimated urban population of 14,188. Port Pirie is the seventh most populous city in [[South Australia]] after [[Adelaide]], [[Mount Gambier]], [[Gawler, South Australia|Gawler]], [[Mount Barker, South Australia|Mount Barker,]] [[Whyalla]], [[Murray Bridge, South Australia|Murray Bridge.]] \n\nThe city's economy is dominated by one of the world's largest [[lead]] [[Lead smelting|smelters]],<ref name=\"ABC2018\">[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-08/port-pirie-lead-smelter-risk-of-breaching-licence-to-operate/10476916 Port Pirie's lead smelter at risk of breaching licence to operate due to spike in lead levels] ''ABC News'', 8 November 2018. Retrieved 14 November 2019.</ref> operated by [[Nyrstar]].<ref name=\"Zinifex PP\">{{cite web |url=http://zinifex.com/Index.aspx?link_id=18.778 |title=Port Pirie Overview |accessdate=12 December 2006 |publisher=Nyrstar Limited |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060819231756/http://www.zinifex.com/Index.aspx?link_id=18.778 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 19 August 2006}}</ref> The smelter is currently undergoing a $650 million upgrade to replace some of the old existing plant and to reduce airborne lead emissions drastically. It also produces refined [[silver]], [[zinc]], [[copper]] and [[gold]]. Port Pirie is the largest city and the main retail centre of the [[Mid North]] region of South Australia.\n\n==History==\nPrior to European settlement, the location that became Port Pirie was occupied by the indigenous tribe of [[Nukunu]]. The location was called 'Tarparrie', which is suspected to mean \"Muddy Creek\". The first European to see the location was [[Matthew Flinders]] in 1802 as he explored the Spencer Gulf by boat. The first land discovery by settlers of the location was by the explorer [[Edward Eyre]] who explored regions around [[Port Augusta, South Australia|Port Augusta]]. [[John Ainsworth Horrocks|John Horrocks]] also discovered a pass through the Flinders Ranges to the coast, now named ''[[Horrocks Pass]]''.\n\nThe town was originally called Samuel's Creek after the discovery of Muddy Creek by [[Ben Germein#Family|Samuel Germein]]. In 1846, Port Pirie Creek was named by Governor Robe after the {{ship||John Pirie|ship|2}}, the first vessel to navigate the creek when transporting sheep from Bowman's Run near Crystal Brook. In 1848, Matthew Smith and [[Emanuel Solomon]] bought {{convert|85|acre|ha}} and subdivided it as a township to be known as Port Pirie. Little development occurred on site and by the late 1860s there were only three woolsheds on the riverfront.<ref>Erik Eklund, ''[http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/163809700?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1370392639995&versionId=178587537 Mining Towns: making a living, making a life']', New South Publishing, Sydney, 2012, p. 137</ref>\n\nThe government town was surveyed in December 1871 by Charles Hope Harris. The thoroughfares and streets were named after the family of [[George Goyder]], Surveyor General of South Australia, with the streets running parallel and at right angles to the river. In 1873 the land of Solomon and Smith was re-surveyed and named Solomontown. On 28 September 1876, Port Pirie was declared a municipality, with a population of 947.\n\nWith the discovery of rich silver-, lead- and zinc-bearing ore at [[Broken Hill]] in 1883, and the completion of a narrow gauge railway from Port Pirie to close to the Broken Hill field in 1888, the economic activities of the town shifted. In 1889 a lead smelter was built by the British Blocks company to treat Broken Hill ore. [[Broken Hill Proprietary]] initially leased the smelter from British Blocks and then began constructing their own smelter from 1892. In 1913 the Russian consul-general [[Alexander Nikolayevich Abaza|Alexander Abaza]] reported that Port Pirie had a population of over 500 Russians, mostly [[Ossetians]], who had come to work at the smelter. The town supported a Russian-language school and library.<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/n4325/pdf/ch08.pdf|chapter=Alexander Abaza|title=A New Rival State?: Australia in Tsarist Diplomatic Communications|year=2018|publisher=ANU Press|editor-first1=Alexander|editor-last1=Massov|editor-first2=Marina|editor-last2=Pollard|editor-first3=Kevin|editor-last3=Windle|page=304}}</ref>\n\nIn 1915 the smelter was taken over by a major joint venture of Broken Hill-based companies, Broken Hill Associated Smelters (BHAS). Led by the Collins House Group, BHAS became the biggest lead smelter in the world by 1934.<ref>Eklund, ''[http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/163809700?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1370392639995&versionId=178587537 Mining Towns]'', pp. 137-138.</ref> The smelter gradually passed to [[Pasminco]], then [[Zinifex]], and is now operated by [[Nyrstar]].\n\nBy 1921 the town's population had grown to 9801 living in 2308 occupied dwellings. By this date there were also 62 boarding houses to cater for the labour demands at the smelter and on the increasingly busy waterfront.<ref>Eklund, [http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/163809700?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1370392639995&versionId=178587537 Mining Towns], pp. 143-144.</ref> Port Pirie was declared South Australia's first provincial city in 1953, and today it is South Australia's second largest port. It is characterised by a gracious main street and some interesting and unusual historic buildings.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/South-Australia/Port-Pirie/2005/02/17/1108500204638.html \"Port Pirie\"], Travel section, smh.com.au, 17 February 2005. Retrieved on 28 June 2008.</ref>\n\n===Heritage listings===\n[[File:Pt Pirie butcher 21503.jpg|thumb|This former Sampson's butcher shop at 64-68 Ellen Street, Port Pirie, has been converted into a residence.]]\nPort Pirie has a number of heritage-listed sites, including:\n\n* 1 Alexander Street: [[Barrier Chambers Offices]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13524 | title=Barrier Chambers Offices | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 32 Ellen Street: [[Adelaide Steamship Company Building]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13525 | title=Former Adelaide Steamship Company Building | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 64-68 Ellen Street: [[Sampson's Butcher Shop]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13526 | title=Dwelling (former Sampson's Butcher Shop) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 69-71 Ellen Street: [[Port Pirie Customs House]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13528 | title=National Trust Museum (former Port Pirie Customs House) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 73-77 Ellen Street: [[Port Pirie (Ellen Street) railway station]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13529 | title=National Trust Museum (former Port Pirie Railway Station) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 79-81 Ellen Street: [[Port Pirie Post Office]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13530 | title=Port Pirie Post Office | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 85 Ellen Street: [[Development Board Building, Port Pirie|Development Board Building]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13527 | title=Development Board Building (former Port Pirie Courthouse, later Customs House) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 94 Ellen Street: Sample Rooms, rear of [[Portside Tavern]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13531 | title=Sample Rooms, rear of Jubilee (former Royal Exchange) Hotel | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 134 Ellen Street: [[Family Hotel, Port Pirie|Family Hotel]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13532 | title=Family Hotel | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 32 Florence Street: [[Carn Brae]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13533 | title=Dwelling ('Carn Brae') | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 50-52 Florence Street: [[Waterside Workers' Federation Building, Port Pirie|Waterside Workers' Federation Building]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13534 | title=Waterside Workers' Federation (former Amalgamated Workers' Association) Building | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 105 Gertrude Street: [[Good Samaritan Catholic Convent School]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13535 | title=Good Samaritan Catholic Convent School | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* Memorial Drive: [[Second World War Memorial Gates, Port Pirie|Second World War Memorial Gates]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13536 | title=Second World War Memorial Gates | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 5 Norman Street: [[AMP Society Building, Port Pirie]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13537 | title=Former AMP [Australian Mutual Provident Society] Port Pirie Office Building | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2006 Census, the population of the Port Pirie census area was 13,206 people. Approximately 51.8% of the population were female, 86.9% are Australian born, over 92.7% of residents are Australian citizens and 2.6% were Aboriginal people.\n\nThe most popular industries for employment were Basic Non-Ferrous Metal Manufacturing (9.7%), School Education (6%), Hospitality (only including hotels) (11%),{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Health (5.4%) and Animal Husbandry (4%), while the unemployment rate is approx. 11%. The median weekly household income is A$608 or more per week, compared with $924 in Adelaide. 27.1% of the population identify themselves as [[Catholic]], while 23.7% identify with no religion at all.<ref name=\"ABS\">{{Census 2006 AUS | id = UCL422200 | name = Port Pirie (Urban Centre/Locality) | quick = on | accessdate=28 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nPort Pirie is at an elevation of 4 metres above [[sea level]]. It is approximately {{convert|8|km}} inland, on the Pirie River, which is a tidal saltwater inlet from [[Spencer Gulf]]. It is on the coastal plain between Spencer Gulf (to the west) and the [[Flinders Ranges]] to the east.\n\n==Climate==\nPort Pirie exists in a region with a [[semi-arid climate]], outside [[Goyder's Line]], surrounded by [[mallee Woodlands and Shrublands|mallee]] scrub. Average daily maximum temperatures vary from a mild 16.4&nbsp;\u00b0C in winter to 32.0&nbsp;\u00b0C in summer. Its average annual rainfall is 345.2 millimetres, most of which falls in winter.\n\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Port Pirie has a warm semi-arid climate, noted as ''BSh''.\n\n{{Weather box\n| location     = Port Pirie\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line  = Yes\n| Jan record high C = 48.6\n| Feb record high C = 45.5\n| Mar record high C = 42.5\n| Apr record high C = 37.7\n| May record high C = 31.0\n| Jun record high C = 25.5\n| Jul record high C = 26.5\n| Aug record high C = 30.0\n| Sep record high C = 35.0\n| Oct record high C = 39.5\n| Nov record high C = 44.0\n| Dec record high C = 46.6\n| year record high C = 48.6\n| Jan high C = 32.0\n| Feb high C = 31.8\n| Mar high C = 29.4\n| Apr high C = 24.8\n| May high C = 20.4\n| Jun high C = 17.1\n| Jul high C = 16.4\n| Aug high C = 18.1\n| Sep high C = 21.3\n| Oct high C = 24.5\n| Nov high C = 27.7\n| Dec high C = 30.0\n| year high C = 24.4\n| Jan low C = 17.7\n| Feb low C = 17.9\n| Mar low C = 16.0\n| Apr low C = 13.2\n| May low C = 10.7\n| Jun low C = 8.4\n| Jul low C = 7.7\n| Aug low C = 8.2\n| Sep low C = 9.8\n| Oct low C = 11.9\n| Nov low C = 14.4\n| Dec low C = 16.3\n| year low C = 12.7\n| Jan record low C = 4.8\n| Feb record low C = 7.1\n| Mar record low C = 7.4\n| Apr record low C = 4.4\n| May record low C = -0.6\n| Jun record low C = -1.7\n| Jul record low C = -0.6\n| Aug record low C = 0.3\n| Sep record low C = 0.6\n| Oct record low C = 1.1\n| Nov record low C = 1.1\n| Dec record low C = 4.4\n| year record low C = -1.7\n| Jan precipitation mm = 18.6\n| Feb precipitation mm = 17.8\n| Mar precipitation mm = 18.6\n| Apr precipitation mm = 27.5\n| May precipitation mm = 38.2\n| Jun precipitation mm = 40.7\n| Jul precipitation mm = 33.9\n| Aug precipitation mm = 34.9\n| Sep precipitation mm = 35.5\n| Oct precipitation mm = 33.1\n| Nov precipitation mm = 24.1\n| Dec precipitation mm = 23.0\n| year precipitation mm = 345.9\n| source 1 = [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology]]<ref>{{BoM Aust stats|site_ref=cw_021043|site_name=Port Pirie Nyrstar Comparison AWS|accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n| date     = February 2014\n}}\n\n==Transport==\nPort Pirie is {{convert|5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} off the [[Augusta Highway]]. It is serviced by [[Port Pirie Airport]], six kilometres south of the city.\n\n=== Railways ===\nThe first railway in Port Pirie opened in 1875 when the [[South Australian Railways]] {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge [[Crystal Brook-Broken Hill railway line|Port Pirie-Cockburn line]] opened to [[Gladstone railway station, South Australia|Gladstone]], ultimately being extended to [[Broken Hill railway station|Broken Hill]].<ref>Wilson, John, ''Port Pirie - The Narrow Gauge Era (1873\u20131935)'', [[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]], March 1970, pp. 49\u201362</ref> The original Ellen Street station was located on the street with the track running down the middle.<ref>Bakewell, Guy and Wilson, John, ''Farewell to Ellen Street'', [[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]] September 1968, pp. 210\u2013213</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ward|first1=Andrew|title=Railway Stations of Australia|date=1982|publisher=MacMillan Company of Australia|location=South Melbourne|isbn=0 333338 53 7|pages=60\u201361}}</ref> The station today is occupied by the Port Pirie National Trust Museum.<ref>[http://www.southaustralia.com/info.aspx?id=9000743 Port Pirie National Trust Museum] Explore South Australia</ref>\n\nIn 1937, it became a [[break-of-gauge]] station when the broad gauge [[Adelaide-Port Augusta railway line|Adelaide-Redhill line]] was extended to Port Pirie. At the same time the [[Commonwealth Railways]] [[standard gauge]] [[Trans-Australian Railway]] was extended south from [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]] to terminate at the new [[Port Pirie Junction railway station|Port Pirie Junction station]] where it met the broad gauge line, in the suburb of Solomontown.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article30759205 Solomontown Railway Station] ''[[Adelaide Advertiser]] 14 July 1937</ref><ref>[http://www.natrailmuseum.org.au/downloads/documents/Multi_Gauge_Muddle.compressed.pdf Port Pirie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228020700/http://natrailmuseum.org.au/downloads/documents/Multi_Gauge_Muddle.compressed.pdf |date=28 February 2016 }} National Railway Museum</ref>\n\nAs far back as 1943, a plan existed to build a new station to remove trains from Ellen Street.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96357055 Council Wants No Trains in Ellen Street] ''[[The Recorder (Port Pirie)|The Recorder]]'' 31 March 1943</ref> As part of the [[Track gauge conversion|gauge conversion]] of the [[Crystal Brook-Broken Hill railway line|Port Pirie to Broken Hill line]], [[Port Pirie (Mary Elie Street) railway station|Mary Elie Street station]] was built to replace both Ellen Street and Port Pirie Junction stations.<ref>[http://www.atrf.info/papers/1976/1976_Webb.pdf The Planning & Evaluation of Rail Standardisation Projects in Australia] GR Webb 1976</ref>\n\nWhen opened, the new station was the meeting point for the [[Commonwealth Railways]] and [[South Australian Railways]] networks with through trains changing locomotives and crews, so the disadvantages were not as notable. However, after both became part of [[Australian National Railways Commission|Australian National]] in July 1975 and trains began to operate in and out with the same locomotives, trains began to operate via [[Coonamia railway station|Coonamia station]] on the outskirts of the city.\n\nMary Ellie Street station was eventually closed in the 1990s and in 2009 was redeveloped as the city's library. Until 2012, a [[Commonwealth Railways GM class|GM class locomotive]] and three carriages were stabled at the platform.<ref>[http://www.westonlangford.com/images/photo/127936/ Port Pirie Marie Elie Street Display] Western Langford Railway Photography</ref>\n\n=== Sea transport ===\n\nPort Pirie's marine facilities, managed by [[Flinders Ports]], handle up to 100 ship visits annually, up to [[Handymax]] size, for  commodities such as mineral concentrates, refined lead and zinc, coal, grain, and general cargo.<ref>[https://www.pirie.sa.gov.au/about-council/business-and-investment/access-to-prime-infrastructure Access to Prime Infrastructure] Port Pirie Regional Council. Retrieved 26 February 2020.</ref>\n\n==Industry and employment==\n{{Update|Zinifex which has spun out and floated Nyrstar owning the smelters|date=March 2009}}\nThe main industries are the [[smelting]] of metals, and the operation of [[Storage silo|silos]] to hold grain.\n\nPort Pirie's main employer is Nyrstar, which operates the largest lead smelter/refinery in the southern hemisphere.<ref name=\"Zinifex PP\"/> A lead smelter has been operating in Port Pirie since the 1880s, and high blood lead levels in the local population are an ongoing concern.<ref name=\"ABC2018\" /> The Stack, which can be seen kilometres away, is 205 metres tall, and is the tallest structure in the state.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} In 2006 Zinifex formed a joint venture with [[Umicore]] to create Nyrstar, which owns the smelter, with the intention that it would eventually be an entity separate from the parent companies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zinifex and Umicore seek to create the world's leading producer of zinc metal |url=http://asx.com.au/asx/statistics/showAnnouncementPDF.do?idsID=00677174 |publisher=[[Australian Securities Exchange|ASX]] |work=Zinifex Limited |accessdate=12 December 2006 |date=12 December 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070325234959/http://asx.com.au/asx/statistics/showAnnouncementPDF.do?idsID=00677174 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 25 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2006/12/12/1165685650493.html |title=Zinifex, Umicore to combine zinc assets |date=12 December 2006 |accessdate=12 December 2006 |publisher=[[The Age]]}}</ref>\n\nFlinders Industrial, a new industrial estate, is currently{{When|date=March 2009}} in its second stage and is planned to be home to the new council depot.{{When|date=March 2009}} There were plans to build a sulphuric acid plant for the benefit of the Nyrstar Smelter, but this project has been shelved and deemed not feasible.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\n===Development===\nA new $3.3 million cultural precinct was completed in 2010 built by the [[Port Pirie Regional Council]] in partnership with the Federal Government. A committee is also looking at building a [[multi-purpose stadium]]. The swimming pool is now state of the art after receiving a $1 million refit. A major Waste Recovery Facility was opened in 2013, which allows all waste and recycled material to be sorted and sorted under one roof. In 2012 [[Port Pirie Regional Council]] completed a $5m Community Water Recycling project with Nyrstar which allows 350ML of water to be reused from the smelter. Plans are underway to establish a large shopping complex in the city with an additional supermarket and department store. The city's population is continually growing and property prices continue to rise. The Port Pirie Regional Council has a number of large projects that will be launched or completed next financial year.\n\n===Waterfront development===\nThe PPRC completed a major redevelopment of its foreshore area in 2014 including the construction of the Solomontown Beach Plaza, opening up Beach abroad to through traffic, replacing lighting along the beach as well as improvements to security in the region. In addition, by the end of 2014, the council aims to replace and duplicate the current Solomontown boat ramp and undertake dredging in the vicinity of the ramp. This investment is aimed at creating a waterfront which will revitalise the area from the Main Road boat ramp up to the area off Ellen street.\n\n==Tenby10 (Lead levels)==\n{{Further|Lead poisoning}}\nLead smelters contribute to several environmental problems, especially raised blood lead levels in some of the town population. The problem is particularly significant in many children who have grown up in the area. There is a government project to address this.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.sa.gov.au/pehs/branches/branch-ptpirie.htm |title=Pt Pirie Environmental Health Centre |accessdate=11 June 2006 }}</ref> Nyrstar plans to progressively reduce lead in blood levels such that ultimately 95% of all children meet the national goal of 10 micrograms per decilitre. This has been known as the tenby10 project. Community lead in blood levels in children are now at less than half the level that they were in the mid 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zinifex.com/index.aspx?link_id=18.779 |title=Zinifex Port Pirie Strategy |accessdate=4 May 2007 |publisher=Zinifex Limited |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928222714/http://www.zinifex.com/index.aspx?link_id=18.779 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 28 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Port Pirie smelter has a project underway to reduce [[Lead poisoning|lead levels]] in children to under 10 micrograms per decilitre by the end of 2010.<ref name=\"tenby10.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tenby10.com/Index|title=10 by Ten \u2013 10 Ways To Have An Impact|website=www.tenby10.com|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The goal we are committed to achieving is for at least 95% of our children aged 0 to 4 to have a blood lead level below ten micrograms per decilitre of blood (the first ten in tenby10) by the end of 2010 (the second ten in tenby10).\"<ref name=\"tenby10.com\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nHigher concentrations of lead have been found in the organs of bottlenose dolphins stranded near the lead smelter, compared to dolphins stranded elsewhere in South Australia.<ref>Lavery, T.J., Butterfield, N., Kemper, C.M., Reid, R.J., Sanderson, K. 2008. ''Metals and selenium in the liver and bone of three dolphin species from South Australia, 1988\u20132004.'' Science of the Total Environment, 390: 77\u201385</ref> The health impacts of these metals on dolphins has been examined and some associations between high metal concentrations and kidney toxicity were noted.<ref>Lavery, T.J., Kemper, C.M., Sanderson, K., Schultz, C.G., Coyle, P., Mitchell, J.G., Seuront, L. 2008. ''Heavy metal toxicity of kidney and bone tissues in South Australian adult bottlenose dolphins (Tursiops aduncus)'', {{doi|10.1016/jmarenvres.2008.09.005}}</ref>\n\n==Education and culture ==\n[[File:Port Pirie Railway Station.jpg|thumb|250px|The former [[Port Pirie (Ellen Street) railway station|Ellen Street railway station]] now a museum]]\nPort Pirie is the main centre for the [[Mid North]] area. Many towns in the area rely on Port Pirie for shopping and employment. It also has many educational institutions such as [[Risdon Park High School|John Pirie Secondary School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnpirihs.sa.edu.au|title=Welcome to John Pirie Secondary School's website|website=www.johnpirihs.sa.edu.au|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> (years 8-12), St Mark's College<ref>[http://www.stmarks.pp.catholic.edu.au/ St Mark's College] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091030074553/http://stmarks.pp.catholic.edu.au/ |date=30 October 2009 }}</ref> (reception - year 12), Mid North Christian College<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midnorthcc.sa.edu.au/|title=Mid North Christian College - Port Pirie, SA - Home|website=www.midnorthcc.sa.edu.au|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> (reception - year 12), many preschools and primary schools, and a [[Technical and Further Education|TAFE]] Campus (Adult Education).\n\nPort Pirie is home to the National Trust Historic and Folk Museum and Memorial Park. Every September and October it hosts a country music festival. It has significant Italian & Greek communities. The ''Keith Michell Theatre'', within the Northern Festival Centre, is named after the actor [[Keith Michell]] who grew up in [[Warnertown, South Australia|Warnertown]], {{convert|5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from Port Pirie.\n\n==Media==\nThe town's main newspaper, ''[[The Recorder (Port Pirie)|The Recorder]],'' was first published 21 March 1885 as ''The Port Pirie Advocate and Areas News''. In 1971, a brief experiment, known as the ''Northern Observer'' (7 July - 30 August 1971), occurred when ''The Recorder'' and ''[[The Transcontinental]]'' from Port Augusta were published under a combined title in Port Pirie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guides.slsa.sa.gov.au/c.php?g=410317&p=2796365|title=LibGuides: SA Newspapers: M-N|last=Laube|first=Anthony|website=guides.slsa.sa.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref> ''The Recorder'', which is still in print today (Tuesdays and Thursdays), has recently changed to a morning paper, after being delivered at around 3:00 pm.<ref>[http://www.portpirierecorder.com.au/about-us/ ''The Recorder'' - About Us] Accessed 2 June 2013.</ref> Other Port Pirie newspapers include the free ''[[The Flinders News]]'' (Wednesdays), and ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'', which covers some Port Pirie news, but to a very small extent.\n\nAnother newspaper, the ''[[The Port Pirie Advertiser|Port Pirie Advertiser]]'' (7 April 1898 \u2013 28 June 1924) was also published locally by Robert Osborne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.samemory.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm?c=6275|title=Port Pirie advertiser|website=www.samemory.sa.gov.au|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> A further publication was the short-lived ''Saturday Times'' (6 December 1913 \u2013 15 August 1914), printed by Roy Harold Butler and closed at the start of the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guides.slsa.sa.gov.au/c.php?g=410317&p=2796357|title=LibGuides: SA Newspapers: S|last=Laube|first=Anthony|website=guides.slsa.sa.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-08-24}}</ref> Another former publication was the ''Port Pirie Star'' (1971-1972). Another previous publication, called ''Desert Sun'' (December 1973-July 1974), and published bi-monthly by the Flinders Travel Service and [[Commonwealth Railways]], was aimed at people interested in, or travelling on, the [[Indian Pacific|Indian-Pacific]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guides.slsa.sa.gov.au/c.php?g=410317&p=2796332|title=LibGuides: SA Newspapers: C-E|last=Laube|first=Anthony|website=guides.slsa.sa.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref>\n\nTelevision coverage is broad. [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] and [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] are available in the city with [[Southern Cross Austereo|Southern Cross]] (7, 9 and 10) as well as [[Austar]]. Several radio stations cover Port Pirie including ABC 639AM, ABC 891AM, 1044 5CS, 1242 5AU, [[triple j]], Magic FM and Trax FM (a community station).\n\n==Politics==\n===State & Federal===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em\"\n! colspan=\"4\" | Port Pirie West<br />State Elections\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n!2006<ref>[http://results.aec.gov.au/13745/website/HousePollingPlaceFirstPrefs-13745-6983.htm Port Pirie West Polling Booth], District of Frome, House of Assembly Division First Preferences, 2006 State Election. Retrieved on 28 June 2008.</ref>\n!2009<ref>[http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/byelection2009/results/polling516.htm Port Pirie West Polling Booth], District of Frome, House of Assembly Division First Preferences, 2009 By-election, 24 January 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 60.2%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 36.6%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 28.8%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 16.9%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Family First}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Family First Party|Family First]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 5.7%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Greens}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Greens|SA Greens]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 3.4%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 2.6%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Democrats}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Democrats|Democrats]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 1.9%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#D8D8D8\" |&nbsp;\n| [[Geoff Brock]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 40.9%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Nationals}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian National Party|Nationals SA]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 2.4%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|One Nation}}|&nbsp;\n| [[One Nation (Australia)|One Nation]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 0.5%\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em\"\n! colspan = 3 | Port Pirie West<br />2007 Federal Election<ref>[http://results.aec.gov.au/13745/website/HousePollingPlaceFirstPrefs-13745-6956.htm Port Pirie West Polling Booth], Division of Grey, House of Representatives Division First Preferences, 2007 Federal Election. Retrieved on 28 June 2008.</ref>\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 58.79%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 28.02%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Family First}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Family First Party|Family First]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 5.18%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Greens}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Greens|Greens]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 4.29%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Nationals}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian National Party|National]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 1.46%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Democrats}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Democrats|Democrats]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 1.38%\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#D8D8D8\" |&nbsp;\n| [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 0.89%\n|}\n\nThe results shown are from \"Port Pirie West\", the largest polling booth in Port Pirie, which is at the SA TAFE Campus.\n\nPort Pirie is part of the federal [[division of Grey]], and has been represented by Liberal MP [[Rowan Ramsey]] since 2007. Grey is held with a margin of 4.43% but is considered a safe Liberal seat.\n\nThe city is part of the state [[electoral district of Frome]], which had been held since 1993 by former Liberal Premier, [[Rob Kerin]], with a margin of 3.4%. It also has been considered a safe Liberal seat.\n\nAlthough the region is generally Liberal-leaning because of its agricultural base, Port Pirie is an industrial centre that is favourable to the ALP (Australian Labor Party).\n\nIn late 2008 Rob Kerin announced his retirement, which led to a by-election being held in January 2009. Port Pirie mayor Geoff Brock announced his candidacy as an independent, and subsequently took the seat from the Liberals at the [[Frome state by-election, 2009|2009 Frome by-election]]. After the poll for the by-election had closed and first preferences had been counted, (but before other preferences had been distributed), the result was Lib: 39.2%; ALP: 26.1%; Brock 23.6%; Nat: 6.6%; Greens: 3.8%; Other: 0.7%.<ref name=byelection1>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/sa/2009/frome/ Frome 2009 By-election results], abc.net.au, 2 February 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref><ref name=byelection2>[http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/byelection2009/results.php District of Frome - Electoral Results], Electoral Commission SA, 24 January 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref>\n\nState Opposition Leader Martin Hamilton-Smith (Liberal Party) claimed victory (prematurely).<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,24943402-2682,00.html Libs claim Frome victory], AdelaideNow, 21 January 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref> Distribution of National, Greens and other preferences placed Brock ahead of the ALP candidate. Hence with the assistance of the ALP candidate's preferences, Geoff Brock won the by-election 51.7% to 48.3% for the Liberal candidate.<ref name=byelection1/><ref name=byelection2/>\n\n===Local===\nPort Pirie is in the [[Port Pirie Regional Council]] (PPRC) [[Local government in Australia|local government area]] (along with some of the sparsely inhabited areas around it).\n\n==Notable residents==\n;Sportspeople\n* [[Nip Pellew]] (1893-1981), Australian Test cricketer and North Adelaide player\n* [[Mark Bickley]] (1969-), Adelaide Crows dual premiership captain\n* [[Mark Jamar]] (1982-), Melbourne Demons player and all-Australian\n* [[David Tiller]] (1958-), North Adelaide Roosters captain and premiership player\n* [[Brodie Atkinson]] (1972-), St. Kilda, Adelaide Crows, North Adelaide premiership player (1991), Sturt premiership player (2002) and Magarey Medal winner (1997)\n* [[Elijah Ware]] (1983-), Port Adelaide and Central Districts player and premiership player\n* [[Abby Bishop]] (1989-), Canberra Capitals player\n* [[Lewis Johnston]] (1991-), Sydney Swans, Adelaide Crows\n* [[Sam Mayes]] (1994-), North Adelaide, Brisbane Lions (2013-)\n;Others\n* [[Geoff Brock]], State Politician\n* [[Ted Connelly]], State Politician\n* [[Andrew Lacey]] (1887\u20131946), Federal and State Politician, State Leader of the ALP 1933\u20131938\n* [[Hugh Cairns (surgeon)|Sir Hugh Cairns]] (1896\u20131952), Rhodes Scholar, Neurosurgeon and crash helmet proponent\n* [[Keith Michell]] (1928-2015), Actor\n* [[John Noble]] (1948-), Actor and director\n* [[Robert Stigwood]] (1934-2016), Music entrepreneur and impresario<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/music-mogul-robert-stigwood-dies-aged-81/news-story/a10966a487421f5634f62eb472d69c68 Late Port Pirie-raised music mogul Robert Stigwood who changed the entertainment world], ''The Advertiser'', 5 January 2016. Accessed 6 January 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-01-05/robert-stigwood-music-mogul-behind-bee-gees-dies/7068478 Robert Stigwood, music mogul behind Bee Gees and Clapton, dies aged 81], ''ABC News'', 5 January 2016. Accessed 6 January 2016.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[:Category:People from Port Pirie]]\n* [[Diocese of Willochra]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Port Pirie]]\n* [[Sir John Pirie, 1st Baronet]], for whom several places and features are named\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category| Port Pirie, South Australia|Port Pirie}}\n*[http://www.wilmap.com.au/ausmaps/maps/ac26.gif Port Pirie, South Australia reference]\n*[http://www.pirie.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm/ Port Pirie Regional Council]\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/news/South-Australia/Port-Pirie/2005/02/17/1108500204638.html \"Port Pirie\"], Travel section, Sydney Morning Herald, 14 January 2008.\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/08/31/2020197.htm \"Port Pirie smelter changes from Zinifex to Nyrstar\"], ABC News, 31 August 2007.\n*[http://www.nyrstar.com/en/ Nystar], Home page - English.\n\n{{Port Pirie Regional Council localities}}\n{{South Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1845 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Cities in South Australia]]\n[[Category:Mid North (South Australia)]]\n[[Category:Port cities in South Australia]]\n[[Category:Port Pirie]]\n[[Category:Spencer Gulf]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Port Pirie (disambiguation){{!}}Port Pirie}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = city\n|name          = Port Pirie\n|state         = sa\n|image         = Port Pirie1.JPG\n|caption       = The lead smelter and grain silos at the wharf of Port Pirie\n|pop           = 14188\n|pop_year      = 2018\n|pop_footnotes = <ref name=ABSSUA>{{cite web|title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2017-18: Population Estimates by Significant Urban Area, 2008 to 2018|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3218.02017-18|website=Australian Bureau of Statistics|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=25 October 2019}} Estimated resident population, 30 June 2018.</ref>\n|poprank       =\n|postcode      = 5540\n|density       =\n|est           = 1845\n|elevation     = 4\n|coordinates   = {{coord|33|11|9|S|138|1|1|E|display=inline,title}}\n|area          =\n|timezone      = [[Australian Central Standard Time|ACST]]\n|utc           = +9:30\n|timezone-dst  = [[Australian Central Daylight Time|ACDT]]\n|utc-dst       = +10:30\n|lga           = Port Pirie Regional Council\n|stategov      = [[Electoral district of Frome|Frome]]\n|fedgov        = [[Division of Grey|Grey]]\n|dist1         = 223\n|location1     = Adelaide\n}}\n\n'''Port Pirie''' is a city  and [[seaport]] on the east coast of the [[Spencer Gulf]] in [[South Australia]], {{convert|223|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}<ref>UBD South Australia and Northern Territory Country Road Atlas, 6th Edition, 2005. Universal Publishers Pty Ltd. {{ISBN|0 7319 1606 9}}</ref> north of the state capital, [[Adelaide]]. The settlement was founded in 1845 and at June 2018 had an estimated urban population of 14,188. Port Pirie is the seventh most populous city in [[South Australia]] after [[Adelaide]], [[Mount Gambier]], [[Gawler, South Australia|Gawler]], [[Mount Barker, South Australia|Mount Barker,]] [[Whyalla]], [[Murray Bridge, South Australia|Murray Bridge.]] \n\nThe city's economy is dominated by one of the world's largest [[lead]] [[Lead smelting|smelters]],<ref name=\"ABC2018\">[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-08/port-pirie-lead-smelter-risk-of-breaching-licence-to-operate/10476916 Port Pirie's lead smelter at risk of breaching licence to operate due to spike in lead levels] ''ABC News'', 8 November 2018. Retrieved 14 November 2019.</ref> operated by [[Nyrstar]].<ref name=\"Zinifex PP\">{{cite web |url=http://zinifex.com/Index.aspx?link_id=18.778 |title=Port Pirie Overview |accessdate=12 December 2006 |publisher=Nyrstar Limited |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060819231756/http://www.zinifex.com/Index.aspx?link_id=18.778 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 19 August 2006}}</ref> The smelter is currently undergoing a $650 million upgrade to replace some of the old existing plant and to reduce airborne lead emissions drastically. It also produces refined [[silver]], [[zinc]], [[copper]] and [[gold]]. Port Pirie is the largest city and the main retail centre of the [[Mid North]] region of South Australia.\n\n==History==\nPrior to European settlement, the location that became Port Pirie was occupied by the indigenous tribe of [[Nukunu]]. The location was called 'Tarparrie', which is suspected to mean \"Muddy Creek\". The first European to see the location was [[Matthew Flinders]] in 1802 as he explored the Spencer Gulf by boat. The first land discovery by settlers of the location was by the explorer [[Edward Eyre]] who explored regions around [[Port Augusta, South Australia|Port Augusta]]. [[John Ainsworth Horrocks|John Horrocks]] also discovered a pass through the Flinders Ranges to the coast, now named ''[[Horrocks Pass]]''.\n\nThe town was originally called Samuel's Creek after the discovery of Muddy Creek by [[Ben Germein#Family|Samuel Germein]]. In 1846, Port Pirie Creek was named by Governor Robe after the ''John Pirie'', the first vessel to navigate the creek when transporting sheep from Bowman's Run near Crystal Brook. In 1848, Matthew Smith and [[Emanuel Solomon]] bought {{convert|85|acre|ha}} and subdivided it as a township to be known as Port Pirie. Little development occurred on site and by the late 1860s there were only three woolsheds on the riverfront.<ref>Erik Eklund, ''[http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/163809700?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1370392639995&versionId=178587537 Mining Towns: making a living, making a life']', New South Publishing, Sydney, 2012, p. 137</ref>\n\nThe government town was surveyed in December 1871 by Charles Hope Harris. The thoroughfares and streets were named after the family of [[George Goyder]], Surveyor General of South Australia, with the streets running parallel and at right angles to the river. In 1873 the land of Solomon and Smith was re-surveyed and named Solomontown. On 28 September 1876, Port Pirie was declared a municipality, with a population of 947.\n\nWith the discovery of rich silver-, lead- and zinc-bearing ore at [[Broken Hill]] in 1883, and the completion of a narrow gauge railway from Port Pirie to close to the Broken Hill field in 1888, the economic activities of the town shifted. In 1889 a lead smelter was built by the British Blocks company to treat Broken Hill ore. [[Broken Hill Proprietary]] initially leased the smelter from British Blocks and then began constructing their own smelter from 1892. In 1913 the Russian consul-general [[Alexander Nikolayevich Abaza|Alexander Abaza]] reported that Port Pirie had a population of over 500 Russians, mostly [[Ossetians]], who had come to work at the smelter. The town supported a Russian-language school and library.<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/n4325/pdf/ch08.pdf|chapter=Alexander Abaza|title=A New Rival State?: Australia in Tsarist Diplomatic Communications|year=2018|publisher=ANU Press|editor-first1=Alexander|editor-last1=Massov|editor-first2=Marina|editor-last2=Pollard|editor-first3=Kevin|editor-last3=Windle|page=304}}</ref>\n\nIn 1915 the smelter was taken over by a major joint venture of Broken Hill-based companies, Broken Hill Associated Smelters (BHAS). Led by the Collins House Group, BHAS became the biggest lead smelter in the world by 1934.<ref>Eklund, ''[http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/163809700?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1370392639995&versionId=178587537 Mining Towns]'', pp. 137-138.</ref> The smelter gradually passed to [[Pasminco]], then [[Zinifex]], and is now operated by [[Nyrstar]].\n\nBy 1921 the town's population had grown to 9801 living in 2308 occupied dwellings. By this date there were also 62 boarding houses to cater for the labour demands at the smelter and on the increasingly busy waterfront.<ref>Eklund, [http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/163809700?q&sort=holdings+desc&_=1370392639995&versionId=178587537 Mining Towns], pp. 143-144.</ref> Port Pirie was declared South Australia's first provincial city in 1953, and today it is South Australia's second largest port. It is characterised by a gracious main street and some interesting and unusual historic buildings.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/South-Australia/Port-Pirie/2005/02/17/1108500204638.html \"Port Pirie\"], Travel section, smh.com.au, 17 February 2005. Retrieved on 28 June 2008.</ref>\n\n===Heritage listings===\n[[File:Pt Pirie butcher 21503.jpg|thumb|This former Sampson's butcher shop at 64-68 Ellen Street, Port Pirie, has been converted into a residence.]]\nPort Pirie has a number of heritage-listed sites, including:\n\n* 1 Alexander Street: [[Barrier Chambers Offices]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13524 | title=Barrier Chambers Offices | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 32 Ellen Street: [[Adelaide Steamship Company Building]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13525 | title=Former Adelaide Steamship Company Building | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 64-68 Ellen Street: [[Sampson's Butcher Shop]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13526 | title=Dwelling (former Sampson's Butcher Shop) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 69-71 Ellen Street: [[Port Pirie Customs House]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13528 | title=National Trust Museum (former Port Pirie Customs House) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 73-77 Ellen Street: [[Port Pirie (Ellen Street) railway station]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13529 | title=National Trust Museum (former Port Pirie Railway Station) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 79-81 Ellen Street: [[Port Pirie Post Office]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13530 | title=Port Pirie Post Office | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 85 Ellen Street: [[Development Board Building, Port Pirie|Development Board Building]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13527 | title=Development Board Building (former Port Pirie Courthouse, later Customs House) | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 94 Ellen Street: Sample Rooms, rear of [[Portside Tavern]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13531 | title=Sample Rooms, rear of Jubilee (former Royal Exchange) Hotel | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 134 Ellen Street: [[Family Hotel, Port Pirie|Family Hotel]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13532 | title=Family Hotel | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 32 Florence Street: [[Carn Brae]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13533 | title=Dwelling ('Carn Brae') | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 50-52 Florence Street: [[Waterside Workers' Federation Building, Port Pirie|Waterside Workers' Federation Building]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13534 | title=Waterside Workers' Federation (former Amalgamated Workers' Association) Building | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 105 Gertrude Street: [[Good Samaritan Catholic Convent School]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13535 | title=Good Samaritan Catholic Convent School | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* Memorial Drive: [[Second World War Memorial Gates, Port Pirie|Second World War Memorial Gates]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13536 | title=Second World War Memorial Gates | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n* 5 Norman Street: [[AMP Society Building, Port Pirie]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://apps.planning.sa.gov.au/HeritageSearch/HeritageItem.aspx?p_heritageno=13537 | title=Former AMP [Australian Mutual Provident Society] Port Pirie Office Building | publisher=Department of Environment, Water and Natural Resources | work=South Australian Heritage Register | accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2006 Census, the population of the Port Pirie census area was 13,206 people. Approximately 51.8% of the population were female, 86.9% are Australian born, over 92.7% of residents are Australian citizens and 2.6% were Aboriginal people.\n\nThe most popular industries for employment were Basic Non-Ferrous Metal Manufacturing (9.7%), School Education (6%), Hospitality (only including hotels) (11%),{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Health (5.4%) and Animal Husbandry (4%), while the unemployment rate is approx. 11%. The median weekly household income is A$608 or more per week, compared with $924 in Adelaide. 27.1% of the population identify themselves as [[Catholic]], while 23.7% identify with no religion at all.<ref name=\"ABS\">{{Census 2006 AUS | id = UCL422200 | name = Port Pirie (Urban Centre/Locality) | quick = on | accessdate=28 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nPort Pirie is at an elevation of 4 metres above [[sea level]]. It is approximately {{convert|8|km}} inland, on the Pirie River, which is a tidal saltwater inlet from [[Spencer Gulf]]. It is on the coastal plain between Spencer Gulf (to the west) and the [[Flinders Ranges]] to the east.\n\n==Climate==\nPort Pirie exists in a region with a [[semi-arid climate]], outside [[Goyder's Line]], surrounded by [[mallee Woodlands and Shrublands|mallee]] scrub. Average daily maximum temperatures vary from a mild 16.4&nbsp;\u00b0C in winter to 32.0&nbsp;\u00b0C in summer. Its average annual rainfall is 345.2 millimetres, most of which falls in winter.\n\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Port Pirie has a warm semi-arid climate, noted as ''BSh''.\n\n{{Weather box\n| location     = Port Pirie\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line  = Yes\n| Jan record high C = 48.6\n| Feb record high C = 45.5\n| Mar record high C = 42.5\n| Apr record high C = 37.7\n| May record high C = 31.0\n| Jun record high C = 25.5\n| Jul record high C = 26.5\n| Aug record high C = 30.0\n| Sep record high C = 35.0\n| Oct record high C = 39.5\n| Nov record high C = 44.0\n| Dec record high C = 46.6\n| year record high C = 48.6\n| Jan high C = 32.0\n| Feb high C = 31.8\n| Mar high C = 29.4\n| Apr high C = 24.8\n| May high C = 20.4\n| Jun high C = 17.1\n| Jul high C = 16.4\n| Aug high C = 18.1\n| Sep high C = 21.3\n| Oct high C = 24.5\n| Nov high C = 27.7\n| Dec high C = 30.0\n| year high C = 24.4\n| Jan low C = 17.7\n| Feb low C = 17.9\n| Mar low C = 16.0\n| Apr low C = 13.2\n| May low C = 10.7\n| Jun low C = 8.4\n| Jul low C = 7.7\n| Aug low C = 8.2\n| Sep low C = 9.8\n| Oct low C = 11.9\n| Nov low C = 14.4\n| Dec low C = 16.3\n| year low C = 12.7\n| Jan record low C = 4.8\n| Feb record low C = 7.1\n| Mar record low C = 7.4\n| Apr record low C = 4.4\n| May record low C = -0.6\n| Jun record low C = -1.7\n| Jul record low C = -0.6\n| Aug record low C = 0.3\n| Sep record low C = 0.6\n| Oct record low C = 1.1\n| Nov record low C = 1.1\n| Dec record low C = 4.4\n| year record low C = -1.7\n| Jan precipitation mm = 18.6\n| Feb precipitation mm = 17.8\n| Mar precipitation mm = 18.6\n| Apr precipitation mm = 27.5\n| May precipitation mm = 38.2\n| Jun precipitation mm = 40.7\n| Jul precipitation mm = 33.9\n| Aug precipitation mm = 34.9\n| Sep precipitation mm = 35.5\n| Oct precipitation mm = 33.1\n| Nov precipitation mm = 24.1\n| Dec precipitation mm = 23.0\n| year precipitation mm = 345.9\n| source 1 = [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology]]<ref>{{BoM Aust stats|site_ref=cw_021043|site_name=Port Pirie Nyrstar Comparison AWS|accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n| date     = February 2014\n}}\n\n==Transport==\nPort Pirie is {{convert|5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} off the [[Augusta Highway]]. It is serviced by [[Port Pirie Airport]], six kilometres south of the city.\n\n=== Railways ===\nThe first railway in Port Pirie opened in 1875 when the [[South Australian Railways]] {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge [[Crystal Brook-Broken Hill railway line|Port Pirie-Cockburn line]] opened to [[Gladstone railway station, South Australia|Gladstone]], ultimately being extended to [[Broken Hill railway station|Broken Hill]].<ref>Wilson, John, ''Port Pirie - The Narrow Gauge Era (1873\u20131935)'', [[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]], March 1970, pp. 49\u201362</ref> The original Ellen Street station was located on the street with the track running down the middle.<ref>Bakewell, Guy and Wilson, John, ''Farewell to Ellen Street'', [[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]] September 1968, pp. 210\u2013213</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Ward|first1=Andrew|title=Railway Stations of Australia|date=1982|publisher=MacMillan Company of Australia|location=South Melbourne|isbn=0 333338 53 7|pages=60\u201361}}</ref> The station today is occupied by the Port Pirie National Trust Museum.<ref>[http://www.southaustralia.com/info.aspx?id=9000743 Port Pirie National Trust Museum] Explore South Australia</ref>\n\nIn 1937, it became a [[break-of-gauge]] station when the broad gauge [[Adelaide-Port Augusta railway line|Adelaide-Redhill line]] was extended to Port Pirie. At the same time the [[Commonwealth Railways]] [[standard gauge]] [[Trans-Australian Railway]] was extended south from [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]] to terminate at the new [[Port Pirie Junction railway station|Port Pirie Junction station]] where it met the broad gauge line, in the suburb of Solomontown.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article30759205 Solomontown Railway Station] ''[[Adelaide Advertiser]] 14 July 1937</ref><ref>[http://www.natrailmuseum.org.au/downloads/documents/Multi_Gauge_Muddle.compressed.pdf Port Pirie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228020700/http://natrailmuseum.org.au/downloads/documents/Multi_Gauge_Muddle.compressed.pdf |date=28 February 2016 }} National Railway Museum</ref>\n\nAs far back as 1943, a plan existed to build a new station to remove trains from Ellen Street.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96357055 Council Wants No Trains in Ellen Street] ''[[The Recorder (Port Pirie)|The Recorder]]'' 31 March 1943</ref> As part of the [[Track gauge conversion|gauge conversion]] of the [[Crystal Brook-Broken Hill railway line|Port Pirie to Broken Hill line]], [[Port Pirie (Mary Elie Street) railway station|Mary Elie Street station]] was built to replace both Ellen Street and Port Pirie Junction stations.<ref>[http://www.atrf.info/papers/1976/1976_Webb.pdf The Planning & Evaluation of Rail Standardisation Projects in Australia] GR Webb 1976</ref>\n\nWhen opened, the new station was the meeting point for the [[Commonwealth Railways]] and [[South Australian Railways]] networks with through trains changing locomotives and crews, so the disadvantages were not as notable. However, after both became part of [[Australian National Railways Commission|Australian National]] in July 1975 and trains began to operate in and out with the same locomotives, trains began to operate via [[Coonamia railway station|Coonamia station]] on the outskirts of the city.\n\nMary Ellie Street station was eventually closed in the 1990s and in 2009 was redeveloped as the city's library. Until 2012, a [[Commonwealth Railways GM class|GM class locomotive]] and three carriages were stabled at the platform.<ref>[http://www.westonlangford.com/images/photo/127936/ Port Pirie Marie Elie Street Display] Western Langford Railway Photography</ref>\n\n=== Sea transport ===\n\nPort Pirie's marine facilities, managed by [[Flinders Ports]], handle up to 100 ship visits annually, up to [[Handymax]] size, for  commodities such as mineral concentrates, refined lead and zinc, coal, grain, and general cargo.<ref>[https://www.pirie.sa.gov.au/about-council/business-and-investment/access-to-prime-infrastructure Access to Prime Infrastructure] Port Pirie Regional Council. Retrieved 26 February 2020.</ref>\n\n==Industry and employment==\n{{Update|Zinifex which has spun out and floated Nyrstar owning the smelters|date=March 2009}}\nThe main industries are the [[smelting]] of metals, and the operation of [[Storage silo|silos]] to hold grain.\n\nPort Pirie's main employer is Nyrstar, which operates the largest lead smelter/refinery in the southern hemisphere.<ref name=\"Zinifex PP\"/> A lead smelter has been operating in Port Pirie since the 1880s, and high blood lead levels in the local population are an ongoing concern.<ref name=\"ABC2018\" /> The Stack, which can be seen kilometres away, is 205 metres tall, and is the tallest structure in the state.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} In 2006 Zinifex formed a joint venture with [[Umicore]] to create Nyrstar, which owns the smelter, with the intention that it would eventually be an entity separate from the parent companies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zinifex and Umicore seek to create the world's leading producer of zinc metal |url=http://asx.com.au/asx/statistics/showAnnouncementPDF.do?idsID=00677174 |publisher=[[Australian Securities Exchange|ASX]] |work=Zinifex Limited |accessdate=12 December 2006 |date=12 December 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070325234959/http://asx.com.au/asx/statistics/showAnnouncementPDF.do?idsID=00677174 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 25 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2006/12/12/1165685650493.html |title=Zinifex, Umicore to combine zinc assets |date=12 December 2006 |accessdate=12 December 2006 |publisher=[[The Age]]}}</ref>\n\nFlinders Industrial, a new industrial estate, is currently{{When|date=March 2009}} in its second stage and is planned to be home to the new council depot.{{When|date=March 2009}} There were plans to build a sulphuric acid plant for the benefit of the Nyrstar Smelter, but this project has been shelved and deemed not feasible.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\n===Development===\nA new $3.3 million cultural precinct was completed in 2010 built by the [[Port Pirie Regional Council]] in partnership with the Federal Government. A committee is also looking at building a [[multi-purpose stadium]]. The swimming pool is now state of the art after receiving a $1 million refit. A major Waste Recovery Facility was opened in 2013, which allows all waste and recycled material to be sorted and sorted under one roof. In 2012 [[Port Pirie Regional Council]] completed a $5m Community Water Recycling project with Nyrstar which allows 350ML of water to be reused from the smelter. Plans are underway to establish a large shopping complex in the city with an additional supermarket and department store. The city's population is continually growing and property prices continue to rise. The Port Pirie Regional Council has a number of large projects that will be launched or completed next financial year.\n\n===Waterfront development===\nThe PPRC completed a major redevelopment of its foreshore area in 2014 including the construction of the Solomontown Beach Plaza, opening up Beach abroad to through traffic, replacing lighting along the beach as well as improvements to security in the region. In addition, by the end of 2014, the council aims to replace and duplicate the current Solomontown boat ramp and undertake dredging in the vicinity of the ramp. This investment is aimed at creating a waterfront which will revitalise the area from the Main Road boat ramp up to the area off Ellen street.\n\n==Tenby10 (Lead levels)==\n{{Further|Lead poisoning}}\nLead smelters contribute to several environmental problems, especially raised blood lead levels in some of the town population. The problem is particularly significant in many children who have grown up in the area. There is a government project to address this.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.sa.gov.au/pehs/branches/branch-ptpirie.htm |title=Pt Pirie Environmental Health Centre |accessdate=11 June 2006 }}</ref> Nyrstar plans to progressively reduce lead in blood levels such that ultimately 95% of all children meet the national goal of 10 micrograms per decilitre. This has been known as the tenby10 project. Community lead in blood levels in children are now at less than half the level that they were in the mid 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zinifex.com/index.aspx?link_id=18.779 |title=Zinifex Port Pirie Strategy |accessdate=4 May 2007 |publisher=Zinifex Limited |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928222714/http://www.zinifex.com/index.aspx?link_id=18.779 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 28 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Port Pirie smelter has a project underway to reduce [[Lead poisoning|lead levels]] in children to under 10 micrograms per decilitre by the end of 2010.<ref name=\"tenby10.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tenby10.com/Index|title=10 by Ten \u2013 10 Ways To Have An Impact|website=www.tenby10.com|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The goal we are committed to achieving is for at least 95% of our children aged 0 to 4 to have a blood lead level below ten micrograms per decilitre of blood (the first ten in tenby10) by the end of 2010 (the second ten in tenby10).\"<ref name=\"tenby10.com\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nHigher concentrations of lead have been found in the organs of bottlenose dolphins stranded near the lead smelter, compared to dolphins stranded elsewhere in South Australia.<ref>Lavery, T.J., Butterfield, N., Kemper, C.M., Reid, R.J., Sanderson, K. 2008. ''Metals and selenium in the liver and bone of three dolphin species from South Australia, 1988\u20132004.'' Science of the Total Environment, 390: 77\u201385</ref> The health impacts of these metals on dolphins has been examined and some associations between high metal concentrations and kidney toxicity were noted.<ref>Lavery, T.J., Kemper, C.M., Sanderson, K., Schultz, C.G., Coyle, P., Mitchell, J.G., Seuront, L. 2008. ''Heavy metal toxicity of kidney and bone tissues in South Australian adult bottlenose dolphins (Tursiops aduncus)'', {{doi|10.1016/jmarenvres.2008.09.005}}</ref>\n\n==Education and culture ==\n[[File:Port Pirie Railway Station.jpg|thumb|250px|The former [[Port Pirie (Ellen Street) railway station|Ellen Street railway station]] now a museum]]\nPort Pirie is the main centre for the [[Mid North]] area. Many towns in the area rely on Port Pirie for shopping and employment. It also has many educational institutions such as [[Risdon Park High School|John Pirie Secondary School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnpirihs.sa.edu.au|title=Welcome to John Pirie Secondary School's website|website=www.johnpirihs.sa.edu.au|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> (years 8-12), St Mark's College<ref>[http://www.stmarks.pp.catholic.edu.au/ St Mark's College] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091030074553/http://stmarks.pp.catholic.edu.au/ |date=30 October 2009 }}</ref> (reception - year 12), Mid North Christian College<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midnorthcc.sa.edu.au/|title=Mid North Christian College - Port Pirie, SA - Home|website=www.midnorthcc.sa.edu.au|accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> (reception - year 12), many preschools and primary schools, and a [[Technical and Further Education|TAFE]] Campus (Adult Education).\n\nPort Pirie is home to the National Trust Historic and Folk Museum and Memorial Park. Every September and October it hosts a country music festival. It has significant Italian & Greek communities. The ''Keith Michell Theatre'', within the Northern Festival Centre, is named after the actor [[Keith Michell]] who grew up in [[Warnertown, South Australia|Warnertown]], {{convert|5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from Port Pirie.\n\n==Media==\nThe town's main newspaper, ''[[The Recorder (Port Pirie)|The Recorder]],'' was first published 21 March 1885 as ''The Port Pirie Advocate and Areas News''. In 1971, a brief experiment, known as the ''Northern Observer'' (7 July - 30 August 1971), occurred when ''The Recorder'' and ''[[The Transcontinental]]'' from Port Augusta were published under a combined title in Port Pirie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guides.slsa.sa.gov.au/c.php?g=410317&p=2796365|title=LibGuides: SA Newspapers: M-N|last=Laube|first=Anthony|website=guides.slsa.sa.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref> ''The Recorder'', which is still in print today (Tuesdays and Thursdays), has recently changed to a morning paper, after being delivered at around 3:00 pm.<ref>[http://www.portpirierecorder.com.au/about-us/ ''The Recorder'' - About Us] Accessed 2 June 2013.</ref> Other Port Pirie newspapers include the free ''[[The Flinders News]]'' (Wednesdays), and ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'', which covers some Port Pirie news, but to a very small extent.\n\nAnother newspaper, the ''[[The Port Pirie Advertiser|Port Pirie Advertiser]]'' (7 April 1898 \u2013 28 June 1924) was also published locally by Robert Osborne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.samemory.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm?c=6275|title=Port Pirie advertiser|website=www.samemory.sa.gov.au|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref> A further publication was the short-lived ''Saturday Times'' (6 December 1913 \u2013 15 August 1914), printed by Roy Harold Butler and closed at the start of the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guides.slsa.sa.gov.au/c.php?g=410317&p=2796357|title=LibGuides: SA Newspapers: S|last=Laube|first=Anthony|website=guides.slsa.sa.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-08-24}}</ref> Another former publication was the ''Port Pirie Star'' (1971-1972). Another previous publication, called ''Desert Sun'' (December 1973-July 1974), and published bi-monthly by the Flinders Travel Service and [[Commonwealth Railways]], was aimed at people interested in, or travelling on, the [[Indian Pacific|Indian-Pacific]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guides.slsa.sa.gov.au/c.php?g=410317&p=2796332|title=LibGuides: SA Newspapers: C-E|last=Laube|first=Anthony|website=guides.slsa.sa.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref>\n\nTelevision coverage is broad. [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] and [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] are available in the city with [[Southern Cross Austereo|Southern Cross]] (7, 9 and 10) as well as [[Austar]]. Several radio stations cover Port Pirie including ABC 639AM, ABC 891AM, 1044 5CS, 1242 5AU, [[triple j]], Magic FM and Trax FM (a community station).\n\n==Politics==\n===State & Federal===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em\"\n! colspan=\"4\" | Port Pirie West<br />State Elections\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n!2006<ref>[http://results.aec.gov.au/13745/website/HousePollingPlaceFirstPrefs-13745-6983.htm Port Pirie West Polling Booth], District of Frome, House of Assembly Division First Preferences, 2006 State Election. Retrieved on 28 June 2008.</ref>\n!2009<ref>[http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/byelection2009/results/polling516.htm Port Pirie West Polling Booth], District of Frome, House of Assembly Division First Preferences, 2009 By-election, 24 January 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 60.2%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 36.6%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 28.8%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 16.9%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Family First}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Family First Party|Family First]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 5.7%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Greens}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Greens|SA Greens]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 3.4%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 2.6%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Democrats}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Democrats|Democrats]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 1.9%\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#D8D8D8\" |&nbsp;\n| [[Geoff Brock]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 40.9%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Nationals}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian National Party|Nationals SA]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 2.4%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|One Nation}}|&nbsp;\n| [[One Nation (Australia)|One Nation]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" |\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 0.5%\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em\"\n! colspan = 3 | Port Pirie West<br />2007 Federal Election<ref>[http://results.aec.gov.au/13745/website/HousePollingPlaceFirstPrefs-13745-6956.htm Port Pirie West Polling Booth], Division of Grey, House of Representatives Division First Preferences, 2007 Federal Election. Retrieved on 28 June 2008.</ref>\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 58.79%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 28.02%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Family First}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Family First Party|Family First]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 5.18%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Greens}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Greens|Greens]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 4.29%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Nationals}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian National Party|National]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 1.46%\n|-\n| {{Australian party style|Democrats}}|&nbsp;\n| [[Australian Democrats|Democrats]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 1.38%\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#D8D8D8\" |&nbsp;\n| [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| bgcolor=\"FFFF99\" | 0.89%\n|}\n\nThe results shown are from \"Port Pirie West\", the largest polling booth in Port Pirie, which is at the SA TAFE Campus.\n\nPort Pirie is part of the federal [[division of Grey]], and has been represented by Liberal MP [[Rowan Ramsey]] since 2007. Grey is held with a margin of 4.43% but is considered a safe Liberal seat.\n\nThe city is part of the state [[electoral district of Frome]], which had been held since 1993 by former Liberal Premier, [[Rob Kerin]], with a margin of 3.4%. It also has been considered a safe Liberal seat.\n\nAlthough the region is generally Liberal-leaning because of its agricultural base, Port Pirie is an industrial centre that is favourable to the ALP (Australian Labor Party).\n\nIn late 2008 Rob Kerin announced his retirement, which led to a by-election being held in January 2009. Port Pirie mayor Geoff Brock announced his candidacy as an independent, and subsequently took the seat from the Liberals at the [[Frome state by-election, 2009|2009 Frome by-election]]. After the poll for the by-election had closed and first preferences had been counted, (but before other preferences had been distributed), the result was Lib: 39.2%; ALP: 26.1%; Brock 23.6%; Nat: 6.6%; Greens: 3.8%; Other: 0.7%.<ref name=byelection1>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/sa/2009/frome/ Frome 2009 By-election results], abc.net.au, 2 February 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref><ref name=byelection2>[http://www.ecsa.sa.gov.au/byelection2009/results.php District of Frome - Electoral Results], Electoral Commission SA, 24 January 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref>\n\nState Opposition Leader Martin Hamilton-Smith (Liberal Party) claimed victory (prematurely).<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,24943402-2682,00.html Libs claim Frome victory], AdelaideNow, 21 January 2009. Retrieved on 15 March 2009.</ref> Distribution of National, Greens and other preferences placed Brock ahead of the ALP candidate. Hence with the assistance of the ALP candidate's preferences, Geoff Brock won the by-election 51.7% to 48.3% for the Liberal candidate.<ref name=byelection1/><ref name=byelection2/>\n\n===Local===\nPort Pirie is in the [[Port Pirie Regional Council]] (PPRC) [[Local government in Australia|local government area]] (along with some of the sparsely inhabited areas around it).\n\n==Notable residents==\n;Sportspeople\n* [[Nip Pellew]] (1893-1981), Australian Test cricketer and North Adelaide player\n* [[Mark Bickley]] (1969-), Adelaide Crows dual premiership captain\n* [[Mark Jamar]] (1982-), Melbourne Demons player and all-Australian\n* [[David Tiller]] (1958-), North Adelaide Roosters captain and premiership player\n* [[Brodie Atkinson]] (1972-), St. Kilda, Adelaide Crows, North Adelaide premiership player (1991), Sturt premiership player (2002) and Magarey Medal winner (1997)\n* [[Elijah Ware]] (1983-), Port Adelaide and Central Districts player and premiership player\n* [[Abby Bishop]] (1989-), Canberra Capitals player\n* [[Lewis Johnston]] (1991-), Sydney Swans, Adelaide Crows\n* [[Sam Mayes]] (1994-), North Adelaide, Brisbane Lions (2013-)\n;Others\n* [[Geoff Brock]], State Politician\n* [[Ted Connelly]], State Politician\n* [[Andrew Lacey]] (1887\u20131946), Federal and State Politician, State Leader of the ALP 1933\u20131938\n* [[Hugh Cairns (surgeon)|Sir Hugh Cairns]] (1896\u20131952), Rhodes Scholar, Neurosurgeon and crash helmet proponent\n* [[Keith Michell]] (1928-2015), Actor\n* [[John Noble]] (1948-), Actor and director\n* [[Robert Stigwood]] (1934-2016), Music entrepreneur and impresario<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/music-mogul-robert-stigwood-dies-aged-81/news-story/a10966a487421f5634f62eb472d69c68 Late Port Pirie-raised music mogul Robert Stigwood who changed the entertainment world], ''The Advertiser'', 5 January 2016. Accessed 6 January 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-01-05/robert-stigwood-music-mogul-behind-bee-gees-dies/7068478 Robert Stigwood, music mogul behind Bee Gees and Clapton, dies aged 81], ''ABC News'', 5 January 2016. Accessed 6 January 2016.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[:Category:People from Port Pirie]]\n* [[Diocese of Willochra]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Port Pirie]]\n* [[Sir John Pirie, 1st Baronet]], for whom several places and features are named\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category| Port Pirie, South Australia|Port Pirie}}\n*[http://www.wilmap.com.au/ausmaps/maps/ac26.gif Port Pirie, South Australia reference]\n*[http://www.pirie.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm/ Port Pirie Regional Council]\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/news/South-Australia/Port-Pirie/2005/02/17/1108500204638.html \"Port Pirie\"], Travel section, Sydney Morning Herald, 14 January 2008.\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/08/31/2020197.htm \"Port Pirie smelter changes from Zinifex to Nyrstar\"], ABC News, 31 August 2007.\n*[http://www.nyrstar.com/en/ Nystar], Home page - English.\n\n{{Port Pirie Regional Council localities}}\n{{South Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1845 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Cities in South Australia]]\n[[Category:Mid North (South Australia)]]\n[[Category:Port cities in South Australia]]\n[[Category:Port Pirie]]\n[[Category:Spencer Gulf]]\n", "name_user": "ScottDavis", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilinkJohn Pirie (ship)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port_Pirie"}
{"title_page": "Mythology of Benjamin Banneker", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\nAccording to accounts that began to appear during the 1960s or earlier, a substantial [[mythology]] has exaggerated the accomplishments of [[Benjamin Banneker]] (1731\u20131806), who was a [[Free Negro|free African American]] [[almanac]] author, [[astronomy|astronomer]], [[surveying|surveyor]], [[Natural history|naturalist]], and [[farmer]]. Well-known speakers, writers, artists and others have created, repeated and embellished a large number of such questionable reports during the two centuries that have elapsed since Banneker lived.<ref>(1) {{cite book|last=Whiteman|first=Maxwell|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=7|title=BENJAMIN BANNEKER: Surveyor and Astronomer: 1731-1806: A biographical note|work=Banneker's Almanack and Ephemeris for the Year of Our Lord 1793; being The First After Bisixtile or Leap Year and Banneker's almanac, for the year 1795: Being the Third After Leap Year: Afro-American History Series:  Rhistoric Publication No. 202 (1969 Reprint Edition)|editor=Whiteman, Maxwell|publisher=Rhistoric Publications, a division of Microsurance Inc.|lccn=72077039|oclc=907004619|quote=A number of fictional accounts of Banneker are available.  All of them were dependent upon the following: ''Proceedings of the Maryland Historical Society for 1837 and 1854'' which respectively contain the accounts of Banneker by John B. H. Latrobe and Martha E. Tyson. They were subsequently reprinted as pamphlets.|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]|accessdate=2017-06-14}}<br>(2) {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r_5ZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Locating the Federal District: Editorial Note: Footnote number 119|work=The Papers of Thomas Jefferson: 24 January\u201331 March 1791|volume=19|editor-first=Julian P.|editor-last=Boyd|editor-link=Julian P. Boyd|location=[[Princeton, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=1974|pages=41-43|oclc=1045069058|isbn=9780691185255|lccn=50007486|accessdate=2019-03-27|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br>Recent biographical accounts of Benjamin Banneker (1731\u20131806), a mulatto whose father was a native African and whose grandmother was English, have done his memory a disservice by obscuring his real achievements under a cloud of extravagant claims to scientific accomplishment that have no foundation in fact. The single notable exception is Silvio A. Bedini's ''The Life of Benjamin Banneker'' (New York, 1972), a work of painstaking research and scrupulous attention to accuracy which also benefits from the author's discovery of important and hitherto unavailable manuscript sources. ....}}<br>(3) [https://archive.org/details/banneker00char/page/142/mode/1up Cerami, 2002, p. 142.] \"He (Banneker) has existed in dim memory mainly on mangled ideas about his work, and even utter falsehoods that are unwise attempts to glorify a man who needs no such embellishments.\"<br>(4) Fasanelli, Florence D, \"Benjamin Banneker's Life and Mathematics: Web of Truth? Legends as Facts; Man vs. Legend\", a talk given on January 8, 2004, at the MAA/AMS meeting in Phoenix, AZ. ''Cited in'' {{cite journal|last=Mahoney|first=John F|url=http://www.maa.org/publications/periodicals/convergence/benjamin-bannekers-inscribed-equilateral-triangle-references|title=Benjamin Banneker's Inscribed Equilateral Triangle - References|journal=Loci|volume=2|date=July 2010|publisher=[[Mathematical Association of America]]|accessdate=2017-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226172738/https://www.maa.org/press/period|archive-date=December 26, 2017|url-status=dead}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Richard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309161429/http://www.blackpast.org/aah/banneker-benjamin-1731-1806|archivedate=2014-03-09|url=http://www.blackpast.org/aah/banneker-benjamin-1731-1806|title=Banneker, Benjamin (1731-1806)|work=Online Encyclopedia of Significant People and Places in African American History|year=2007|publisher=BlackPast.org|accessdate=2015-05-14|quote=(Banneker's) life and work have become enshrouded in legend and anecdote.}}<br>(6) {{cite web|author=Maryland Historical Society Library Department|url=http://www.mdhs.org/underbelly/2014/02/06/the-dreams-of-benjamin-banneker/|title=The Dreams of Benjamin Banneker|work=Underbelly: African American History|publisher=[[Maryland Historical Society]]|date=2014-02-06|accessdate=2018-02-19|quote=Over the 200 years since the death of Benjamin Banneker (1731-1806), his story has become a muddled combination of fact, inference, misinformation, hyperbole, and legend. Like many other figures throughout history, the small amount of surviving source material has nurtured the development of a degree of mythology surrounding his story.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219030526/http://www.mdhs.org/underbelly/2014/02/06/the-dreams-of-benjamin-banneker/|archive-date=February 19, 2018|url-status=dead}}<br>(7) {{cite web|url=https://www.haverford.edu/library/news/book-month-bannekers-almanac|title=A look into Benjamin Banneker's 1793 Almanac.|work=Book of the Month: Banneker's Almanac|date=April 18, 2016|location=[[Haverford, Pennsylvania]]|publisher=[[Haverford College]]|accessdate=April 9, 2020|quote=In 1806, shortly after Banneker's death, a fire at his home destroyed most of his personal papers (Gillispie). This gap in substantial archival material has hardly hindered the development of the Benjamin Banneker legend; perhaps it has even aided its growth. ..... The narrative that tells of Banneker's life as one of mythical success and unprecedented exceptionalism easily draws an audience, but it washes over what might be more intellectually rewarding questions about the man's life. .... For now, the legend of Benjamin Banneker will continue to exist in his old almanacs and in present culture, serving as an inspiring enigma for those who wonder what lies beyond the surface-level stories of the past.}}<br>(8) {{cite web|author=Biography.com Editors|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623172855/https://www.biography.com/scientist/benjamin-banneker|archivedate=June 23, 2019|url=https://www.biography.com/scientist/benjamin-banneker|title=Benjamin Banneker Biography|work=The Biography.com website|date=April 12, 2019|publisher=[[A&E Networks|A&E Television Networks]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020|quote=With limited materials having been preserved related to Banneker's life and career, there's been a fair amount of legend and misinformation presented.}}<br>(6) {{cite web|first=Louis|last=Keene|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831054904/https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|archivedate=August 31, 2019|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Black Tobacco Farmer Who The Presidents Couldn't Ignore|publisher=[[White House Historical Association|The White House Historical Association]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020|quote=Perhaps owing to the scarcity of recorded fact about his remarkable life, and because he was often invoked symbolically to advance social causes like abolition, Banneker\u2019s story has been susceptible to mythmaking. He has been incorrectly credited with drawing the street grid of Washington, D.C., making the first clock on the Eastern seaboard, being the first professional astronomer in America, and discovering the seventeen-year birth cycle of cicadas.}}</ref><ref name=Shipler>{{cite book|last=Shipler|first=David K.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1rLbI73FctUC&pg=PA196#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Myths of America|work=A Country of Strangers: Blacks and Whites in America|pages=196\u2013197|year=1998|location=New York|publisher=[[Vintage Books]]|isbn=0679734546|lccn=97002810|oclc=39849003|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=The Banneker story, impressive as it was, got embellished in 1987, when the public school system in Portland, Oregon, published ''[[African-American Baseline Essays]]'', a thick stack of loose-leaf background papers for teachers, commissioned to encourage black history instruction.  They have been used in Detroit, Atlanta, Fort Lauderdale, Newark, and scattered schools elsewhere, although they have been attacked for gross inaccuracy in an entire literature of detailed criticism by respected historians. ....}}</ref> \n\nSeveral such [[urban legend]]s describe Banneker's alleged activities in the [[Washington, D.C.]] area around the time that he assisted [[Andrew Ellicott]] in the initial survey of the boundaries of the future federal district.<ref name=Shipler/><ref>(1) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171226172141/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969, p. 7.] \"The name of Benjamin Banneker, the Afro-American self-taught mathematician and almanac-maker, occurs again and again in the several published accounts of the survey of Washington City begun in 1791, but with conflicting reports of the role which he played. Writers have implied a wide range of involvement, from the keeper of horses or supervisor of the woodcutters, to the full responsibility of not only the survey of the ten mile square but the design of the city as well. None of these accounts has described the contribution which Banneker actually made.\"<br>(2) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/126/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 126.] \"Benjamin Banneker's name does not appear on any of the contemporary documents or records relating to the selection, planning, and survey of the City of Washington.  An exhaustive search of the files under Public Buildings and Grounds in the U.S. National Archives and of the several collections in the Library of Congress have proved fruitless.  A careful perusal of all known surviving correspondence and papers of Andrew Ellicott and of Pierre Charles L'Enfant has likewise failed to reveal mention of Banneker.  This conclusively dispels the legend that after L'Enfant's dismissal and his refusal to make available his plan of the city, Ellicott was able to reconstruct it in detail from Banneker's recollection. Equally untrue are legends that Thomas Jefferson as Secretary of State invited Banneker to luncheon at the White House. Jefferson during this period was in Philadelphia, the national capital had not yet been built, and there was no White House.\u201d<br>(3) {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r_5ZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Locating the Federal District: Editorial Note: Footnote number 119|work=The Papers of Thomas Jefferson: 24 January\u201331 March 1791|volume=19|editor-first=Julian P.|editor-last=Boyd|editor-link=Julian P. Boyd|location=[[Princeton, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=1974|pages=41\u201343|oclc=1045069058|isbn=9780691185255|lccn=50007486|accessdate=2019-03-27|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br/>Recent biographical accounts of Benjamin Banneker (1731\u20131806), a mulatto whose father was a native African and whose grandmother was English, have done his memory a disservice by obscuring his real achievements under a cloud of extravagant claims to scientific accomplishment that have no foundation in fact. The single notable exception is Silvio A. Bedini's ''The Life of Benjamin Banneker'' (New York, 1972), a work of painstaking research and scrupulous attention to accuracy which also benefits from the author's discovery of important and hitherto unavailable manuscript sources. However, as Bedini points out, the story of Banneker's involvement in the survey of the Federal District \"rests on extremely meager documentation\" (p. 104). This consists of a single mention by TJ, two brief statements by Banneker himself, and the newspaper allusion quoted above. In consequence, Bedini's otherwise reliable biography accepts the version of Banneker's role in this episode as presented in reminiscences of nineteenth-century authors. These recollections, deriving in large part from members of the Ellicott family, who were prompted by Quaker inclinations to justice and equality, have compounded the confusion. The nature of TJ's connection with Banneker is treated in the Editorial Note to the group of documents under 30 Aug. 1791, but because of the obscured record it is necessary here to attempt a clarification of the role of this modest, self-taught tobacco farmer in the laying out of the national capital.<br/>First of all, because of unwarranted claims to the contrary, it must be pointed out that there is no evidence whatever that Banneker had anything to do with the survey of the Federal City or indeed with the final establishment of the boundaries of the Federal District. All available testimony shows that he was present only during the few weeks early in 1791 when the rough preliminary survey of the ten mile square was made; that, after this was concluded and before the final survey was begun, he returned to his farm and his astronomical studies in April, accompanying Ellicott part way on his brief journey back to Philadelphia; and that thenceforth he had no connection with the mapping of the seat of government. ...<br/>In any case, Banneker's participation in the surveying of the Federal District was unquestionably brief and his role uncertain.}}<br>(4) {{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1994/02/20/the-egyptian-illusion/ee123656-ca7f-4ef7-8f28-99d7edd166ba/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918055745/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1994/02/20/the-egyptian-illusion/ee123656-ca7f-4ef7-8f28-99d7edd166ba/|archivedate=2018-09-18|url-status=live|title=The Egyptian Illusion|last=Martel|first=Erich|work=Opinions|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=1994-02-20|accessdate=2018-09-17|quote=Teachers who want reliable information on African American history often don't know where to turn. Many have unfortunately looked to unreliable books and publications by Afrocentric writers. The African American Baseline Essays, developed by the public school system in Portland, Ore., are the most widespread Afrocentric teaching material. Educators should be aware of their crippling flaws. ....<br>\"Thomas Jefferson appointed Benjamin Banneker to survey the site for the capital, Washington, D.C.; ....\" according to the essay on African American scientists.<br>Had the author consulted \"The Life of Benjamin Banneker\" by Silvio Bedini, considered the definitive biography, he would have discovered no evidence for these claims. Jefferson appointed Andrew Ellicott to conduct the survey; Ellicott made Banneker his assistant for three months in 1791.}}<br>(6) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/318/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 318.] \"In the two centuries since Banneker's death, his achievements have been forgotten or misrepresented ..... In November 1971, on the anniversary of Banneker's birthday, the secretary of the interior authorized the 10th Street Overlook outside L'Enfant Plaza in Washington to be renamed and dedicated by the mayor as Benjamin Banneker Park. Once again, the reasons presented by the speakers on the occasion and widely reported by the press had been all based on erroneous information: Banneker was hailed for his contribution after L'Enfant was dismissed and Banneker \"saved the plan by reconstructing it from memory\u201d.\u201d<br>(7) [https://web.archive.org/web/20171226172305/https://www.amazon.com/The-Life-Benjamin-Banneker-African-American/product-reviews/0938420593 Murdock]. \"This very well-researched book also helps lay to rest some of the myths about what Banneker did and did not do during his most unusual lifetime; unfortunately, many websites and books continue to propagate these myths, probably because those authors do not understand what Banneker actually accomplished.\"<br>(8) [https://web.archive.org/web/20140426233224/http://www.profsurv.com/magazine/article.aspx?i=567 Toscano, 2000.] \"Some writers, in an effort to build up their hero, claim that Banneker was the designer of Washington. Other writers have asserted that Banneker's role in the survey is a myth without documentation. Neither group is correct. Bedini does a professional job of sorting out the truth from the falsehoods.\"<br>(9) [https://archive.org/details/banneker00char/page/142/mode/1up Cerami, 2002, pp. 142\u2013143.]<br>(10) {{cite web |url=http://dcpages.ari.net/History/Planning_DC.shtml|4=|title=L'Enfant designed more than D.C.: He designed a 200-year-old controversy |publisher=DCpages.com|first=Michael|last=Levine|work=History: Planning Our Capital City: Get to know the District of Columbia|date=2003-11-10|accessdate=2016-12-31|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031206191132/http://dcpages.ari.net/History/Planning_DC.shtml|archivedate=2003-12-06}}<br>(11) {{cite web|author=Bigbytes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031206191132/http://dcpages.ari.net/History/Planning_DC.shtml|archivedate=2003-12-06|url=http://dcsymbols.com/ovason/banneker.htm |title=Benjamin Banneker Stories |publisher=dcsymbols dot com |accessdate=2017-01-01}}<br/>(12) {{cite book|last=Weatherly|first=Myra|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827150959/https://books.google.com/books?id=I9iwiT_k4WoC&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=2019-08-27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I9iwiT_k4WoC&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=An Important Task|work=Benjamin Banneker: American Scientific Pioneer|year=2006|location=[[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]|publisher=[[Capstone Publishers|Compass Point Books]]|pages=76\u201377|isbn=0756515793|oclc=61864300|lccn=2005028708|accessdate=2019-08-27|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br/>The conflicts surrounding L'Enfant gave rise to an often\u2014repeated story that involved Banneker.  According to the story, Banneker, having seen the original design for the city only once, re-created it in detail after L'Enfant returned to France with the original plans. This legend has led some people to credit Banneker with a greater role in creating the capital city. However, there is no evidence that Banneker contributed anything to the design of the city or that he ever met L'Enfant.<br>Modern historians acknowledge that the inaccurate information\u2014the myths surrounding Banneker\u2014resulted in his contributions to the city being overvalued. Unfortunately, those myths sometimes obscure Banneker's greatest contribution to society\u2014the almanacs that he would publish in his later years.}}<br>(13) {{cite web |url= https://blogs.weta.org/boundarystones/2016/02/08/benjamin-bannekers-capital-contributions|title=Benjamin Banneker's Capital Contributions|date=2016-02-08|first=Richard|last=Brownell|work=Boundary Stones: WETA's Local History Blog|location=[[Arlington County, Virginia]]|publisher=[[WETA-TV|WETA]]|accessdate=2018-05-28}}<br>(14) {{cite web|last=Arnebeck|first=Bob|url=http://dcswamp.blogspot.com/2017/01/seat-of-empire.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129062551/http://dcswamp.blogspot.com/2017/01/seat-of-empire.html|archivedate=2018-01-29|title=Washington Examined: Seat of Empire: the General and the Plan 1790 to 1801|date=2017-01-02|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogger]]|accessdate=2018-01-29|quote=Meanwhile Andrew Ellicott, the nation's Surveyor General, finished surveying the boundary lines of the federal district, and joined L'Enfant in laying out the city. (Ellicott showed a fine sense of the opportunity presented by the project by hiring a mathematician who was a \"free Negro,\" to help with the survey. The Georgetown newspaper noted the significance of Benjamin Banneker's participation but, nearly sixty years old, he left the arduous project in May and returned to Baltimore to publish his almanac, and thus, contrary to legend, had nothing to do with L'Enfant's plan).<br>In late August L'Enfant took his completed plan to Philadelphia. The president approved but thought it premature to designate the sites of the other buildings and many monuments that L'Enfant envisioned.}}<br>(15) {{cite web|first=Louis|last=Keene|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831054904/https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|archivedate=August 31, 2019|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Black Tobacco Farmer Who The Presidents Couldn't Ignore|publisher=[[White House Historical Association|The White House Historical Association]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020|quote=Perhaps owing to the scarcity of recorded fact about his remarkable life, and because he was often invoked symbolically to advance social causes like abolition, Banneker\u2019s story has been susceptible to mythmaking. He has been incorrectly credited with drawing the street grid of Washington, D.C., ....}}</ref> Others involve his clock, his astronomical works, his almanacs and his journals.<ref name=Shipler/><ref>(1) [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=7 Whiteman, Maxwell (1969). BENJAMIN BANNEKER: Surveyor and Astronomer: 1731-1806: A biographical note] ''In'' [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=5 Whiteman, Maxwell (ed.)] \"The plan for a \"Peace Office\" in the Government of the United States, which also appeared in this issue (Banneker's 1793 Philadelphia almanac) has been attributed to Banneker. According to Edwin Wolf 2nd, Librarian of the [[Library Company of Philadelphia]] from whose institution these copies have been made, the \"Peace Office\" is the work of Dr. [[Benjamin Rush]].\"<br>(2) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/186/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 186.] \"Another important item in the 1793 almanac was \"A Plan Of a ''Peace-Office'' for the United States,\" which aroused a good deal of comment at the time. It was believed by many to have been Banneker's own work. Even within recent decades its authorship has been debated. In 1947 it was identified without question as the work of Dr. Benjamin Rush, in a volume of his writings that appeared in that year.\"<br>(3) {{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1994/02/20/the-egyptian-illusion/ee123656-ca7f-4ef7-8f28-99d7edd166ba/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918055745/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1994/02/20/the-egyptian-illusion/ee123656-ca7f-4ef7-8f28-99d7edd166ba/|archivedate=2018-09-18|url-status=live|title=The Egyptian Illusion|last=Martel|first=Erich|work=Opinions|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=1994-02-20|accessdate=2018-09-17|quote=.... \"Banneker \"wrote a proposal for the establishment of a United States Department of Peace,\" according to the essay on African American scientists.<br>Had the author consulted \"The Life of Benjamin Banneker\" by Silvio Bedini, considered the definitive biography, he would have discovered no evidence for these claims. .... Benjamin Rush authored the Department of Peace proposal; the confusion arose among earlier biographers because the proposal appeared in Banneker's 1793 almanac.}}<br>(4) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/43/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 43.] \"Banneker's clock was by no means the first timepiece in tidewater Maryland, as occasionally has erroneously been claimed. Timepieces were well known and available from the very earliest English settlements, ....\"<br>(5) {{cite web|first=Louis|last=Keene|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831054904/https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|archivedate=August 31, 2019|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Black Tobacco Farmer Who The Presidents Couldn't Ignore|publisher=[[White House Historical Association|The White House Historical Association]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020|quote=Perhaps owing to the scarcity of recorded fact about his remarkable life, and because he was often invoked symbolically to advance social causes like abolition, Banneker\u2019s story has been susceptible to mythmaking. He has been incorrectly credited with ......, making the first clock on the Eastern seaboard, being the first professional astronomer in America, and discovering the seventeen-year birth cycle of cicadas.}}</ref> Although parts of [[African-American culture]], all lack support by historical evidence. Some are contradicted by such evidence. \n\nA United States postage stamp and the names of a number of recreational and cultural facilities, schools, streets and other facilities and institutions throughout the United States have commememorated Banneker's documented and mythical accomplishments during the two centuries since he lived (see [[Commemorations of Benjamin Banneker]]).\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==Plan of the City of Washington==\n[[File:Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government of the United States - projected agreeable to the direction of the President of the United States... (14726320702).jpg|thumb|right|300px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Boston Public Library]]</sup></div>Facsimile of manuscript of Peter Charles L'Enfant's 1791 plan for the federal capital city ([[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]], 1887).<ref name=facsimile>{{cite web |first1=Peter Charles|last1=L'Enfant|last2=[[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]]|url=http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.gmd/g3850.ct000514|last3=United States Commissioner of Public Buildings|title=Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government of t(he) United States: projected agreeable to the direction of the President of the United States, in pursuance of an act of Congress passed the sixteenth day of July, MDCCXC, \"establishing the permanent seat on the bank of the Potowmac\": [Washington, D.C.]|location=Washington|publisher=[[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]]|lccn=88694201|year=1887|accessdate=2017-03-05}} [[Facsimile]] of the 1791 L'Enfant plan ''in'' Repository of the [[Library of Congress]] Geography and Map Division, Washington, D.C.</ref>]]\nWhile [[Andrew Ellicott]] and his team were conducting a survey of the boundaries of the future federal district during 1791-1792 (see [[Boundary Markers of the Original District of Columbia]]), [[Pierre Charles L'Enfant|Pierre (Peter) Charles L'Enfant]] was preparing a plan for the federal capital city (the City of Washington) (see [[L'Enfant Plan]]).<ref name=planning>{{cite book|url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015013259695;view=1up;seq=13|last=National Capital Planning Commission|year=1976|title=History|work=Boundary markers of the Nation's Capital: a proposal for their preservation & protection: a National Capital Planning Commission Bicentennial report |pages=3\u20139|place=Washington, D.C.|publisher=National Capital Planning Commission; For sale by the Superintendent of Documents, [[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]]|oclc=3772302|accessdate=2016-02-22|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]}}</ref><ref>(1) {{cite web |last=Ellicott|first=Andrew|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/88694130/|title=Territory of Columbia|work=Maps|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|year=1793|accessdate=2016-10-22|quote=Notes: ...  Accompanied by positive and negative photocopies of 3 letters dated 1793 relating to the map, 1 of which signed by: And'w Ellicott.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011082202/https://www.loc.gov/item/88694130/ |archivedate=2016-10-11}}<br/>(2) L'Enfant identified himself as \"Peter Charles L'Enfant\" during most of his life, while residing in the United States.  He wrote this name on his [http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.gmd/g3850.ct000512 \"Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government of t(he) United States ....\"] (Washington, D.C.) and on other legal documents. However, during the early 1900s, a French ambassador to the U.S., [[Jean Jules Jusserand]], popularized the use of L'Enfant's birth name, \"Pierre Charles L'Enfant\". (Reference: {{cite book|last=Bowling |first=Kenneth R. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1PZ4AAAAMAAJ|year=2002|title=Peter Charles L'Enfant: vision, honor, and male friendship in the early American Republic |publisher=George Washington University|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=2015-04-24 |via=[[Google Books]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701061754/http://books.google.com/books?id=1PZ4AAAAMAAJ |archivedate=2014-07-01}}) The [[United States Code]] states in {{USC|40|3309}}: \"(a) In General.\u2014The purposes of this chapter shall be carried out in the District of Columbia as nearly as may be practicable in harmony with the plan of Peter Charles L'Enfant.\" The [[National Park Service]] identifies L'Enfant as \"[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/Wash/text.htm#washington Major Peter Charles L'Enfant] \u00a0{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405134623/http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/Wash/text.htm |date=2014-04-05}}\" and as  \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20120113011410/http://www.nps.gov/history/Nr/travel/presidents/washington_monument.html Major Pierre (Peter) Charles L'Enfant]\" on its website.</ref> The capital city was to occupy a relatively small area bounded by [[Rock Creek (Potomac River)|Rock Creek]], the [[Potomac River]], the [[Anacostia River]] (known at the time as the \"Eastern Branch\") and the base of the [[escarpment]] of the [[Atlantic Seaboard fall line|Atlantic Seaboard Fall Line]].<ref name=planning/><ref name=planning2>(1) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969], p. 22-23.\"Considerable confusion developed among subsequent writers concerning the relative roles of Ellicott, L'Enfant and Banneker in the survey of the Federal City. Ellicott was, contrary to popular misconception, the first to receive an appointment to the project. His assignment was specifically to produce a survey of a ten-mile square within which the national capital was to be designed and laid out by L'Enfant. Ellicott and L'Enfant each worked independently under the supervision of the Commissioners appointed by Washington. After L'Enfant's subsequent dismissal, Ellicott was assigned the dual responsibility for continuing L'Enfant's work on the design of the city, and layout of public buildings, streets and property lots, in addition to completing his survey. Banneker was employed directly by Ellicott and did not at any time, as far as can be determined, work with or for L'Enfant.\"</ref><ref name=Passonneau>{{cite book |first=Joseph R. |last=Passonneau |title=Washington Through Two Centuries: A History in Maps and Images |place=New York |publisher=The Monacelli Press, Inc. |year=2004 |pages=14\u201316, 24\u201327|isbn=1-58093-091-3|oclc=53443052}}<br/>(2) {{cite web |last=Ellicott |first=Andrew |url=https://www.loc.gov/item/88694130/ |title=Territory of Columbia |work=Maps |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |year=1793 |accessdate=2016-10-22 |quote=Notes: ...  Accompanied by positive and negative photocopies of 3 letters dated 1793 relating to the map, 1 of which signed by: And'w Ellicott.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011082202/https://www.loc.gov/item/88694130/|archivedate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\nThe capital city was to be located at the center of the much larger {{convert|100|sqmi|km2|adj=on}} federal district, which was known at the time as the \"Territory of Columbia\" (see [[History of Washington, D.C.#Founding|Founding of Washington, D.C.]]).<ref name=planning/><ref name=planning2/><ref name=Bedini22>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969], p. 22-23.\"Considerable confusion developed among subsequent writers concerning the relative roles of Ellicott, L'Enfant and Banneker in the survey of the Federal City. Ellicott was, contrary to popular misconception, the first to receive an appointment to the project. His assignment was specifically to produce a survey of a ten-mile square within which the national capital was to be designed and laid out by L'Enfant. Ellicott and L'Enfant each worked independently under the supervision of the Commissioners appointed by Washington. After L'Enfant's subsequent dismissal, Ellicott was assigned the dual responsibility for continuing L'Enfant's work on the design of the city, and layout of public buildings, streets and property lots, in addition to completing his survey. Banneker was employed directly by Ellicott and did not at any time, as far as can be determined, work with or for L'Enfant.\"</ref> In late February 1792, [[Presidency of George Washington|President George Washington]] dismissed L'Enfant, who had failed to have his plan published and who was experiencing frequent conflicts with the three Commissioners that Washington had appointed to supervise the planning and survey of the federal district and city.<ref name=planning/><ref name=\"Bowling\">Bowling</ref><ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/centennialhisto00woolgoog/page/n112 Crew, pp. 101-102] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151111093014/https://books.google.com/books?pg=PA101&id=5Q81AAAAIAAJ |date=2015-11-11}}<br/>(2) {{cite web |url=http://home.earthlink.net/~docktor/wmslogo.htm |title=Plan of the City of Washington|publisher=Washington Map Society|date=1997-03-22|accessdate=2012-06-29|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623142642/http://home.earthlink.net/~docktor/wmslogo.htm |archivedate=2012-06-23}}</ref>\n[[File:Silvio Bedini with bust of Thomas Jefferson 1981.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Smithsonian Institution]]</sup><br />Silvio Bedini (1981)</div>]]\nA number of undocumented stories connecting Benjamin Banneker with the planning and survey of the federal capital city have appeared over the years. During the late 1900s and early 2000s, historian [[Silvio Bedini]] wrote and performed research about Banneker that refuted some of these tales while working in Washington, D.C. for over 40 years at the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[National Museum of American History|Museum of History and Technology/National Museum of American History]].<ref name=Founders>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r_5ZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Locating the Federal District: Editorial Note: Footnote number 119|work=The Papers of Thomas Jefferson: 24 January\u201331 March 1791|volume=19|editor-first=Julian P.|editor-last=Boyd|editor-link=Julian P. Boyd|location=[[Princeton, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=1974|pages=41\u201343|oclc=1045069058|isbn=9780691185255|lccn=50007486|accessdate=2019-03-27|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br>Recent biographical accounts of Benjamin Banneker (1731\u20131806), a mulatto whose father was a native African and whose grandmother was English, have done his memory a disservice by obscuring his real achievements under a cloud of extravagant claims to scientific accomplishment that have no foundation in fact. The single notable exception is Silvio A. Bedini's ''The Life of Benjamin Banneker'' (New York, 1972), a work of painstaking research and scrupulous attention to accuracy which also benefits from the author's discovery of important and hitherto unavailable manuscript sources. However, as Bedini points out, the story of Banneker's involvement in the survey of the Federal District \"rests on extremely meager documentation\" (p. 104). This consists of a single mention by TJ, two brief statements by Banneker himself, and the newspaper allusion quoted above. In consequence, Bedini's otherwise reliable biography accepts the version of Banneker's role in this episode as presented in reminiscences of nineteenth-century authors. These recollections, deriving in large part from members of the Ellicott family, who were prompted by Quaker inclinations to justice and equality, have compounded the confusion. The nature of TJ's connection with Banneker is treated in the Editorial Note to the group of documents under 30 Aug. 1791, but because of the obscured record it is necessary here to attempt a clarification of the role of this modest, self-taught tobacco farmer in the laying out of the national capital.<br>First of all, because of unwarranted claims to the contrary, it must be pointed out that there is no evidence whatever that Banneker had anything to do with the survey of the Federal City or indeed with the final establishment of the boundaries of the Federal District. All available testimony shows that he was present only during the few weeks early in 1791 when the rough preliminary survey of the ten mile square was made; that, after this was concluded and before the final survey was begun, he returned to his farm and his astronomical studies in April, accompanying Ellicott part way on his brief journey back to Philadelphia; and that thenceforth he had no connection with the mapping of the seat of government. ...<br/>In any case, Banneker's participation in the surveying of the Federal District was unquestionably brief and his role uncertain.}}</ref><ref>(1) [https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst2311964unit#page/n8/mode/1up Bedini, 1964.]<br>(2) [http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007223056/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf |date=October 7, 2017 }}<br>(3) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/n8/mode/1up Bedini, 1972.]<br>(4) Bedini, 1991.<br>(5) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/n7/mode/1up Bedini,1999.]<br>(6) [https://web.archive.org/web/20160310095152/http://www.amazon.com/The-Life-Benjamin-Banneker-African-American/dp/0938420593#customerReviews Murdock]<br>(7) [https://web.archive.org/web/20140426233224/http://www.profsurv.com/magazine/article.aspx?i=567 Toscano, 2000.]<br>(8) [http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Benjamin_Banneker.aspx Bedini, 2008.]</ref>\n\nIn a 1969 publication, Bedini reported that a story connecting Banneker with the survey and planning of the federal city had appeared within a work that a member of the Ellicott family had edited. The [[Quakers in North America|Friends' (Quakers')]] Book Association published the work in [[Philadelphia]] during 1884. \n\nThe story stated:<blockquote>Major Ellicott selected Benjamin Banneker as his assistant upon this occasion, and it was with his aid that the lines of the Federal Territory, as the District of Columbia was then called, were run.<br />It was the work, also of Major Elllicott, under the orders of General Washington, then President of the United States, to locate the sites of the Capitol, President's House, Treasury and other public buildings. In this, also, Banneker was his assistant.<ref>{{cite book |last=Tyson |first=Martha Ellicott |editor=Kirk, Anne Tyson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1YBiPwAACAAJ |title=Banneker, the Afric-American Astronomer. From the posthumous papers of M.E. Tyson. Edited by her daughter|pages=38\u201339|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |publisher=Friends' Book Association|year=1884|lccn=04013085|oclc=79879919|via=[[Google Books]] |quote=Major Ellicott selected Benjamin Banneker as his assistant upon this occasion, and it was with his aid that the lines of the Federal Territory, as the District of Columbia was then called, were run.<br/>It was the work, also of Major Elllicott, under the orders of General Washington, then President of the United States, to locate the sites of the Capitol, President's House, Treasury and other public buildings.  In this, also, Banneker was his assistant.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203192640/https://books.google.com/books?id=1YBiPwAACAAJ |archivedate=2016-02-03}} ''Quoted in'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969], p. 26.</ref></blockquote>\n\nBedini noted that writers had repeated and embellished the story, sometimes in conflicting ways.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969, p. 7.] \"The name of Benjamin Banneker, the Afro-American self-taught mathematician and almanac-maker, occurs again and again in the several published accounts of the survey of Washington City [D.C.] begun in 1791, but with conflicting reports of the role which he played. Writers have implied a wide range of involvement, from the keeper of horses or supervisor of the woodcutters, to the full responsibility of not only the survey of the ten-mile square but the design of the city as well. None of these accounts has described the contribution which Banneker actually made.\"</ref> One version of the tale claims that Banneker \"made astronomical calculations and implementations\" that established points of significance within the city, including those of the [[White House]], the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]], the [[Treasury Building (Washington, D.C.)|Treasury Building]] and the \"16th Street Meridian\" (see [[Washington meridians#White House meridian|White House meridian]]). Other versions state that Banneker assisted Andrew Ellicott in locating the sites of some or all of those features or \"laid out Washington\".<ref>The following websites and publications relate parts or all of various versions of this story:<br>(1) {{cite book |last=Tyson |first=Martha Ellicott |editor=Kirk, Anne Tyson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1YBiPwAACAAJ |title=Banneker, the Afric-American Astronomer. From the posthumous papers of M.E. Tyson. Edited by her daughter |pages=38\u201339 |location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |publisher=Friends' Book Association |year=1884 |lccn=04013085 |oclc=79879919 |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=Major Ellicott selected Benjamin Banneker as his assistant upon this occasion, and it was with his aid that the lines of the Federal Territory, as the District of Columbia was then called, were run.<br>It was the work, also of Major Elllicott, under the orders of General Washington, then President of the United States, to locate the sites of the Capitol, President's House, Treasury and other public buildings.  In this, also, Banneker was his assistant. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203192640/https://books.google.com/books?id=1YBiPwAACAAJ |archivedate=2016-02-03 }} ''Quoted in'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969], p. 26.<br>(2) {{cite book|last=Cromwell|first=John W.|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=loc.ark:/13960/t0pr7v773;view=1up;seq=122|title=Benjamin Banneker|work=The Negro in American History: Men and Women Eminent in the Evolution of the American of African Descent|page=90|location=Washington|publisher=The Negro Academy|year=1914|lccn=14007742|oclc=1049895792|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]|accessdate=2019-03-10|quote=In keeping with the provisions of the Constitutional Convention, Maryland and Virginia had ceded to the central government certain territory, known as the Federal Territory, to be used as the Nation's Capital, but its exact bondaries had not been fixed. Mr. Andrew Ellicott was commissioned to survey the boundaries and Benjamin Banneker was invited as a man of scientific attainments and professional skill to assist in the work. He accepted the invitation and shared in the fixing of the boundaries of the District, in the selection of the site of the Capitol Building, in locating an eligible site for the Executive Mansion, the Treasury and other buildings.}}<br>(4) {{cite book|first1=John Walton|last1=Caughey|first2=John Hope|last2=Franklin|author2-link=John Hope Franklin|first3=Ernest R.|last3=May|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015170343/https://books.google.com/books?id=EUNCAAAAIAAJ&q=%22George+Ellicott%22|archivedate=2019-10-15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EUNCAAAAIAAJ&q=%22George+Ellicott%22|title=Land of the Free: A History of the United States|pages=192\u2013193|year=1966|location=New York|publisher=Benziger Brothers|lccn=66012962|oclc=654547410|accessdate=2019-10-15|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=.... . The third member was a Quaker businessman and scientist, George Ellicott. L'Enfant, Banneker and Ellicott drew up plans for a city that was greater than Rome, Paris, or London.}}<br>(4) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425142547/https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED042751.pdf|archivedate=2015-04-25|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED042751.pdf|title=Grade Four: Social Studies|work=Education for Intercultural Relations (Grades K-12)|publisher=Evansville-Vanderburgh School Corporation|location=[[Evansville, Indiana]]|year=1967|page=26|author=Committees of the Professional Staff During the School Year 1967-1968|accessdate=2019-02-15|quote=Benjamin Banneker, laid out Washington}}<br>(5) {{cite web|author=Diversity Development |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019094625/http://about.usps.com/publications/pub354.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-19 |url=http://about.usps.com/publications/pub354.pdf |title=Benjamin Banneker |work=Publication 354: African Americans on Stamps: A Celebration of African-American Heritage |page=3 |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |year=2004 |accessdate=2015-03-14 |quote=A self-taught mathematician and astronomer, Benjamin Banneker was probably the most accomplished African American of America's colonial period. .... In 1791 he helped design and survey the city of Washington, D.C. }}<br>(6) {{cite web|url=https://arago.si.edu/exhibit_461_3.html|title=Early Pioneers|work=Arago: People, Postage & The Post (Exhibits)|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Postal Museum]]|accessdate=2018-01-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203015753/http://arago.si.edu/exhibit_461_3.html|archivedate=2016-02-03|quote=A self-taught mathematician and astronomer, Benjamin Banneker was probably the most accomplished African American of America's colonial period. .... In 1791 he helped design and survey the city of Washington, D.C.}}<br>(7) {{cite web|last=Seats |first=Peggy C. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915184529/http://www.bannekermemorial.org/bbwhitepaper.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-15 |url=http://www.bannekermemorial.org/bbwhitepaper.pdf |title=Two Centuries Later: Rumors Continue to Abound Regarding Benjamin Banneker's Contributions in the Planning of WDC |work=The Memorial: Benjamin Banneker White Paper |publisher=Washington Interdependence Council: Administrators of the Benjamin Banneker Memorial |date=2004-04-21 |accessdate=2015-09-15 |quote=In an effort to cover up the role Banneker played as one of the Founding Architects of DC, it was George Washington who insisted, however, that the L'Enfant Plan was named for L'Enfant although, in actuality, it was produced by Ellicott and Banneker. This mandate was made by Washington, in addition to authorizing the raiding of Ellicott's office for evidence of Banneker's journals, and astronomical charting, including his prediction of an eclipse, as they were embarrassed by L'Enfant's inability to technically execute a plan and had to save face. .... Benjamin Banneker played a critical role in not only helping to survey the nation's capitol, but also in helping to determine astrological influences upon the capitol by virtue of the timing of certain dominating astronomical, astrological influences and strategic metaphysical influences as implemented in concert with the stars which directly impacted the selection for the placement of key buildings and grand boulevards such as 16th St., NW. }}<br/>(8) {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tjc8AQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Ellicott|title=Time Almanac 2005|author=((Editors of Time Magazine))|work=[[Time Almanac with Information Please]]|authorlink=Time (magazine)|date=2004-12-28|page=204|oclc=57219160|isbn=1932273352|accessdate=2018-12-13|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time Home Entertainment, Inc.]]|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=The city was planned and partly laid out by Maj. Pierre Charles L'Enfant, a French engineer. That work was perfected and completed by Maj. Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker, a freeborn black man, who was an astronomer and mathematician.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213162343/https://books.google.com/books?id=Tjc8AQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Ellicott|archive-date=December 13, 2018|url-status=dead}}<br/>(9) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060506043112/http://bannekermemorial.org/history.htm|archivedate=2006-05-06|url=http://www.bannekermemorial.org/history.htm|title=His Story: A Man of Many Firsts|publisher=Washington Interdependence Council: Administrators of the Benjamin Banneker Memorial|year=2005|accessdate=2012-06-29|via=The JBG Companies|quote=Banneker was a member of the first presidential appointed team charged with the establishment of the nation's capitol. His astronomical calculations and implementations played a critical role is establishing points of astronomical significance in the nation's capitol, including the location of the 16th Street Meridian, Boundary Stones, White House, Capitol and Treasury Building. Banneker worked as Assistant to Major Andrew Ellicott, America's Geographer General, thereby serving as a critical member of the team of the first presidential commission. In this capacity, he provided the astronomical calculations for the project, and assisted in the reconstruction of the plans for laying out the streets of the nation's capitol. He and Major Ellicott both surveyed the area of, and configured the final layout for, the placement of major governmental buildings, boulevards and avenues as drawn for the map for the nation's capitol, producing the finished document commonly deferred to as the L'Enfant Plan.}}<br/>(10) {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qqbdya4yMmoC&pg=PA169&lpg=PA169|first1=Dutch|last1=Sheet|first2=Chuck D|last2=Pierce|title=Brief History of Washington, D.C.|work=Releasing The Prophetic Destiny Of A Nation: Discovering How Your Future Can Be Greater Than Your Past|location=[[Shippensburg, Pennsylvania]]|publisher=Destiny Image Publishers, Inc.|year=2005|isbn=0768422841|oclc=60768598|page=169|accessdate=2018-12-14|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=The city was planned and partly laid out by [Major] Pierre Charles L'Enfant, a French engineer. That work was perfected and completed by [Major] Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker, a freeborn black man, who was an astronomer and mathematician.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612155246/https://books.google.com/books?id=Qqbdya4yMmoC&pg=PA169&lpg=PA169#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=June 12, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n[[File:Daniel murray.jpg|thumb|right|175px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup><br/>Daniel A. P. Murray</div>]]\n\nIn 1921, [[Daniel Alexander Payne Murray|Daniel A. P. Murray]], an African American serving as an assistant librarian of the [[Library of Congress]], read a paper before the Banneker Association of Washington that connected Banneker with L'Enfant's plan for the capital city. The paper stated:\n\n<blockquote> ... L'Enfant made a demand that could not be accorded and ... in a fit of high dudgeon gathered all his plans and papers and unceremoniously left. ... Washington was in despair, since it involved a defeat of all of his cherished plans in regard to the \"Federal City.\" This perturbation on his part was quickly ended, however, when it transpired that Banneker had daily for the purposes of calculation and practice, transcribed nearly all L'Enfant's field notes and through the assistance they afforded Mr. Andrew Ellicott, L'Enfant's assistant, Washington City was laid down very nearly on the original lines. ... By this act the brain of the Afro-American is indissolubly linked with the Capital and nation.<ref>{{cite book|last=Murray|first=Daniel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7bYqADpiU4C&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Paper Read Before the Banneker of Association of Washington}} ''In'' {{cite book |title=Banneker: The Afro-American Astronomer|last=Allen|first=Will W.|year=1921|location=Washington, D.C.|oclc=10344679|lccn=21017456}} Reprinted in {{cite book|first1=Will W.|last1=Allen|first2=Daniel|last2=Murray|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7bYqADpiU4C|title=Banneker: The Afro-American Astronomer|pages=12\u201315|publisher=Black Classic Press|location=Baltimore, Maryland|year=2005|oclc=808618979|isbn=0933121-48-2|via=[[Google Books]]|accessdate=2017-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215012211/https://books.google.com/books?id=K7bYqADpiU4C&pg=PA12|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1976 (more than 50 years later), Jerome Klinkowitz stated within a book that described the works of Banneker and other early black American writers that Murray's report had initiated a myth about Banneker's career. Klinkowitz noted that Murray had not provided any support for his claim that Banneker had recalled L'Enfant's plan for Washington, D.C. Klinkowitz also described a number of other Banneker myths and subsequent works that had refuted them.<ref>{{cite book|last=Klinkowitz|first=Jerome |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A_uuCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA18#v=onepage&f=false |title=Benjamin Banneker|work=Early Writers: Jupiter Hammon, Phillis Wheatley, and Benjamin Banneker.}} ''In'' {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A_uuCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Black American Writers: Biographical Essays\"|volume=1: Beginnings Through the Harlem Renaissance and Langston Hughes|editor1-last=Inge|editor1-first=M. Thomas |editor2-last=Duke|editor2-first=Maurice|editor3-last=Bryer|editor3-first=Jackson R.|pages=18\u201320|location=New York|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|year=1978|isbn=0312082606|lccn=77085987 |doi=10.1007/978-1-349-81436-7|oclc=756464907|accessdate=March 22, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\nBy 1929, variations of the myth had become widespread. When describing the ceremonial presentation to [[Howard University]] in Washington, D.C., of a [[sundial]] memorializing Banneker, the ''[[Chicago Defender]]'' newspaper reported in that year that a speaker had claimed that:\n\n<blockquote>.... he (Banneker) was appointed by President George Washington to aid Major L'Enfant, famed French architect, to plan the layout of the District of Columbia. L'Enfant died before the work was completed, which required Banneker to carry on in his stead.<ref name=Defender>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepearlofomega.org/Resources/Documents/The%20Dial,%20Ch%20iDefender,%202-16-29.pdf|format=PDF|title=Howard U Gets Memorial to Benjamin Banneker |work=Chicago, Illinois: [[The Chicago Defender]] (National edition)|date=1929-02-16 |page=A1 |publisher=[[ProQuest]] Historical Newspapers |accessdate=2017-11-09|via=[http://www.thepearlofomega.org The Pearl of Omega]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109123630/http://www.thepearlofomega.org/Resources/Documents/The%20Dial,%20Ch%20iDefender,%202-16-29.pdf|archivedate=2017-11-09}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, as a book that won the 1917 [[Pulitzer Prize for History]] had earlier reported, L'Enfant lived long after he developed his plan for the federal capital city. He died near the City of Washington in 1825.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/withamericansofp01juss/page/190 Jusserand, p. 190.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610081848/https://books.google.com/books?id=u2MUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA190 |date=2016-06-10 }}</ref>\n[[File:Portrait of Shirley Graham.jpg|thumb|left|125px|<sup><center>Library of Congress</center></sup><center>Shirley Graham (1946)</center>]]\n\nIn 1946, an activist for African American causes, [[Shirley Graham DuBois|Shirley Graham]], authored a book about Banneker's life entitled ''Your Humble Servant''. Graham's notes on her sources stated that she had constructed the book's story \"within the framework of little known true facts\". Her notes further stated that \"all dates and main events can be documented\" and that she had filled in all gaps with incidents of whose probability she was convinced.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/yourmosthumblese00dubo/page/227/mode/1up Graham, 1946, ''Notes on Sources'', p. 227.] \"This story of Benjamin Banneker has been constructed within the framework of little known true facts. All dates and main events can be documented. All gaps have been filled in with incidents of whose probablity I am convinced\".</ref> However, when describing Graham's book in a 1972 biography of Banneker, Bedini stated that her book had been written for children, was highly fictionalized and, having become popular, had \"resulted in yet more confusion concerning Banneker's achievements and their importance\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/300/mode/1up/search/Graham Bedini, 1972, p. 300.]</ref>\n\nGraham's account of Banneker's involvement in the origins of the District of Columbia stated that Banneker had worked with L'Enfant. Her story stated that in early 1792, L'Enfant \"packed everything and departed --- taking the plans with him.\" Her account further stated that Banneker then reconstructed L'Enfant's plan from memory within a period of three days, during which time he visited his home in Ellicott's Mills, Maryland. Her account additionally stated that the plans that Banneker had drawn from memory provided upon his return to the federal territory the basis for the later construction of the City of Washington.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/yourmosthumblese00dubo/page/170/mode/1up Graham, 1946, Chapter XI: ----- ''Sir, I Have the Plans in My Head'', pp. 170-178.]</ref>\n\nA number of accounts have repeated or extended Graham's fable before and after the publication of Bedini's 1972 biography.<ref>The following websites and publications relate parts or all of various versions of this myth:\n*{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=C. L.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5zkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Saved Washington, D. C.|work=[[Negro Digest]]: Negro History Issue|pages=18\u201320|volume=15|number=4|date=February 1966|location=Chicago, Illinois|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company, Inc.|via=[[Google Books]]|accessdate=2019-02-17}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b4pHvAEACAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22sites%22|title=Black Heroes in Our Nation's History: A Tribute to Those Who Helped Shape America|last=Drotning|first=Phillip T.|year=1969|page=35|location=New York|publisher=[[Cowles Media Company|Cowles Book Company, Inc.]]|lccn=69017306|oclc=558488211|accessdate=2019-02-12|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=Banneker and George Ellicott, a Quaker friend, selected the sites for the Capitol, the White House, and other major government buildings. The black surveyor also helped L'Enfant lay out the ingenious arrangement of broad avenues, mall, circles, and parks that make Washington such an attractive city even today. When a dispute arose between George Washington and L'Enfant in 1792, resulting in the French architect's dismissal ....}}\n*{{cite book|last=Haber|first=Louis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kh6GOI_258YC&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Banjamin Banneker: 1731\u20141806|work=Black Pioneers of Science and Invention|edition=First Oddssey Classics (1992)|year=1970|pages=15\u201316|publisher=[[Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt]]|oclc=1024156094|isbn=9780152085667|lccn=91008923|accessdate=2019-03-15|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br/>At about the time that Banneker began working on his almanac, President Washington had decided to move the capital from Philadelphia to a new location that was to be called Washington. He appointed Major Pierre Charles L'Enfant who had served in the Continental Army in the Corps of Engineers, to be in charge of building the new city. Major Andrew Ellicott, one of the Ellicott boys, was named Chief Surveyor. At Jefferson's request, Banneker was appointed as the third member of the team.<br/>The assignment was to define the boundaries of the new city and then design and lay out its streets and major buildings. Banneker worked closely with L'Enfant and his maps. But the bureaucrats of that day did not take kindly to a foreigner being given so much power and authority and they interfered in many frustrating ways.  This resulted in the highly sensitive and hot-tempered L'Enfant resigning his position and returning to France, taking all of the plans and maps with him. Everyone was dismayed and Jefferson called a meeting of the men involved. What was to be done? Start all over again after more than a year's work? Dispair and frustration showed on their faces. Suddenly Banneker asked, \"Did you like the plans that were made?\" All eyes turned to him. \"Of course, but we don't have them.\" \"I think I can reproduce them from memory\", said Banneker. The men were astounded and somewhat skeptical. Banneker then went home, and because of his remarkable memory, was able to reproduce all the plans in two days. The work of laying out the city of Washington, with its streets and major buildings, was completed and stands today as a monument to Banneker's genius.}}\n*{{cite book |year=1970 |first=Claude |last=Lewis |url=https://archive.org/details/benjaminbanneker00lewi |url-access=registration |title=Chapter 9: Planning the Nation's Capital |work=Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Saved Washington |location=New York |publisher=McGraw-Hill |pages=[https://archive.org/details/benjaminbanneker00lewi/page/79 79]\u201395 |oclc=72113 |lccn=79092101 |accessdate=2019-09-19 |quote=He probably does, Mr. Secretary. Benjamin Banneker has an incredible memory. I've known him for years and if he says that he remembers the plans, I believe he does. |via=[[Internet Archive]] }} \n*{{cite news|last=Oliver|first=Elizabeth M.|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19781216&id=pvkmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MwMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1220,4936390&hl=en|title=Ossie Davis Stars as Benjamin Banneker|work=[[Baltimore Afro-American]]|date=1978-12-09|page=36|location=Baltimore, Maryland|accessdate=2019-02-15|via=[[Google News]]|quote=Before his death in 1806, Banneker had gained fame in America, France and England as a scientist, astronomer inventor of the first clock and the mathematician who laid out Washington, D.C. .... Suddenly, Major L'Enfant, chairman of the D.C. committee went back to France with the plans. But Banneker, who had an unbelievable memory reproduced the plans and the Capital was completed.}}\n*{{cite web |title=BENJAMIN BANNEKER (1731\u20131806) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826032841/http://www.nathanielturner.com/benbanneker2.htm |archivedate=2012-08-26 |url=http://www.nathanielturner.com/benbanneker2.htm |work=Source: Empak \"Black History\" Publication Series (1985) |publisher=\"ChickenBones: A Journal for Literary & Artistic African-American Themes |date=2007-10-18 |accessdate=2012-06-29|quote=Banneker helped in selecting the sites for the U.S. Capitol building, the U.S. Treasury building, the White House and other Federal buildings. When the chairman of the civil engineering team, Major L'Enfant, abruptly resigned and returned to France with the plans, Banneker's photographic memory enabled him to reproduce them in their entirety. Washington, D.C., with its grand avenues and buildings, was completed and stands today as a monument to Banneker's genius.}}\n*{{cite web|last=Miller|first=E. Lynn|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.c064181081;view=1up;seq=21|title=Banneker, Benjamin|pages=13\u201315|work=Pioneers of American Landscape Design II: An Annotated Biography: [[United States Department of the Interior]], [[National Park Service]], Cultural Resources, Heritage Preservation Services, Historic Landscape Initiative|editor-last1=Birnbaum|editor-first1=Charles A.|editor-last2=Fix|editor-first2=Julie K.|location=Washington, D.C.|year=1995|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]]|isbn=0160480604|lccn=96118947|oclc=605386759|quote=Since L'Enfant kept his plans and work secret, the only people who ever saw them were Ellicott and Banneker, who were surveying the land and responsible for providing him (Thomas Jefferson) with topographic information. L'Enfant, running into difficulties with land owners, was dismissed by President George Washington and promptly left town with all of his drawings. When Jefferson summoned Ellicott and Banneker to assess the damage and to possibly start over, Banneker told Jefferson that he could redraw the plans from memory in no more than three or four days.<br>Although the accuracy of this account cannot be completely documented, it seems that Banneker was the only one who had the mathematical mind and the photographic memory to accomplish such a stunning feat. The plan which is known today as the Ellicott plan is most likely the work of Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker.|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]|accessdate=2019-03-11}}\n*{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Mitchell C.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000818203634/http://www.princeton.edu/~mcbrown/display/banneker.html|archivedate=August 18, 2000|url=http://www.princeton.edu:80/~mcbrown/display/banneker.html|title=Benjamin Banneker: Mathematician, Astronomer|work=The Faces of Science: African Americans in the Sciences|publisher=[[Princeton University]]|year=2000|accessdate=2019-01-07|quote=Banneker and Ellicott worked closely with Pierre L'Enfant who was the architect in charge of planning Washington D.C. L'Enfant was suddenly dismissed from project, due to his temper. When he left, he took the plans with him. Banneker recreated the plans from memory, saving the U.S. government the effort and expense of having someone else design the capital.|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.bnl.gov/bera/activities/globe/banneker.htm |title=Benjamin Banneker (1731\u20131806) |publisher=Brookhaven Employees' Recreation Association, [[Brookhaven National Laboratory]] |location=[[Upton, New York]] |accessdate=2018-12-13 |quote=Without Benjamin Banneker, our nation's capital would not exist as we know it.  After a year of work, the Frenchman hired by George Washington to design the capital, L'Enfant, stormed off the job, taking all the plans.  Banneker, placed on the planning committee at Thomas Jefferson's request, saved the project by reproducing from memory, in two days, a complete layout of the streets, parks, and major buildings. Thus Washington, D.C. itself can be considered a monument to the genius of this great man. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010914091456/http://www.bnl.gov/bera/activities/globe/banneker.htm |archive-date=September 14, 2001 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite book |chapter=Benjamin Banneker |first=Molefi Kete |last=Asante |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HwuGTSnc2CsC&pg=PA49 |title=100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia |location=Amherst, New York |publisher=Prometheus Books |year=2002 |page=49 |isbn=1-57392-963-8 |oclc=606853456 |lccn=2002018993 |accessdate=2018-12-12 |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=... when President George Washington, in February 1791, commissioned Ellicott and the French engineer L'Enfant to help plan the construction of the nation's capital on an area of land twenty-five sq kilometer (10 sq mi) in Virginia and Maryland, Ellicott asked Banneker to assist him. Soon thereafter the Frenchman abandoned the project over a dispute with some Americans. L'Enfant refused to leave his plans with the surveying team, but because Banneker had placed close attention to the mathematical details, he was able to reproduce most of the plans and ideas from memory. For this reason, some refer to Washington, D.C., as Banneker's Town. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213222457/https://books.google.com/books?id=HwuGTSnc2CsC&pg=PA49#v=onepage&q&f=false |archive-date=December 13, 2018 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.harcourtschool.com/activity/biographies/banneker/ |work=Harcourt Multimedia Biographies|title=Benjamin Banneker: 1731-1806|publisher=[[Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt School Publishers]]|accessdate=2012-07-02|quote=Major Pierre-Charles L'Enfant was asked to design the city. After a short time, L'Enfant was fired from the job and left town with the blueprints, or plan, of the city's layout. Luckily, Banneker had seen the plans and was able to redraw the layout of Washington, D.C., in two days. For this, Banneker won the admiration of the new American government.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021228111534/http://www.harcourtschool.com/activity/biographies/banneker/|archive-date=December 28, 2002}}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030529082100/http://www.successmaker.com/Subscriber/1,22/ReadingActivities/hero.html|archivedate=2003-05-29|url=http://www.successmaker.com/Subscriber/1,22/ReadingActivities/hero.html#reading|title=An Early American Hero: Benjamin Banneker|work=SuccessMaker Enterprise|publisher=[[Pearson Education|Pearson Education, Inc.]]|accessdate=2012-05-06|quote=In 1792, when it seemed as if work on the United States of America's new capital city was about to come to a grinding halt, Benjamin Banneker came to the rescue. The French architect who had been in charge of planning the city, Pierre L'Enfant, was fired because of his hotheaded behavior. He immediately left the country and returned to France, taking with him all the plans for the city of Washington. President George Washington and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson were distressed. Would they have to start all over, having a year's worth of work go to waste? Perhaps not. Noted surveyor Benjamin Banneker had been working closely with L'Enfant and Chief Surveyor Andrew Ellicott. Banneker thought he might be able to redraw all the plans\u2014from memory! Two days later he delivered the plans, and construction proceeded without significant delay. Today the city of Washington, D.C., stands as a reminder of Banneker's genius. .... Today we remember Banneker for many different reasons. His great mind saved the plans for our nation's capital.}}\n*{{cite web|last=Newbold|first=Ken|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423173814/http://www.jmu.edu/madison/center/main_pages/madison_archives/era/african/free/banneker/bio.htm|archivedate=2009-05-23|url=http://www.jmu.edu/madison/center/main_pages/madison_archives/era/african/free/banneker/bio.htm|title=Benjamin Banneker: A Brief Biography|publisher=The James Madison Center, [[James Madison University]]|location=[[Harrisonburg, Virginia]]|date=2004-05-17|accessdate=2011-12-25|quote=In 1791, Major Andrew Ellicott asked Banneker to help him survey the \"Federal Territory\", which would become the nation's Capital. Working alongside, Pierre L'Enfant, Banneker became an expert on the plans for the city. L'Enfant was dismissed because of his temper and took the plans for Washington with him. Banneker recreated the plans from memory, saving the government the time and money of having to design the city.}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Site_Evaluation_Study__PhaseI_Data_Gathering_Report.pdf|title=Site Evaluation Study: Phase I: Data Gathering Report|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]]|date=2005-09-30|page=31|quote=Benjamin Banneker, an African American, worked with Major Andrew Ellicott to play a central role in Pierre L'Enfant's original plan of the Nation's Capital. ... Banneker and Ellicott worked closely with Pierre L'Enfant in the planning of Washington, D.C. When L'Enfant was dismissed from the project and took his plans with him, Banneker recreated the plans from memory.|accessdate=2017-11-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194520/http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Site_Evaluation_Study__PhaseI_Data_Gathering_Report.pdf|archivedate=2015-09-23}}\n*The thirteenth paragraph of {{cite web|last=Bofah|first=Kofi|url=https://login.yahoo.com/config/login?.src=ycn&.intl=us&.done=http%3A%2F%2Fvoices.yahoo.com%2Fblack-history-benjamin-banneker-genius-2703097.html|title=Black History: Benjamin Banneker, Genius: The Legend of an Intellectual and Architect of Washington, D.C.|date=2009-02-20|work=[[Associated Content|Yahoo! Voices]]|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=2012-09-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402194747/https://login.yahoo.com/config/login?.src=ycn&.intl=us&.done=http%3A%2F%2Fvoices.yahoo.com%2Fblack-history-benjamin-banneker-genius-2703097.html|archivedate=2015-04-02}}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301084135/http://benjaminbanneker.k12.dc.us/benjamin_banneker.html|title=Who was Benjamin Banneker?|archivedate=2012-03-01|url=http://benjaminbanneker.k12.dc.us/benjamin_banneker.html|publisher=[[Benjamin Banneker Academic High School]]|location=Washington, D.C.|year=2009|accessdate=2012-06-29|quote=Banneker helped in selecting the sites for the U.S. Capitol building, the U.S. Treasury building, the White House and other Federal buildings. When the chairman of the civil engineering team, Major L'Enfant, abruptly resigned and returned to France with the plans, Banneker's photographic memory enabled him to reproduce them in their entirety. Washington, DC, with its grand avenues and buildings, was completed and stands today as a monument to Banneker's genius.}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.blackinventor.com/pages/benjamin-banneker.html|first=Gaius|last=Chamberlain|title=Benjamin Banneker|work=\"The Black Inventor Online Museum\"|publisher=[[Adscape|Adscape International, LLC]]|date=2012-03-11|accessdate=2012-06-29|quote=Major Pierre L'Enfant from France was commissioned to develop the plans for the new city and at Jefferson's request, Banneker was included as one of the men appointed to assist him. Banneker consulted frequently with L'Enfant and studied his draft and plans for the Capitol City carefully. L'Enfant was subject to great criticism and hostility because he was a foreigner and abruptly resigned from the project and moved back to France.  As the remaining members of the team gathered, they began debating as to how they should start from scratch. Banneker surprised them when he asserted that he could reproduce the plans from memory and in two days did exactly as he had promised. The plans he drew were the basis for the layout of streets, buildings and monuments that exist to this day in Washington D.C.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109002649/http://blackinventor.com/benjamin-banneker/|archivedate=2018-01-09}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.africanglobe.net/featured/benjamin-banneker-man-designed-washington-dc/ |title=Benjamin Banneker The Man Who Designed Washington DC |date=2013-12-08 |publisher=African Globe |accessdate=2018-12-13 |quote=Impressed by his abilities, Jefferson recommended Benjamin Banneker to be a part of a surveying team to lay out Washington, D.C. Appointed to the three-man team by president George Washington, Benjamin Banneker wound up saving the project when the lead architect quit in a fury \u2013 taking all the plans with him. Using his meticulous memory, Benjamin Banneker was able to recreate the plans. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210109/https://www.africanglobe.net/featured/benjamin-banneker-man-designed-washington-dc/ |archive-date=November 3, 2018 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|last=Cohan-Lawson|first=Elizabeth|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103000034/http://iforcolor.org/benjamin-banneker-elizabeth-cohan-lawson/|archivedate=2014-11-03|url=http://iforcolor.org/benjamin-banneker-abolitionist-inventor-and-intellectual-by-elizabeth-cohan-lawson/5/|title=Benjamin Banneker\u2014Abolitionist, Inventor, and Intellectual|work=I for Color: African American Voices in Art & History, created by Dale Ricardo Shields|date=2014-01-31|page=5|accessdate=2014-03-04|quote=It appeared as though the plan would have to be scrapped, but Banneker, with his eidetic memory, spent the next two days recreating the entirety of the schematics, saving the entire project. Dubbed \"The Man Who Saved Washington\", we owe the layout of our capital solely on Banneker's memory and dedication to a project that was almost a complete failure.}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4pwhAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA334|title=Who Made the First Clock in the American Colonies and was the First African American To Publish an Almanac?|work=African American Firsts: Famous, Little-Known and Unsung Triumphs of Blacks in America|first=Joan|last=Potter|page=334|location=[[New York City|New York]]|publisher=Dafina Books, [[Kensington Books|Kensington Publishing Corporation]]|year=2014|accessdate=2018-12-14|oclc=864822516|lccn=2013388865|isbn=9780758292421|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=In 1791, George Washington appointed a French engineer, Pierre L'Enfant, to design a plan for the nation's capital, and Banneker was chosen as one of the surveyors. But L'Enfant suddenly returned to France, taking the plans with him. Banneker, working only from memory, quickly reconstructed the entire design.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214055002/https://books.google.com/books?id=4pwhAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://kids.britannica.com/comptons/article-9273098/Benjamin-Banneker|work=Student Encyclopedia|title=Benjamin Banneker|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]: Compton's by Britannica. Britannica Online for Kids|accessdate=2014-03-04|quote=A story about Benjamin Banneker\u2014African-American mathematician, astronomer, and inventor\u2014suggests to what degree he had trained his memory. Appointed to the District of Columbia Commission by President George Washington in 1790, he worked with Pierre L'Enfant, Andrew Ellicott, and others to plan the new capital of Washington, D.C. After L'Enfant was dismissed from the project and took his detailed maps away with him, Banneker was able to reproduce them from memory.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721154327/http://kids.britannica.com/students/article/Benjamin-Banneker/273098|archive-date=July 21, 2017|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906021609/http://lemelson.mit.edu/resources/benjamin-banneker|archivedate=2015-09-06|url=https://lemelson.mit.edu/resources/benjamin-banneker|title=Benjamin Banneker|work=Historical Inventors|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]: School of Engineering: Lemelson-MIT Program|accessdate=2019-01-07|quote=Banneker became one of three surveyors appointed by President George Washington. Architect Pierre L'Enfant had been assigned the job of planning the city, but he was later dismissed from the project. When he left, he took the plans with him. Banneker recreated the plans in two days, including a complete layout of the streets, parks, and major buildings. Thus, the city of Washington, D.C. itself is somewhat of a tribute to Banneker's memory.}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://arago.si.edu/category_2035961.html|title=1980 Black Heritage Series: Benjamin Banneker Issue|work=Arago: People, Postage & The Post ([[Philately]])|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Postal Museum]]|accessdate=2018-01-08|quote=As a member of the surveying team that laid out the plans for the new capitol, Washington, D.C., Banneker stepped up as chief architect when Pierre L'Enfant was fired. The first architect had taken the plans with him when he left so Banneker had to recreate the plans for the city from memory.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223141132/http://arago.si.edu/category_2035961.html|archivedate=2015-12-23}}</ref> Titles of works relating various versions of Graham's tale have touted Banneker as \"The Man Who Designed Washington\", \"The Man Who Saved Washington\", \"An Early American Hero\", \"Benjamin Banneker, Genius\", and as one of the \"100 Greatest African Americans\".<ref>(1) {{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=C. L.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5zkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Saved Washington, D. C.|work=[[Negro Digest]]: Negro History Issue|pages=18\u201320|volume=15|number=4|date=February 1966|location=Chicago, Illinois|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company, Inc.|via=[[Google Books]]|accessdate=2019-02-17}}<br>(2) {{cite book|year=1970|first=Claude|last=Lewis|url=https://archive.org/details/benjaminbanneker00lewi|url-access=registration|title=Chapter 9: Planning the Nation's Capital|work=Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Saved Washington|location=New York|publisher=McGraw-Hill|pages=[https://archive.org/details/benjaminbanneker00lewi/page/79 79]\u201395|oclc=72113|lccn=79092101|accessdate=2019-09-19|quote=He probably does, Mr. Secretary. Benjamin Banneker has an incredible memory. I've known him for years and if he says that he remembers the plans, I believe he does.|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}<br>(3) {{cite book|chapter=Benjamin Banneker|first=Molefi Kete|last=Asante|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HwuGTSnc2CsC&pg=PA49|title=100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia|location=Amherst, New York|publisher=Prometheus Books|year=2002|page=49|isbn=1-57392-963-8|oclc=606853456|lccn=2002018993|accessdate=2018-12-12|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=... when President George Washington, in February 1791, commissioned Ellicott and the French engineer L'Enfant to help plan the construction of the nation's capital on an area of land twenty-five sq kilometer (10 sq mi) in Virginia and Maryland, Ellicott asked Banneker to assist him. Soon thereafter the Frenchman abandoned the project over a dispute with some Americans. L'Enfant refused to leave his plans with the surveying team, but because Banneker had placed close attention to the mathematical details, he was able to reproduce most of the plans and ideas from memory. For this reason, some refer to Washington, D.C., as Banneker's Town.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213222457/https://books.google.com/books?id=HwuGTSnc2CsC&pg=PA49#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=December 13, 2018|url-status=dead}}<br>(4) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030529082100/http://www.successmaker.com/Subscriber/1,22/ReadingActivities/hero.html|archivedate=2003-05-29|url=http://www.successmaker.com/Subscriber/1,22/ReadingActivities/hero.html#reading|title=An Early American Hero: Benjamin Banneker|work=SuccessMaker Enterprise|publisher=[[Pearson Education|Pearson Education, Inc.]]|accessdate=2012-05-06|quote=Noted surveyor Benjamin Banneker had been working closely with L'Enfant and Chief Surveyor Andrew Ellicott. Banneker thought he might be able to redraw all the plans\u2014from memory! Two days later he delivered the plans, and construction proceeded without significant delay. Today the city of Washington, D.C., stands as a reminder of Banneker's genius.}}<br/>(5) {{cite web|last=Bofah|first=Kofi|url=https://login.yahoo.com/config/login?.src=ycn&.intl=us&.done=http%3A%2F%2Fvoices.yahoo.com%2Fblack-history-benjamin-banneker-genius-2703097.html|title=Black History: Benjamin Banneker, Genius: The Legend of an Intellectual and Architect of Washington, D.C.|date=2009-02-20|work=[[Associated Content|Yahoo! Voices]]|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=2012-09-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402194747/https://login.yahoo.com/config/login?.src=ycn&.intl=us&.done=http%3A%2F%2Fvoices.yahoo.com%2Fblack-history-benjamin-banneker-genius-2703097.html|archivedate=2015-04-02}}<br>(6) {{cite web|url=http://www.africanglobe.net/featured/benjamin-banneker-man-designed-washington-dc/|title=Benjamin Banneker The Man Who Designed Washington DC|date=2012-12-08|publisher=African Globe|accessdate=2018-12-13|quote=Impressed by his abilities, Jefferson recommended Benjamin Banneker to be a part of a surveying team to lay out Washington, D.C. Appointed to the three-man team by president George Washington, Benjamin Banneker wound up saving the project when the lead architect quit in a fury \u2013 taking all the plans with him. Using his meticulous memory, Benjamin Banneker was able to recreate the plans.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103210109/https://www.africanglobe.net/featured/benjamin-banneker-man-designed-washington-dc/|archive-date=November 3, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\"Benjamin Banneker- Surveyor-Inventor-Astronomer,\" mural by Maxime Seelbinder, at the Recorder of Deeds building, built in 1943. 515 D St., NW, Washington, D.C LCCN2010641717.tif|thumb|right|200px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup></div>Mural in the Recorder of Deeds building in Washington, D.C., illustrating Banneker with an 1800 ''Plan of the City of Washington'', William Thornton's design for the west view of the Capitol building and a model of the White House. (2010 photograph).<ref name=Seelbinder/><ref name=mural/>]] A lobby in the [[Recorder of deeds|Recorder of Deeds]] Building, which was constructed from 1940 to 1943 in Washington, D.C., displays a [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Department]], [[Section of Painting and Sculpture|Section of Fine Arts]] mural that perpetuates a Banneker legend. The mural features an imaginary portrait of Banneker as a young man, an 1800 ''Plan of the City of Washington'', [[William Thornton]]'s design for the west view of the Capitol building and a model of the White House. A corner of the mural portrays Banneker and Andrew Ellicott showing to three men a map of the area between the \"Potowmack River\" and the Eastern Branch within which the City of Washington would later be planned.<ref name=Seelbinder>(1) {{cite web|last=Highsmith|first=Carol M. (photographer)|authorlink=Carol M. Highsmith|url=http://loc.gov/pictures/resource/highsm.09905/|format=photograph|title=\"Benjamin Banneker: Surveyor-Inventor-Astronomer,\" mural by Maxime Seelbinder, at the Recorder of Deeds building, built in 1943. 515 D St., NW, Washington, D.C.|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101123251/http://www.loc.gov/pictures/resource/highsm.09905/|archive-date=November 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}<br>(2) {{cite web |url=https://livingnewdeal.org/projects/recorder-deeds-building-seelbinder-mural-washington-dc/ |title=Recorder of Deeds Building: Seelbinder Mural \u2013 Washington DC |publisher=The Living New Deal |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111054138/https://livingnewdeal.org/projects/recorder-deeds-building-seelbinder-mural-washington-dc/ |archive-date=January 11, 2020 |url-status=dead }}<br>(3) {{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/09/AR2010030903458.html |title=D.C. Recorder of Deeds moving but fate of murals unclear |first=Nicole |last=Norfleet |date=March 11, 2010 |work=The Breaking News Blog |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=October 3, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003210410/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/09/AR2010030903458.html |archive-date=October 3, 2016 |url-status=dead }}<br>(4) For source of the ''Plan of the City of Washington'' depicted in lower right corner of mural, see: {{cite web|last1=Ellicott|first1=Andrew|last2=Thackara & Vallance, Philadelphia (1792)|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/88694160/|title=Plan of the city of Washington in the territory of Columbia: ceded by the states of Virginia and Maryland to the United States of America, and by them established as the seat of their government, after the year MDCCC|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=March 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190309150208/https://www.loc.gov/item/88694160/|archive-date=March 9, 2019|url-status=dead}}<br>(5) For source of the map depicted in upper right corner of mural, see: {{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/87694269/|title=View of the City of Washington in 1792|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=March 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190309141646/https://www.loc.gov/item/87694269/|archive-date=March 9, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:William J. Thompkins.jpg|thumb|left|150px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">William J. Thompkins (circa 1911)</div>]]\nThe [[Oil painting|oil portrait]] was the winner of a [[Juried (competition)|juried competition]] that the Section held on behalf of Doctor [[William J. Thompkins]], an African American political figure who was at the time serving as the Recorder of Deeds for the District of Columbia. The competition announcement stated that seven mural subjects had been \"carefully worked out by the Recorder...following intensive research\" to \"reflect a phase of the contribution of the Negro to the American nation.\" A mural on the subject of \"Benjamin Banneker Surveys the District of Columbia\" was to \"show the presentation by Banneker and Mayor Ellicott, of the plans of the District of Columbia to the President, [and] Mr. [[Thomas Jefferson]]\" in the presence of [[Benjamin Franklin]] and [[Alexander Hamilton]].<ref name=mural>{{cite web|url=http://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Recorder%20of%20Deeds%20Building.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Recorder of Deeds Building|last=Sefton|first=D.P., DC Preservation League, Washington, DC|date=2010-07-01|publisher=District of Columbia Office of Planning. Section 9, pp. 18-19|location=Washington, D.C|accessdate=2016-10-03|quote=Although the ROD Building was a municipal building, the District of Columbia's peculiar sovereignty status required that the federal government approve its construction, and the Treasury Department Section of Fine Arts play a major role in its arts program. .... The Treasury Section's December 1, 1942 announcement of the ROD Building mural competition was a term paper-like, ten page document that required artists to submit their entries unsigned for anonymous judging.81 Mural subjects had been \"carefully worked out by the Recorder...following intensive research.\" Dr. Tompkins had determined that \"in view of the history of the office of the Recorder of Deeds... the united theme... [will] reflect a phase of the contribution of the Negro to the American nation.\" The announcement prescribed each of the seven mural's placement, size, subject, and setting in detail, citing historical reference works for its content. For example, \"Benjamin Banneker Surveys the District of Columbia\" was to \"show the presentation by Banneker and Mayor Ellicott, of the plans of the District of Columbia to the President, [and] Mr. Thomas Jefferson\" in the presence of Benjamin Franklin and Alexander Hamilton.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005064938/http://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Recorder%20of%20Deeds%20Building.pdf|archive-date=October 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, an Afro-American [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial]] Corporation historian told the following tale within a [[National Register of Historic Places]] nomination form for the \"[[Benjamin Banneker: SW-9 Intermediate Boundary Stone|Benjamin Banneker: SW-9 Intermediate Boundary Stone (milestone) of the District of Columbia]]\":\n\n<blockquote>.... Major L'Enfant resigned his position before the planned design was completed. It was only through the efforts of Major Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker that the Federal City was completed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Graves |first=Lynne Gomez, Historical Projects Director, Afro-American Bicentennial Corporation, Washington, D.C |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001145447/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0015_%20Banneker_SW-9_Intermediate_Boundary_Stone_1976_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf |archivedate=2016-10-01 |url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0015_%20Banneker_SW-9_Intermediate_Boundary_Stone_1976_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf |title=Benjamin Banneker: SW-9 Intermediate Boundary Stone (milestone) of the District of Columbia |work=United States Department of the Interior: National Park Service: National Register of Historic Places Inventory\u2013\u2013Nomination Form |location=Richmond, Virginia |publisher=[[Virginia Department of Historic Resources]]|date=1976-02-03|page=Continuation Sheet: Item No. 8, p. 2|accessdate=2016-10-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nCiting a 1963 article in the ''[[Washington Star]]'' newspaper,<ref>{{cite news |last=Nye |first=Edwin Darby |title=Boundary Stones |work=The Washington Star Sunday Magazine |date=1963-06-23 |page=7}}</ref> a 1990 documentation form related the following version of the story when supporting a listing in the National Register of Historic Places for twelve historic marker stones from the federal district boundary survey: <blockquote> .... Fearing profiteering land speculators, L'Enfant would not allow anyone to see the plan. Ordered by the commissioners to reveal the plan, he instead left the United States, taking all copies of his plan for the District of Columbia with him. Banneker reproduced it from memory in minute detail, thereby allowing the work to continue.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hynak |first=Barbara A.(Chairman, District V Boundary Markers Committee, Virginia Daughters of the American Revolution) |url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0022_Boundary_Marker_of_the_Original_District_of_Columbia_1991_Final_Nomination.pdf |title=Boundary Markers of the original District of Columbia |work=[[United States Department of the Interior]]: [[National Park Service]]: National Register of Historic Places Multiple Property Documentation Form |location=Richmond, Virginia |publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources |date=1990-07-09 |page=E.2 |accessdate=2011-08-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806071641/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0022_Boundary_Marker_of_the_Original_District_of_Columbia_1991_Final_Nomination.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-06 }}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Roy Dyson 97th Congress 1981.jpg|thumb|left|100px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Roy Dyson (1981)</div>]]\n[[File:Bengilman.jpg|thumb|right|100px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Benjamin Gilman (1999)</div>]]\n\nDuring a commemoration of [[Black History Month]] in February 1990, Congressman [[Roy Dyson]] of Maryland told the [[United States House of Representatives]] that Banneker had \"helped to draw the plans for the District of Columbia\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dyson|first=Roy|author-link=Roy Dyson|page=2691|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/search/pagedetails.action?collectionCode=GPO&granuleId=GPO-CRECB-1990-pt2-8&packageId=GPO-CRECB-1990-pt2&fromBrowse=true|title=Black History Month|journal=[[Congressional Record]] \u2014 House: [[101st United States Congress|101st Congress]], 2nd Session|volume=136|number=2|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]]|date=1990-02-27|accessdate=2018-09-24}}</ref> Congressman [[Benjamin Gilman]] of [[New York (state)|New York]] stated during the same commemoration that Banneker had assisted in the layout of \"our beautiful Capitol City\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gilman|first=Benjamin|author-link=Benjamin Gilman|page=2676|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/search/pagedetails.action?collectionCode=GPO&granuleId=GPO-CRECB-1990-pt2-8&packageId=GPO-CRECB-1990-pt2&fromBrowse=true|title=Black History Month|journal=[[Congressional Record]] \u2014 House: [[101st United States Congress|101st Congress]], 2nd Session|volume=136|number=2|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]]|date=1990-02-27|accessdate=2018-09-24}}</ref> \n[[File:Major owens portrait -- Cropped --.png|thumb|left|100px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Major Owens</div>]]\n\nDuring Congress' February 2000 commemoration of Black History Month, Congressman [[Major Owens]] of New York stated that Banneker was part of a commission that determined how Washington would be laid out and had reconstructed some of L'Enfant's plans from memory after they were lost.  After crediting the African American historian/author [[Carter G. Woodson|Carter Woodson]] as the source of this information, Owens stated: \"There was a black man, Benjamin Banneker, involved. Nobody bothers to note that.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Owens|first=Major|url=https://www.congress.gov/crec/2000/02/15/CREC-2000-02-15-pt1-PgH431.pdf|title=Black History|journal=[[Congressional Record]] \u2014 House: [[106th United States Congress|106th Congress]], 2nd Session|volume=146|number=14|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]]|page=H431|date=February 15, 2000|accessdate=April 14, 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Smithsonian-nmaahc-outside-20160720.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture (2016)]]\n\nDocuments published in 2003 and 2005 supporting the establishment of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]] in Washington, D.C. (including a report that a presidential commission planning the museum sent to the President and the [[United States Congress|Congress]]), later also connected Banneker with L'Enfant's plan of the city of Washington.<ref name=Wright>{{cite web|first=Robert L. (Chair)|last=Wright|url=http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/The_Time_Has_Come.pdf|title=Introduction: The Near 100 Year Struggle to Build The Museum|work=The Time Has Come: Report to the President and to the Congress: National Museum of African American History Plan For Action Presidential Commission (Final Report)|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Museum of African American History]]|page=7|date=2003-04-02|accessdate=2017-11-05|quote=Benjamin Banneker, an African American astronomer, surveyor, and inventor, worked with Andrew Ellicott to play a central role in Pierre L'Enfant's original plan of the nation's capital.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105174311/http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/The_Time_Has_Come.pdf|archivedate=2017-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Site_Evaluation_Study__PhaseI_Data_Gathering_Report.pdf|title=Site Evaluation Study: Phase I: Data Gathering Report|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]]|date=2005-09-30|page=31|quote=Benjamin Banneker, an African American, worked with Major Andrew Ellicott to play a central role in Pierre L'Enfant's original plan of the Nation's Capital. ... Banneker and Ellicott worked closely with Pierre L'Enfant in the planning of Washington, D.C. When L'Enfant was dismissed from the project and took his plans with him, Banneker recreated the plans from memory.|accessdate=2017-11-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194520/http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Site_Evaluation_Study__PhaseI_Data_Gathering_Report.pdf|archivedate=2015-09-23}}</ref> When the museum opened on the [[National Mall]] in September 2016, an exhibit entitled \"The Founding of America\" further perpetuated the legend when displaying a statue of Banneker holding a small telescope while standing in front of a plan of that city.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g28970-d10895065-r423572634-National_Museum_of_African_American_History_and_Culture-Washington_DC_District_o.html#photos;geo=28970&detail=10895065&ff=220556582&albumViewMode=hero&aggregationId=101&albumid=101&baseMediaId=220556582&thumbnailMinWidth=50&cnt=30&offset=-1&filter=7&autoplay=|title=NMAAHC statue of Benjamin Banneker, famous scientist, astronomer and author|\nauthor=Pam105|date=September 2016|format=photograph|work=|publisher=[[Trip Advisor]]|accessdate=2017-12-19}}<br/>(2) {{cite web|first1=Charlie|last1=Wright|first2=Maya ([[Capital News Service (Maryland)|Capital News Service]])|last2=Pottiger|url=https://wtop.com/dc/2016/09/smithsonians-new-museum-captures-sweep-african-american-experience/|title=Slavery and Freedom Galleries|work=Smithsonian's new museum captures sweep of the African-American experience|date=2016-09-23|publisher=[[WTOP-FM|WTOP]]: Washington, DC News|accessdate=2017-11-05|quote=After walking through the dark hallways, visitors enter an open room, greeted by the Declaration of Independence and statues of notable founders. One statue depicts Benjamin Banneker, an African American born in Baltimore County who was called on to help design Washington, D.C.}}<br/>(3) {{cite web |author=Toure88 (Washington, D.C.) |url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/LocationPhotoDirectLink-g28970-d10895065-i233511419-National_Museum_of_African_American_History_and_Culture-Washington_DC_Di.html|title=Photo: Benjamin Banneker |format=photograph |date=2016-12-19|work=\"One of the Best\": Review of National Museum of African American History and Culture |publisher=[[TripAdvisor]] |accessdate=2017-09-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912190818/https://www.tripadvisor.com/LocationPhotoDirectLink-g28970-d10895065-i233511419-National_Museum_of_African_American_History_and_Culture-Washington_DC_Di.html|archivedate=2017-09-12}}<br />(4) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312192637/http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bs-lt-smithsonian-maryland-contributions-20161228-story.html|archivedate=2018-03-12|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bs-lt-smithsonian-maryland-contributions-20161228-story.html|title=Photograph of statue of Benjamin Banneker standing in front of a plan of the City of Washington}} ''in'' {{cite news|last=Hairston|first=Kim (''[[Baltimore Sun]]'')|title=Maryland's contributions to national African-American museum|quote=A sculpture of Benjamin Banneker is seen near bricks marked with the names of people Thomas Jefferson enslaved in the \"Founding of America\" exhibit in the National Museum of African American History and Culture.}} ''In'' Image number 2 of photo gallery ''in'' {{cite web|first=Donna M.|last=Owens|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bs-lt-smithsonian-maryland-contributions-20161228-story.html|title=Marylanders well represented in national African-American museum|work=Baltimore Sun|date=2016-12-28|accessdate=2018-06-28|quote=\"Banneker wrote a farming almanac and sent it to Jefferson as a gift, with a letter about the inhumanity of slavery,\" said curator Mary Elliott. Jefferson did reply to the inventor, mathematician, astronomer and surveyor, who is credited with helping map the layout of the nation's capital.}}<br/>(5) {{cite web|author=Tenighir|date=February 2017|url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g28970-d10895065-r423572634-National_Museum_of_African_American_History_and_Culture-Washington_DC_District_o.html#photos;geo=28970&detail=10895065&ff=242087202&albumViewMode=hero&aggregationId=101&albumid=101&baseMediaId=242087202&thumbnailMinWidth=50&cnt=30&offset=-1&filter=7&autoplay=|title=Statue of Benjamin Banneker in National Museum of African American History and Culture, Washington, D.C.|format=photograph|publisher=[[TripAdvisor]]|accessdate=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n\nNews reports of the museum's opening stated that Banneker \"was called on to help design Washington, D.C.\" and \"is credited with helping map the layout of the nation's capital\".<ref>(1) {{cite web|first1=Charlie|last1=Wright|first2=Maya ([[Capital News Service (Maryland)|Capital News Service]])|last2=Pottiger|url=https://wtop.com/dc/2016/09/smithsonians-new-museum-captures-sweep-african-american-experience/|title=Slavery and Freedom Galleries|work=Smithsonian's new museum captures sweep of the African-American experience|date=2016-09-23|publisher=[[WTOP-FM|WTOP]]: Washington, DC News|accessdate=2017-11-05|quote=After walking through the dark hallways, visitors enter an open room, greeted by the Declaration of Independence and statues of notable founders. One statue depicts Benjamin Banneker, an African American born in Baltimore County who was called on to help design Washington, D.C.}}<br/>(2) {{cite web|first=Donna M.|last=Owens|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bs-lt-smithsonian-maryland-contributions-20161228-story.html|title=Marylanders well represented in national African-American museum|work=Baltimore Sun|date=2016-12-28|accessdate=2018-06-28|quote=\"Banneker wrote a farming almanac and sent it to Jefferson as a gift, with a letter about the inhumanity of slavery,\" said curator Mary Elliott. Jefferson did reply to the inventor, mathematician, astronomer and surveyor, who is credited with helping map the layout of the nation's capital.}}</ref> A [[National Park Service]] [[web page]] subsequently stated in 2017 that Banneker had \"surveyed the city of Washington with Major Pierre Charles L'Enfant\".<ref name=NPS1>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/places/sw-9-intermediate-boundary-stone-of-the-district-of-columbia.htm/index.htm|title=Benjamin Banneker and the Boundary Stones of the District of Columbia|publisher=[[United States Department of the Interior]] [[National Park Service]]|date=2017-08-11|accessdate=2018-03-21|quote=Benjamin Banneker was one of the most famous black men in colonial America. He was a farmer, a mathematician, an inventor, an astronomer, a writer, a surveyor, a scientist, and a humanitarian. When he surveyed the city of Washington with Major Pierre Charles L'Enfant, Banneker became one of the first black civil servants of the new nation. Along with a team, Banneker identified the boundaries of the capitol city. They installed intermittent stone markers along the perimeter of the District. .... In 1753, Banneker constructed one of the first entirely wooden clocks in America. .... Banneker's scientific research led him to write one of the first series of almanacs printed in the United States.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321194817/https://www.nps.gov/places/sw-9-intermediate-boundary-stone-of-the-district-of-columbia.htm/index.htm|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHowever, historical research has shown that none of these legends can be correct.<ref name=Founders/><ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\">[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/132/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 132-136.] \"An exhaustive search of government repositories, including the Public Buildings and Grounds files in the National Archives, and various collections in the Library of Congress, failed to turn up Banneker's name on any of the contemporary documents or records related to the selection, planning and survey of the City of Washington. Nor was he mentioned in any of the surviving correspondence and papers of Andre Ellicott and of Pierre Charles L'Enfant. .... Although the exact date of Banneker's departure from the survey is not specified in Ellicott's report of expenditures, it occurred sometime late in the month of April 1791, following the arrival of one of Ellicott's brothers. It was not until some ten months after Banneker's departure from the scene that L'Enfant was dismissed, by means of a letter from Jefferson dated February 27, 1792. This conclusively dispels any basis for the legend that after L'Enfant's dismissal and his refusal to make available his plan of the city, Banneker recollected the plan in detail from which Ellicott was able to reconstruct it. Equally untrue and in fact impossible is the legend that Thomas Jefferson as secretary of state invited Banneker to luncheon at the White House. Jefferson during this period was in Philadelphia, the national capital in Washington had yet not been built, and there was no White House.\"</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969], pp. 7, 29.</ref> As Bedini reported in 1969, Ellicott's 1791 assignment was to produce a survey of a square, the length of whose sides would each be {{convert|10|mi|km|1}} (a \"ten mile square\").<ref name=Bedini22/> L'Enfant was to survey, design and lay out the national capital city within this square.<ref name=Bedini22/><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA50#v=onepage&q=Banneker&f=false Stewart, p. 50] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426112936/https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA50 |date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Ellicott and L'Enfant each worked independently under the supervision of the three Commissioners that President Washington had earlier appointed.<ref name=Bedini22/> Bedini could not find any evidence that showed that Banneker had ever worked with or for L'Enfant.<ref name=Bedini22/><ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\"/>\n\nBanneker left the federal capital area and returned to his home near [[Ellicott City, Maryland#History|Ellicott's Mills]] in April 1791.<ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\"/><ref name=Arnebeck>{{cite web|last=Arnebeck|first=Bob|url=http://dcswamp.blogspot.com/2017/01/seat-of-empire.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129062551/http://dcswamp.blogspot.com/2017/01/seat-of-empire.html|archivedate=2018-01-29|title=Washington Examined: Seat of Empire: the General and the Plan 1790 to 1801|date=2017-01-02|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogger]]|accessdate=2018-01-29|quote=Meanwhile Andrew Ellicott, the nation's Surveyor General, finished surveying the boundary lines of the federal district, and joined L'Enfant in laying out the city. (Ellicott showed a fine sense of the opportunity presented by the project by hiring a mathematician who was a \"free Negro,\" to help with the survey. The Georgetown newspaper noted the significance of Benjamin Banneker's participation but, nearly sixty years old, he left the arduous project in May and returned to Baltimore to publish his almanac, and thus, contrary to legend, had nothing to do with L'Enfant's plan).<br/>In late August L'Enfant took his completed plan to Philadelphia. The president approved but thought it premature to designate the sites of the other buildings and many monuments that L'Enfant envisioned.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bedini, 1969, pp. 28-29\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969, pp. 28-29.]</ref> At that time, L'Enfant was still developing his plan for the federal city and had not yet been dismissed from his job.<ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\"/> L'Enfant presented his plans to President Washington in June and August 1791, two and four months after Banneker had left.<ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\"/><ref name=Arnebeck/><ref name=Kite>{{cite book |last=Kite |first=Elizabeth S. |year=1929 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVVYPwAACAAJ |title=L'Enfant and Washington 1791\u20131792 |location=Baltimore |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press|The Johns Hopkins Press]], reprinted by New York: Arno Press & [[The New York Times]], 1970 |isbn=0405024606 |oclc=128234 |accessdate=2015-04-24 |via=[[Google Books]]}} ''quoted in'' {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216191348/http://www.freemasonry.bcy.ca/anti-masonry/washington_dc/kite.html|archivedate=2013-12-16 |url=http://www.freemasonry.bcy.ca/anti-masonry/washington_dc/kite.html |title=L'Enfant and Washington |publisher=Grand Lodge of British Columbia and Yukon, Ancient Free and Accepted Masons (Freemasons) |accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Stewart52>(1) {{cite book |author=L'Enfant, P.C. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=To The President of the United States|location=Georgetown|date=June 22, 1791|accessdate=2013-01-31|via=[[Google Books]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105114854/http://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA32 |archivedate=November 5, 2013}} ''in'' {{cite journal |year=1899 |title=L'Enfant's Reports To President Washington Bearing Dates of March 26, June 22, and August 19, 1791|journal=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=[[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]]|location=Washington, D.C.|volume=2|pages=32\u201337}}<br >(2) {{cite book |last=L'Enfant |first=P.C. |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=1899 |via=[[Google Books]] |chapter=L'Enfant's Reports To President Washington Bearing Dates of March 26, June 22, and August 19, 1791 |title=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=[[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]] |location=Washington, D.C.|volume=2|pages=38\u201348}}<br/>(3) [https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false Stewart, pp. 52-54] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426130718/https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA52 |date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>Banneker sent his letter denouncing slavery to Thomas Jefferson during the same month (August 1791) in which L'Enfant presented his second plan for the federal city to President Washington.  The heading of Banneker's letter identified Banneker's address at the time as \"Baltimore County, Maryland, near Ellicotts Lower Mills\". Banneker's letter noted that he had made calculations for his 1792 almanac after returning home by stating: \"And altho I had almost declined to make my calculation for the ensuing year, in consequence of that time which I had allotted therefor, being taken up at the Federal Territory, by the request of Mr. Andrew Ellicott, ..., on my return to my place of residence, I industriously applied my Self thereto, which I hope I have accomplished with correctness and accuracy; ...\". In: {{cite book |last=Allaben |first=Frank |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2vEQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=falsel|title=Original Document: Banneker's Appeal to Jefferson for Emancipation |work=The National Magazine: A Journal Devoted To American History: Vol. XVII, November, 1892 \u2014 April, 1893|pages=65\u201369 |location=New York |publisher=The National History Company |accessdate=2016-02-28 |via=[[Google Books]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130182246/https://books.google.com/books?id=2vEQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA65 |archivedate=2017-01-30}}</ref>\n\nFurther, there never was any need to reconstruct L'Enfant's plan. After completing the initial phases of the district boundary survey, Andrew Ellicott began to survey the future federal city's site to help L'Enfant develop the city's plan.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2/page/n124 Tindall, pp. 116\u2014117].</ref> During a contentious period in February 1792, Ellicott informed the Commissioners that L'Enfant had refused to give him an original plan that L'Enfant possessed at the time.<ref name=\"Ellicott 1792\">(1) Ellicott, Andrew (February 23, 1792). \"To Thomas Johnson, Daniel Carroll and David Stuart, Esqs.\" ''In'' {{cite web |last=Arnebeck |first=Bob |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708074954/http://www.bobarnebeck.com/ellicott.html |archivedate=2011-07-08 |url=http://www.bobarnebeck.com/ellicott.html |title=Ellicott's letter to the commissioners on engraving the plan of the city, in which no reference is made to Banneker |work=The General and the Plan |publisher=Bob Arnebeck's Web Pages |accessdate=2012-05-06}}<br/>(2) Letter from Andrew Ellicott to the Commissioners, February 23, 1792 ''in'' [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2/page/n156 Tindall, p. 148] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426120058/https://books.google.com/books?id=D_ZJBxoCYeAC&pg=PA148 |date=April 26, 2016}}.</ref><ref>(1) {{cite book|last=Phillips|first=Philip Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/eksportnafaktura00gulu|title=The Beginnings of Washington, As Described in Books, Maps and Views |pages=[https://archive.org/details/eksportnafaktura00gulu/page/29 29]\u201330|oclc=420824175|publisher=Published for the author|location=Washington, D.C.|date=1917|accessdate=2016-12-29 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}<br>(2) {{cite journal |last=Bartlett|first=Dr. G. Hunter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7S0tAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Andrew and Joseph Ellicott: The Plans of Washington City and the Village of Buffalo and Some of the Persons Concerned |page=7 |editor=Frank H. Severance|volume=26|journal=Publications of the Buffalo Historical Society: Recalling Pioneer Days |year=1922|location=Buffalo, New York |publisher=[[Buffalo Historical Society]] |accessdate=2016-12-29|via=[[Google Books]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229031806/https://books.google.com/books?id=7S0tAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7 |archivedate=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\nEllicott stated in his letters that, although he was refused the original plan, he was familiar with L'Enfant's system and had many notes of the surveys that he had made himself.<ref>{{cite book |last=Partridge |first=William T. |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112106620468;view=1up;seq=31;size=125 |title=L'Enfant's Methods And Features of His Plan For The Federal City |work=Reports and plans, Washington region: supplementary technical data to accompany annual report: [[National Capital Planning Commission]] |year=1930 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]] |page=23 |oclc=15250016 |accessdate=2016-12-04|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]}}</ref> Additionally, L' Enfant had earlier given to Washington at least two versions of his plan, one of which Washington had sent to Congress in December 1791.<ref name=Kite/><ref name=Stewart52/><ref>{{cite news |title=New City of Washington |work=Gazette of the United States |location=Philadelphia |date=1792-01-04 |quote=The following description is annexed to the Plan of the City of Washington, in the District of Columbia, as sent to Congress by the President some days ago. .....}}. ''In'' upper right hand corner of:  {{cite web |last=L'Enfant |first=Peter Charles |url=http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.gmd/g3850.ct000512 |title=Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government of t(he) United States : projected agreeable to the direction of the President of the United States, in pursuance of an act of Congress passed the sixteenth day of July, MDCCXC, \"establishing the permanent seat on the bank of the Potowmac\": (Washington, D.C.) |work=Washington: U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey, 1887 |quote='''Description''':  Photocopy of a facsim. of the 1791 L'Enfant plan. Original facsim. extensively annotated in ink by Lawrence Martin, chief, Division of Maps, Library of Congress. Includes text, indexed \"References,\" and photocopied newspaper article titled \"New city of Washington,\" from the Gazette of the United States, Philadelphia, Jan. 4, 1792. |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |year=1791 |lccn=88694380 |accessdate=2016-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205200511/https://www.loc.gov/resource/g3850.ct000512 |archive-date=February 5, 2017 |url-status=dead }}<br /> ''In'' Repository of the [[Library of Congress]] Geography and Map Division, Washington, D.C.</ref>\n\n[[File:Plan of the city of Washington in the territory of Columbia, ceded by the states of Virginia and Maryland to the United States of America ... (8249620373).jpg|right|thumb|300px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Boston Public Library]]</sup></div>Andrew Ellicott's ''Plan of the City of Washington in the Territory of Columbia'', engraved by Thackera & Vallance, Philadelphia, 1792.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/g3850.ct004180/|title=1792 engraving of Plan of the City of Washington in the Territory of Columbia by Thackera & Vallance, Philadelphia|publisher=Library of Congress|lccn=88694160|accessdate=2019-03-24}}</ref>]]\nAndrew Ellicott, with the aid of his brother, [[Benjamin Ellicott]], then revised L'Enfant's plan, despite L'Enfant's protests.<ref name=\"Ellicott 1792\"/><ref name=Levine>(1) {{cite web |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20031206191132/http://dcpages.ari.net/History/Planning_DC.shtml |archivedate=2003-12-06 |url= http://dcpages.ari.net/History/Planning_DC.shtml|title=L'Enfant designed more than D.C.: He designed a 200-year-old controversy |publisher=DCpages.com|first=Michael|last=Levine|work=History: Planning Our Capital City: Get to know the District of Columbia|date=2003-11-10|accessdate=2016-12-31}}<br>(2) {{cite web |url= https://blogs.weta.org/boundarystones/2016/02/08/benjamin-bannekers-capital-contributions|title=Benjamin Banneker's Capital Contributions|date=2016-02-08|first=Richard|last=Brownell|work=Boundary Stones: WETA's Local History Blog|location=[[Arlington County, Virginia]]|publisher=[[WETA-TV|WETA]]|accessdate=2018-05-28}}</ref><ref name=Partridge>{{cite book|last=Partridge |first=William T. |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112106620468;view=1up;seq=27;size=125 |title=L'Enfant's Methods And Features of His Plan For The Federal City|work=Reports and plans, Washington region: supplementary technical data to accompany annual report: [[National Capital Planning Commission|National Capital Park and Planning Commission]]|year=1930|location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|pages=21\u201338 |oclc=15250016|accessdate=2016-12-04|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/333/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 333: Document 14: \"Letter from Andrew Ellicott  from Philadelphia to the Commissioners, March 7, 1792\".]</ref> Shortly thereafter, Washington dismissed L'Enfant.<ref name=\"Ellicott 1792\"/><ref name=Levine/><ref name=Partridge/>\n\nAfter L'Enfant departed, the Commissioners assigned to Ellicott the dual responsibility for continuing L'Enfant's work on the design of the city and the layout of public buildings, streets and property lots, in addition to completing the boundary survey.<ref name=Bedini22/><ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\"/> Andrew Ellicott therefore continued the city survey in accordance with the revised plan that he and his brother had prepared.<ref name=\"Bowling\"/><ref name=Kite/><ref name=\"Ellicott 1792\"/><ref name=Partridge/><ref name=\"stewart-p55-56\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q&f=false Stewart, pp. 55-56] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105122407/http://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA55 |date=2013-11-05 }}</ref><ref>(1) {{cite journal|author=Bryan, W.B. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA113#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Something About L'Enfant And His Personal Affairs |journal=Records of the Columbia Historical Society|year=1899|volume=2|page=113|via=[[Google Books]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426070313/https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA113 |archivedate=April 26, 2016}}<br/>(2) [http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/wash/lenfant.htm The L'Enfant and McMillan Plans] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209165503/http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/Wash/lenfant.htm |date=2010-12-09 }} ''in'' [http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/wash/ \"Washington, D.C., A National Register of Historic Places Travel Inventory\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010001704/http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/wash/ |date=2009-10-10 }} ''in'' [http://www.nps.gov official website of the U.S. National Park Service] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626215809/http://www.nps.gov/|date=2009-06-26}} Retrieved August 14, 2008-09-14.</ref>\n\nThere is no historical evidence that shows that Banneker was involved in any of this.<ref name=Founders/><ref name=Levine/> Six months before Ellicott revised L'Enfant's plan, Banneker sent a letter to Thomas Jefferson from \"Maryland, Baltimore County, near Ellicotts Lower Mills\" that he dated as \"Augt. 19th: 1791\", in which he described the time that he had earlier spent \"at the Federal Territory by the request of Mr. Andrew Ellicott\".<ref>(1) {{cite book |last=Allaben|first=Frank|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2vEQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=falsel|title=Original Document: Banneker's Appeal to Jefferson for Emancipation|work=The National Magazine: A Journal Devoted To American History: Vol. XVII, November, 1892 \u2014 April, 1893 |pages=65\u201369 |location=New York |publisher=The National History Company |accessdate=2016-02-28 |quote=And altho I had almost declined to make my calculation for the ensuing year, in consequence of that time which I had allotted therefor, being taken up at the Federal Territory, by the request of Mr. Andrew Ellicott, ..., on my return to my place of residence, I industriously applied my Self thereto, which I hope I have accomplished with correctness and accuracy; ... |via=[[Google Books]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130182246/https://books.google.com/books?id=2vEQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA65|archivedate=2017-01-30}}<br>(2) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222154918/http://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-22-02-0049 |archivedate=2016-12-22|url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-22-02-0049 |title=\"To Thomas Jefferson from Benjamin Banneker, 19 August 1791\" (with editorial notes)|work=Founders Online: Thomas Jefferson|publisher=National Historical Publications & Records Commission: [[National Archives and Records Administration|U.S. National Archives and Records Administration]], last modified 2016-12-06. (Original source: The Papers of Thomas Jefferson, vol 22, 6 August 1791 - 31 December 1791, ed. Charles T. Cullen.  Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1986, pp. 49\u201354.)|date=1791-08-19|accessdate=2016-12-22}}<br>(3) {{cite book|last=Banneker|first=Benjamin|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/rbc0001.2019amimp22848/?sp=11&r=-1.207,-0.053,3.414,1.653,0|title=Copy of a letter from Benjamin Banneker to the secretary of state, with his answer|publisher=Daniel Lawrence |location=No. 33. North Fourth-Street, near Race, Philadelphia|lccn=17022848|oclc=614046208|year=1792b|accessdate=March 16, 2020|via=[[Library of Congress]]}} \n:(a) Pages 3&ndash;10: {{cite book|last=Banneker|first=Benjamin|date=August 19, 1791|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/rbc0001.2019amimp22848/?sp=13|title=Copy of a letter from Benjamin Banneker, &c.|location=[[Baltimore County, Maryland]]}}\n:(b) Pages 11&ndash;12: {{cite book|last=Jefferson|first=Thomas|url=https://www.loc.gov/resource/rbc0001.2019amimp22848/?sp=21|title=To Mr. Benjamin Banneker|date=August 30, 1791|location=[[Philadelphia]]}}<br>\n(4) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/152/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, pp. 152\u2014156.]</ref> \n\nAs a researcher has reported, the letter that Ellicott addressed to the Commissioners in February 1792 describing his revision of L'Enfant's plan did not mention Banneker's name.<ref>{{cite web|last=Arnebeck|first=Bob |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708074954/http://www.bobarnebeck.com/ellicott.html |archivedate=2011-07-08 |url=http://www.bobarnebeck.com/ellicott.html|title=Ellicott's letter to the commissioners on engraving the plan of the city, in which no reference is made to Banneker|work=The General and the Plan |publisher=Bob Arnebeck's Web Pages |accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref> Jefferson did not describe any connection between Banneker and the plan for the federal city when relating his knowledge of Banneker's works in a letter that he sent to [[Joel Barlow]] in 1809, three years after Banneker's death.<ref name=\"Barlow\">(1) {{cite book|last=Jefferson|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fWIFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA476|title=Correspondence: To Mr Barlow|date=1809-10-08|editor=Washington, H.A. (1853)|work=The Writings of Thomas Jefferson; being his Autobiography, Correspondence, Reports, Messages, Addresses, and Other Writings, Official and Private. Published by the order of the Joint Committee of Congress on the Library, from the original manuscripts, deposited in the Department of State.|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Taylor & Maury|volume=5|pages=475\u2013476|oclc=924409|via=[[Google Books]]|access-date=July 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429061306/https://books.google.com/books?id=fWIFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA476#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=April 29, 2016|url-status=dead}}<br/>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831231259/https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/03-01-02-0461|archivedate=2019-08-31|url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/03-01-02-0461|title=\"Thomas Jefferson to Joel Barlow, 8 October 1809 (with editorial notes)|work=Founders Online: Thomas Jefferson|publisher=National Historical Publications & Records Commission: [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]]|accessdate=2019-08-31}} (Original source: {{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U_5ZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA588#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Papers of Thomas Jefferson, Retirement Series, vol. 1, 4 March 1809 to 15 November 1809|editor-first=J. Jefferson|editor-last=Looney|location=[[Princeton, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=2004|pages=588\u2013590|accessdate=2019-08-31|isbn=9780691184593|oclc=1045069067|lccn=2004048327|via=[[Google Books]]}})<br/>(3) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/282/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, pp. 282\u2014283.]</ref>\n\nL'Enfant did not leave the United States after ending his work on the federal capital city's plan. Soon afterwards, he began to plan the city of [[Paterson, New Jersey]].<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/withamericansofp01juss/page/184 Jusserand, p. 184: ''\"Almost on leaving his work at Washington, he'' (L'Enfant) ''was asked to draw the plans of the first manufacturing city, devised as such, in the United States, and which today is one of the most important in existence, Paterson, N. J.\"''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113020029/https://books.google.com/books?id=u2MUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA184 |date=2016-01-13 }}<br/>(2) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311194613/http://patersongreatfalls.org/letters/Intro_NJ.pdf |archivedate=2015-03-11 |accessdate=2015-03-11 |url=http://patersongreatfalls.org/letters/Intro_NJ.pdf |title=Introduction: Project Copy of the Calendar of the S.U.M. Collection of Manuscripts |work=New Jersey Historical Records Survey |publisher=Paterson Friends of the Great Falls}}</ref> The [[United States Congress]] acknowledged the work that he had performed when preparing his plan for the city of Washington by voting to pay him for his efforts.<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/withamericanspa00jussgoog/page/n206 Jusserand, pp. 188-189]<br />(2) {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0Sk7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA609&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Claims of L'Enfant, Peter Charles: 1800-1810 |work=Digested Summary and Alphabetical List of Private Claims which Have Been Presented to the House of Representatives from the First to the Thirty-first Congress: Exhibiting the Action of Congress on Each Claim, with References to the Journals, Reports, Bills, &c., Elucidating Its Progress |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States House of Representatives]]|volume=2|page=309|year=1853|accessdate=2015-01-03|via=[[Google Books]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518071216/https://books.google.com/books?id=0Sk7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA609&f=false|archivedate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 1887, the [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]] created and distributed a [[facsimile]] of a manuscript plan for the future City of Washington. The plan contains in the last line of an oval in its upper left hand corner the words \"By Peter Charles L'Enfant\" (L'Enfant's adopted name).<ref name=facsimile/>\nA 1914 book describing the history of the City of Washington reported that L'Enfant's plan contained a title legend that identified L'Enfant as the plan's author.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2/page/n156 Tindall, p. 148] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426120058/https://books.google.com/books?id=D_ZJBxoCYeAC&pg=PA148 |date=April 26, 2016}} \"Major L'Enfant's plan contained in the upper left hand corner a title legend giving his name as the author.\"</ref>\n\n[[File:Explanatory text.JPG|300px|right|thumb|Name of \"Peter Charles L'Enfant\" in depiction of the L'Enfant Plan in [[Freedom Plaza]], Washington, D.C. (2006)]]\nA 1902 report of a committee of the [[United States Senate]] (the [[McMillan Plan]]), an inlay of a city plan in a Washington, D.C., plaza constructed in 1980 ([[Freedom Plaza]]), and at least one book relating the history of the District of Columbia contain copies of the portion of a plan for the federal capital city that contains the oval that bears L'Enfant's name.<ref name=Passonneau/><ref>(1) {{cite report |last=McMillan |first=James |editor=Moore,Charles |title=The Improvement Of The Park System Of The District of Columbia: Report by the United States Congress: Senate Committee on the District of Columbia and District of Columbia Park Commission |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Government Printing Office |year=1902 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ob7PAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA11 |id=No. 166 |at=Figure No. 61 - \"L'Enfant Map of Washington (1791)\" |accessdate=2011-03-21|via=[[Google Books]]}}<br/>(2) A copy of an oval in L'Enfant's plan that identifies the plan's author as \"Peter Charles L'Enfant\" is inscribed several yards west of an inlay of the plan in Freedom Plaza on [[Pennsylvania Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Pennsylvania Avenue NW]], in downtown Washington, D.C.</ref><ref group=\"a\">Coordinates of inscription of L'Enfant's name in Freedom Plaza: {{coord|38.895838|-77.031254|type:landmark|name=Inscription of name of \"Peter Charles L'Enfant\" in inlay of L'Enfant's plan in Freedom Plaza|format=dms}}</ref> The U.S. Library of Congress now holds in its collections a manuscript of a plan for the federal city that contains that oval.<ref>(1) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205200453/http://www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/tri001.html |archivedate=2017-02-05 |url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/tri001.html |title=Original Plan of Washington, D.C. |work=American Treasures of the [[Library of Congress]]: Imagination: Pierre Charles L'Enfant's 1791 \"Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government ....\":  Manuscript map on paper, 1791, Geography & Map Division |publisher=Library of Congress |date=2010-07-29 |accessdate=2017-03-05 |quote=Selected by Washington to prepare a ground plan for the new city, L'Enfant arrived in Georgetown on March 9, 1791, and submitted his report and plan to the president about August 26, 1791. It is believed that this plan is the one that is preserved in the Library of Congress.<br/>After showing L'Enfant's manuscript to Congress, the president retained custody of the original drawing until December 1796, when he transferred it to the City Commissioners of Washington, D.C. One hundred and twenty-two years later, on November 11, 1918, the map was presented to the Library of Congress for safekeeping.}}<br/>Note: The plan that this web page describes identifies the plan's author as \"Peter Charles L'Enfant\". The web page nevertheless identifies the author as \"Pierre-Charles L'Enfant.\"<br/>(2) {{cite web|last1=L'Enfant|first1=Peter Charles|last2=[[Library of Congress]]|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/91684074/ |title=Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government of t[he] United States: projected agreeable to the direction of the President of the United States, in pursuance of an act of Congress, passed on the sixteenth day of July, MDCCXC, \"establishing the permanent seat on the bank of the Potowmac\" |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Library of Congress|year=1991|lccn=91684074|accessdate=2017-03-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306135150/https://www.loc.gov/item/91684074/ |archivedate=2017-03-06 }} Full-color [[facsimile]] of Peter Charles L'Enfant's 1791 manuscript plan for the City of Washington. ''In'': Repository of the [[Library of Congress]] Geography and Map Division, Washington, D.C.<br />(3) {{cite web |last1=L'Enfant |first1=Peter Charles|last2=[[Library of Congress]]|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/97683585/|title=Plan of the city intended for the permanent seat of the government of t[he] United States: projected agreeable to the direction of the President of the United States, in pursuance of an act of Congress, passed on the sixteenth day of July, MDCCXC, \"establishing the permanent seat on the bank of the Potowmac\"|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Library of Congress|year=1991|lccn=97683585|accessdate=2017-03-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306133135/https://www.loc.gov/item/97683585/ |archivedate=2017-03-06 }} Computer-assisted reproduction of Peter Charles L'Enfant's 1791 manuscript plan for the city of Washington, produced by the [[U.S. Geological Survey]] for the Library of Congress. ''In'': Repository of the [[Library of Congress]] Geography and Map Division, Washington, D.C.</ref> As an original version of L'Enfant's plan still exists, President Washington and Ellicott clearly had at least one such version available for their use when L'Enfant departed.\n\nIn November 1971, the National Park Service held a public ceremony to dedicate and name Benjamin Banneker Park on [[L'Enfant Promenade]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Bedini p. 318\">[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/318/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 318.] \"In the two centuries since Banneker's death, his achievements have been forgotten or misrepresented ..... In November 1971, on the anniversary of Banneker's birthday, the secretary of the interior authorized the 10th Street Overlook outside L'Enfant Plaza in Washington to be renamed and dedicated by the mayor as Benjamin Banneker Park. Once again, the reasons presented by the speakers on the occasion and widely reported by the press had been all based on erroneous information: Banneker was hailed for his contribution after L'Enfant was dismissed and Banneker \"saved the plan by reconstructing it from memory\u201d.\"</ref><ref name=\"environmental assessment 1\">{{cite book|url=https://comp.ddot.dc.gov/Documents/L%27Enfant%20Promenade%20and%20Benjamin%20Banneker%20Park%20Environmental%20Assessment.pdf|chapter=Development of L'Enfant Promenade and Benjamin Banneker Park|title=Environmental Assessment for Improvements to L'Enfant Promenade and Benjamin Banneker Park|date=March 2006|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[District Department of Transportation]], Government of the District of Columbia (DC.gov) and Eastern Federal Lands Highway Division, [[Federal Highway Administration]], [[United States Department of Transportation]]|pages=1\u20135, 1\u20136, 1\u20137|accessdate=2017-11-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116232714/https://comp.ddot.dc.gov/Documents/L%27Enfant%20Promenade%20and%20Benjamin%20Banneker%20Park%20Environmental%20Assessment.pdf|archivedate=2017-11-16}}</ref> The [[United States Department of the Interior]] authorized the naming as an official commemorative designation celebrating Banneker's role in the survey and design of the nation's capital.<ref name=\"environmental assessment 1\"/>\n[[File:Austin H. Kiplinger.jpg|thumb|left|250px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Ronald Reagan Presidential Library and Museum|Ronald Reagan Presidential Library]]</sup><br>Austin H. Kiplinger (1981)</div>]]\n[[File:Walterwashington.jpg|thumb|right|110px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup></div><div style=\"text-align: center;\">Walter E. Washington</div>]]\n\nSpeakers at the event hailed Banneker for his contributions to the plan of the capital city after L'Enfant's dismissal, claiming that Banneker had saved the plan by reconstructing it from memory.<ref name=\"Bedini p. 318\"/> Bedini later pointed out in a 1999 biography of Banneker that these statements were erroneous.<ref name=\"Bedini p. 318\"/>\n\nDuring a 1997 ceremony that again commemorated Banneker while rededicating the park, speakers stated that Banneker had surveyed the original City of Washington.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1997/11/15/after-reversal-of-decline-banneker-park-rededicated/a1195f2a-2495-4ade-ae3b-80c9464fb51c/|title=After Reversal of Decline, Banneker Park Rededicated|first=Patrice|last=Gaines|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=1997-11-15|accessdate=2017-11-12|quote=The park, originally dedicated in 1971, was named for the man described in speeches yesterday as \"the first African American man of science and surveyor of the original City of Washington.\"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118194142/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1997/11/15/after-reversal-of-decline-banneker-park-rededicated/a1195f2a-2495-4ade-ae3b-80c9464fb51c/|archivedate=2016-11-18}}</ref> However, research reported more than two decades earlier had found that such statements lacked supporting evidence and appeared to be incorrect.<ref name=Founders/>\n\nIn May 2000, [[Austin H. Kiplinger]] and [[Walter Washington|Walter E. Washington]], the co-chairmen of the Leadership Committee for the planned [[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.#City Museum of Washington, D.C.|City Museum of Washington, D.C.]], wrote in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that the museum would remind visitors about how Banneker had brought his mathematical expertise to complete L'Enfant's project to map the city.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kiplinger|first1=Austin H.|author1-link=Austin H. Kiplinger|last2=Washington|first2=Walter E.|author2-link=Walter Washington|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/2000/05/07/a-museum-to-call-our-own/994d4214-2b41-4c53-aa02-b9de55a52773/|title=A Museum to Call Our Own |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|work=Close to Home|place=Washington, D.C.|date=2000-05-07|page=B.8|accessdate=2019-10-22|quote=The City Museum, for example, will remind visitors about how George Washington engaged Pierre L'Enfant to map the city and about how Benjamin Banneker brought his mathematical expertise to complete the project.}}</ref> A letter to the editor of the ''Post'' entitled \"District History Lesson\" then responded to this statement by noting that Andrew Ellicott was the person who revised L'Enfant's plan and who completed the capital city's mapping, and that Banneker had played no part in this.<ref>{{cite news |last=Berne|first=Bernard H.|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/53933685.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:FT&date=May+20%2C+2000&author=&desc=District+History+Lesson |title=District History Lesson |work=Letters to the Editor|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|place=Washington, D.C.|date=2000-05-20|page=A.22|accessdate=2011-03-23|quote=Austin H. Kiplinger and Walter E. Washington write that a proposed city museum at Mount Vernon Square will remind visitors that \"George Washington engaged Pierre L' Enfant to map the city and about how Benjamin Banneker [helped] complete the project\" [Close to Home, May 7]. Let's hope not.<br/>Benjamin Banneker performed astronomical observations in 1791 when assisting Maj. Andrew Ellicott in a survey of the federal District's boundaries.  He departed three months after the survey began, more than a year before its completion.<br/>Meanwhile, a \"Plan for the City of Washington\" was drawn by one \"Peter Charles L'Enfant\" (sic). When George Washington chose to dismiss L'Enfant, it was Ellicott who revised L'Enfant's plan and completed the city's mapping. Banneker played no part in this.}}</ref>\n\n==Appointment to planning commission for Washington, D.C.==\n[[File:Henry Edwin Baker.jpg|thumb|right|125px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup><br>Henry E. Baker</div>]]\n\nIn 1918, [[Henry E. Baker]], an African American serving as an assistant [[Patent examiner|examiner]] in the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office|United States Patent Office]], wrote a biography of Banneker in ''The Journal of Negro History'' (now titled ''[[Journal of African American History|The Journal of African American History]]''), which Carter Woodson edited. Baker's biography stated: \"It is on record that it was on the suggestion of his friend, Major Andrew Ellicott, ...., that Thomas Jefferson nominated Banneker and Washington appointed him a member of the commission\" whose duties were to \"define the boundary line and lay out the streets of the Federal Territory, later called the District of Columbia\".<ref name=Baker>{{cite journal |last=Baker |first=Henry E. |date=April 1918 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7aMIZXgDMkC&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=It is on record that it was at the suggestion of his friend, Major Andrew Ellicott, who so thoroughly appreciated the value of his scientific attainments, that Thomas Jefferson nominated Banneker and Washington appointed him a member of the commission to define the boundary line and lay out the streets of the Federal Territory, later called the District of Columbia. This Commission, was appointed by Washington, in 1879, and was composed of David Stuart, Daniel Carrol, Thomas Johnson, Andrew Ellicott and Pierre Charles L'Enfant, a famous French engineer. |title=Benjamin Banneker, the Negro Mathematician and Astronomer |journal=The Journal of Negro History |volume=III |number=2 |editor=Carter G. Woodson |publisher=The Association for the Study of Negro Life and History |location=Lancaster, PA. and Washington, D.C. |pages=111\u2013112 |accessdate=2011-12-28 |doi=10.2307/2713484|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224202920/https://books.google.com/books?id=z7aMIZXgDMkC&pg=PA111 |archivedate=2016-12-24 }}</ref> However, Baker did not identify the record on which he based this statement. Baker additionally stated that Andrew Ellicott and L'Enfant were also members of this commission.<ref name=Baker/>\n[[File:John Hope Franklin.png|thumb|left|200px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">John Hope Franklin (1998)</div>]]\n\nIn 1947, [[John Hope Franklin]] wrote in the first edition of his book ''From Slavery to Freedom: A History of American Negroes'' that the \"most distinguished honor that Banneker received was his appointment to serve with the commission to define the boundary line and lay out the streets of the District of Columbia.\" Franklin also stated that Banneker's \"friend\", [[George Ellicott]]  (Andrew Ellicott's cousin), was a member of the commission.<ref>{{cite book |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015163518/https://books.google.com/books?id=6z__lEiMUj0C&q=%22friend+George%22\n|archivedate=2019-10-15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6z__lEiMUj0C&q=%22friend+George%22|title=From Slavery to Freedom: A History of American Negroes|last=Franklin|first=John Hope|author-link=John Hope Franklin|location=New York |publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf]]|year=1947|edition=First|page=157|oclc=558185337|lccn=47031171|accessdate=2019-10-15 |quote=The most distinguished honor that Banneker received was his appointment to serve with the commission to define the boundary line and lay out the streets of the District of Columbia. It was perhaps at the suggestion of his friend [[George Ellicott]], himself a member of the commission, that Banneker's name was submitted .....|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, a book that Franklin co-authored made a similar statement, claiming that L'Enfant, Banneker and George Ellicott were the survey's commissioners.<ref>{{cite book|first1=John Walton|last1= Caughey|first2=John Hope|last2=Franklin|first3=Ernest R.|last3=May|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191015170343/https://books.google.com/books?id=EUNCAAAAIAAJ&q=%22George+Ellicott%22|archivedate=2019-10-15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EUNCAAAAIAAJ&q=%22George+Ellicott%22|title=Land of the Free: A History of the United States|pages=192\u2013193|year=1966|location=New York|publisher=Benziger Brothers|lccn=66012962|oclc=654547410|accessdate=2019-10-15|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=.... . The third member was a Quaker businessman and scientist, George Ellicott. L'Enfant, Banneker and Ellicott drew up plans for a city that was greater than Rome, Paris, or London.}}</ref> Bedini subsequently wrote in a 1972 biography of Banneker that the claim was incorrect.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/403/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 403, reference number 84]: \"John W. Caughey, John Hope Franklin, Ernest R. May, ''Land of the Free, A History of the United States'', New York, Bensinger Brothers, 1966, pp. 192\u2014193.: Includes a brief and inaccurate mention of the survey of the Federal City, claiming that the Commissioners for the survey were Pierre L'Enfant, Benjamin Banneker, and George Ellicott.\"</ref>\n\nNevertheless, Franklin repeated in a 2000 edition of his book (whose title had become ''From Slavery to Freedom: A History of African Americans'') the statements that he had made in the book's first edition. The 2000 edition also stated  that Thomas Jefferson had submitted Banneker's name to President Washington. The edition cited Baker's 1918 biography as the source of this information.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Franklin|first1=John Hope|last2=Moss|first2=Alfred A., Jr.|title=From Slavery to Freedom: A History of African Americans|location=New York|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|year=2000|edition=Eighth|isbn=0375406719|oclc=654597580|lccn=2005299886|via=[[Google Books]]}}:<br/>(1) [https://books.google.com/books?id=vksaAQAAIAAJ&q=%22distinguished+honor%22 p. 109] \"The most distinguished honor that Banneker received was his appointment to serve with the commission to define the boundary line and lay out the streets of the District of Columbia. .... \"<br/>(2) [https://books.google.com/books?id=vksaAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22lay+out+the+streets%22 p. 110] \"Banneker, perhaps the most accomplished black in the early national period, .... served on the commission to define the boundary line and lay out the streets of the District of Columbia.\"</ref>\n\nFranklin's books did not cite any documentation to support their contention that George Ellicott participated in the planning and design of the nation's capital. Andrew (not George) Ellicott led the survey that defined the District's boundary lines and, with L'Enfant, laid out the capital city's streets. There is no historical evidence that shows that President Washington participated in the process that resulted in Banneker's appointment as an assistant to Andrew Ellicott on the District boundary survey team.<ref name=\"Bedini p113\">[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/113/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 113.]</ref>\n[[File:James Avery.jpg|thumb|left|100px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">James Avery (2001)</div>]]\n\nIn 2005, actor [[James Avery (actor)|James Avery]] narrated a [[DVD]] entitled ''A History of Black Achievement in America''. A quiz based on a section of the DVD entitled \"Emergence of the Black Hero\" asked:\n\n<blockquote>\nBenjamin Banneker was a member of the planning commission for ____________ .<br /> a. New York City<br /> b. Philadelphia <br /> c. Washington, D.C.<br /> d. Atlanta<ref>Question 4 in {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217224738/http://www.ambrosevideo.com/resources/documents/297.pdf |archivedate=2013-02-17 |url=http://www.ambrosevideo.com/resources/documents/297.pdf |format=PDF |title=Black Achievement in American History: Blackline Master 2A Quiz: Program Two: Emergence of the Black Hero }} ''Based on'' {{cite web |last=Avery |first=James |date=April 2005 |url=https://dvd.ambrosevideo.com/items.cfm?id=1166 |title=A History of Black Achievement in America |work=DVD No. 1, Program Two: \"Emergence of the Black Hero\": \"1791 - The First Black Man of Science, Benjamin Banneker, Surveys Washington, D.C.\" |publisher=Ambrose Video Publishing, Inc. |accessdate=2018-06-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609050225/https://dvd.ambrosevideo.com/items.cfm?id=1166 |archive-date=June 9, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHistorical evidence contradicts the statements that Baker and Franklin made and suggests that the question in the quiz has no correct answer. In 1791, President Washington appointed [[Thomas Johnson (jurist)|Thomas Johnson]], [[Daniel Carroll]] and [[David Stuart (Virginia)|David Stuart]] to be the three commissioners who, in accordance with the authority that the federal [[Residence Act]] of 1790 had granted to the President, would oversee the survey of the federal district, and \"according to such Plans, as the President shall approve\", provide public buildings to accommodate the federal government in 1800.<ref name=\"residence act\">{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llsl&fileName=001%2Fllsl001.db&recNum=253|title=Text of Residence Act|work=American Memory: A Century of Lawmaking for a New Nation: U.S. Congressional Documents and Debates, 1774 - 1875: Statutes at Large, 1st Congress, 2nd Session, p. 130, July 16, 1790: Chapter 28: \"An Act for establishing the temporary and permanent seat of the Government of the United States\"|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=2018-06-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090913134846/http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llsl&fileName=001%2Fllsl001.db&recNum=253|archive-date=September 13, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Mathews p83\">{{cite book |last=Mathews |first=Catherine Van Cortlandt |year=1908 |url=https://archive.org/details/andrewellicotth03mathgoog |title=Andrew Ellicott: His Life and Letters |publisher=Grafton Press |location=New York |page=[https://archive.org/details/andrewellicotth03mathgoog/page/n57 83] |accessdate=2015-04-24 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref><ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/centennialhisto00woolgoog/page/n98 Crew, pp. 87-88] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622171422/http://books.google.com/books?id=5Q81AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA87 |date=2013-06-22 }}<br/>(2) {{cite book |last=Hazelton |first=George Cochrane |year=1914 |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924028858078 |title=The National Capitol: its architecture, art, and history |publisher=J.F. Taylor & Company |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/cu31924028858078/page/n13 2]\u20133 |accessdate=2015-04-24 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Residence Act did not authorize the President to appoint any more than three commissioners that could serve at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llsl&fileName=001%2Fllsl001.db&recNum=253|title=Text of Residence Act|work=American Memory: A Century of Lawmaking for a New Nation: U.S. Congressional Documents and Debates, 1774 - 1875: Statutes at Large, 1st Congress, 2nd Session, p. 130, July 16, 1790: Chapter 28: \"An Act for establishing the temporary and permanent seat of the Government of the United States\"|page=130|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|quote=Sec. 2. ''And be it further enacted,'' That the President of the United States be authorized to appoint, and by supplying vacancies happening from refusals to act or any other causes, to keep in appointment as long as may be necessary, three commissioners, who, or any two of whom, shall, under the direction of the President, survey, and by proper metes and bounds define and limit a district of territory, .....|accessdate=2018-06-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090913134846/http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llsl&fileName=001%2Fllsl001.db&recNum=253|archive-date=September 13, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> As Banneker, Andrew Ellicott, and L'Enfant performed their tasks during the time that Johnson, Carroll and Stuart were serving as commissioners, President Washington could not have legally appointed either Banneker, Ellicott or L'Enfant to serve as members of the \"commission\" that Baker and Franklin described.\n\nIn 1972 and 1999, Bedini reported that an exhaustive survey of U.S. government repositories, including the Public Buildings and Grounds files in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]] and collections in the [[Library of Congress]], had failed to identify Banneker's name on any contemporary documents or records relating to the selection, planning and survey of the City of Washington. Bedini also noted that none of L'Enfant's survey papers that he had found had contained Banneker's name.<ref name=\"Bedini 1999, p. 132\"/> Another researcher has been unable to find any documentation that shows that Washington and Banneker ever met.<ref name=Cerami135>(1) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120905204059/http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=7440 Corrigan], p. 3. \"Washington hired Ellicott and presumably was aware of Banneker's work, though Cerami uncovered no documentary evidence of their encounter.\"<br/>(2) [https://archive.org/details/banneker00char/page/135/mode/1up Cerami, 2002, p. 135.] \"No account mentions actual encounters between Banneker and the President (Washington).\"</ref>\n\n==Boundary markers of the District of Columbia==\n[[File:Map of the District of Columbia, 1835.jpg|thumb|right|200px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">[[Library of Congress]]</div>1835 map of the District of Columbia, showing the City of Washington in the center of the District and the town of Alexandria in the District's south corner.]]\n[[File:Boundary Stone (District of Columbia) NE 4.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Northeast No. 4 boundary marker stone of the original District of Columbia in Washington, D.C., and [[Prince George's County, Maryland]] (2005)]]\nDuring 1791 and 1792, a survey team that Andrew Ellicott led placed forty [[milestone|mile marker stones]] along the {{convert|10|mi|km|1}}-long sides of a square that would form the boundaries of the future District of Columbia. Ellicott's survey began at the square's south corner at [[Jones Point (Virginia)|Jones Point]] in [[Alexandria, Virginia]] (see [[Boundary markers of the original District of Columbia]]).<ref name=planning/><ref>[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2/page/n159 Tindall, p. 151]</ref> Several accounts of the marker stones incorrectly attribute their placement to Banneker.\n\nIn 1994, historians preparing a National Register of Historic Places registration form for the L'Enfant plan of the City of Washington wrote that forty boundary stones laid at one-mile intervals had established the District's boundaries based on Banneker's celestial calculations.<ref name=Leach>{{cite web|url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/pdfhost/docs/NRHP/Text/97000332.pdf|title=L' Enfant Plan of the City of Washington, District of Columbia|work=[[United States Department of the Interior]]: [[National Park Service]]: National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Section 8, p. 7|date=1994-07-20|first=Sara Amy|last=Leach|first2=Elizabeth, HABS/HAER, NPS|last2=Barthold|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2017-11-05|quote=Forty boundary stones, laid at one-mile intervals, established the boundaries based on celestial calculations by Banneker, a self-taught astronomer of African descent and one of few free blacks living in the vicinity. Within this 100-square-mile diamond, which would become the District of Columbia, a smaller area was laid out as the City of Washington.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105215223/https://npgallery.nps.gov/pdfhost/docs/NRHP/Text/97000332.pdf|archivedate=2017-11-05}}</ref> In 2005, a data gathering report for the planned Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture (NMAAHC) in Washington, D.C., stated that Banneker had assisted Andrew Ellicott in laying out the forty boundary marker stones.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194520/http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Site_Evaluation_Study__PhaseI_Data_Gathering_Report.pdf|archivedate=2015-09-23|url=http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Site_Evaluation_Study__PhaseI_Data_Gathering_Report.pdf|title= \nSite Evaluation Study: Phase I: Data Gathering Report|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]]|date=2005-09-30|page=31|quote=He (Banneker) was a self-taught mathematician and astronomer, and one of the few free blacks living in the vicinity. Banneker assisted Major Ellicott in laying out forty boundary stones, at one-mile intervals, based on celestial calculations, to establish the boundaries of the District of Columbia.|accessdate=2017-11-05}}</ref> Both the 2005 data gathering report and a 2007 historic preservation report for the NMAAHC repeated the statement that the boundary stones' locations had been based on Banneker's \"celestial calculations\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Robinson and Associates, Washington, D.C.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104161652/http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Final_Historic_Preservation_Report.pdf|archivedate=2015-11-04|url=http://nmaahceis.si.edu/documents/Final_Historic_Preservation_Report.pdf|title=Historic Preservation Report For the National Museum Of African American History and Culture: District of Columbia: Final Report: Prepared For: Smithsonian Institution Office of Planning and Project Management|page=11|date=July 2007|accessdate=2019-01-07|quote=Emplacements of the 40 stones were based on celestial calculations by Banneker, a self-taught astronomer and mathematician of African descent and one of few free blacks living in the vicinity.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Penny Carr, a [[wiktionary:regent|regent]] of the [[Falls Church, Virginia]], chapter of the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] (DAR) wrote in an online community newspaper that Andrew Ellicott and Banneker had in 1791 put in place the westernmost boundary marker stone of the original D.C. boundary. Carr stated that the marker now sits on the boundary line of Falls Church City, Fairfax County, and Arlington County.<ref>{{cite web |first=Penny |last=Carr |date=2012-11-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127132931/http://www.fallschurchtimes.com/37429/dar-scouts-protect-historic-boundary-stone/ |archivedate=2012-11-27 |url=http://www.fallschurchtimes.com/37429/dar-scouts-protect-historic-boundary-stone/ |title=DAR, Scouts Protect Historic Boundary Stone |work=Falls Church Times: Falls Church City's Online Community Newspaper |quote=In its path through the Washington D.C. Metro area, the [[derecho]] dropped massive limbs, power lines and trees on houses and streets.  It also dropped a massive limb on the Westernmost Boundary Marker of the original D.C. boundary \u2013 the \"Ellicott Stone.\"  This stone was put in place by Mr. Andres Ellicott and Mr. Benjamin Banneker in 1791.  Today it sits on the boundary line of Falls Church City, Fairfax County, and Arlington County.}}</ref> Carr did not provide the source of this information.\n\nA book published in May 2014 entitled \"''A History Lover's Guide to Washington''\" stated that both Ellicott and Banneker had \"carefully placed the forty original boundary stones along the Washington, D.C. borders with Virginia and Maryland in 1791-1792\".<ref>{{cite book|first=Alison|last=Fortier|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-w53CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT24#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Original Boundary Markers|work=A History Lover's Guide to Washington, D.C.: Designed for Democracy|page=24|location=[[Charleston, South Carolina]]|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing|Arcadia Publishing: The History Press]]|date=2014-05-06|isbn=9781625850645|lccn=2014011085|oclc=879612020|accessdate=2018-01-28|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Similarly, on May 8, 2015, a ''[[Washington Post]]'' article describing a rededication ceremony for one of the marker stones reported that Sharon K. Thorne-Sulima, a regent of a chapter of the District of Columbia DAR, had said: <blockquote>These stones are our nation's oldest national landmarks that were placed by Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker. They officially laid the seat of government of our new nation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Hamil R. |last=Harris |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510022310/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2015/05/08/200-year-old-boundary-markers-in-d-c-rededicated/|archivedate=2015-05-10 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2015/05/08/200-year-old-boundary-markers-in-d-c-rededicated/ |title=200-year-old boundary markers in D.C. rededicated |work=Local |date=2015-05-08 |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2016-04-01 |quote=\"These stones are our nation's oldest national landmarks that were placed by Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker,\" said Sharon K. Thorne-Sulima, regent for the Martha Washington chapter of the D.C. Daughters of the American Revolution. \"They officially laid the seat of government of our new nation.\"}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn May 30, 2015, a [[World Wide Web|web]] version of a follow-up article in the ''Post'' carried the headline \"''Stones laid by Benjamin Banneker in the 1790s are still standing''\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Hamil R. |last=Harris |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150531012001/http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/stones-laid-by-benjamin-banneker-in-the-1790s-are-still-standing/2015/05/30/11c39d04-0007-11e5-833c-a2de05b6b2a4_story.html|archivedate=2015-05-31|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/stones-laid-by-benjamin-banneker-in-the-1790s-are-still-standing/2015/05/30/11c39d04-0007-11e5-833c-a2de05b6b2a4_story.html|title=Stones laid by Benjamin Banneker in the 1790s are still standing|work=Local|date=May 30, 2015|publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Disputing the headline's information, a June 1, 2015, comment following the article stated while citing an extensively referenced source<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630043053/http://www.boundarystones.org/|archivedate=2015-06-30|url=http://www.boundarystones.org/|title=Boundary Stones of the District of Columbia|publisher=boundarystones.org|accessdate=2016-04-03|quote=''Ellicott, a prominent professional surveyor, hired Benjamin Banneker, an astronomer and mathematician from Maryland, to make the astronomical observations and calculations necessary to establish the south corner of the square at Jones Point in Alexandria. According to legend, \"Banneker fixed the position of the first stone by lying on his back to find the exact starting point for the survey ... and plotting six stars as they crossed his spot at a particular time of night.\" On April 15, 1791, the Alexandria Masonic Lodge placed a small stone at the south corner at Jones Point in ceremonies attended by Ellicott, federal district commissioners Daniel Carroll and David Stuart, and other dignitaries. .... Ellicott's team, minus Banneker, who left after the placement of the south stone, then began the formal survey by clearing twenty feet of land on both sides of each boundary and placing other stones, made of Aquia Creek sandstone, at one-mile intervals.''}}</ref> that Banneker had, \"according to legend\", made the astronomical observations and calculations needed to establish the location of the south corner of the District's square, but had not participated in any later parts of the square's survey.<ref>{{cite web |author=RossEmery |date=2015-06-01|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802135404/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/stones-laid-by-benjamin-banneker-in-the-1790s-are-still-standing/2015/05/30/11c39d04-0007-11e5-833c-a2de05b6b2a4_story.html|archivedate=2015-08-02|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/stones-laid-by-benjamin-banneker-in-the-1790s-are-still-standing/2015/05/30/11c39d04-0007-11e5-833c-a2de05b6b2a4_story.html |title=Comment |work=Stones laid by Benjamin Banneker in the 1790s are still standing |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2016-04-01 |quote=\"Stones laid by Benjamin Banneker in the 1790s are still standing\" ''Actually: Ellicott, a prominent professional surveyor, hired Benjamin Banneker, an astronomer and mathematician from Maryland, to make the astronomical observations and calculations necessary to establish the south corner of the square at Jones Point in Alexandria. According to legend, \"Banneker fixed the position of the first stone by lying on his back to find the exact starting point for the survey ... and plotting six stars as they crossed his spot at a particular time of night.\" From there, Ellicott's team (minus Banneker, who worked only on the south corner) embarked on a forty mile journey, surveying ten-mile lines first to the northwest, then the northeast, next southeast, and finally southwest back toward the starting point, clearing twenty feet of land on each side of the boundary.'' http://www.boundarystones.org}}</ref> \n\nOne of the references in the source that the comment in the ''Post'' cited was a 1969 publication that Silvio Bedini had authored. In that publication, Bedini stated that Banneker apparently left the federal capital area and returned to his home at Ellicott's Mills in late April 1791, shortly after the south cornerstone (the first boundary marker stone) was set in place during an April 15, 1791, ceremony.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini 1969, pp. 25\u201329.]</ref> In 1794, a permanent south cornerstone reportedly replaced the stone that was set in place during the 1791 ceremony.<ref> {{cite web|last=Mackintosh|first=Barry, Regional Historian, National Capital Region, [[National Park Service]], Washington, D.C.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005192235/http://focus.nps.gov/pdfhost/docs/NRHP/Text/80000352.pdf|archivedate=October 5, 2016|url=http://focus.nps.gov/pdfhost/docs/NRHP/Text/80000352.pdf|title=Jones Point Lighthouse and District of Columbia South Cornerstone|work=[[United States Department of the Interior]]: National Park Service: [[National Register of Historic Places]] Inventory \u2014 Nomination Form for Federal Properties|publisher=United States Department of the Interior: National Park Service: Sheet #2: Statement of Significance|date=January 24, 1980|accessdate=February 25, 2020|quote=The Alexandria Masonic Lodge placed a stone at the south corner on April 15, 1791, in ceremonies attended by Ellicott, federal district commissioners Daniel Carroll and David Stuart, and other dignitaries. Other stones were subsequently placed at approximately one-mile intervals along the District boundary with Virginia and along the District-Maryland line in 1792. In 1794 a permanent south cornerstone replaced that laid originally; ...}}</ref>\n\nCiting a statement that Bedini had made in a biography of Banneker published in 1972,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/103/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 103.]</ref> historian [[Julian P. Boyd]] pointed out in a 1974 publication that there was no evidence that Banneker had anything to do with the survey of the Federal City or with the final establishment of the boundaries of the Federal District.<ref name=Founders/> Nevertheless, in 2016, Charlie Clark, a columnist writing in a Falls Church newspaper, stated that Banneker had placed a District boundary stone in Clark's [[Arlington County, Virginia]], neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news |first=Charlie |last=Clark |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219093704/https://fcnp.com/2016/02/17/our-man-in-arlington-166/ |archivedate=2016-02-19 |url=https://fcnp.com/2016/02/17/our-man-in-arlington-166/ |title=Our Man in Arlington |date=2016-02-17 |publisher=[[Falls Church News-Press]] |accessdate=2016-04-01 |quote=Our enclave's earliest landmark is the District of Columbia boundary stone placed in 1791 by Benjamin Banneker.}}</ref>\n[[File:Boundary Stone (District of Columbia) South Cornerstone close-up.jpg|thumb|right|200px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">South cornerstone of the original District of Columbia at Jones Point in Alexandria, Virginia (2010)</div>]]\nA 2016 booklet that the government of Arlington County, Virginia, published to promote the County's African American history stated, \"On April 15, 1791, officials dedicated the first boundary stone based on Banneker's calculations.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Liebertz |first=John |url=https://arlingtonva.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/31/2016/09/A-Guide-to-the-African-American-Heritage-of-Arlington-County-Virginia.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007171712/https://arlingtonva.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/31/2016/09/A-Guide-to-the-African-American-Heritage-of-Arlington-County-Virginia.pdf |archivedate=2016-10-07 |accessdate=2016-10-07 |title=Boundary Markers of the District of Columbia: Benjamin Banneker |work=A Guide to the African American Heritage of Arlington County |edition=2nd |publisher=Historic Preservation Program: Department of Community Planning, Housing and Development, Government of Arlington County, Virginia |year=2016 |page=1 |quote=A free, self-taught African American astronomer and mathematician, Benjamin Banneker assisted Andrew Ellicott on the original survey of the District of Columbia from February to April 1791. Ellicott retained Banneker to make astronomical observations and calculations to establish the location of the south cornerstone of the 10-mile square. On April 15, 1791, officials dedicated the first boundary stone based on Banneker's calculations.}}</ref> However, it was actually a March 30, 1791, presidential proclamation by George Washington that established \"Jones's point, the upper [[Cape (geography)|cape]] of [[Hunting Creek]] in Virginia\" as the starting point for the federal district's boundary survey.<ref>{{cite book |last=Washington |first=George |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qhk_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA254&lpg=PA254&onepage&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Proclamation: Georgetown, March 30, 1791 |work=The Writings of George Washington from the Original Manuscript Sources: 1745-1799 |editor=John C. Fitzpatrick |volume=31: January 22, 1790\u2014March 9, 1792 |location=Washington |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]] (August, 1939) |accessdate=2016-10-07 |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=Now therefore for the purposes of amending and completing the location of the whole of the said territory of the ten miles square in conformity with the said amendatory act of Congress, I do hereby declare and make known that the whole of said territory shall be located and included within the four lines following, that is to say: Beginning at Jones's point, the upper cape of Hunting Creek in Virginia, and at an angle in the outset of 45 degrees west of the north: ...}}.</ref>\n\nWashington did not need any calculations to determine the location of Jones Point. Further, according to an April 21, 1791, news report of the dedication ceremony for the first boundary stone (the south cornerstone), it was Andrew Ellicott who \u2033ascertained the precise point from which the first line of the district was to proceed\". The news report did not mention Banneker's name.<ref>(1) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini 1969, pp. 25\u201329.]<br>(2) {{cite news |location=Boston, Massachusetts |publisher=Benjamin Russell |url=http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/columbian_centinel_1791.pdf |title=New Federal City |work=Columbian Centennial |number=744 |date=1791-05-07 |accessdate=2016-10-09 |quote=When Mr. Ellicott had ascertained the precise point from which the line of the district was to proceed, the Master of the Lodge and Dr. Stewart, assisted by others of their brethren placed the stone; ... |via=[http://www.boundarystones.org boundarystones.org] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630220952/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/columbian_centinel_1791.pdf |archivedate=2016-06-30}}</ref>\n\nA National Park Service web page entitled ''Benjamin Banneker and the Boundary Stones of the District of Columbia'' stated in 2017:<blockquote>Along with a team, Banneker identified the boundaries of the capitol city. They installed intermittent stone markers along the perimeter of the District.<ref name=NPS1/></blockquote> The Park Service did not provide a source for this statement.\n\n==Banneker's clock==\nIn 1845, [[John H. B. Latrobe|John Hazelhurst Boneval Latrobe]], an American lawyer, inventor and future president of the [[American Colonization Society]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Semmes|first=John E.|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015070464642;view=1up;seq=195|title=Chapter 6: African Colonization|work=John H. B. Latrobe and His Times|pages=139\u2013171|location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=The Norman, Remington Company|date=October 1917|oclc=262462816|lccn=18002814|accessdate=2019-03-22|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]}}</ref> read a ''Memoir of Benjamin Banneker'' at a meeting of the [[Maryland Historical Society]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memoirbenjaminb00socigoog/page/n25 <!-- pg=1 --> Latrobe]</ref> Latrobe's memoir, presented 39 years after Banneker's death, contains the first known account of Banneker's clock. The memoir stated:<blockquote>It was at this time, when he (Banneker) was about thirty years of age, that he contrived and made a clock, which proved an excellent time\u2013piece. He had seen a watch, but not a clock, such an article having not yet having found its way into the quiet and secluded valley in which he lived. The watch was therefore his model.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/memoirbenjaminb00socigoog/page/n13 Latrobe, p. 7.]</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Portrait of Moncure D. Conway.jpg|thumb|left|100 px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Moncure D. Conway</div>]]\nIn 1863, the ''[[Atlantic Monthly]]'' magazine published during the [[American Civil War]] a brief biography of Banneker that an American abolitionist minister, [[Moncure D. Conway]], had written.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044103018420;view=1up;seq=89 Conway, pp. 79\u201484.]</ref> Embellishing Latrobe's account of Banneker's clock, Conway described the timepiece as follows:<blockquote>Perhaps the first wonder amongst his comparatively illiterate neighbors was excited, when about the thirtieth year of his age, Benjamin made a clock. It is probable that this was the first clock of which every portion was made in America; it is certain that it was as purely as his own invention as if none had ever been made before. He had seen a watch, but never a clock, such an article not being within fifty miles of him. The watch was his model.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044103018420;view=1up;seq=91 Conway, p. 81.]</ref></blockquote> Conway's biography concluded by stating \"... history must record that the most original scientific intellect which the South has yet produced was that of the pure African, Benjamin Banneker.\"<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044103018420;view=1up;seq=94 Conway, p. 84.]</ref>\n\n[[File:Lydia Maria Child.jpg|thumb|right|150px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup><br>Lydia Maria Child (circa 1865)</div>]]\nIn 1865, an American abolitionist, [[Lydia Maria Child]], authored a book intended to be used to teach recently freed African Americans to read and to provide them with inspiration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/wcidentities/lccn-n80001490|title=Most widely held works by Lydia Maria Child|work=Child, Lydia Maria 1802-1880|publisher=[[WorldCat]]|accessdate=2018-05-28|quote=Published in 1865 and edited by abolitionist L. Maria Child, The Freedmens Book was intended to be used to teach recently freed African Americans to read and to provide them with inspiration. Thirsting for education, Freedmen were eagerly enrolling in any schools that would accept them. Child saw a need for texts and provided one of collected stories and poems written by former slaves and noted abolitionists, herself included.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529053847/https://www.worldcat.org/wcidentities/lccn-n80001490|archive-date=May 29, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Child's book stated that Banneker had constructed \"the first clock ever made in this country\".<ref name=Child>[https://archive.org/stream/freedmensbook01chil#page/n28/mode/1up/mode/1up Child, p. 15.] \"At thirty years old, he made a clock, which proved to be an excellent time piece. .... This was the first clock ever made in this country.\"</ref>\n\n[[File:Kelly Miller.jpg|thumb|left|125px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup><br>Kelly Miller</div>]]\nIn 1902, [[Kelly Miller (scientist)|Kelly Miller]], a professor of mathematics at Howard University, made a similar undocumented claim in a [[United States Department of Education#History|United States Bureau of Education]] publication. Miller, who later became a professor of [[sociology]] and [[Dean (education)|dean]] of the [[Howard University#Schools and colleges|school's College of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Jefferson|first=Karen L.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220161941/https://dh.howard.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1133&context=finaid_manu|archivedate=February 20, 2020|url=https://dh.howard.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1133&context=finaid_manu|title=Kelly Miller Papers: Collection 71-1 to 71-8|work=Digital Howard @ Howard University|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Manuscript Division, Howard University|date=June 1980|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> stated in his paper that Banneker had in 1770 \"constructed a clock to strike the hours, the first to be made in America\".<ref name=KMiller>{{cite book |last=Miller |first=Kelly |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sLwtAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA856&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Chapter XVI. The Education of the Negro: X. Negroes who have achieved Distinction along Lines calling for Definite Intellectual Activity |work=Report of the Commissioner of Education for the Year 1900-1901|volume=1|year=1902|location=Washington, D.C.|page=856|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|accessdate=March 23, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> In contrast, Philip Lee Phillips, a Library of Congress librarian,<ref>Note: Phillip Lee Phillips (1857-1924) was the first Superintendent of Maps for the [[Library of Congress]], where he devoted over thirty years to the development of the Library's map and atlas collection. See:<br/>(1) {{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/phillipsbrochure.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909202635/http://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/phillipsbrochure.pdf |archivedate=2013-09-09 |title=Philip Lee Phillips Society Programs and Activities |publisher=Library of Congress Geography and Map Division |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=2015-04-06}}<br/> (2) {{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/pdf/plp/brochure.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406182429/http://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/pdf/plp/brochure.pdf|archivedate=2015-04-06|title=Philip Lee Phillips Map Society: The Friends Group of the Geography and Map Division: Library of Congress |publisher=Library of Congress Geography and Map Division |location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=2015-04-06}}<br/>(3) {{cite journal |last=Seavey |first=Charles A. |title=Philip Lee Phillips and the growth of the library of Congress map collection, 1897\u20131924 |journal=Government Publications Review |volume=20 |number=3 |pages=283\u2013295 |year=1993 |doi=10.1016/0277-9390(93)90004-9 |issn=0277-9390 |oclc=4656134177 |publisher=[[Elsevier]]}}</ref> more cautiously stated in a 1916 paper read before the Columbia Historical Society in Washington, D.C. that Banneker \"is said to have made, entirely with his own hand, a clock of which it is said every portion was made in America.\"<ref name=Phillips120/>\n[[File:Benjamin Brawley portrait.jpg|thumb|right|125px|<center>Benjamin Griffith Brawley (circa 1920-1930)</center>]] \n\nIn 1919, Carter Woodson wrote in the second edition of his book ''The Education of the Negro Prior to 1861'' that Banneker had \"made in 1770 the first clock manufactured in the United States\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=U6sQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false Woodson, 1919, p. 91.]  \"Although he had never seen a clock, watches being the only timepieces in the vicinity, he made in 1770 the first clock manufactured in the United States.\"</ref> In 1921, [[Benjamin Griffith Brawley]], who had earlier worked at Howard University and had served as the first dean of [[Morehouse College]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Salo|first=Jessica|url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brawley-benjamin-griffith-1882-1939/|title=Benjamin Griffith Brawley (1882-1939)|work=BlackPast|publisher=BlackPast.org|date=June 11, 2008|accessdate=April 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411071824/https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brawley-benjamin-griffith-1882-1939/|archive-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> authored a book entitled ''A Social History of the American Negro''. Repeating Kelly Miller's claim, Brawley's book stated that Banneker had in 1770 \"constructed the first clock striking the hours that was made in America.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Brawley|first=Benjamin|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=yale.39002005698320&view=1up&seq=97|title=Chapter III: The Revolutionary Era|work=A Social History of the American Negro, Being a History of the Negro Problem in the United States, Including a History and Study of the Republic of Liberia|page=75|year=1921|location=New York|publisher=[[Macmillan Inc.|The Macmillan Company]]|oclc=271206977|accessdate=April 11, 2020|via=[[HathiTrust]]}}</ref> \n\nIn 1929, ''[[The Chicago Defender]]'' newspaper reported that a speaker at a ceremony dedicating a sundial commemorating Banneker at Howard University had stated that \"Banneker made the first clock used in America which was constructed of all American materials\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepearlofomega.org/Resources/Documents/The%20Dial,%20Ch%20iDefender,%202-16-29.pdf |format=PDF|title=Howard U Gets Memorial to Benjamin Banneker |work=Chicago, Illinois: [[The Chicago Defender]] (National edition)|date=1929-02-16|page=A1|publisher=[[ProQuest]] Historical Newspapers |accessdate=2017-11-09 |via=[http://www.thepearlofomega.org The Pearl of Omega] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109123630/http://www.thepearlofomega.org/Resources/Documents/The%20Dial,%20Ch%20iDefender,%202-16-29.pdf|archivedate=2017-11-09|quote=It was also noted that Banneker made the first clock used in America which was constructed of all American materials.}}</ref> In 1967, [[William Loren Katz]] repeated this statement in his book, ''Eyewitness: The Negro in American History'', claiming that Banneker as a teenager \"constructed a clock, the first one made entirely with American parts\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Katz|first=William Loren|author-link=William Loren Katz|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014074338/https://books.google.com/books?id=RxlCAAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22a+clock%22|archivedate=2019-10-14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RxlCAAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22a+clock%22|title=Eyewitness: The Negro in American History|page=30|location=New York|publisher=[[James Pitman|Pitman Publishing Corporation]]|year=1974|lccn=67010838|oclc=558242071|accessdate=2019-10-14|quote=..., Banneker began his studies as a teenager. Using crude tools, he constructed a clock, the first one made entirely with American parts.|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> In 1968, a writer for the magazine ''[[Negro Digest]]'' stated that, at the age of 21, Banneker \"perfected the first clock in Maryland, possibly in America\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=C. L.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5zkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Man Who Saved Washington, D. C.|work=[[Negro Digest]]: Negro History Issue|page=20|volume=15|number=4|date=February 1966|location=Chicago, Illinois|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company, Inc.|via=[[Google Books]]|accessdate=2019-02-17|quote=<br/>At the age of 21, with knowledge gained from taking apart a watch, he (Banneker) perfected the first clock in Maryland, possibly in America.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, Louis Haber stated in a book entitled ''Black Pioneers of Science and Invention'' that Banneker had by 1753 completed \"the first clock ever built in the United States\" and that \"People came from all over the country to see his clock.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Haber|first=Louis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kh6GOI_258YC&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Banjamin Banneker: 1731\u20141806|work=Black Pioneers of Science and Invention|edition=First Oddssey Classics (1992)|year=1970|pages=5\u20136|publisher=[[Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt]]|oclc=1024156094|isbn=9780152085667|lccn=91008923|accessdate=2019-03-15|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br />For two years Banneker spent all his spare time working on the clock. He built it entirely of wood and carved each of the gears by hand. By 1753 it was completed. It was the first clock ever built in the United States.  The clock kept perfect time, striking every hour four more than 40 years. People came from all over the country to see his clock. It created a sensation.}}</ref> The book's preface reported that the work had resulted in part from a [[United States Department of Education#History|United States Office of Education]] grant to \"gather resource materials that could then be incorporated into science curricula at elementary and secondary schools as well as at the college level\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Haber|first=Louis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kh6GOI_258YC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Preface|work=Black Pioneers of Science and Invention|edition=First Oddssey Classics (1992)|year=1970|page=vii|publisher=[[Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt]]|oclc=1024156094|isbn=9780152085667|lccn=91008923|accessdate=2019-03-15|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=<br />The author began research into this area many years ago. His objective was to gather resource materials that could then be incorporated into science curricula at elementary and secondary schools as well as at the college level. In 1966 he was given a grant by the U.S. Office of Education to pursue this study.}}</ref> A book authored by Otto Lindenmeyer and entitled ''Black History: Lost, Stolen, or Strayed'' that was also published in 1970 stated that Banneker had constructed his clock's frame and movements \"entirely of wood, the first such instrument made in America\".<ref>{{cite book|first=Otto J.|last= Lindenmeyer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L7ERAQAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22mechanical+clock%22|title=Black History: Lost, Stolen or Strayed|work=\"Of Black America\" series|page=43|location=New York|publisher=[[Avon (publisher)|Avon Books]]|year=1970|oclc=755240778|accessdate=2019-03-14|via=Google Books|quote=<br />At an early age, for example, he (Banneker) used a small watch as a model for his own mechanical clock and constructed its frame and its movements entirely of wood, the first such instrument made in America.}}</ref> \n\nIn 1976, an Afro-American Bicentennial Corporation historian prepared a National Register of Historic Places nomination form for a District of Columbia boundary marker stone whose proposed name would commemorate Banneker. The form's \"Statement of Significance\" claimed that Banneker was an inventor whose   \"ability as a mathematician enabled him to construct what is believed to have been the first working wooden clock in America\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Graves|first=Lynne Gomez, Historical Projects Director, Afro-American Bicentennial Corporation, Washington, D.C |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001145447/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0015_%20Banneker_SW-9_Intermediate_Boundary_Stone_1976_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf |archivedate=October 1, 2016|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0015_%20Banneker_SW-9_Intermediate_Boundary_Stone_1976_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf|title=Benjamin Banneker: SW-9 Intermediate Boundary Stone (milestone) of the District of Columbia|work=United States Department of the Interior: National Park Service: National Register of Historic Places Inventory\u2013\u2013Nomination Form |location=Richmond, Virginia |publisher=[[Virginia Department of Historic Resources]]|date=February 3, 1976|page=3|accessdate=November 8, 2019|quote=He (Banneker) was a farmer, a mathematician, an inventor, an astronomer, a writer, a surveyor, a scientist, and a humanitarian. .... Banneker's ability as a mathematician enabled him to construct what is believed to have been the first working wooden clock in America in 1753.}}</ref> In 1978, the ''[[Baltimore Afro-American]]'' reported that Banneker was the \"inventor of the first clock\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Oliver|first=Elizabeth M.|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19781216&id=pvkmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MwMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1220,4936390&hl=en|title=Ossie Davis Stars as Benjamin Banneker|work=[[Baltimore Afro-American]]|date=1978-12-09|page=36|location=Baltimore, Maryland|accessdate=2019-02-15|via=[[Google News]]|quote=Before his death in 1806, Banneker had gained fame in America, France and England as a scientist, astronomer inventor of the first clock ..... .}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal Square Building.jpg|thumb|right|250px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">National Postal Museum (2008)</div>]]\n\nIn 1980, the [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) issued a postage stamp that commemorated Banneker. The USPS' description of Banneker stated: \"... In 1753, he built the first watch made in America.\"<ref name=stamp2>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150818215049/http://www.xyht.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Banneker2.jpg |archivedate=2015-08-18 |url=http://www.xyht.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Banneker2.jpg |title=Image and United States Postal Service description of Benjamin Banneker postage stamp |quote=The U.S. Postal Service issued a stamp in 1980 with this description: \"Benjamin Banneker first achieved national recognition for his scientific work in the 1791 survey of the Federal Territory ... In 1773, he built the first watch made in America ...\" }} ''In'' {{cite journal|last=Glawe|first=Eddie|url=http://www.xyht.com/professional-surveyor-archives/feature-benjamin-banneker/|title=Feature: Benjamin Banneker|work=Professional Surveyor Magazine|date=2014-02-13|volume=39|issue=6|publisher=Flatdog Media, Inc.|accessdate=2018-02-18|via=[http://www.xyht.com xyHt]|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130044246/http://www.xyht.com/professional-surveyor-archives/feature-benjamin-banneker/|archive-date=January 30, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA 2004 USPS pamphlet illustrating the stamp stated that Banneker \"constructed the first wooden [[striking clock]] made in America\",<ref name=stamp1>{{cite web |author=Diversity Development |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140824090919/http://about.usps.com/publications/pub354.pdf|archivedate=2014-08-24|url=http://about.usps.com/publications/pub354.pdf |title=Benjamin Banneker |work=Publication 354: African Americans on Stamps: A Celebration of African-American Heritage |page=3 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |date=January 2004 |accessdate=2015-03-14 |quote=A self-taught mathematician and astronomer, Benjamin Banneker was probably the most accomplished African American of America's colonial period. In 1753, he constructed the first wooden striking clock made in America. His studies and calculations in astronomy allowed him to successfully predict a solar eclipse in 1789 and to publish farmer's almanacs in the 1790s. In 1791 he helped design and survey the city of Washington, D.C. This stamp was issued February 15, 1980.}}</ref> a statement which also appeared on a web page of the Smithsonian Institution's [[National Postal Museum]] entitled \"''Early Pioneers''\".<ref name=Arago1>{{cite web|url=https://arago.si.edu/exhibit_461_3.html|title=Early Pioneers|work=Arago: People, Postage & The Post (Exhibits)|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] [[National Postal Museum]]|accessdate=2018-01-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108022223/https://arago.si.edu/exhibit_461_3.html|archivedate=2018-01-08|quote=A self-taught mathematician and astronomer, Benjamin Banneker was probably the most accomplished African American of America's colonial period. In 1753, he constructed the first wooden striking clock made in America. His studies and calculations in astronomy allowed him to successfully predict a solar eclipse in 1789 and to publish farmer's almanacs in the 1790s. In 1791 he helped design and survey the city of Washington, D.C.}}</ref> \nThe website of the [[Banneker-Douglass Museum]], the State of [[Maryland]]'s official museum of African American heritage, similarly claimed in 2015 that Banneker crafted \"the first wooden striking clock in America\".<ref name=Museum>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314193326/http://bdmuseum.maryland.gov/history/ |archivedate=2015-03-14 |url=http://bdmuseum.maryland.gov/ |title=History |work=Banneker-Douglass Museum |publisher=Government of Maryland |accessdate=2015-03-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, [[Oregon]]'s [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools District]] published a series of educational materials entitled ''[[African-American Baseline Essays]]''. The Essays were to be \"used by teachers and other District staff as a reference and resource just as adopted textbooks and other resources are used\" as part of \"a huge multicultural curriculum-development effort.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pps.net/cms/lib/OR01913224/Centricity/Domain/179/pdfs/prefc-af.pdf |title=Preface to the African/African-American Baseline Essays |last=Prophet |first=Matthew W. |date=Spring 1987 |publisher=Portland Public Schools |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> An Essay entitled ''African-American Contributions to Science and Technology'' stated that Banneker had \"made America's first clock\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Hunter Havelin, III|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623175045/https://www.pps.net/cms/lib/OR01913224/Centricity/Domain/179/pdfs/be-af-sc.pdf|archivedate=2017-06-23|url=https://www.pps.net/cms/lib/OR01913224/Centricity/Domain/179/pdfs/be-af-sc.pdf|page=S-74|title=Geocultural Baseline Essay Series: African and African-American Contributions to Science and Technology|work=Patents, Inventions, and Contributions: Benjamin Banneker|publisher=[[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]]|year=1986|accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, a critic writing for the ''Washington Post'' who had earlier authored a 1991 paper describing the Essays' deficiencies<ref>{{cite web|title=How Valid Are the Portland Baseline Essays?|last=Martel|first=Erich|url=http://shop.ascd.org/ASCD/pdf/journals/ed_lead/el_199112_martel.pdf|date=December 1991|work=[[Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development#Educational Leadership|Educational Leadership]]|location=Alexandria, Virginia|publisher=[[Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development|Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development (ASCD)]]|accessdate=2019-09-18}}</ref> cited the Essays' \"crippling flaws\" while noting that the Essays \"are the most widespread Afrocentric teaching material\".<ref name=Martel2>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1994/02/20/the-egyptian-illusion/ee123656-ca7f-4ef7-8f28-99d7edd166ba/|title=The Egyptian Illusion|last=Martel|first=Erich|work=Opinions|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=1994-02-20|accessdate=2018-09-17|quote=Teachers who want reliable information on African American history often don't know where to turn. Many have unfortunately looked to unreliable books and publications by Afrocentric writers. The African American Baseline Essays, developed by the public school system in Portland, Ore., are the most widespread Afrocentric teaching material. Educators should be aware of their crippling flaws. ....<br>\"Thomas Jefferson appointed Benjamin Banneker to survey the site for the capital, Washington, D.C.\" and Banneker \"wrote a proposal for the establishment of a United States Department of Peace,\" according to the essay on African American scientists.<br>Had the author consulted \"The Life of Benjamin Banneker\" by Silvio Bedini, considered the definitive biography, he would have discovered no evidence for these claims. Jefferson appointed Andrew Ellicott to conduct the survey; Ellicott made Banneker his assistant for three months in 1791. Benjamin Rush authored the Department of Peace proposal; the confusion arose among earlier biographers because the proposal appeared in Banneker's 1793 almanac.}}</ref> The specified flaws included several Banneker stories that Silvio Bedini had refuted more than a decade before the Essays appeared.<ref name=Martel2/>\n\nIn 1998, the author of a book entitled ''A Country of Strangers: Blacks and Whites in America'' wrote in a section entitled \"Myths of America\" that the Essays had \"been attacked for gross inaccuracy in an entire literature of detailed criticism by respected historians\". The author noted that the science section of the Essays had embellished Banneker's accomplishments in several ways, one of which was the demonstrably false claim that Banneker's clock was America's first such instrument.<ref name=Shipler/> Nevertheless, ''Benjamin Banneker: Invented America's First Clock'' became the title of a 2008 [[web page]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205154950/http://www.black-inventor.com/Benjamin-Banneker.asp|archivedate=2009-02-05|url=http://www.black-inventor.com/Benjamin-Banneker.asp|title=Benjamin Banneker: Invented America's First Clock|publisher=Famous Black Inventors|year=2008|accessdate=2019-03-29}}</ref> In 2014, a revised edition of a 1994 book entitled ''African-American Firsts'' repeated a statement made in the initial edition that claimed that Banneker had \"designed and built the first clock in the colonies\".<ref>(1) {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/africanamericanf00pott|url-access=registration|title=Who Made the First Clock in the American Colonies and was the First African-American To Publish an Almanac?|work=African-American Firsts: Famous, Little-Known and Unsung Triumphs of Blacks in America|first1=Joan|last1=Potter|first2=Constance|last2=Claytor|location=[[Elizabethtown, New York]]|publisher=Pinto Press|year=1994|page=[https://archive.org/details/africanamericanf00pott/page/232 232]|oclc=654686287|lccn=93084716|isbn=0963247611|via=[[Internet Archive]]|quote=At the age of twenty-three, assisted only by a picture of a clock, an English journal, and a geometry book, he (Banneker) designed and built the first clock in the colonies.|access-date=December 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214061436/https://archive.org/details/africanamericanf00pott/page/232|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}<br/>(2) {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4pwhAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA334|title=Who Made the First Clock in the American Colonies and was the First African American To Publish an Almanac?|work=African American Firsts: Famous, Little-Known and Unsung Triumphs of Blacks in America|first=Joan|last=Potter|page=334|location=[[New York City|New York]]|publisher=Dafina Books, [[Kensington Books|Kensington Publishing Corporation]]|year=2014|accessdate=2018-12-14|oclc=864822516|lccn=2013388865|isbn=9780758292421|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=At the age of twenty-two, using a pocket watch as a guide, he (Banneker) designed and built the first clock in the colonies.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214055002/https://books.google.com/books?id=4pwhAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=December 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the author of an article entitled ''A Salute to African American Inventors'' that a [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], newspaper published wrote that in 1753, Banneker \"built one of the first watches made in America, a wooden pocket watch\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Alcorn, Jr.|first=George Edward|url=https://library.uafs.edu/sites/librarydev.uafs.edu/files/Departments/lincoln_echo/le_2009-03.pdf|title=A Salute to African American Inventors|work=The Lincoln Echo|volume=17|issue=1|page=7|date=March 2009|location=[[Fort Smith, Arkansas]]|publisher=Napoleon Black|accessdate=April 13, 2019|via=Boreham Library, [[University of Arkansas\u2013Fort Smith]]|quote=In 1753, he (Banneker) built one of the first watches made in America, a wooden pocket watch.}}</ref> The article did not provide a source for this statement. \n\nWhen supporting the establishment of the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture, a 2004 report to the [[President of the United States]] and the [[United States Congress]] stated that Banneker was an African American inventor.<ref name=Wright/> In 2015, columnists Al Kamen and Colby Itkowitz repeated that statement in a ''Washington Post'' article.<ref name=\"Banneker memorial\">{{cite news |last=Kamen|first=Al|last2=Itkowitz|first2=Colby |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/john-kerry-gets-dissed-on-scholars-list/2015/02/05/d38f8f00-ad7e-11e4-ad71-7b9eba0f87d6_story.html |title=No sights to see |work=John Kerry gets dissed on scholars' list |publisher=The Washington Post |date=2015-02-05 |accessdate=2017-11-05 |quote=A memorial for Banneker, an African American inventor, was approved in 1998, and a location was chosen at the L'Enfant Promenade in Southwest Washington, but its authorization expired in 2005.| |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105233635/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/john-kerry-gets-dissed-on-scholars-list/2015/02/05/d38f8f00-ad7e-11e4-ad71-7b9eba0f87d6_story.html |archivedate=2017-11-05 }}</ref> A 2017 National Park Service web page, which also claimed that Banneker was an inventor, stated that Banneker had \"constructed one of the first entirely wooden clocks in America.\"<ref name=NPS1/>\n\nHowever, while several 19th, 20th and 21st century biographers have written that Banneker constructed a clock, none cited documents that showed that Banneker had not seen or read about clocks before he constructed his own. None showed that Banneker's clock had any characteristics that earlier American clocks had lacked.<ref name=Phillips120>{{cite journal|last=Phillips|first=P. Lee|year=1917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSkkCeq5R1AC&pg=PA120#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Negro, Benjamin Banneker; Astronomer and Mathematician, Plea for Universal Peace (Read before the Society, April 18, 1916)|work=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=Columbia Historical Society, Washington, D.C.|volume=20|page=120|issn=0897-9049|oclc=1564221 |accessdate=2009-04-15|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref><ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/memoirbenjaminb00socigoog Latrobe, p. 7.]<br>(2) [https://archive.org/stream/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso#page/5/mode/1up Tyson, p. 5.]<br>(3) {{cite journal|last=Phillips|first=P. Lee|year=1917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSkkCeq5R1AC&pg=PA114#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Negro, Benjamin Banneker; Astronomer and Mathematician, Plea for Universal Peace (Read before the Society, April 18, 1916)|work=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=Columbia Historical Society, Washington, D.C.|volume=20|page=120|issn=0897-9049 |oclc=1564221 |accessdate=2009-04-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}<br>(4) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/42/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, pp. 42\u201444.]<br>(5) {{cite book |last=Hurry |first=Robert J. |editor=Hockey, Thomas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t-BF1CHkc50C&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Biographical Encyclopedia of Astronomers]] |title=Banneker, Benjamin |year=2007 |pages=91\u201392 |location=New York|publisher=[[Springer Publishing|Springer]]|isbn=9780387310220 |oclc=65764986 |accessdate=2015-01-24 |via=[[Google Books]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607141631/https://books.google.com/books?id=t-BF1CHkc50C&pg=PA91 |archivedate=2015-06-07}}<br>(5) [http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Benjamin_Banneker.aspx Bedini, 2008.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203192640/http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Benjamin_Banneker.aspx |date=2016-02-03}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972, Silvio Bedini reported that a number of watch and clockmakers were already established in Maryland before Banneker completed his clock in 1753. Prior to 1750, at least four such craftsmen were working in [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]], {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} from Banneker's home.<ref name=Annapolis>(1) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/44/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, pp. 44\u201446.] \"Timepieces were well known and available from the very earliest English settlements, .... A number of watch- and clockmakers were already established in Maryland prior to the time that Banneker made his clock. In [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] alone there were at least four such craftsmen prior to 1750.\"<br/>(2) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/43/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, pp. 43\u201444.]. \"Banneker's clock was by no means the first timepiece in tidewater Maryland, as occasionally has erroneously been claimed. Timepieces were well known and available from the very earliest English settlements, .... A number of watch- and clockmakers were already established in Maryland prior to the time that Banneker made his clock. In [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] alone there were at least four such craftsmen prior to 1750.\"</ref> The only accounts of Banneker's clock by people who had observed it reported only that it was made of wood, that it was suspended in a corner of his log cabin, that it had struck the hour and that Banneker had said that its only model was a borrowed watch.<ref>Tyson, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso#page/5/mode/1up 5], [https://archive.org/stream/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso#page/9/mode/1up 9]\u2014[https://archive.org/stream/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso#page/10/mode/1up 10], [https://archive.org/stream/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso#page/14/mode/1up 18].</ref>\n\nBedini stated that \"Banneker's clock continued to operate until his death\".<ref name=clock1>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/45/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 45.] \"Completed in 1753, Bannekers' clock continued to operate until his death, more than 50 years later.\"</ref> However, a later author more cautiously wrote that the clock \"was apparently used\" until a fire destroyed Banneker's home during his funeral.<ref name=Bailey>{{cite book|last=Bailey|first=Chris H.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q6kRAQAAMAAJ&dq=banneker+clock+death&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22it+was+destroyed%22|title=Two Hundred Years of American Clocks & Watches|page=73|location=[[Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[Prentice Hall|Prentice-Hall, Inc.]]|year=1975|oclc=756413530|isbn=0139351302|lccn=75013714|accessdate=2019-03-29|quote=Of his own design, the clock employed wooden gears and was apparently used until it was destroyed by the fire that consumed Banneker's home while his funeral was in progress in October, 1806|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> The first known report of the fire, published in 1854 from notes taken in 1836, stated that flames had consumed the clock, but provided no supporting documentation or any information as to whether the clock was still operational at the time.<ref name=Tyson18>[https://archive.org/stream/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso#page/18/mode/1up Tyson, p. 18.]</ref>\n[[File:Tall case clock, Benjamin Bagnall, Sr., Boston, Massachusetts, 1730-1745, walnut, maple, beech, cedar, brass, glass, paint - Dallas Museum of Art - DSC04743.jpg|thumb|right|150px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Dallas Museum of Art]]</sup></div>Tall-case striking clock constructed in Boston by Benjamin Bagnall, Sr., between 1730 and 1745<br />(2017)]]\nDocuments describing the history of clockmaking in America show that Banneker's clock was not the first of its kind made in America (see: [[History of timekeeping devices]]). Clockmakers came to the [[Thirteen Colonies|American colonies]] from England and Holland during the early 1600s. Among the earliest known clockmakers in the colonies were Thomas Nash of [[New Haven, Connecticut]] (1638),<ref name=Uselding/> William Davis of Boston (1683), Edvardus Bogardus of New York City (1698) and James Batterson of Boston (1707).<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=N. Hudson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HKMaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=American Clocks and Clockmakers|work=The Old Clock Book|year=1911|location=New York|publisher=Frederick A. Stokes Company|pages=91\u201392|oclc=680744401|lccn=11029009|accessdate=2019-02-23|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Connecticut]] clockmakers were crafting [[striking clock]]s throughout the 1600s, before Banneker was born.<ref name=Uselding>{{cite web |last=Uselding |first=Paul |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513081258/http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/clock.aspx |archivedate=2016-05-13 |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/clock.aspx |title=Clock and Watch Industry |work=Dictionary of American History |publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|The Gale Group Inc.]] |year=2003 |accessdate=2017-05-31 |quote=The first clockmaker of record in America was Thomas Nash, an early settler of New Haven in 1638. Throughout the seventeenth century, eight-day striking clocks with brass movements, similar to those made in England, were produced by craft methods in several towns and villages in Connecticut. .... By 1745 Benjamin Cheney of East Hartford was producing wooden clocks, and there is some evidence that these clocks were being made as early as 1715 near New Haven.|via=[http://www.encyclopedia.com/ Encyclopedia.com]}}</ref> The [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City holds in its collections a [[Grandfather clock|tall-case]] striking clock that Benjamin Bagnall, Sr., constructed in [[Boston]] before 1740 (when Banneker was 9 years old) and that [[Elisha Williams]] probably acquired between 1725 and 1739 while he was rector of [[Yale University|Yale College]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Frances Gruber|last=Safford|first2=Morrison H.|last2=Heckscher|first3=Mary-Alice |last3=Rogers|last4=Metropolitan Museum of Art|author4-link=Metropolitan Museum of Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kWIh7QgkBe8C&pg=PA290#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=290\u2013291|title=187. Tall Clock: Boston, 1725-1740: Movement by Benjamin Bagnall (1689-1773)|work=American furniture in the Metropolitan Museum of Art: 1, Late Colonial Period: The Queen Anne and Chippendale Styles|location=New York|publisher=The [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and [[Random House]]|year=1985|isbn=9780300116472|oclc=11971332|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=The movement is an eight-day rack and snail striking clock with anchor-recoil escapement.}}</ref> The [[Dallas Museum of Art]] holds in its collections a similar striking clock made entirely of American parts that Bagnall constructed in Boston between 1730 and 1745.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/dallasmuseumofart/docs/dallasmuseumofart_guidetothecollection/166|title= Benjamin Bagnall, Sr., Boston, Massachusetts, 1730-1745: Tall case clock|work=Guide To The Collection|date=2012-02-08|location=Dallas, Texas|publisher=[[Dallas Museum of Art]]|accessdate=2019-01-02|via=[[issuu]]|quote=This eight-day striking clock closely follows English design ...}}<br/>(2) {{citeweb|url=https://collections.dma.org/artwork/4084483|title=Tall Case Clock||work=Collections|location=Dallas, Texas|publisher=[[Dallas Museum of Art]]|accessdate=2019-01-02|quote=MAKER: Benjamin Bagnall Sr. (British, active in Boston, Massachusetts, America, 1689 - 1773): DATE: 1730\u20131745: MATERIAL AND TECHNIQUE: Walnut, maple, beech, cedar, brass, glass, and paint .... This tall case clock is among the very first of its type made entirely in America and one of only four existing examples by clockmaker Benjamin Bagnall. Rather than fit British works into a colonial cabinet, which was typical considering the cost and complexity of the mechanical components, Bagnall created the works himself with parts acquired from fellow Bostonians. He then installed them in an elegant walnut cabinet created by a local cabinetmaker.}} '''Note''': Slideshow contains enlargeable high-resolution images of the clock's parts, gears and striking mechanism.</ref>\n\nDuring the 1600s, when metal was harder to come by in the colonies than wood, works for many American clocks were made of wood, including the gears, which were whittled and fashioned by hand, as were all other parts.<ref>{{cite book|first=Franklin H.|last=Gottshall|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XVnCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101&#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Making Antique Furniture Reproductions: Instructions and Measured Drawings for 40 Classic Projects|year=1971|location=New York|publisher=[[Dover Publications]]|page=101|isbn=9780486161648|oclc=829166996|lccn=93048643|accessdate=2019-02-23|quote=Before the eighteenth century, when metal was harder to come by in the colonies than wood, which was in plentiful supply, works for many of these clocks were made of wood, including the gears, which were whittled and fashioned by hand, as indeed were all other parts.|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> There is some evidence that wooden clocks were being made as early as 1715 near [[New Haven, Connecticut]].<ref name=\"Uselding\" /><ref name=Bedini1964>[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst2311964unit#page/66/mode/2up Bedini, 1964: Instruments of Wood: The Use of Wood, pp. 66-69.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408055636/https://archive.org/details/bulletinunitedst2311964unit|date=2015-04-08 }} \"Wooden clocks were made as early as the 17th century in Germany and Holland, and they were known in England in the early 18th century. In the Colonies the wooden clock was first produced in Connecticut, and the earliest type was associated with Hartford County. ....\"</ref> Benjamin Cheney of [[East Hartford, Connecticut]], was producing wooden striking clocks by 1745,<ref name=\"Uselding\" /><ref name=Bedini1964/><ref name=Cheney3>(1) {{cite book |author=[[Federal Writers Project]] of the [[Works Progress Administration]] for the State of Connecticut |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OpxRPBjvrUcC&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |page=59 |title=Industry and Commerce |work=Connecticut: A Guide to Its Roads, Lore and People |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company |location=Boston |year=1938 |oclc=905140234 |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=Benjamin Cheney produced wooden clocks about 1745, in a small back-yard shop at East Hartford. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203192640/https://books.google.com/books?id=OpxRPBjvrUcC&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&f=false |archivedate=2016-02-03 }}<br />(2) {{cite web |last=Zea |first=Phillip M. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409193734/http://resources.osv.org/explore_learn/document_viewer.php?Action=View&DocID=882 |archivedate=2015-04-09 |url=http://resources.osv.org/explore_learn/document_viewer.php?Action=View&DocID=882 |title=Timekeeping: The Lifestyle of Accuracy--An Interpretive Essay for the J. Cheney Wells Collection of New England Clocks at Old Sturbridge Village |year=1986 |publisher=[[Old Sturbridge Village]] |location=[[Sturbridge, Massachusetts]] |accessdate=2015-04-09 |quote=In inland New England, the demand to know the time also increased, and clockmakers devised ways to lower the cost of expensive-looking clocks in order to make them available to more households. Following the lead of Seth Youngs in Hartford, Benjamin Cheney, Jr. (1725-1815) and his brother, Timothy (1731-1795), of East Hartford began offering their customers options in timekeeping. About 1750, they started making clocks, with striking trains, that were largely constructed of oak, cherry, and maple and ran for thirty hours.}}<br />(3) Images and description of face and wooden movement of striking clock constructed by Benjamin Cheney around 1760 on exhibit in 2015 in Clock Gallery of [[Old Sturbridge Village]]: <br />(a) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323045341/http://media.osv.org/FullSize.php?ID=17690|archivedate=2019-03-23|url=http://media.osv.org/FullSize.php?ID=17690|title=Image of face of clock|accessdate=2019-03-23}}<br />(b) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214130419/http://media.osv.org/FullSize.php?ID=17680|archivedate=2016-02-14|url=http://media.osv.org/FullSize.php?ID=17680|title=Image of gears and striking mechanism of clock|accessdate=2019-03-23}}<br>''In'' {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402065843/http://resources.osv.org/explore_learn/collection_viewer.php?N=57.1.117 |archivedate=2016-04-02|url=http://resources.osv.org/explore_learn/collection_viewer.php?N=57.1.117# |title=Collection No.57.1.117: Tall Case Clock by Benjamin Cheney, Hartford, Connecticut, c. 1760 |publisher=Old Sturbridge Village |location=Sturbridge, Massachusetts |accessdate=2015-04-10 |quote=Description: This movement for a tall case clock was made by Benjamin Cheney in Hartford, Connecticut. The wooden, weight-powered, thirty-hour movement with count wheel strike has a recoil escapement. The dial plate is a thin brass sheet with cast brass spandrels, silvered brass chapter ring, second's bit, calendar ring and name boss all attached to a pine board. \"Benjamin Cheney\" is engraved on the name boss. ... Materials: Works: chestnut plates, cherry wheels; maple arbors and pinions; brass. Case: Primary wood is walnut; secondary wood: white pine. |url-status=dead }}<br>(4) {{cite web |last=Zea |first=Philip |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409190558/http://www.chipstone.org/article.php/86/American-Furniture-1995/Diversity-and-Regionalism-in-Rural-New-England |archivedate=2015-04-09 |url=http://www.chipstone.org/article.php/86/American-Furniture-1995/Diversity-and-Regionalism-in-Rural-New-England |title=Diversity and Regionalism in Rural New England |publisher=Chipstone Foundation |accessdate=2015-04-09|quote=Benjamin Cheney, Jr. (1725\u20131815) and Timothy Cheney (1731\u20131795) began making clocks in East Hartford, Connecticut, about 1750. ... Perhaps because their father was a joiner, they developed the concept of offering options in clocks to expand their clientele: thirty-hour wooden movements as well as more expensive, eight-day, brass clocks. .... Two centuries later, these clocks are usually rejected by collectors on the basis of quality, although the ingenious wooden mechanism and the marketing concept behind it were among the more sophisticated ideas afoot in the marketplace of eighteenth-century New England.}}</ref> eight years before Banneker completed his own wooden striking clock in 1753. [[David Rittenhouse]] constructed a clock with wooden gears around 1749 while living on a farm near Philadelphia at the age of 17.<ref name=\"Rittenhouse clock\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://archives.profsurv.com/magazine/article.aspx?i=824|title=Feature: Construction Details of Rittenhouse Compasses|work=Professional Surveyor Magazine|date=December 2001|first=Jeffrey D.|last=Lock|accessdate=2019-02-22|issn=0278-1425|oclc=1043615987|lccn=82643590|location=[[Frederick, Maryland]]|publisher=Professional Surveyors Publishing Company|via=Flatdog Media, Inc.|quote=David Rittenhouse was born April 8, 1732 in Roxborough Township, [[Philadelphia County, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia County]]. Around the age of 17 he constructed a clock with wooden gears. His father, recognizing his son's potential, helped David build a collection of tools necessary for clock making. After construction was completed on a small workshop at the family's Norriton farm, David began making and selling clocks.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222155106/https://archives.profsurv.com/magazine/article.aspx?i=824|archive-date=February 22, 2019|url-status=dead}}<br>(2) {{cite book|last=Barton|first=William|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bRw6AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Memoirs of the Life of David Rittenhouse Anterior to His Settlement in Philadelphia|work=Memoirs of the Life of David Rittenhouse, LLD. F.R.S.: Late President of the American Philosophical Society, &c. Interspersed with Various Notices of Many Distinguished Men: with an Appendix, Containing Sundry Philosophical and Other Papers, Most of which Have Not Hitherto Been Published|page=97|location=Philadelphia|publisher=Edward Parker|year=1813|oclc=166059809|lccn=15004714|accessdate=2019-02-23|quote=It was at this period, or rather at about the seventeenth year of his age, that he made a wooden clock, of very ingenious workmanship:|via=[[Google Books]]}}<br>(3) {{cite journal|first=Fred C.|last=Sweinhart|url=https://hsmcpa.org/images/thebulletin/1941vol3no1.pdf|title=Early Pennsylvania Clocks and Their Makers|page=43|work=The Bulletin of the Historical Society of Montgomery County|volume=3|number=1|date=October 1941|publisher=Historical Society of [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]]|location=[[Norristown, Pennsylvania]]|oclc=1681070|lccn=sf77000139|issn=0362-8590|accessdate=2019-02-22|quote=David Rittenhouse was born in 1732 and died in 1796. .... He is said to have made his first clock at the age of 17 (1749). This was a wooden clock and the records show that he and his brother Benjamin made brass clocks in 1760.|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222154911/https://hsmcpa.org/images/thebulletin/1941vol3no1.pdf|archive-date=February 22, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Banneker's almanacs==\n[[File:Dr. Carter G. Woodson (1875-1950), Carter G. Woodson Home National Historic Site, 1915. (18f7565bf62142c0ad7fff83701ca5f6).jpg|thumb|right|125px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Carter Woodson (1915)</div>]]\nIn addition to incorrectly describing Banneker's clock, Lydia Maria Child's 1865 book stated that Banneker's almanac was the first ever made in America.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/freedmensbook01chil#page/n30/mode/1up Child, p. 17.] \"When he was fifty-nine years old, he made an Almanac. ... This was the first Almanac ever made in this country\".</ref> After also incorrectly describing the clock, Kelly Miller's 1902 publication similarly stated that Banneker's 1792 almanac for Pennsylvania, Virginia and Maryland was \"the first almanac constructed in America\".<ref name=KMiller/> Carter Woodson made a similar statement in his 1919 book, ''The Education of the Negro Pior to 1861.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=U6sQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q=Banneker&f=false Woodson, 1916, p. 91.] \"Despite his limited means, he (Banneker) secured through Goddard and Angell in Baltimore the first almanac published in this country.\"</ref> \n\nA National Register of Historic Places nomination form for the \u2033Benjamin Banneker: SW-9 Intermediate Boundary Stone (milestone) of the District of Columbia\" that an Afro-American Bicentennial Corporation historian prepared in 1976 states that Banneker's astronomical calculations \"led to his writing one of the first series of almanacs printed in the United States.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Graves |first=Lynne Gomez, Historical Projects Director, Afro-American Bicentennial Corporation, Washington, D.C |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001145447/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0015_%20Banneker_SW-9_Intermediate_Boundary_Stone_1976_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf |archivedate=2016-10-01|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-0015_%20Banneker_SW-9_Intermediate_Boundary_Stone_1976_Final_Nomination_NHL.pdf |title=Benjamin Banneker: SW-9 Intermediate Boundary Stone (milestone) of the District of Columbia: Statement of Significance |work=United States Department of the Interior: National Park Service: National Register of Historic Places Inventory\u2013\u2013Nomination Form |location=Richmond, Virginia |publisher=[[Virginia Department of Historic Resources]] |date=1976-02-03 |page=3 |accessdate=2016-10-07}}</ref> A National Park Service web page repeated that statement in 2017.<ref name=NPS1/>\n\n[[File:Poor Richard Almanack 1739.jpg|thumb|right|200px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Library of Congress]]</sup></div>Title page of 1739 edition of Benjamin Franklin's ''[[Poor Richard's Almanack]]'']]\nHowever, William Pierce's 1639 ''An Almanac Calculated for [[New England]]'', which was the first in an annual series of almanacs that [[Stephen Daye]], or Day, printed until 1649 in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], preceded Banneker's birth by nearly a century.<ref>(1) {{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Isiah |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oH0yAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA46&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Catalog of Books printed by Daye |work=The History of Printing in America: With A Biography of Printers: In Two Volumes: With the Author's Corrections and Additions, and a Catalog of American Publications Previous to the Revolution of 1776: Originally published Albany 1874 |location=New York |publisher=Burt Franklin |edition=2nd |volume=1 |pages=46\u201348|accessdate=March 23, 2020|via=[[Google Books]] |quote=1639. An Almanack, calculated for New England. By Mr. Pierce, Mariner}}<br>(2) {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/bookwormanillus03unkngoog|title=The First Almanac |work=The Bookworm: An Illustrated History of Old-Time Literature|location=London|publisher=Elliot Stock, 62, Paternoster Road|year=1888|page=[https://archive.org/details/bookwormanillus03unkngoog/page/n46 34] |accessdate=March 23, 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]|quote=It is a fact upon which most bibliographers agree, that the first almanac printed in America came out in 1639, and was entitled \"An Almanac Calculated for New England\" by Mr. Pierce, Mariner.  The printer was Stephen Day, or Daye, to whom belongs the title of the first printer in North America.  The press was at Cambridge, Mass., and its introduction was effected mainly through Rev. Jesse Glover, a wealthy Nonconformist minister, who had only recently left England.}}<br>(3) {{cite book|last=North|first=Simon Newton Dexter |url=https://archive.org/details/historyandprese00nortgoog|work=History and Present Condition of the Newspaper and Periodical Press, with a Catalogue of the Publications of the Census Year|title=Almanacs and Annual Publications|location=Washington|publisher=Government Printing Office|year=1884|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyandprese00nortgoog/page/n78 55]|accessdate=March 23, 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]|quote=In 1639 appeared in Cambridge  \"An Almanac Calculated for New England\", by Mr. William Pierce, Mariner }}<br>(4) [https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=false Morrison, p. 32.]</ref> [[Nathaniel Ames]] issued his popular ''Astronomical Diary and Almanack'' in [[Massachusetts]] in 1725 and annually after c.1732.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/biographies/85578603/nathaniel-ames|title=Ames, Nathaniel|date=February 2013|work=Columbia Electronic Encyclopedia, 6th ed.|page=1|via=[[EBSCO Information Services|EBSC Host Connection]]|accessdate=2018-05-28}}</ref> [[James Franklin (printer)|James Franklin]] published ''The [[Rhode Island]] Almanack'' by \"Poor Robin\" for each year from 1728 to 1735.<ref>(1) {{cite web|year=1727|author=Poor Robin (James Franklin)|url=https://archive.org/stream/rhodeislandalma00frangoog#page/n5/mode/2up|title=The Rhode-Island almanack. For the year, 1728. Being bissextile, or leap-year. Carefully fitted, and exact- [sic] calculated to the meridian of Newport on Rhode-Island; whose latitude north is 41 gr. 30 m. longitude from London 72 grs. But may without sensible error, serve all parts of New-England. Being the first ever published for that meridian.|oclc=70091122|accessdate=2018-05-28|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}<br>(2) {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fksTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Check List of Rhode Island Almanacs, 1643-1850|first=Howard M.|last=Chapin|pages=14\u201315|publisher=[[American Antiquarian Society]]|location=[[Worcester, Massachusetts]]|lccn=16002536|oclc=964275|accessdate=March 23, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n</ref> James' brother, Benjamin Franklin, published his annual ''[[Poor Richard's Almanack]]'' in Philadelphia from 1732 to 1758, more than thirty years before Banneker wrote his own first almanac in 1791.<ref>{{cite book |last=Goodrich |first=Charles A. |url=https://archive.org/details/livessignerstod02goodgoog |title=Benjamin Franklin |work=Lives of the Signers to the Declaration of Independence |page=[https://archive.org/details/livessignerstod02goodgoog/page/n280 267] |location=New York |publisher=W. Reed & Co. |year=1829 |oclc=2343155 |accessdate=2015-04-24 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Samuel Stearns]] issued the ''North-American Almanack'', published annually from 1771 to 1784, as well as the first American nautical almanac, ''The Navigator's Kalendar, or Nautical Almanack, for 1783''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalheritagemuseum.typepad.com/library_and_archives/jonas-h-brown/|title=New Acquisition: First Masonic Almanac Published in the United States|publisher=[[Scottish Rite Masonic Museum & Library]]|location=[[Lexington, Massachusetts]]|date=2012-07-24|accessdate=2018-12-30|quote=[[Samuel Stearns]] (1741-1809), the author whose name appears on the cover of The Free Mason's Calendar, was a physician and astronomer. In addition to the Free Mason's Calendar, he issued other almanacs, including the North-American Almanack, published annually from 1771-1784, as well as the first American nautical almanac, The Navigator's Kalendar, or Nautical Almanack, for 1783.}}</ref> A decade before printers published Banneker's first almanac, Andrew Ellicott began to author a series of almanacs, ''The United States Almanack'', the earliest known copy of which bears the date of 1782.<ref name=Davis2>(1) {{cite web|last=Davis|first=Nancy M.|url=http://www.lewisandclarkphila.org/philadelphia/philadelphiaellicott.html|title=Andrew Ellicott: Astronomer\u2026mathematician\u2026surveyor|work=Philadelphia Connection|publisher=Lewis and Clark Trail Heritage Foundation: Philadelphia Chapter|date=2001-08-26|accessdate=2018-09-28|quote=After the war, he (Ellicott) returned to Fountainvale, the family home in Ellicott Upper Mills, and published a series of almanacs, ''The United States Almanack''. (The earliest known copy is dated 1782.)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060109215305/http://www.lewisandclarkphila.org/philadelphia/philadelphiaellicott.html|archive-date=January 9, 2006|url-status=dead}}<br>(2) Bedini, 1999, pp. [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/97/mode/1up 97], [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/109/mode/1up 109], [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/210/mode/1up 210].</ref>\n\nIn 1907, the Library of Congress compiled a ''Preliminary Check List of American Almanacs: 1639-1800'', which identified a large number of almanacs that had been printed in the [[Thirteen Colonies|thirteen colonies]] and the United States prior to 1792.<ref name=Morrison>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Morrison]</ref> The printers had published many of these almanacs during more than one year. Eighteen had been printed in Maryland, including ''Ellicott's Maryland and Virginia Almanack'' for 1787 and 1789 and ''Ellicott's Maryland and Virginia almanac and ephemeris for 1791'', each of which John Hayes of Baltimore had printed.<ref name=Goddard>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false Morrison, pp. 30-31.]</ref> [[William Goddard (U.S. patriot/publisher)|William Goddard]] of Baltimore, who later printed Banneker's 1792 almanac, had printed ''The Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland and Virginia almanack and ephemeris'' for each year from 1784 to 1790, except 1786.<ref name=Goddard/>\n\n===Plan of a Peace-Office===\nA Philadelphia edition of Banneker's 1793 almanac contained an anonymous essay entitled \"A Plan of a ''Peace-Office'', for the United States\".<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/191/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 191.]<br>(2) [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=13 A Plan of a ''Peace-Office'', for the United States]. ''In'' [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=9 Banneker, 1792a], pp. 5, 7, 9.</ref> In 1916, Phillip Lee Phillips, who was the first Superintendent of Maps for the [[Library of Congress]],<ref>Phillip Lee Phillips (1857-1924) was the first Superintendent of Maps for the [[Library of Congress]], where he devoted over thirty years to the development of the Library's map and atlas collection. See:<br>(1) {{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/phillipsbrochure.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909202635/http://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/phillipsbrochure.pdf |archivedate=2013-09-09 |title=Philip Lee Phillips Society Programs and Activities |publisher=Library of Congress Geography and Map Division|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=2015-04-06}}<br/> (2) {{cite web |url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/pdf/plp/brochure.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406182429/http://www.loc.gov/rr/geogmap/pdf/plp/brochure.pdf|archivedate=2015-04-06|title=Philip Lee Phillips Map Society: The Friends Group of the Geography and Map Division: Library of Congress |publisher=Library of Congress Geography and Map Division |location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=2015-04-06}}<br>(3) {{cite journal |last=Seavey |first=Charles A. |title=Philip Lee Phillips and the growth of the library of Congress map collection, 1897\u20131924 |journal=Government Publications Review|volume=20|number=3|pages=283\u2013295 |year=1993|doi=10.1016/0277-9390(93)90004-9|issn=0277-9390|oclc=4656134177|publisher=[[Elsevier]]}}</ref> wrote a paper about the almanac that was presented to the [[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]] in Washington, D.C. Phillips' paper, which stated that the almanac contained Banneker's plea for peace, also contained a complete copy of the essay.<ref name=Phillips>{{cite journal|last=Phillips|first=P. Lee|year=1917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSkkCeq5R1AC&pg=PA114#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Negro, Benjamin Banneker; Astronomer and Mathematician, Plea for Universal Peace (Read before the Society, April 18, 1916)|work=Records of the Columbia Historical Society|publisher=Columbia Historical Society, Washington, D.C.|volume=20|pages=114\u2013120|issn=0897-9049|lccn=18019397|oclc=1564221|accessdate=2009-04-15|quote=The almanac ... in which Banneker's plea for peace is found ... .|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\nA report of the presentation that the ''[[The Washington Star|Washington Star]]'' published soon afterwards stated that, in the course of the paper, \"it was brought out that Banneker, who was a free Negro, friend of Washington and Jefferson, published a series of almanacs, unique in that they were his own work throughout.\"<ref>''[[The Washington Star]]'s'' report of the presentation of P. Lee Phillip's April 18, 1916, paper to the Columbia Historical Society. In: {{cite journal|editor-first=Carter G.|editor-last=Woodson|editor-link=Carter G. Woodson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9n4TAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA345&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Notes|journal=The Journal of Negro History|volume=1|number=3|page=345|date=July 1916|issn=0022-2992|oclc=1034304517|jstor=3035631|location=[[Lancaster, Pennsylvania]] and Washington, D.C.|publisher=The Association for the Study of Negro Life and History, Inc.|accessdate=April 11, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=In the course of the paper, entitled \"The Negro, Benjamin Banneker, Astronomer and Mathematician\", it was brought out that Banneker, who was a free Negro, friend of Washington and Jefferson, published a series of almanacs, unique in that they were his own work throughout. In the almanac for 1793 one of the articles from Banneker's pen was \"A Plan for a Peace Office of the United States,\" for promoting and preserving perpetual peace. This article was concise and well written, and contains most of the ideas set forth today by advocates of peace.}}. Note: Phillips' April 18, 1916, paper does not contain the statements in ''The Washington Star's'' report, but states only that Banneker's plea for peace is found in the almanac.</ref> A number of books, journals, newspapers and student teaching aids then credited Banneker with the authorship of the peace plan during the more than 100 years that passed after Phillips' paper and the ''Star's'' report were published.<ref name=\"Woodson 1933\">{{cite book|first=Carter Goodwin|last=Woodson|author-link=Carter G. Woodson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PdMlnIqEKXUC&pg=PA100#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Chapter 14: The New Program|work=The Mis-education of the Negro|year=2009|location=[[Mineola, New York]]|page=100|publisher=[[Dover Publications]] Originally published by Associated Publishers, Washington, D.C., 1933.|isbn=9780486130927|lccn=2005045548|oclc=861276529|accessdate=April 14, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=We would not neglect the unusual contribution of Thomas Jefferson to freedom and democracy; but we would invite attention also to two of his outstanding contemporaries, Phillis Wheatley, the writer of interesting verse, and Benjamin Banneker, the mathematician, astronomer, and advocate of a world peace plan set forth in 1793 with the vital principles of Woodrow Wilson's League of Nations.}}</ref><ref>(1) {{cite journal|editor-first=Charles S.|editor-last=Johnson|editor-link=Charles S. Johnson|date=July 1927|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CMsZAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA192&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Editorial: A Word of Praise for the Elders|work=Opportunity: A Journal of Negro Life|volume=5|number=7|page=192|location=New York|publisher=[[National Urban League]]|accessdate=April 15, 2020|quote=There is, for example, the venerable Benjamin Banneker, who in 1793 proposed a peace plan which could easily enough be accepted as the seed of the present League of Nations.|oclc=6535020|via=[[Google Books]]}}<br>(2) {{cite book|last=Mays|first=Benjamin E. (July 19, 2010)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3bxMAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA107#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Chapter III: Ideas of God in \"Classical\" Literature: 1760-1860|work=The Negro's God As Reflected In His Literature|page=107|location=[[Eugene, Oregon]]|publisher=[[Wipf and Stock]]. Previously published by Chapman & Grimes, Boston, 1938.|isbn=1608997774|lccn=38037550|oclc=663881207|accessdate=April 13, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=Benjamin Banneker, astronomer and mathematician, was born in Baltimore County, Maryland, November 9, 1731. ... One of the earliest plans for peace comes from him. .... Concerning his peace plan, Banneker argues that only God \"has the power to take away the life of a human being\". .... (Reference:) Phillips, Phillip Lee, The Negro, Benjamin Banneker, The Negro, Benjamin Banneker, (Astronomer and Mathematician), Plea for Universal Peace, p. 17, Reprint from the Recorder of the Columbia Historical Society, Vol. 20, 1917)}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Padover|date=February 2, 1948|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/61298/benjamin-banneker-unschooled-wizard|title=Benjamin Banneker: Unschooled Wizard|work=[[The New Republic]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020\n|quote=His (Banneker's) \"A Plan of Peace-office for the United States\" is one of the most interesting, if naive, proposals on record.}}<br>(4) {{cite web|last=Stanford|first=Karin L.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=irw_Lv26eVEC&pg=PA24&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Benjamin Banneker (1731-1806): Letter to the Secretary of State: A Plan of Peace Office For The United States: August 19, 1791|work=If We Must Die: African American Voices on War and Peace: Chapter One: Revolutionary War - My Liberation, Your Freedom: 1775-1783|lccn=2007046310|oclc=182552860|isbn=0742541134|pages=24-26|year=2008|location=[[Lanham, Maryland]]|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|accessdate=April 10, 2020|quote=He (Banneker) wrote this peace plan appealing to two significant principles: the federal government's respnsibility to service its citizens, and most importantly the idea that the country should adhere to the prinicles of Christianity and equal treatment of all men.|via=[[Google Books]]}}<br>(5) {{cite web|first=Dr. Melvin|last=Banks|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021033907/https://urbanfaith.com/2013/10/benjamin-banneker-was-a-peacemaker.html/|archivedate=October 21, 2013|url=https://urbanfaith.com/2013/10/benjamin-banneker-was-a-peacemaker.html/|title=Benjamin Banneker Was A Pacemaker|date=October 17, 2013|work=Urban Faith|quote=Many people know Benjamin Banneker helped to layout Washington, D.C. But this African American, born in 1731, also put out an annual almanac. In it, he promoted peace. He urged the president to adopt this four-point peace plan: Appoint a Secretary of Peace; Set up free schools in every city; Give every family a Bible; Print this Bible verse on every door, \u201cThe Son of Man came into the world not to destroy men\u2019s lives, but to save them.\u201d}}<br>(6) {{cite web|url=https://www.nthurston.k12.wa.us/cms/lib/WA01001371/Centricity/Domain/401/Banneker%20STUDENT%20DOCUMENTS.pdf|title=A Plan for a Department of Peace for the United States \u2013 1792 by Benjamin Banneker|location=[[Lacey, Washington]]|publisher=North Thurston Public Schools|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}<br>(7) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115182710/http://bbamath.org/index.php/benjamin-banneker/|archivedate=November 15, 2017|url=http://bbamath.org/index.php/benjamin-banneker/|title=Views on Racial Discrimination and Slavery|work=Benjamin Banneker|publisher=The Benjamin Banneker Association, Inc. (bbamath.org)|quote=In 1793 he (Banneker) proposed a peace plan for America which included many points including a suggestion that there should be a \u2018Secretary of Peace\u2019.}}<br>(8) {{cite web|url=http://www.bannekermemorial.org/history.htm|title=A Man of Many Firsts|work=His Story|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Washington Interdependence Council|year=2017|quote=Banneker, in his debut almanac of 1792, was the first to recommend the establishment of a U.S. Department of Peace.}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920223551/http://www.bannekermemorial.org/history.htm|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Benjamin Rush Painting by Peale 1783.jpg|thumb|right|150px|\n<sup><div style=\"text-align: center;\">[[Winterthur Museum, Garden and Library|Winterthur Museum]],<br />[[Winterthur, Delaware]]</div></sup>1783 portrait of Dr. Benjamin Rush by [[Charles Willson Peale]]]]\nHowever, in 1798, a Philadelphia printer had earlier published a collection of essays that [[Benjamin Rush|Dr. Benjamim Rush]], a signer of the 1776 [[Declaration of Independence]], had written.<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/DKC0021/mode/1up Rush, 1798, cover page]<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.ushistory.org/declaration/signers/rush.html|title=Benjamin Rush: 1745-1813: Representing Pennsylvania at the Continental Congress|work=Signers of the Declaration of Independence|publisher=ushistory.org|accessdate=2018-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207213452/http://www.ushistory.org/declaration/signers/rush.html|archivedate=2018-02-07}}</ref> Rush's preface to the publication, dated January 9, 1798, stated that most of the essays had been published soon after the end of the [[American Revolutionary War]] (1775\u20131783).<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DKC0021/page/n2/mode/1up Rush, 1798, Preface]</ref> One of the essays, entitled ''A plan of a Peace-Office for the United States'' was similar, but not identical, to the essay  with the same name in Banneker's 1793 almanac.<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/DKC0021/page/n188/mode/1up Rush, 1799, pp. 183\u2013188]<br>(2) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/187/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 187.] \"For some unexplained reason, it (the plan in Banneker's 1793 almanac) was published without identifying the author. Rush included the \"Plan\" in a collection of essays published five years later, with substantial additions to the text.\"</ref> Several historians have therefore attributed to Dr. Rush the authorship of the almanac's peace plan. \n\n[[Henry Cadbury]], a historian serving as a professor of divinity at Harvard University from 1934 to 1954,<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=DeSantis|year=2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515184458/http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Cadbury__Henry_Joel.html|archivedate=May 15, 2013|url=http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Cadbury__Henry_Joel.html|title=Cadbury, Henry Joel|location=[[University Park, Pennsylvania]]|publisher=[[Pennsylvania State University Libraries|The Pennsylvania State University Libraries]]: Pennsylvania Center for the Book|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> discovered within Rush's papers a copy of the peace plan that bore a date that was earlier than the publication of Banneker's 1793 almanac.<ref name=Wesley>{{cite web|first=Charles H.|last=Wesley|editor-first=James L.|editor-last=Conyers, Jr.|year=1997|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bjWCBHygpQ0C&pg=PA99#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Biographical Studies: Carter G. Woodson \u2014 As a Scholar|work=Charles H. Wesley: The Intellectual Tradition of a Black Historian|page=99|isbn=0815327544|lccn=96037837|oclc=36029629|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|accessdate=April 14, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/361/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 361, reference 5.]</ref> In 1946, [[Dagobert D. Runes]] published a collection of Rush's papers that contained the 1798 peace plan, but which Runes dated as 1799.<ref name=Wesley/><ref>(1) Partial copy of book ([[E-book]]): {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQf4CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT29#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A Plan of a Peace Office for the United States (1799)|editor-last=Runes|editor-first=Dagobert D.|editor-link=Dagobert D. Runes|work=The Selected Writings of Benjamin Rush|pages=29\u201333|oclc=928885110|isbn=9781504013062|publisher=[[Open Road Integrated Media]]|date=2015-05-26|via=[[Google Books]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190613054713/https://books.google.com/books?id=KQf4CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT29#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=2019-06-13|accessdate=2019-06-13}}<br>(2) Full text of book: {{cite web|editor-last=Runes|editor-first=Dagobert D.|editor-link=Dagobert D. Runes|url=https://archive.org/stream/selectedwritings030242mbp/selectedwritings030242mbp_djvu.txt|title=A Plan of a Peace Office for the United States (1799)|work=Full text of \"The Selected Writings Of Benjamin Rush\"|pages=19-23|accessdate=April 6, 2020|location=New York|publisher=[[Philosophical Library]]|year=1947|via=[[Internet Archives]]}}</ref> \n\nAfter Runes' collection was published, Carter Woodson, who had in his 1933 book, ''The Mis-education of the Negro'', credited Banneker with being the author of the peace plan,<ref name=\"Woodson 1933\"/> noted that the copy of the plan in Banneker's almanac contained Rush's initials (\"BR\"). Woodson concluded that Phillips had been misled because the initials were not clear. Woodson further concluded that Banneker could not be regarded as the author of the plan.<ref name=Wesley/><ref>Note: Available electronic copies of the almanac show beneath the last page of the plan the letter \"B\", but do not show any other letters. See: [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119&view=1up&seq=17 Whiteman, Maxwell (ed.), p. 13.] and {{cite web|url=https://transcription.si.edu/view/8045/NMAAHC-2014_63_31_009|title=Benjamin Banneker's 1793 Almanack and Ephemeris|page=9|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]: Smithsonian Digital Volunteers: Transcription Center|accessdate=April 15, 2020}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415164631/https://transcription.si.edu/view/8045/NMAAHC-2014_63_31_009|date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Shirley Graham's 1949 book, ''Your Humble Servant'', presented a contrasting view. Graham noted that the editors of Banneker's almanac had placed the peace plan in their work. Stating that Runes' collection contained the first printing of Dr. Rush's peace plan, Graham wrote that Rush had revised the almanac's plan because it was \"too fanciful\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Graham|first=Shirley|author-link=Shirley Graham Du Bois|year=1949|url=https://archive.org/details/yourmosthumblese00dubo/page/191/mode/1up|title=Chapter XII: A Plan For Peace|work=Your Most Humble Servant|pages=191-194|location=New York|publisher=Julian Messner, Inc.|via=[[Internet Archive]] Digital Library|lccn=49011346|oclc=1036934508|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:WEB Du Bois 1946.jpg|thumb|right|125px|<sup><center>Library of Congress</center></sup><center>W.E.B. DuBois (1946)</center>]]\n\nIn a typed draft of an unpublished article that he wrote around 1950, historian and civil rights activist [[W.E.B. Dubois]] concurred with Graham, whom he later married. His article stated that Graham's book indicated the facts and that \"Banneker first published the plan and without much doubt was its author\". The article concluded that \"The credit of this remarkable suggestion should go to Benjamin Banneker\".<ref>{{cite web|first=W. E. B.|last=Du Bois|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415215153/https://credo.library.umass.edu/view/full/mums312-b214-i015|archivedate=April 15, 2020|url=https://credo.library.umass.edu/view/full/mums312-b214-i015|title=Banneker's peace plan, ca. 1950|work=W. E. B. Du Bois Papers (MS 312)|location=[[Amherst, Massachusetts]]|publisher=[[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]: Special Collections and University Archives|accessdate=April 15, 2020}} Note: Typed draft of unpublished article discussing Benjamin Banneker's plan for peace.</ref>  \n\nIn 1969, Maxwell Whiteman authored a book that contained a reproduction of the almanac. Whiteman wrote in the book's introduction that the librarian of the [[Library Company of Philadelphia]], from whose institution the copy had been made, had stated that Dr. Rush had authored the peace plan that the almanac contained.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=7 Whiteman, Maxwell (1969). BENJAMIN BANNEKER: Surveyor and Astronomer: 1731-1806: A biographical note] ''In'' [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112037299119;view=1up;seq=5 Whiteman, Maxwell (ed.)] \"The plan for a \"Peace Office\" in the Government of the United States, which also appeared in this issue (Banneker's 1793 Philadelphia almanac) has been attributed to Banneker. According to Edwin Wolf 2nd, Librarian of the [[Library Company of Philadelphia]] from whose institution these copies have been made, the \"Peace Office\" is the work of Dr. [[Benjamin Rush]].\"</ref> \n\nIn 1972, Silvio Bedini wrote in a biography of Banneker that Runes' 1947 collection of Rush's writings had \"identified beyond question\" that Rush had authored the almanac's peace plan.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/186/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 186.] \"Another important item included in the 1793 almanac was \"A Plan of a Peace Office for the United States\", which aroused considerable comment at the time. Many believed it to have been Banneker's own work. Even recently its authorship has been debated, but in 1947 it was identified beyond question as the work of Dr. [[Benjamin Rush]] in a volume of his own writings that appeared in that year.\"</ref> Bedini stated that Graham's book was written for children, was highly fictionalized and, having become popular, has \"resulted in yet more confusion concerning Banneker's achievements and their importance\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/300/mode/1up/search/Graham Bedini, 1972, p. 300.]</ref>\n\n==Astronomical works==\nIn 2019, a [[Harvard University]] [[website]] describing a program that the \"Banneker Institute\" conducted at the school each summer claimed about Banneker: \"As a forefather to Black American contributions to science, his eminence has earned him the distinction of being the first professional astronomer in America.\"<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331030208/https://bannekerinstitute.fas.harvard.edu/about|archivedate=2019-03-31 |url=http://bannekerinstitute.fas.harvard.edu/about|title=Why Banneker?|work=About Banneker Banneker Institute: Banneker Institute: [[Harvard University]]|year=2019|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|publisher=[[President and Fellows of Harvard College|The President and Fellows of Harvard College]]|accessdate=2019-03-31 |quote=The program and its name are a nod to Benjamin Banneker, a surveyor best known for accompanying Andrew Ellicott in his original land survey of what would become Washington, D.C. Banneker was also an accomplished astronomer, which drove the success of his series of almanacs. As a forefather to Black American contributions to science, his eminence has earned him the distinction of being the first professional astronomer in America.}}</ref> The website, which noted that the program \"prepares undergraduate students of color for graduate programs in astronomy by emphasizing research, building community, and encouraging debate and political action through social justice education\",<ref name=Institute>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120062215/https://bannekerinstitute.fas.harvard.edu/|archivedate=2019-01-20|url=https://bannekerinstitute.fas.harvard.edu|title=Banneker Institute|work=[[Harvard University]]|year=2019|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|publisher=[[President and Fellows of Harvard College|The President and Fellows of Harvard College]]|accessdate=2019-03-31|quote=The Banneker Institute summer program is a full-time, ten-week research and study experience. We prepare undergraduate students of color for graduate programs in astronomy by emphasizing research, building community, and encouraging debate and political action through social justice education.}}</ref> did not cite the source of this questionable information.\n\nBanneker prepared his first published almanac in 1791, during the same year that he participated in the federal district boundary survey.<ref name=\"1792 Almanac\"/><ref>{{cite book |last=Allaben |first=Frank |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2vEQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA67 |title=Original Document: Banneker's Appeal to Jefferson for Emancipation |work=The National Magazine: A Journal Devoted To American History: Vol. XVII, November, 1892 \u2014 April, 1893 |page=67 |location=New York |publisher=The National History Company |accessdate=2017-02-18 |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=...., but that having taken up my pen in order to direct to you as a present a copy of my Almanac which I have calculated for the Succeeding year, ..... and altho I had almost declined to make my calculation for the ensuing year, in consequence of that time which I had allotted therefor being taking up at the Federal Territory by the request of Mr. Andrew Ellicott, yet finding my Self underal several engagements to printers of this State to whom I have communicated my design, on my return to my place of residence, I industrially applied my Self thereto, .... |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304051032/https://books.google.com/books?id=2vEQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q&f=falsel |archivedate=2017-03-04 }}</ref> As a 1942 journal article entitled ''Early American Astronomy'' has reported, American almanacs published as early as 1687 predicted eclipses and other astronomical events. In contrast to the statement in the Banneker Institute's posting, that article and others that have reported the works of 17th and 18th century American astronomers either do not mention Banneker's name or describe his works as occurring after those of other Americans.<ref name=Rumrill/><ref>(1) {{cite web |url=http://www.nyskies.org/articles/pazmino/18-centy.htm |title=Outline of 18th Century Astronomy |first=John |last=Pazmino |date=2008-06-15 |publisher=NYSkies Astronomy Inc. |accessdate=2017-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121050122/http://www.nyskies.org/articles/pazmino/18-centy.htm |archivedate=2008-11-21 }} <br />(2) {{cite web|title=Astronomers and Stargazers: Eyeing a Heliocentric Heaven for Planets, Portents, and Horoscopes|first=Anthony F.|last=Aveni|url=https://www.history.org/Foundation/journal/Winter05-06/telescopes.cfm|date=Winter 2006|work=Colonial Williamsburg Journal|location=[[Williamsburg, Virginia]]|publisher=[[Colonial Williamsburg]] Foundation|accessdate=2017-02-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220092843/http://www.history.org/Foundation/journal/Winter05-06/telescopes.cfm|archivedate=2006-02-20}}</ref>\n[[File:JohnWinthropAstronomer.jpg|thumb|left|150px|<sup><div style=\"text-align: center;\">[[Harvard University]]</div></sup>Circa 1773 portrait of John Winthrop by [[John Singleton Copley]]]]\n[[File:Charles Willson Peale - David Rittenhouse - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|right|150px|<sup><div style=\"text-align: center;\">[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]]</div></sup>1796 portrait of David Rittenhouse by [[Charles Willson Peale]]]]\nColonial Americans [[John Winthrop (educator)|John Winthrop]] (a [[Harvard College]] professor) and David Rittenhouse authored publications that described their telescopic observations of the 1761 and 1769 [[Transit of Venus|transits of Venus]] soon after those events occurred.<ref name=Rumrill>{{cite journal |url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?bibcode=1942PA.....50..408R&db_key=AST&page_ind=0&data_type=GIF&type=SCREEN_VIEW&classic=YES |last=Rumrill |first=H.B. |title=Early American Astronomy |journal=Popular Astronomy |volume=50 |pages=408\u2013419 |date=October 1942 |accessdate=2017-02-18|via=The [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]]/[[NASA|National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] [[Astrophysics Data System]] hosted by the High Energy Astrophysics Division at the [[Harvard\u2013Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics]]}}</ref><ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.apsmuseum.org/tov-event/|title=Sic Transit Glorious: A Transit of Venus Celebration: June 1 \u2013 10, 2012|work=APS museum|year=2012|publisher=[[American Philosophical Society]]|accessdate=2017-03-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424165112/http://www.apsmuseum.org/tov-event/|archivedate=2012-04-24}}<br />(2) {{cite journal|last=Winthrop|first=John|author-link=John Winthrop (educator)|title=Observation of the Transit of Venus, June 6, 1761, at St John's, Newfound-Land|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society|year=1764|volume=54|pages=279\u2013283|doi=10.1098/rstl.1764.0048|doi-access=free}}</ref> Other Americans, some of whom taught at Harvard, also wrote about astronomy and used telescopes when observing celestial bodies and events before 1790 (see also: [[Colonial American Astronomy]]).<ref name=Rumrill/>\n\nA book relating the history of American astronomy stated, that as a result of the [[American Revolution]], \"... what astronomical activity there was from 1776 through 1830 was sporadic and inconsequential\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CWy0pUAquCEC&pg=PA56#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Astronomy and Astrophysics |work=The History of Science in the United States: An Encyclopedia |editor=Rothenberg, Marc ([[Smithsonian Institution]]) |publisher=Garland Publishing, Inc.|location=New York|year=2001|pages=56\u201357|isbn=9780203902806|oclc=682090024|lccn=2003040978|accessdate=2017-02-19|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=This level of (astronomical) activity could not be sustained after the Revolutionary War. A people engaged in war and nation-building were unable to provide its astronomical community with sufficient community resources to be competitive with Europe. .... Individuals interested in astronomy could earn a living as surveyors, through the publications of almanacs or teaching, but not through research.  As a result, what astronomical activity there was during the years of 1776 through 1830 was sporadic and inconsequential.}}</ref> Another such book has stated that \"the dawn of American professional astronomy\" began in the middle of the 19th century.<ref name=Sherrod>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4zjv84hHNPcC&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q&f=false |last=Sherrod |first=P. Clay |last2=Koed |first2=Thomas L. |title=A Complete Manual of Amateur Astronomy: Tools and Techniques for Astronomical Observations|page=2|isbn=9780486152165 |oclc=904451880|lccn=81002441|publisher=[[Prentice Hall|Prentice-Hall]]|location=[[Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey]] |year=1981|accessdate=2017-02-20|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=The dawn of American professional astronomy began midway in the nineteenth century, when the Naval Observatory at Washington, D.C., was established in 1844. In 1847 the giant refractor of Harvard College was put to use by the father of American astronomy, William Cranch Bond, a clockmaker from Boston.  Interestingly, Bond was self-trained in his knowledge of astronomy and was an amateur in the strictest sense until taking the Harvard appointment.}}</ref> In 1839, the [[President and Fellows of Harvard College|Harvard Corporation]] voted to appoint clockmaker [[William Cranch Bond]], whom some consider to be the \"father of American astronomy\", as \"Astronomical Observer to the University\".<ref name=Sherrod/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806024644/https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/hco/grref.html|archivedate=2018-08-06|url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/hco/grref.html|title=HCO: The Great Refractor|work=[[Harvard College Observatory]]|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|publisher=[[Harvard\u2013Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics]]|accessdate=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Seventeen-year cicada==\n[[File:17 Year Cicada - Brood X.jpg|thumb|right|200px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Brood X periodical cicada<br /> (June 2004)</div>]]\nIn 2004, during a year in which [[Brood X]] of the seventeen-year [[Periodical cicadas|periodical cicada]] (''[[Magicicada septendecim]]'' or seventeen-year locust) emerged from the ground in large numbers, columnist Courtland Milloy wrote in ''The Washington Post'' an article entitled ''Time to Create Some Buzz for Banneker''.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last=Milloy |first=Courtland |url=http://www.bannekermemorial.org/news/buzzforbanneker.htm |title=Time to Create Some Buzz for Banneker |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2004-04-21 |page=B01 |location=Washington, D.C.}} Republished by [http://www.bannekermemorial.org/index.html Washington Interdependence Council: Administrators of the Benjamin Banneker Memorial and Banneker Institute of Math & Science] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224034923/http://www.bannekermemorial.org/index.html |date=2013-02-24 }}. Retrieved 2012-10-02.</ref> Milloy claimed that Banneker \"is believed to have been the first person to document this noisy recurrence\" of the insect. Milloy stated that Banneker had recorded in a journal \"published around 1800\" that the \"locusts\" had appeared in 1749, 1766 and 1783.\n\nMilloy further noted that Banneker had predicted that the insects would return in 1800.<ref>Note: Milloy gave Bedini, 1999, as his source of information. [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/264/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 264], quotes the following sentence in a journal that Banneker wrote around 1795 describing the cicadas' periodic appearances: \"''So that if I may venture, So as to express it, their periodic return is Seventeen years.''\" Banneker therefore believed that he was the first to report this periodicity.  Bedini did not express any such belief. Further, Bedini, 1999, does not state that Banneker's handwritten report was printed or published before Banneker died in 1806.</ref> In 2014, the authors of an [[Electronic publishing|online publication]] that reproduced Banneker's handwritten journal report cited Milloy's article and contended that \"Banneker was one of the first naturalists to record scientific information and observations of the seventeen-year cicada\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Barber |first=Janet E. |last2=Nkwanta |first2=Asamoah |url=http://scholarship.claremont.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1070&context=jhm |title=Benjamin Banneker's Original Handwritten Document: Observations and Study of the Cicada |journal=Journal of Humanistic Mathematics |volume=4 |number=1 |page=119 |year=2014 |doi=10.5642/jhummath.201401.07 |accessdate=2015-01-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827123841/http://scholarship.claremont.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1070&context=jhm |archivedate=2014-08-27 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nHowever, earlier published accounts of the periodical cicada's life cycle describe the history of cicada sightings differently. These accounts cite descriptions of fifteen- to seventeen-year recurrences of enormous numbers of noisy emergent cicadas that people had written as early as 1733,<ref name=Marlatt>{{cite book |last=Marlatt |first=C.L |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hc8aAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&f=false |work=The Periodical Cicada: An Account of Cicada Septendecim, Its Natural Enemies and the Means of Preventing its Injury, Together With A Summary of the Distribution of the Different Broods (Bulletin No. 14 - New Series, U.S. Department of Agriculture, Division of Entomology) |title=The Periodical Cicada in Literature |pages=112\u2013118 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]] |year=1898 |oclc=10684275 |accessdate=2016-05-21 |via=[[Google Books]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222053955/https://books.google.com/books?id=hc8aAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |archivedate=2016-12-22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Dudley |first=Paul |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9X4663giukC&pg=PA49&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Periodical Revolutions |year=1733 |work=Additional Manuscripts 4433, Folios 4-11, Division of Manuscripts of the British Library, London |accessdate=2017-05-21 |via=[[Google Books]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216212500/https://books.google.com/books?id=C9X4663giukC&pg=PA49&f=false |archivedate=2017-02-16 }} Cited on page 49 ''of'' {{cite book |last=Kritsky |first=Gene |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9X4663giukC&pg=PA43&f=false#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=America's Curious Botanist: A Tercentennial Reappraisal of John Bartram 1699-1777 |title=John Bartram and the Periodical Cicadas: A Case Study |editors=Hoffmann, Nancy E. and Van Horne, John C |publisher=The American Philosophical Society |location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |year=2004 |pages=43\u201351 |accessdate=2017-05-21 |via=[[Google Books]] |quote=Moreover, the first time the Society had heard about periodical cicadas was from Paul Dudley, who sent a manuscript to the Society in 1733. .... Dudley correctly noted the seventeen-year life cycle and provided evidence. However, Collinson's paper shows that he used Bartram's claim of a fifteen-year cycle in his paper. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216230002/https://books.google.com/books?id=C9X4663giukC&pg=PA43&f=false |archivedate=2017-02-16 }}</ref> when Banneker was two years old.\n\n[[Pehr Kalm]], a [[Sweden|Swedish]] naturalist visiting [[Pennsylvania]] and [[New Jersey]] in 1749 on behalf of his nation's government, observed in late May the first of the three Brood X emergences that Banneker's journal later documented.<ref name=Marlatt/><ref name=Davis>{{cite journal |last=Davis |first=J.J. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103031952/https://kb.osu.edu/bitstream/handle/1811/4028/V53N03_138.pdf;jsessionid=95D493BC5FD5B919ABC2F5CCF1154087?sequence=1%2520|archivedate=2018-11-03 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/1811/4028/V53N03_138.pdf;jsessionid=95D493BC5FD5B919ABC2F5CCF1154087?sequence=1 |title=Pehr Kalm's Description of the Periodical Cicada, Magicicada septendecim L., from Kongl. Svenska Vetenskap Academiens Handlinger, 17:101-116, 1756, translated by Larson, Esther Louise (Mrs. K.E. Doak) |journal=The Ohio Journal of Science |volume=53 |date=May 1953 |pages=139\u2013140 |url-status=dead }} Republished by [https://kb.osu.edu/dspace/ Knowledge Bank: The Ohio State University Libraries and Office of the Chief Information Officer]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003092134/http://kb.osu.edu/dspace/ |date=2015-10-03 }}. Retrieved 2012-10-02.</ref> When reporting the event in a paper that a Swedish academic journal published in 1756, Kalm wrote: <blockquote>The general opinion is that these insects appear in these fantastic numbers in every seventeenth year. Meanwhile, except for an occasional one which may appear in the summer, they remain underground.<br />There is considerable evidence that these insects appear every seventeenth year in Pennsylvania.<ref name=Davis/></blockquote>\n \nKalm then described documents (including one that he had obtained from Benjamin Franklin) that had recorded in Pennsylvania the emergence from the ground of large numbers of cicadas during May 1715 and May 1732. He noted that the people who had prepared these documents had made no such reports in other years.<ref name=Davis /> Kalm further noted that others had informed him that they had seen cicadas only occasionally before the insects appeared in large swarms during 1749.<ref name=Davis /> He additionally stated that he had not heard any cicadas in Pennsylvania and New Jersey in 1750 in the same months and areas in which he had heard many in 1749.<ref name=Davis /> The 1715 and 1732 reports, when coupled with his own 1749 and 1750 observations, supported the previous \"general opinion\" that he had cited.\n\nKalm summarized his findings in a paper translated into English in 1771,<ref>{{cite book |last=Kalm |first=Peter |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qG0FAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA212#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Travels into North America: Translated into English, By John Reinhold Foster |year=1771 |volume=2 |pages=212\u2013213 |location=London |publisher=T. Lowndess |accessdate=2017-05-21 |via=[[Google Books]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111165302/https://books.google.com/books?id=qG0FAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA212 |archivedate=2017-01-11 }}</ref> stating:<blockquote>There are a kind of ''Locusts'' which about every seventeen years come hither in incredible numbers .... In the interval between the years when they are so numerous, they are only seen or heard single in the woods.<ref name=Marlatt/><ref>{{cite book |last=Kalm |first=Peter |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qG0FAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Travels into North America: Translated into English, By John Reinhold Foster |year=1771 |volume=2 |pages=6\u20137 |location=London |publisher=T. Lowndess |accessdate=2017-05-21 |via=[[Google Books]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412223022/https://books.google.com/books?id=qG0FAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA6 |archivedate=2016-04-12 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1758, [[Carl Linnaeus]] gave to the insect that Kalm had described the [[Latin]] name of ''Cicada [[wiktionary:septendecim|septendecim]]'' (seventeen-year cicada) in the [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|tenth edition of his ''Systema Naturae'']].<ref>{{cite book |last=Linnaei |first=Caroli |authorlink=Carl Linnaeus |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/10277#page/458/mode/1up |work=Systema Naturae Per Regna Tria Naturae, Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, Cum Characteribus, Differentiis, Synonymis, Locis |title=Insecta. Hemiptera. Cicada. Mannifera. septendecim. |year=1758 |edition=10 |volume=1 |pages=436\u2013437 |location=[[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]] |publisher=Laurentii Salvii |accessdate=2017-05-24 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library|Biodiversity Heritage Library (BHL)]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325030419/http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/10277 |archivedate=2017-03-25 }}</ref> Banneker's second observation of a Brood X emergence occurred eight years later. A writer documented that emergence in a 1766 journal article entitled ''Observations on the cicada, or locust of America, which appears periodically once in 16 or 17 years''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bartram |first=Moses |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k5lGAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA2-PA103&lpg=RA2-PA103#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Observations on the cicada, or locust of America, which appears periodically once in 16 or 17 years. Communicated by the ingenious Peter Collinson, Esq. |work=The Annual Register, or a View of the History, Politicks, and Literature, for the Year 1767 |location=London |publisher=Printed for J. Dodsley (1768) |pages=103\u2013106 |year=1766 |oclc=642534652 |accessdate=2017-05-21 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>\n\n==Other legends and embellishments==\nIn her 1865 work, ''The Freedmen's Book'', Lydia Maria Child stated that Thomas Jefferson had in 1803 invited Banneker to visit him in [[Monticello]], a claim that Carter Woodson repeated in his 1919 book,''The Education of the Negro Prior to 1861''.<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/stream/freedmensbook01chil#page/n33/mode/1up/ Child, p. 21.] \"In 1803, Mr. Jefferson invited him (Banneker) to visit him in Monticello, ...\".<br>(2) [https://books.google.com/books?id=U6sQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q=Banneker&f=false Woodson, 1919, p. 91] \"It appear's that Jefferson had some doubt about the man's genius, but the fact that the philosopher invited Banneker to visit him at Monticello in 1803, indicates that the increasing reputation of the Negro must have changed his opinion as to the extent of Banneker's attainments and the value of his contributions to mathematics and science.\"</ref> Silvio Bedini later reported that Child had not substantiated this claim.<ref> [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/392/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 392.] \"... the author (Lydia Maria Child) makes the unsubstantiated claim that in 1803 Jefferson invited Banneker to visit him in Monticello, and there are some errors in dates picked up from the scorces stated.\"</ref> \n\nBedini noted that a writer had repeated this statement in 1876 within a [[Scotland|Scottish]] book entitled ''Amongst the Darkies'' <ref>(1) {{cite book|last=MacRae|first=David|title=Amongst the Darkies|year=1876|location=[[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]|publisher=John S.  Marr & Sons|pages=28-30|lccn=84239293|oclc=11848328}}<br>(2) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/393/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, pp. 393\u2014394.] \"Based on other published sources, the account (MacRae, \"Amongst the Darkies\") perpetuates erroneous dates and such apocryphal claims as that in 1803 Banneker was invited to visit Jefferson in Monticello.\"</ref> and that another writer had in 1916 not only repeated the claim but had also stated that Jefferson invited Banneker to dine with him at the Executive Mansion (the [[White House]]).<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/397/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 397.] \"One writer, W. A. L., stated that Jefferson invited Banneker to dine with him at the Executive Mansion and that he had also invited Banneker to Montecello.\"</ref> Bedini further noted that these legends contain dates that are inconsistent with those that are known<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/126/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 126.] \"Equally untrue are legends that Thomas Jefferson as Secretary of State invited Banneker to luncheon at the White House. Jefferson during this period was in Philadelphia, the national capital had not yet been built, and there was no White House.</ref> and that no evidence of any such invitations has been found.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/397/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 397.] \"No evidence of such invitations has been found.\"</ref>\n\nIn 1930, writer Lloyd Morris claimed in an academic journal article entitled ''The Negro \"Renaissance\"'' that \"Benjamin Banneker attracted the attention of a President.... President Thomas Jefferson sent a copy of one of Banneker's almanacs to his friend, the French philosopher Condorcet....\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Morris |first=Lloyd |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K6TFfEvDJREC&pg=PA238#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=February 1930 |title=The Negro 'Renaissance |journal=Southern Workman |volume=59 |pages=82\u201386 |publisher=Press of the Hampton Normal and Agricultural Institute |location=Hampton, Virginia}}  ''Reprinted in'' {{cite book |first=Henry Louis |last=Gates, Jr. |first2=Gene Andrew |last2=Garrett |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K6TFfEvDJREC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The New Negro: Readings on Race, Representation, and African American Culture, 1892\u20131938 |location=Princeton, New Jersey |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2007 |pages=238\u2013239 |isbn=978-0-691-12652-4 |oclc=608490813 |lccn=2006052876 |accessdate=2017-05-23 |via=[[Google Books]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224201512/https://books.google.com/books?id=K6TFfEvDJREC&printsec=frontcover |archivedate=2016-12-24}}</ref> However, Thomas Jefferson sent Banneker's almanac to the [[Marquis de Condorcet]] in 1791, a decade before he became President in 1801.<ref name=\"Jefferson biography\">{{cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/about/presidents/thomasjefferson|title=Biography of Thomas Jefferson|publisher=[[White House|The White House]]|location=Washington, D.C.|date=April 9, 2011|accessdate=August 23, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110409073342/http://www.whitehouse.gov/|archive-date=April 9, 2011|url-status=dead}}.</ref><ref name=\"Jefferson letter1\">{{cite web |last=Jefferson |first=Thomas |url=http://memory.loc.gov/mss/mcc/028/0001.jpg |title=Letter from Thomas Jefferson to Mr. Benjamin Banneker |date=August 30, 1791 |work=Image of letter in \"American Memory\"|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=April 3, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203192640/http://memory.loc.gov/mss/mcc/028/0001.jpg |archivedate=February 3, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:ben banneker.jpg|thumb|270px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[National Archives at College Park]]</sup></div>Benjamin Banneker cartoon by [[Charles Alston]], 1943, claiming that Banneker had been a \"city planner\", \"was placed on the commission which surveyed and laid out the city of Washington, D.C.\", and had \"constructed the first clock made in America\".]]\n[[File:Archives of American Art - Charles Alston - 2465 CROPPED.jpg|thumb|left|150px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><sup>[[Archives of American Art]]</sup><br />Charles Alston (1939)</div>]]\nIn 1943, an African American artist, [[Charles Alston]], who was at the time an employee of the [[United States Office of War Information]], designed a [[cartoon]] that embellished the statements that Henry E. Baker had made in 1918.<ref name=\"Baker\"/> Like Baker, Alston incorrectly claimed that Banneker \"was placed on the commission which surveyed and laid out the city of Washington, D.C.\" Alston extended this claim by also stating that Banneker had been a \"[[urban planning|city planner]]\". Alston's cartoon additionally repeated a claim that Lydia Maria Child had made in 1865<ref name=Child/> by stating that Banneker had \"constructed the first clock made in America\".<ref>1943 Cartoon by Charles Alston: \"BENJAMIN BANNEKER \u2013 ASTRONOMER-CITY PLANNER\".  Image available at the [https://www.archives.gov/research/arc/index.html Archival Research Catalog (ARC) of the National Archives and Records Administration] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801174121/http://www.archives.gov/research/arc/index.html |date=2009-08-01 }} under the ARC Identifier 535626. Retrieved 2009-02-03.</ref>\n[[File:Stevie Wonder 1973.JPG|thumb|left|150px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Stevie Wonder (1973)</div>]]\nIn 1976, the singer-songwriter [[Stevie Wonder]] celebrated Banneker's mythical feats in his song \"[[Black Man (Stevie Wonder song)|Black Man]]\", from the album ''[[Songs in the Key of Life]]''. The lyrics of the song state:\n\n<blockquote>\nWho was the man who helped design the nation's capitol,<br />Made the first clock to give time in America and wrote the first almanac?<br />Benjamin Banneker, a black man<ref>{{cite web |last=Wonder |first=Stevie |last2=Byrd |first2=Gary |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625061704/http://www.metrolyrics.com/black-man-lyrics-stevie-wonder.html |archivedate=2013-06-25 |url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/black-man-lyrics-stevie-wonder.html |title=Black Man Lyrics |publisher=[[MetroLyrics]] |accessdate=2016-03-28}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider --></ref></blockquote>\n\nThe question's answer is incorrect. Banneker did not help design either the [[United States Capitol]] or the nation's capital city and did not write America's first almanac.<ref name=Arnebeck/> The first known clockmaker of record in America was Thomas Nash, an early settler of New Haven, Connecticut, in 1638.<ref name=Uselding/>\n[[File:Autora N Perpinya.tif|thumb|right|150px|N\u00faria Perpiny\u00e0 (2001)]]\n\nIn 1998, a [[Catalonia|Catalan]] writer, [[N\u00faria Perpiny\u00e0]], created a fictional character, Aleph Banneker, in her novel ''Un bon error'' (''A Good Mistake''). The writer's website reported that the character, an \"eminent scientist\", was meant to recall Benjamin Banneker, an eighteenth-century \"black astronomer and [[Urban planner|urbanist]]\".<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=N\u00faria|last=Perpiny\u00e0|author-link=N\u00faria Perpiny\u00e0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GLhjAAAACAAJ|title=Un bon error|work=Narrativa (Emp\u00faries), 77|location=[[Barcelona]]|publisher=Editorial Emp\u00faries|year=1998|language=Catalan|isbn=8475965733|lccn=98158475|oclc=807597706|accessdate=2017-11-17|via=[[Google Books]]}}<br>(2) {{cite web|first=N\u00faria|last=Perpiny\u00e0|author-link=N\u00faria Perpiny\u00e0|url=http://nuriaperpinya.com/?page_id=172&lang=en|title=A Good Mistake|publisher=N\u00faria Perpiny\u00e0|via=Dise\u00f1o web Freelance - FreelandStudio S.L.|year=2014|accessdate=2016-07-31|quote=For example, Aleph Banneker is not a poor black but an eminent scientist.  .... The references to scientists and thinkers, starting with the black astronomer and urbanist from the eighteenth century, Benjamin Banneker, are real.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030061427/http://nuriaperpinya.com/work/a-good-mistake/?lang=en|archivedate=2014-10-30}}</ref> However, none of Banneker's documented activities or writings suggest that he was an \"urbanist\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini 1969]</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the [[National Capital Memorial Advisory Commission|National Capital Memorial Commission]] concluded that the relationship between Banneker and L'Enfant was such that L'Enfant Promenade was the most logical place in Washington, DC on which to construct a proposed memorial to Banneker.<ref name=\"Environmental Assessment\">{{cite book|url=https://comp.ddot.dc.gov/Documents/L%27Enfant%20Promenade%20and%20Benjamin%20Banneker%20Park%20Environmental%20Assessment.pdf|title=Benjamin Banneker Memorial|work=Environmental Assessment for Improvements to L'Enfant Promenade and Benjamin Banneker Park|date=March 2006|publisher=[[District Department of Transportation]], Government of the District of Columbia (DC.gov) and Eastern Federal Lands Highway Division, [[Federal Highway Administration]], [[United States Department of Transportation]]|pages=1\u20136, 1\u20137|accessdate=2017-11-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116232714/https://comp.ddot.dc.gov/Documents/L%27Enfant%20Promenade%20and%20Benjamin%20Banneker%20Park%20Environmental%20Assessment.pdf|archivedate=2017-11-16}}</ref> However, Silvio Bedini was not able find any historical evidence that showed that Banneker had any relationship at all to L'Enfant or to L'Enfant's plan for the city, although he wrote that the two men had \"undoubtedly\" met each other after L'Enfant arrived in [[Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)|Georgetown]] in March 1791 to begin his work.<ref name=\"Bedini p132\">[https://archive.org/details/banneker00char/page/132/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 132.] \"An exhaustive search of government repositories, including the Public Buildings and Ground files in the National Archives, and varied collections in the Library of Congress, failed to turn up Banneker's name on any contemporary documents or records relating to the selection, planning or survey of the City of Washington. Nor was he mentioned in any of the surviving correspondence and papers of Andrew Ellicott and of Pierre Charles L'Enfant.\"</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130322112050/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf Bedini, 1969], p. 24.\"Some of the confusion may have been the result of the assignment of Benjamin Ellicott, Major Andrew Ellicott's younger brother and an assistant surveyor, to assist L'Enfant in preparing a sketch of the city in the summer of 1791. Banneker undoubtedly met L'Enfant during the course of his stay on the project, however.\"</ref> A 2016 National Park Service (NPS) publication later stated that the NPS had renamed an overlook at the southern end of the Promenade to commemorate Banneker even though the area had no specific connection to Banneker himself.<ref name=NPS2016>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncpc.gov/files/projects/2016/7551_Environmental_Assessment_Apr2016.pdf |title=Benjamin Banneker Park |work=Environmental Assessment: Benjamin Banneker Park Connection |date=March 2016 |page=29 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[National Park Service]]: [[National Mall and Memorial Parks]] |accessdate=2017-04-28 |quote=The Tenth Street Overlook was renamed Benjamin Banneker Park in 1971 by the NPS, though the area has no specific connection to Banneker himself, ...}}</ref>\n\nA [[history painting]] by Peter Waddell entitled ''A Vision Unfolds'' debuted in 2005 within an exhibition on [[Freemasonry]] that the [[The Octagon House|Octagon House]]'s museum in Washington, D.C., was hosting. The oil painting was again displayed in 2007, 2009, 2010 and 2011, first in the [[Joslyn Art Museum]] in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] and later in the [[Scottish Rite Masonic Museum & Library|National Heritage Museum]] in [[Lexington, Massachusetts]] and in the Scottish Rite Center of the District of Columbia in Washington, D.C.<ref name=Waddell>(1) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050731022650/http://www.peterwaddell.com/initiated.html |archivedate=2005-07-31 |url=http://peterwaddell.com/initiated.html |4= |title=A Vision Unfolds |work=Exhibitions: The Initiated Eye: Secrets, Symbols, Freemasonry and the Architecture of Washington, DC |publisher=Peter Waddell.com |accessdate=2016-10-22 |quote=A Vision Unfolds: 36\" x 48\", oil on canvas }}<br>(2) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109065208/http://www.peterwaddell.com/biography.html |archivedate=2012-01-09 |url=http://www.peterwaddell.com/biography.html |title=Biography |work=Peter Waddell |publisher=Peter Waddell.com |accessdate=2016-10-22 |quote=Exhibitions: .... 2005: The Initiated Eye: Secrets, Symbols, Freemasonry and the Architecture of Washington DC. The Octagon Museum, Washington, DC. }}<br>(3) {{cite web |url=http://204.3.136.66/web/journal-files/Issues/jul-aug05/cijul-aug.htm |title=Masonic Art Exhibit Opens at the Octagon |work=The Scottish Rite Journal of Freemasonry: Southern Jurisdiction, U.S.A.: Current Interest: July\u2013August 2005 |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=2016-10-23 |quote=Tuesday, May 17, was the grand opening of the Octagon Museum's phenomenal exhibit, \"The Initiated Eye: Secrets, Symbols, Freemasonry, and the Architecture of Washington, D.C.\" Twenty-one paintings by Peter Waddell showcased the little-recognized contribution of Freemasons to the design and architecture of our nation's capital. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024023746/http://204.3.136.66/web/journal-files/Issues/jul-aug05/cijul-aug.htm |archivedate=October 24, 2016 }}<br>(4) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071005060728/http://www.artmagick.com/exhibitions/exhibition.aspx?id=786 |archivedate=2007-10-05 |url=http://www.artmagick.com/exhibitions/exhibition.aspx?id=786 |title=The Initiated Eye: Secrets, Symbols, Freemasonry and the Architecture of Washington, DC |publisher=ArtMagick |year=2007 |accessdate=2016-12-02 |quote=The Initiated Eye: Secrets, Symbols, Freemasonry and the Architecture of Washington, DC, with Paintings by Peter Waddell, features 21 paintings by Waddell, a contemporary history painter, illustrates the Masonic connection to the building of early-19th century Washington. Exhibition Locations and Dates: USA, Nebraska, Omaha, Joslyn Art Museum: April 28, 2007 - June 10, 2007 }}<br>(5) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226233914/http://nationalheritagemuseum.typepad.com/library_and_archives/benjamin-banneker/ |archivedate=2010-02-26 |url=http://nationalheritagemuseum.typepad.com/library_and_archives/benjamin-banneker/ |title=Benjamin Banneker |work=The Initiated Eye: Freemasonry and the Architecture of Washington, D.C. (exhibition) |location=[[Lexington, Massachusetts]] |publisher=[[Scottish Rite Masonic Museum & Library|National Heritage Museum]] |date=2009-12-17 |accessdate=2016-10-22 |quote=The Initiated Eye\" presents 21 oil paintings by Peter Waddell based on the architecture of Washington, D.C., and the role that our founding fathers and prominent citizens \u2013 many of whom were Freemasons \u2013 played in establishing the layout and design of the city. .... The painting shown here depicts a meeting between President George Washington (1732-1799) and surveyors Andrew Ellicott (1754-1820) and Benjamin Banneker (1731-1806).  Congress designated the location of the new capital on January 24, 1791.  Elliott and Banneker surveyed the ten-mile-square tract of land and produced a base map of the area. .... The Initiated Eye\" opens December 19, 2009 and will be on view through January 9, 2011. }}<br>(6) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023133646/http://www.dcgrandlodge.org/masonic-art.html |archivedate=2016-10-23 |url=http://www.dcgrandlodge.org/masonic-art.html |title=A Vision Unfolds |work=The Initiated Eye: Panel 1 |publisher=The Grand Lodge of Free And Accepted Masons of the District of Columbia |location=Washington, D.C. |year=2013 |accessdate=2016-12-02 |quote=A Vision Unfolds - Congress designated the location of the new Capitol on January 24, 1791. It was a ten-mile square parcel of land along the Potomac and Eastern Branch Rivers. Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker surveyed the tract of land and produced the base map. Banneker, a self taught African American surveyor and astronomer, plotted the locations of the forty boundary stones one mile apart along the entire perimeter. }} '''Note: Panel 1 contains a high-resolution image of ''A Vision Unfolds''.'''<br />(7) {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023185503/http://www.dcgrandlodge.org/news/a-scottish-rite-salute-to-the-grand-lodge-of-dc |archivedate=2016-10-23 |url=http://www.dcgrandlodge.org/news/a-scottish-rite-salute-to-the-grand-lodge-of-dc |title=Grand Lodge History & The Initiated Eye Painting Exhibit |date=2011-10-26 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=The Grand Lodge of Free and Accepted Masons of the District of Columbia |accessdate=2016-10-23 |quote=Illustrious Leonard Proden, 33\u02da, S.G.I.G. of the Supreme Council in D.C and Past Grand Master of Masons in D.C is pleased to announce that the Valley of Washington, Orient of the District of Columbia, will celebrate the 200th Anniversary of the founding of the Grand Lodge of Free and Accepted Masons of the District of Columbia on Tuesday, November 15, 2011.  All brethren, their family, and friends are invited to participate in this festive evening which will include:  .... A special viewing of \"The Initiated Eye\", the heralded collection of D.C. Masonic-themed paintings, on exhibition in Washington, D.C. again for the first time in over five years.  The artist, Peter Waddell, will be on hand to present his latest addition to the collection, a celebratory painting commemorating the Bicentennial of the Grand Lodge of D.C. }}</ref> Waddell's painting contains elements present in [[Edward Savage (artist)|Edward Savage]]'s 1789-1796 painting ''[[The Washington Family]]'', which portrays President George Washington and his wife [[Martha Washington|Martha]] viewing a plan of the City of Washington.<ref>{{cite web |last=Savage |first=Edward|author-link=Edward Savage (artist) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914070401/http://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/Collection/art-object-page.561.html |archivedate=2016-09-14 |url=http://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/Collection/art-object-page.561.html |title=''The Washington Family'' 1789-1796 |work=Collection |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[National Gallery of Art]] |accessdate=2016-10-24 |quote=Edward Savage's ''The Washington Family'' quickly became a veritable icon of our early national pride. In the winter of 1789\u20131790, President Washington and his wife posed for Savage in New York City, then the nation's capital. ... With a map before her, Martha Washington is \"pointing with her fan to the grand avenue,\" now known as Pennsylvania Avenue.}}</ref>\n\n''A Vision Unfolds'' depicts a meeting that is taking place within an elaborate surveying tent. In the imaginary scene, Banneker presents a map of the federal district (the Territory of Columbia) to President Washington and Andrew Ellicott.<ref name=Waddell/><ref name=\"Ellicott 1793\">{{cite web |last=Ellicott|first=Andrew|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/88694130/ |title=Territory of Columbia |work=Maps|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|year=1793|accessdate=2016-10-22|quote=Notes: ...  Accompanied by positive and negative photocopies of 3 letters dated 1793 relating to the map, 1 of which signed by: And'w Ellicott.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011082202/https://www.loc.gov/item/88694130/ |archivedate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Andrew Ellicott completed his survey of the federal district's boundaries in 1792.<ref name=Bedini22/><ref name=planning/> On January 1, 1793, Ellicott submitted to the three commissioners \"a report of his first map of the four lines of experiment, showing a half mile on each side, including the district of territory, with a survey of the different waters within the territory\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false Stewart, p. 57]</ref> The Library of Congress has attributed to 1793 the year of Ellicott's earliest map of the Territory of Columbia that the Library holds within its collections.<ref name=\"Ellicott 1793\"/> As Banneker left the federal capital area in 1791,<ref name=Founders/><ref name=\"Bedini, 1972, p. 136\">[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/136/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 136.] \"Although the exact date of Banneker's departure from the survey is not specified in Ellicott's report of expenditures, it occurred some time late in the month of April 1791, following the arrival of one of Ellicott's brothers. It was not until some ten months after Banneker's departure from the scene that L'Enfant was dismissed, by means of a letter from Jefferson dated February 27, 1792. This conclusively dispels any basis for the legend that after L'Enfant's dismissal and his refusal to make available his plan of the city, Banneker recollected the plan in detail from which Ellicott was able to reconstruct it. Equally untrue and in fact impossible is the legend that Thomas Jefferson as secretary of state invited Jefferson to luncheon at the White House. Jefferson during this period was in Philadelphia, the national capital had not yet been built, and there was no White House.</ref><ref name=\"Bedini, 1969, pp. 28-29\"/> Banneker could not have had any association with the map that Waddell depicted.\n\nFurther, writers have pointed out that there is no evidence that Banneker had anything to do with the final establishment of the federal district's boundaries.<ref name=Founders/> Additionally, a researcher has been unable to find any documentation that shows that President Washington and Banneker ever met.<ref name=Cerami135/>\n\nA 2017 article on the [[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian Magazine]]'s website entitled ''Three Things to Know About Benjamin Banneker\u2019s Pioneering Career'' stated that the first two of these three things were \"He built America\u2019s first home-grown clock\u2013out of wood\" and \"He produced one of the United States\u2019 first almanacs.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Kat|last=Eschner|date=November 9, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235422/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/three-things-know-about-astronomer-benjamin-bannekers-pioneering-career-180967136/|archivedate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/three-things-know-about-astronomer-benjamin-bannekers-pioneering-career-180967136/|title=Three Things to Know About Benjamin Banneker\u2019s Pioneering Career|work=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian Magazine]]: SmartNews|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> However, a wooden clock that David Rittenhouse constructed around 1749<ref name=\"Rittenhouse clock\"/> was among those made at home in the thirteen American colonies before Banneker built his own around 1753.<ref name=clock1/> A report that the Library of Congress published in 1907 identified many almanacs that printers had distributed in the thirteen colonies and the United States between William Pierce's 1639 Cambridge, Massachusetts, publication and Banneker's first (Baltimore, Maryland, 1792).<ref>Morrison, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q&f=false 31], [https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=false 32.]</ref>\n\nIn 2018, an NPS web page stated that \"Banneker became one of the first black civil servants of the new nation\" when \"he surveyed the city of Washington\".<ref name=NPS1/> However, Bedini had reported more than 40 years earlier that it was Andrew Ellicott (not the federal government) who hired Banneker to participate in the survey of the federal district.<ref name=Bedini22/> Ellicott paid Banneker $60 for his participation, including travel expenses.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/133/mode/2up Bedini, 1999, pp. 133\u2014134.]</ref>\n\nA 2019 article on the [[White House Historical Association]]'s website entitled ''Benjamin Banneker: The Black Tobacco Farmer Who The Presidents Couldn't Ignore'' stated that President Washington was aware of Banneker\u2019s participation in the federal city's boundary survey. However, the article neither cited a source for this claim nor referenced a contemporary document that supported the statement.<ref>{{cite web|first=Louis|last=Keene|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831054904/https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|archivedate=August 31, 2019|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/benjamin-banneker|title=Benjamin Banneker: The Black Tobacco Farmer Who The Presidents Couldn't Ignore|publisher=[[White House Historical Association|The White House Historical Association]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020|quote=Letters from Ellicott show that in February 1791, he set out with Banneker and several field laborers for Jones Point, Virginia, to plot the boundary lines of the nascent Federal City. .... President Washington and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson \u2013 whose 1785 book ''Notes on the State of Virginia'' stated that people of African descent were intellectually inferior to whites \u2013 were aware of Banneker\u2019s participation.}}</ref> \n\nThe article's reference list cited a 2002 book whose author had claimed that \"President Washington must have been thunderstruck by finding an African-American on the (survey) team\"<ref>[https://archive.org/details/banneker00char/page/129/mode/1up/ Cerami, 2002, p. 129.]</ref> and that \"there is evidence\" that a newspaper reporter \"asked the President about Banneker on one of his visits to the survey site\".<ref>[https://archive.org/details/banneker00char/page/136/mode/1up/ Cerami, 2002, p. 136.]</ref> However, a reviewer of that book stated that such statements lacked direct documentation and ended the review by stating that the author's \"documentation is sloppy\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120905204059/http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=7440 Corrigan, p. 3.]</ref> \n\n===Commemorative U.S. quarter dollar coin nomination===\n[[File:Adrian Fenty, Mayor of DC, November 5, 2007.jpg|thumb|right|125px|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Adrian M. Fenty (2007)</div>]]\nIn 2008, the [[Government of the District of Columbia#Government|District of Columbia government]] considered selecting an image of Banneker for the [[obverse and reverse|reverse side]] of the District of Columbia [[Quarter (United States coin)|quarter]] in the 2009 [[District of Columbia and United States Territories quarters|District of Columbia and United States Territories quarters program]].<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.coinnews.net/2008/06/04/washington-dc-quarter-designs-ready-public-asked-to-vote-for-favorite-4147/|title=Washington DC Quarter Design Images Released, Public Asked to Vote for Favorite|date=2008-06-04|accessdate=2018-01-15|publisher=CoinNews.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115230136/http://www.coinnews.net/2008/06/04/washington-dc-quarter-designs-ready-public-asked-to-vote-for-favorite-4147/|archivedate=2018-01-15}} <br />(2) {{cite web|url=https://www.usmint.gov/coins/coin-medal-programs/dc-and-us-territories/district-of-columbia|title=District of Columbia Quarter|work=Coin and Medal Programs: D.C. and U.S. Territories Quarters|publisher=[[United States Mint]]|date=2016-06-01|accessdate=2018-01-15}}</ref> The original narrative supporting this selection<ref name=\"dc1\">{{cite news|title=Benjamin Banneker: Abolitionist, Mathematician, Scientist, Inventor|work=District of Columbia Quarter Dollar Coin Design Narratives: Office of the [[Secretary of the District of Columbia]]: Letter from Adrian M. Fenty, Mayor of the District of Columbia to Edmund C. Moy, Director, United States Mint: News Release: \"DC Submits Quarter Dollar Designs to the US Mint\"|publisher=Newsroom, [[Government of the District of Columbia]]|date=2008-02-25|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303002222/http://newsroom.dc.gov/show.aspx?agency%3Dos%26section%3D2%26release%3D12831%26year%3D2008%26file%3Dfile.aspx%2Frelease%2F12831%2FDC%2520Quarter%2520Submission.pdf|archivedate=2008-03-03|format=PDF|url=http://newsroom.dc.gov/show.aspx?agency%3Dos%26section%3D2%26release%3D12831%26year%3D2008%26file%3Dfile.aspx/release/12831/DC%2520Quarter%2520Submission.pdf|accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref> (subsequently revised)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.dc.gov:80/show.aspx?agency=os&section=2&release=12831&year=2008&file=file.aspx%2Frelease%2F12831%2FFinal%2520Narratives%2520Only.pdf|title=Benjamin Banneker: Abolitionist, Mathematician, Astronomer|work=District of Columbia Quarter Dollar Coin Design Final Narratives|page=2|publisher=Office of the [[Secretary of the District of Columbia]]: Newsroom, [[Government of the District of Columbia]]|date=2008-03-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512021947/http://newsroom.dc.gov/show.aspx?agency=os&section=2&release=12831&year=2008&file=file.aspx%2Frelease%2F12831%2FFinal%2520Narratives%2520Only.pdf|archivedate=2008-05-12}}</ref> alleged that Banneker was an inventor, \"was hired as part of an official six-man team to help survey and design the new capital city of the fledgling nation, making Benjamin Banneker among the first-ever African-American presidential appointees\" and that Banneker was \"a founder of Washington D.C.\" When describing the finalists for the image, the [[Fiscal year|Fiscal Year]] 2008 annual report of the [[Secretary of the District of Columbia|Secretariat of the District of Columbia]] stated that Banneker \"helped Pierre L\u2019Enfant create the plan for the capital city\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Office of the [[Secretary of the District of Columbia]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228015311/https://mpdc.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/os/publication/attachments/OS_Fiscal_Year_2008_Annual_Report.pdf|archivedate=February 28, 2020|url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/os/publication/attachments/OS_Fiscal_Year_2008_Annual_Report.pdf|title=DC's Duke Ellington Quarter|work=Secretariat of the District of Columbia: Executive Office: FY 2008 Annual Report|page=3|publisher=[[Government of the District of Columbia]]|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the District chose to commemorate another person on the coin, the District's mayor, [[Adrian Fenty|Adrian M. Fenty]], sent a letter to the [[Director of the United States Mint]], [[Edmund C. Moy]], that claimed that Banneker \"played an integral role in the physical design of the nation's capital.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Fenty|first=Adrian M. |date=2008-06-19 |url=https://os.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/os/publication/attachments/OS_Recommendation_Letter_to_the_%20US_Mint_June_19_2008.pdf |title=Recommendation Letter to the U.S. Mint |publisher=Office of the [[Secretary of the District of Columbia]]:  [[Government of the District of Columbia]] |accessdate=2018-01-15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115223440/https://os.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/os/publication/attachments/OS_Recommendation_Letter_to_the_%20US_Mint_June_19_2008.pdf |archivedate=2018-01-15}}</ref> However, there are no known documents that show that any president ever appointed Banneker to any position or that Banneker ever invented anything. Further, a writer had stated in 1974 that Banneker had played no role at all in the design, development or founding of the nation's capital beyond his brief participation in the two-year survey of the federal district's boundaries.<ref name=Founders/>\n\n==Historical markers==\nSeveral [[historical marker]]s in Maryland and Washington, D.C., contain information relating to Benjamin Banneker that is unsupported by historical evidence or is contradicted by such evidence:\n\n===Historical marker in Benjamin Banneker Historical Park, Baltimore County, Maryland===\n[[File:Benjamin Banneker Historical Park and Museum Feb 18, 2017, 1-06 PM edit (33112774375).jpg|250px|thumb|Historical marker in Benjamin Banneker Historical Park, Baltimore County, Maryland, stating that Banneker published the first Maryland almanac in 1792. (February 2017)]]\nA commemorative historical marker that the [[Maryland Historical Society]] erected on the present grounds of Benjamin Banneker Historical Park in [[Baltimore County, Maryland]], states that Banneker \"published the first Maryland almanac\" in 1792.<ref name=\"Banneker marker\">{{cite web |author=Maryland Historical Society |url=http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=5407 |title=\"Benjamin Banneker (1731\u20131806)\" marker |publisher=HMmdb.org: [[Historical Marker Database|The Historical Marker Database]] |accessdate=2010-09-21 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019092107/http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=5407 |archivedate=2011-10-19}}</ref> Silvio Bedini reported in 1999 that the marker's statement is incorrect.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/317/mode/1up Bedini, 1999, p. 317.]</ref>\n\nBedini stated that Banneker may have modeled the format of his almanac after a series of almanacs (''The United States Almanack'') that Andrew Ellicott had authored from 1781 to 1785.<ref name=Davis2/><ref>Bedini, 1999, pp. [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/96/mode/1up 96\u201497], [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/148 148].</ref> Ellicott had lived in Maryland during some of those years.<ref name=Davis2/> Ellicott's almanacs were published in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi Bedini, 1999], pp. [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/97/mode/1up 97], [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/210/mode/1up 210].</ref>\n\nFurther, Banneker did not \"[[publishing|publish]]\" his 1792 almanac. Although he authored this work, others printed, distributed and sold it.<ref name=\"1792 Almanac\">Title page ''of'' {{cite web |last=Banneker |first=Benjamin |url=http://memory.loc.gov/rbc/rbcmisc/ody/ody0214/0214001v.jpg |title=Benjamin Banneker's Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland and Virginia Almanack and Ephemeris For the YEAR of our LORD 1792 |publisher=William Goddard, James Angell, Joseph Crukshank, Daniel Humphreys, Messrs. Hanson and Bond |location=Baltimore, Philadelphia, Alexandria |accessdate=2010-08-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528081727/http://memory.loc.gov/rbc/rbcmisc/ody/ody0214/0214001v.jpg |archivedate=2013-05-28 }} Image ''in'' {{cite web |url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/index.html |title=American Memory |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=2015-04-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422002641/http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/index.html |archivedate=2015-04-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Historical marker in Benjamin Banneker Park, Washington, DC===\nA historical marker that the [[National Park Service]] erected in Benjamin Banneker Park in Washington, D.C., in 1997<ref name=inventory>{{cite web |url=https://irma.nps.gov/DataStore/DownloadFile/520058 |title=Benjamin Banneker Park (10th Street Overlook)|work=Cultural Landscapes Inventory|pages=8, 29\u201336 |year=2013|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[National Mall and Memorial Parks]], [[National Park Service]]|accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref group=a name=\"Banneker marker2 group=a\">Coordinates of National Park Service's historical marker in Benjamin Banneker Park, Washington, D.C.: {{coord|38.8818496|-77.026037|type:landmark|name=Historical marker in Benjamin Banneker Park, Washington, D.C.|format=dms}}</ref> states in an unreferenced paragraph:\n\n<blockquote>Banneker became intrigued by a pocket watch he had seen as a young man. Using a knife he intricately carved out the wheels and gears of a wooden timepiece. The remarkable clock he constructed from memory kept time and struck the hours for the next fifty years.<ref name=\"Banneker marker3\">(1) {{cite web|last=Miller|first=Richard E.|editor=Kevin W.|work=[[National Park Service]], [[United States Department of the Interior]]|url=http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=20384|title=\"Benjamin Banneker Park\" marker|publisher=HMdb.org: [[Historical Marker Database|The Historical Marker Database]]|date=2009-06-30|accessdate=2018-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020034828/http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=20384|archive-date=October 20, 2011|url-status=dead}}<br/>(2) {{cite web|first=Richard E.|last=Miller|url=https://www.hmdb.org/Photos/68/Photo68879o.jpg|title=\"Benjamin Banneker Park\" marker|format=photograph|publisher=HMdb.org: [[Historical Marker Database|The Historical Marker Database]]|date=2009-06-27|accessdate=2018-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715202724/https://www.hmdb.org/Photos/68/Photo68879o.jpg|archive-date=July 15, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, Banneker reportedly completed his clock in 1753 at the age of 21, when he was still a young man.<ref>(1) [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/45/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 45.] \"Completed in 1753, Bannekers' clock continued to operate until his death, more than 50 years later.\"<br>(2) {{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3opAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA729#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Book Notice: Banneker, ''the Afric-American Astronomer.'' From the posthumous papers of M.E. Tyson. Edited by Her Daughter. Phila. 1020 Arch Street. 1884|work=Friends Review: A Religious, Literary and Miscellaneous Journal|volume=37|number=46|page=729|editor=Hartshorne, Henry |location=1316 Filbert Street, Philadelphia|publisher=Franklin E. Paige|date=1884-06-21|via=[[Google Books]] |quote=Showing his inventive facility while quite a youth by making a good wooden clock without ever seeing a clock, being only guided by examining a borrowed watch, he (Banneker) .... |accessdate=2017-01-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116214505/https://books.google.com/books?id=_3opAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA729|archivedate=2017-01-16}}</ref> No historical evidence shows that he constructed the clock from memory.<ref>Note:  Silvio Bedini wrote in 1964 that Banneker had constructed his clock based on drawings that he had made from a watch that he had acquired from a trader ([https://archive.org/details/bulletinunitedst2311964unit/page/22/mode/1up Bedini, 1964, p. 22]). In 1972 and 1999, Bedini wrote that Banneker had constructed his clock from his recollections of that watch ([https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/42/mode/1up Bedini, 1972, p. 42.] and [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/42/mode/2up Bedini, 1999, pp. 42\u201443.]). Bedini did not identify his source for those statements. In 2008, when again describing Banneker's clock, Bedini more cautiously wrote: \"It is said that it was based on his recollections of the mechanism of a pocket watch.\" ([http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Benjamin_Banneker.aspx Bedini, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203192640/http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Benjamin_Banneker.aspx|date=2016-02-03}}).</ref>\n\nFurther, it is open to question as to whether the clock was actually \"remarkable\". Silvio Bedini reported that at least four clockmakers were working in Annapolis, Maryland, before 1753, when Banneker completed his own clock.<ref name=Annapolis/>\n\nA photograph on the historical marker illustrates a wooden striking clock that Benjamin Cheney constructed around 1760.<ref name=\"Banneker marker3\"/><ref>Note: [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/n7/mode/1up Bedini, 1999] contains on [https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/45/mode/1up page 45] a photograph of a striking wooden clock that Benjamin Cheney constructed in Connecticut around 1760 that the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[National Museum of American History]] holds in its collections. The wooden clock shown in the Benjamin Banneker Park historical marker is identical to the one shown in the photograph in Bedini, 1999.</ref> The marker does not indicate that the clock is not Banneker's.<ref name=\"Banneker marker3\"/> A fire on the day of Banneker's funeral reportedly destroyed his own clock.<ref name=Bailey/><ref name=Tyson18/>\n\n===Historical marker in Newseum, Washington, DC===\nIn 2008, when the [[Newseum]] opened to the public on [[Pennsylvania Avenue]] in Washington, D.C., visitors looking over the Avenue could read a historical marker that stated:\n\n<blockquote>\nBenjamin Banneker assisted Chief Surveyor Andrew Ellicott in laying out the Avenue based on Pierre L'Enfant's Plan. President George Washington appointed Ellicott and Banneker to survey the boundaries of the new city.<ref>Text of historic marker entitled \"1800\u20131860 \u2013 Benjamin Banneker\" on outdoor overlook of Pennsylvania Avenue on Level 6 of Newseum, 555 Pennsylvania Avenue NW, Washington, D.C. Text of marker recorded on 2008-04-11.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nLittle or none of this appears to be correct. Banneker had no documented involvement with the laying out of Pennsylvania Avenue or with L'Enfant's Plan.<ref name=Founders/><ref name=\"Bedini, 1972, p. 136\"/><ref name=Arnebeck/> Andrew Ellicott surveyed the boundaries of the federal district (not the \"boundaries of the new city\") at the suggestion of Thomas Jefferson.<ref name=\"Mathews p83\" /> Ellicott (not Washington) appointed Banneker to assist in the boundary survey.<ref name=Bedini22 /><ref name=\"Bedini p113\" />\n\n==List and map of coordinates==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{reflist|group=\"a\"|30em}}\n==See also==\n[[List of common misconceptions]]: a list of many common misconceptions, including [[List of common misconceptions#Early modern|some about Benjamin Banneker]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|45em}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Bedini|first=Silvio A.|authorlink=Silvio Bedini|url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst2311964unit#page/n7/mode/1up|title=Early American Scientific Instruments and Their Makers|place=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[National Museum of American History|Smithsonian Institution Museum of History and Technology]]|year=1964|lccn=64062352|oclc=999972|accessdate=2019-01-04|journal=United States National Museum Bulletin|number=231|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Bedini|first=Silvio A. |url=http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf|format=pdf |title=Benjamin Banneker and the Survey of the District of Columbia, 1791 |journal=Records of the [[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]]|volume=69/70|pages=7\u201330|year=1969|jstor=40067703|oclc=3860814 |accessdate=2013-01-13|via=[http://www.boundarystones.org boundarystones.org]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007223056/http://www.boundarystones.org/articles/rchs_1969.pdf |archivedate=2017-10-07}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bedini|first=Silvio A.|year=1972|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00silv/page/n8/mode/1up|title=The Life of Benjamin Banneker|place=New York|publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons]]. Republished by Landmark Enterprises, [[Rancho Cordova, California]], 1984.|isbn=0910845204|oclc=593414330|lccn=78162755|accessdate=August 29, 2019|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Bedini |first=Silvio A. |jstor=40072968 |title=The Survey of the Federal Territory: Andrew Ellicott and Benjamin Banneker |journal=Washington History |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=[[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.]] |volume=3 |date=Spring\u2013Summer 1991 |number=1 |pages=76\u201395}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bedini|first=Silvio A.|url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofbenjaminba00bedi/page/n7/mode/1up|year=1999|title=The Life of Benjamin Banneker: The First African-American Man of Science|edition=2nd|location=Baltimore|publisher=Maryland Historical Society|isbn=0-938420-59-3|oclc=894558859|lccn=98022848|accessdate=2019-09-11|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n** {{cite web |last=Murdock |first=Gail T.|date=November 11, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310095152/http://www.amazon.com/The-Life-Benjamin-Banneker-African-American/d