mer|pages=79\u201384|volume=11|date=January 1863|number=63|journal=[[The Atlantic|The Atlantic Monthly]]|location=[[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]|publisher=Ticknor & Fields|via=[[HathiTrust|HathiTrust Digital Library]]|accessdate=2019-03-21}}\n* {{cite book|last=Crew|first=Harvey W., Webb, William Bensing, Wooldridge, John |year=1892 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=5Q81AAAAIAAJ&&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=Centennial History of the City of Washington, D.C. |publisher=United Brethren Publishing House |place=Dayton, Ohio |title=IV. \"Permanent Capital Site Selected\"|page=87|lccn=06028029|oclc=2843595 |accessdate=2009-05-07|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n*{{cite book|last=Graham|first=Shirley|author-link=Shirley Graham Du Bois|year=1949|url=https://archive.org/details/yourmosthumblese00dubo/page/n8/mode/1up|title=Your Most Humble Servant|lccn=49011346|oclc=1036934508|accessdate=April 15, 2020|location=New York|publisher=[[Julian Messner|Julian Messner, Inc.]]|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jusserand|first=Jean Jules|author-link=Jean Jules Jusserand |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u2MUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=With Americans of Past and Present Days||oclc=1075914 |title=Major L'Enfant and the Federal City |location=New York |publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons]] |pages=137\u2013195 |year=1916 |accessdate=2011-08-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Latrobe|first=John H. B., Esq.|url=https://archive.org/details/memoirbenjaminb00socigoog/page/n7/mode/1up|title=Memoir of Benjamin Banneker: Read before the Maryland Historical Society at the Monthly Meeting, May 1, 1845|location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=Printed by John D. Toy|year=1845|lccn=rc01003345|oclc=85791076|accessdate=February 29, 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Hugh Alexander|url=https://archive.org/details/preliminarycheck00morr|title=Preliminary Check List of American Almanacs: 1639-1800|work=Library of Congress|year=1907|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|oclc=577096527|lccn=06035021|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=December 31, 2018|via=[[Internet Archive]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231033020/https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0|archive-date=December 31, 2018}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/DKC0021/mode/1up|title=A plan of a Peace-Office for the United States|work=Essays, Literary, Moral and Philosophical.|last=Rush|first=Benjamin, M.D.|author-link=Benjamin Rush|year=1798|place=Philadelphia |publisher=Thomas and William Bradford |accessdate=2019-06-13|oclc=53177918|isbn=0912756225|lccn=88080672|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Stewart |first=John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Early Maps and Surveyors of the City of Washington, D.C. |year=1899 |journal=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=[[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]] |location=Washington, D.C. |volume=2 |pages=48\u201371 |issn=0897-9049 |oclc=40326234 |accessdate=2011-08-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2 |title=Standard History of the City of Washington From a Study of the Original Sources |last=Tindall |first=William |location=Knoxville, Tennessee |publisher=H. W. Crew and Company |year=1914 |lccn=14013663|oclc=7059152 |accessdate=2013-01-31 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso/page/n4/mode/1up|title=A sketch of the life of Benjamin Banneker: from notes taken in 1836: read by J. Saurin Norris, before the Maryland Historical Society, October 5th, 1854 |first=Martha Ellicott |last=Tyson |location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=Printed for the Maryland Historical Society by John D. Toy |lccn=rc01003357|oclc=85794847|accessdate=2015-04-24|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first=Carter Goodwin|last=Woodson|author-link=Carter G. Woodson|year=1919|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6sQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Education of the Negro Prior to 1861: A History of the Education of the Colored People of the United States from the Beginning of Slavery to the Civil War|edition=Second|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=The Associated Publishers, Inc.|lccn=68029024|oclc=1003200476|accessdate=April 15, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Benjamin Banneker}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|History|United States|Maryland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banneker, Mythology and legacy of Benjamin}}\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:Misconceptions]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n[[Category:Legacies by person]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlan of the City of Washington:editorial change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythology_of_Benjamin_Banneker"}
{"title_page": "Vikram Bhatt", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vikram Bhatt\n| image              = Vikram bhatt.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|1|27}}<ref name=\"Gupta16296838\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| occupation         = Film director<br/> film producer<br/>screenwriter\n| parents            = \n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Bhatt family|Bhatt family]]\n}}\n\n'''Vikram Bhatt''' (born 27 January 1969 in [[Mumbai|Bombay]]) is an Indian film director, producer, screenwriter and now also an actor. Formerly, he was the creative head of [[ASA Productions and Enterprises Pvt. Ltd.]]; however, he has resigned from the company in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reliance upset with ASA Entertainment over 1920 London |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2511540/Reliance-upset-with-ASA-Entertainment-over-1920-London |date=27 May 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBhatt is the grandson of [[Vijay Bhatt]] from (Gujarat, Palitana), one of the pioneers of the Indian film industry, and the son of cinematographer [[Pravin Bhatt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Romancing The Reel |url=http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ws010308Romancing.asp |date=21 February 2008 |publisher=Tehelka |accessdate=10 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204132116/http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ws010308Romancing.asp |archivedate=4 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[http://www.monstersandcritics.com/movies/indiancinema/news/article_1307087.php/Vikram_Bhatt_now_turns_producer_too \"Vikram Bhatt now turns producer too\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505174357/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/movies/indiancinema/news/article_1307087.php/Vikram_Bhatt_now_turns_producer_too |date=5 May 2011 }} ''Indian Cinema News'', by Subhash K. Jha, 21 May 2007.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the age of 14,<ref name=\"Gupta16296838\">{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Priya |title=Ameesha and I never loved each other: Vikram Bhatt |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news-interviews/Ameesha-and-I-never-loved-each-other-Vikram-Bhatt/articleshow/16296838.cms |date=8 September 2012 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> in 1982, Bhatt started his career with director [[Mukul Anand]] in Anand's first film, ''Kanoon Kya Karega''. Bhatt also assisted Mukul Anand as the chief assistant on the sets of ''[[Agneepath (1990 film)|Agneepath]]''. This film turned out to be a cult classic, though not very successful at the box office.\n\nSubsequently, Bhatt worked with director [[Shekhar Kapur]] for two and a half years and later with director [[Mahesh Bhatt]] for two years approximately. He has been an assistant director on the sets of several successful films including ''[[Hum Hain Rahi Pyar Ke]]'' and ''[[Junoon (1992 film)|Junoon]]''.\n\nHis career as a director began with the film ''[[Jaanam]]'', which was produced by [[Mukesh Bhatt]]. His first four films did not fare well at the box office; his first successful directorial venture was ''[[Fareb (1996 film)|Fareb]]''. Following this, he had a string of successful films such as ''[[Ghulam (film)|Ghulam]]'', ''[[Kasoor]]'', ''[[Raaz (2002 film)|Raaz]]'' and ''[[Awara Paagal Deewana]]''. After ''Awara Paagal Deewana '', He gave flops like ''[[Aap Mujhe Achche Lagne Lage]]'', ''[[Deewane Huye Paagal]]'' and [[Ankahee]].\nIn 2008, Bhatt came back with the horror genre and he delivered three films that were successful at the box office; these include ''[[1920 (film)|1920]]''. ''[[Shaapit]]'' and ''[[Haunted \u2013 3D]]''. In 2010, Bhatt introduced stereoscopic 3D for the first time in India with his film Haunted \u2013 3D;<ref>{{cite news |title=Haunted 3D: 10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About The Movie |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/haunted-3d-10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-film/ |date=5 May 2011 |publisher=KoiMoi.com |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> the film was released in May 2011 and it then set the record of the highest grossing [[Bollywood horror films|Hindi horror film]] of all time, making [[Indian Rupees|Rs.]] 270 million at the box office.\n\nIn 2012, Bhatt's [[Raaz 3D]] recorded domestic box office collection of 729&nbsp;million after the 3rd weekend and the overseas collection was at 46&nbsp;million.<ref>http://www.koimoi.com/box-office/raaz-3-3rd-week-box-office-collections</ref> Riding high with the success, Bhatt is writing another horror-thriller for Bipasha in the central role, with a more shocking image than Raaz 3.<ref name=Jha>{{cite news|last1=Jha|first1=Subhash|title=Vikram Bhatt, Bipasha Basu team up again for next film|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Vikram-Bhatt-Bipasha-Basu-team-up-again-for-next-film/articleshow/16460927.cms?referral=PM|accessdate=21 January 2015|publisher=The Times of India|date=19 September 2012}}</ref> Following the success of Raaz 3, Vikram Bhatt's written Hindi horror movie [[1920: Evil Returns]] which has been directed by debutant Bhushan Patel topped the first weekend collection chart at the box office and the approximate collection was Rs 124.3&nbsp;million nett.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/box-office/2012/1920-evil-returns-lstck-weekend-collection-box-office-100908.html | title=1920 \u2013 Evil Returns, LSTCK weekend collection at Box Office | work=[[OneIndia Entertainment]] | date=5 November 2011 | accessdate=12 November 2011 | author=Shekhar}}</ref> The movie further collected approx Rs 37.5&nbsp;million nett in the second Weekend, taking the total to Rs 228.6&nbsp;million nett. The film has been declared a 'Hit'.<ref name=\"Taran Adarsh\">{{cite web|title=Midweek: '1920 \u2013 Evil Returns' & 'Student Of The Year' dominate|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/trade/top5/id/913/date/2012-11-12|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref> Soon after, Bhatt signed a deal with Bhushan Kumar's T-Series to produce 5 films of sci-fi, thriller and horror genre. Two of the films will be directed by Bhatt himself.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/vikram-bhatt-bhushan-kumar-sign-5-film-deal-295808 | title=Vikram Bhatt, Bhushan Kumar sign 5-film deal | work=[[NDTV Movies]] | date=22 November 2012  | accessdate=16 April 2013 | author=Press Trust of India}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Bhatt announced his upcoming projects, [[Creature 3D]], India's First 3D Monster Movie with Bipasha Basu in the lead role<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/13/jan/10-news-bipasha-basu-in-vikram-bhatts-next-creature-011304.asp | title=Bipasha Basu in Vikram Bhatt's next CREATURE | work=[[Glamsham.com]] | date=10 January 2013  | accessdate=16 April 2013 | author=Glamsham Editorial}}</ref> and 1920 London, third in the 1920 series.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/prachi-desai-to-play-princess-in-vikram-bhatts-next-1920/ | title=Prachi Desai to play princess in Vikram Bhatt's next '1920' | work=[[The Indian Express]] | date=20 February 2013  | accessdate=16 April 2013 }}</ref> Vikram Bhatt will mark his foray into Marathi cinema with 'Ek Doosrey Ke Liye', which will be directed by Ashwini Kumar Patil.\n\nStarting from 16 February 2014, he would be seen hosting the TV Show ''Ishq Kills'' based on Real Life Romances on [[Star Plus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikram Bhatt to host TV Show Ishq Kills on Star Plus|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/vikram-bhatt-to-host-tv-show-ishq-kills-on-star-plus/|work=IANS|publisher=Biharprabha News|accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Notable achievements==\nBhatt's movies, [[1920: Evil Returns]]'s social media promotion campaign was studied by [[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore]]. The management institute assessed Internet activities and campaigns; the team finally establish the connection between box office collections and promotions on social media. This case study is published by [[Harvard Business Publishing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hbr.org/product/1920-evil-returns-bollywood-and-social-media-marketing/an/IMB437-PDF-ENG |accessdate=25 December 2014|publisher=[[Harvard Business Publishing]] |title=1920 Evil Returns - Bollywood and Social Media Marketing |date=1 September 2013}}</ref> and is being used by students in the US, Canada, Norway, Slovenia and Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/on-campus/iimb-scripts-case-on-digital-promos-of-bollywood-film/article5627380.ece |accessdate=25 December 2014|publisher=[[The Hindu Business Line]] |title=IIM-B scripts case on digital promos of Bollywood film  |date=28 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iimb.ernet.in/research/news-events/iimb-case-study-bollywood-film-finds-its-way-harvard-business-publishing |accessdate=25 December 2014|publisher=[[IIM Bangalore]] |title=IIMB CASE STUDY ON A BOLLYWOOD FILM FINDS ITS WAY TO HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING}}</ref>\n\nBhatt's scripts for [[Khamoshiyan]], [[1920: Evil Returns]] and 1920 are set to turn into novels and release in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vikram Bhatt thrilled as scripts for 'Khamoshiyan', '1920 - Evil Returns' turn into novels |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/vikram-bhatt-thrilled-as-scripts-for-khamoshiyan-1920--evil-returns-turn-into-novels/519449-8-66.html |date=23 December 2014 |publisher=[[IBN Live]] |accessdate=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBhatt is married to his childhood sweetheart, Aditi Bhatt, and they have a daughter, Krishna Bhatt.<ref name=\"Gupta16204366\">{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Priya |title=Vikram Bhatt's holiday with wife and daughter |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Vikram-Bhatts-holiday-with-wife-and-daughter/articleshow/16204366.cms |date=3 September 2012 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>  Later, Bhatt was reportedly dating [[Ameesha Patel]] for five years.<ref name=\"Gupta16296838\"/> Bhatt shares a great bond with his daughter and she has been assisting him on his sets.<ref>{{cite news |title=THE MOST HEARTWARMING FATHER-DAUGHTER STORY FOR VALENTINE\u2019S DAY!|url=http://www.thefilmstreetjournal.com/generalarticle.aspx?id=149 |date=February 2012 |publisher=TheFilmStreetJournal |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n! Year\n! Film\n! Note\n|-\n| 1992\n|''[[Jaanam]]''\n| Inspired by  ''[[Bobby (1973 film)|Bobby]]''\n|-\n| 1994\n|''[[Madhosh (1994 film)|Madhosh]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n|''[[Gunehgar (1995 film)|Gunehgar]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[Fareb (1996 film)|Fareb]]''\n| Based on ''[[Unlawful Entry (film)|Unlawful Entry]]''\n|-\n| 1996\n|''Bambai guys''\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n|''[[Ghulam (film)|Ghulam]]''\n| Based on ''[[On the Waterfront]]'' and ''[[Kabzaa]]''\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[Kasoor]]''\n| Based on ''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]''<br> Also rendered his voice for Aftab Shivdasani\n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Raaz (2002 film)|Raaz]]''\n| Based on ''[[What Lies Beneath]]''\n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Aap Mujhe Achche Lagne Lage]]''\n| \n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Awara Paagal Deewana]]''\n| Based on ''[[The Whole Nine Yards (film)|The Whole Nine Yards]]''\n|-\n| 2003\n|''[[Inteha (2003 film)|Inteha]]''\n| Based on ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''\n|-\n| 2003\n|''[[Footpath (2003 film)|Footpath]]''\n| Based on ''[[State of Grace (1990 film)|State of Grace]]''\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Aetbaar]]''\n| Based on ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[Elaan (2005 film)|Elaan]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[Jurm (2005 film)|Jurm]]''\n| Based on ''[[Double Jeopardy (1999 film)|Double Jeopardy]]''\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[Deewane Huye Pagal]]''\n| Based on ''[[There's Something About Mary]]''\n|-\n| 2006\n|''[[Ankahee (2006 film)|Ankahee]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Red: The Dark Side]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Speed (2007 film)|Speed]]''\n| Based on ''[[Cellular (film)|Cellular]]''\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Life Mein Kabhie Kabhiee]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n|''[[1920 (film)|1920]]''\n| Inspired by ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]''\n|-\n| 2010\n|''[[Shaapit]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n|''[[Haunted \u2013 3D]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n|''[[Dangerous Ishhq]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n|''[[Raaz 3D]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[Creature 3D]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n|''[[Mr. X (2015 film)|Mr. X]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Love Games (2016 film)|Love Games]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Raaz Reboot]]''\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[1921 (2018 film)|1921]]''\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Ghost (2019 film)|Ghost]]''\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Hacked (film) | Hacked]]''\n|\n|}\n\n===Writer===\n* ''[[Dastak (1996 film)|Dastak]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Aetbaar]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Bardaasht]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Yakeen (2005 film)|Yakeen]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Ankahee (2006 film)|Ankahee]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Three- Love, Lies and Betrayal]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Hate Story]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[1920: Evil Returns]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Ankur Arora Murder Case]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Khamoshiyan]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[1920 London]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Ghost (2019 film)|Ghost]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Chehre]]'' (2020)\n\n===Producer===\n*''[[Muthirai]]'' (2009)\n*''1920'' (2008)\n*''[[Three- Love, Lies and Betrayal]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Lanka (2011 film)|Lanka]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Hate Story]]'' (2012)\n*''[[1920: Evil Returns]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Dangerous Ishq]]'' (2012)\n\n*''[[Horror Story (film)|Horror Story]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Hate Story 2]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Bhaag Johnny]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Hate Story 3]]'' (2015)\n\n===Web series===\n\n*''[[Gehraiyaan]]''\n*''[[Untouchables (web series)|Untouchables]]''\n*''[[Zindabaad (web series)|Zindabaad]]''\n*''[[Zakhmi]]''\n*''Tantra ''\n*''[[Twisted (web series)|Twisted]]''\n*''[[Twisted (web series)|Twisted 2]]''\n*''[[Maaya (TV series)|Maaya]]''\n*''[[Maaya 2]]''\n*''[[Maaya 3]]''\n*Spotlight\n*[[Spotlight 2 (web series)|Spotlight 2]]\n* Rain\n* Faceless\n*Hadh\n\n===Actor===\n\n*''[[Bhaag Johnny]]'' as Jinn\n*''[[Khamoshi (2019 film)|Khamoshi]]'' as Dev's Father\n* ''[[Ghost (2019 film)]]'' as Doctor Singh, Barkha's father\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===[[Filmfare Awards]]===\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"|  Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:33em;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:39em;\"| Nominated work\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;\"| Result\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Awards | 1999]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Filmfare Best Director Award | Best Director]]\n| ''[[Ghulam (film)|Ghulam]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Awards | 2003]]\n| ''[[Raaz (2002 film) | Raaz]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{IMDb name|0080333|Vikram Bhatt}}\n\n{{Vikram Bhatt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhatt, Vikram}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Bhatt family|Vikram]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Hindi screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male writers]]\n{{[https://www.lyricsmitra.com/2020/04/dil-maang-raha-hai.html GHOST]}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vikram Bhatt\n| image              = Vikram bhatt.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|1|27}}<ref name=\"Gupta16296838\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n| occupation         = Film director<br/> film producer<br/>screenwriter\n| parents            = \n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film clans#Bhatt family|Bhatt family]]\n}}\n\n'''Vikram Bhatt''' (born 27 January 1969 in [[Mumbai|Bombay]]) is an Indian film director, producer, screenwriter and now also an actor. Formerly, he was the creative head of [[ASA Productions and Enterprises Pvt. Ltd.]]; however, he has resigned from the company in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reliance upset with ASA Entertainment over 1920 London |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2511540/Reliance-upset-with-ASA-Entertainment-over-1920-London |date=27 May 2014 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBhatt is the grandson of [[Vijay Bhatt]] from (Gujarat, Palitana), one of the pioneers of the Indian film industry, and the son of cinematographer [[Pravin Bhatt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Romancing The Reel |url=http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ws010308Romancing.asp |date=21 February 2008 |publisher=Tehelka |accessdate=10 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204132116/http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main37.asp?filename=Ws010308Romancing.asp |archivedate=4 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[http://www.monstersandcritics.com/movies/indiancinema/news/article_1307087.php/Vikram_Bhatt_now_turns_producer_too \"Vikram Bhatt now turns producer too\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110505174357/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/movies/indiancinema/news/article_1307087.php/Vikram_Bhatt_now_turns_producer_too |date=5 May 2011 }} ''Indian Cinema News'', by Subhash K. Jha, 21 May 2007.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the age of 14,<ref name=\"Gupta16296838\">{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Priya |title=Ameesha and I never loved each other: Vikram Bhatt |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news-interviews/Ameesha-and-I-never-loved-each-other-Vikram-Bhatt/articleshow/16296838.cms |date=8 September 2012 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> in 1982, Bhatt started his career with director [[Mukul Anand]] in Anand's first film, ''Kanoon Kya Karega''. Bhatt also assisted Mukul Anand as the chief assistant on the sets of ''[[Agneepath (1990 film)|Agneepath]]''. This film turned out to be a cult classic, though not very successful at the box office.\n\nSubsequently, Bhatt worked with director [[Shekhar Kapur]] for two and a half years and later with director [[Mahesh Bhatt]] for two years approximately. He has been an assistant director on the sets of several successful films including ''[[Hum Hain Rahi Pyar Ke]]'' and ''[[Junoon (1992 film)|Junoon]]''.\n\nHis career as a director began with the film ''[[Jaanam]]'', which was produced by [[Mukesh Bhatt]]. His first four films did not fare well at the box office; his first successful directorial venture was ''[[Fareb (1996 film)|Fareb]]''. Following this, he had a string of successful films such as ''[[Ghulam (film)|Ghulam]]'', ''[[Kasoor]]'', ''[[Raaz (2002 film)|Raaz]]'' and ''[[Awara Paagal Deewana]]''. After ''Awara Paagal Deewana '', He gave flops like ''[[Aap Mujhe Achche Lagne Lage]]'', ''[[Deewane Huye Paagal]]'' and [[Ankahee]].\nIn 2008, Bhatt came back with the horror genre and he delivered three films that were successful at the box office; these include ''[[1920 (film)|1920]]''. ''[[Shaapit]]'' and ''[[Haunted \u2013 3D]]''. In 2010, Bhatt introduced stereoscopic 3D for the first time in India with his film Haunted \u2013 3D;<ref>{{cite news |title=Haunted 3D: 10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About The Movie |url=http://www.koimoi.com/bollywood-news/haunted-3d-10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-film/ |date=5 May 2011 |publisher=KoiMoi.com |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> the film was released in May 2011 and it then set the record of the highest grossing [[Bollywood horror films|Hindi horror film]] of all time, making [[Indian Rupees|Rs.]] 270 million at the box office.\n\nIn 2012, Bhatt's [[Raaz 3D]] recorded domestic box office collection of 729&nbsp;million after the 3rd weekend and the overseas collection was at 46&nbsp;million.<ref>http://www.koimoi.com/box-office/raaz-3-3rd-week-box-office-collections</ref> Riding high with the success, Bhatt is writing another horror-thriller for Bipasha in the central role, with a more shocking image than Raaz 3.<ref name=Jha>{{cite news|last1=Jha|first1=Subhash|title=Vikram Bhatt, Bipasha Basu team up again for next film|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Vikram-Bhatt-Bipasha-Basu-team-up-again-for-next-film/articleshow/16460927.cms?referral=PM|accessdate=21 January 2015|publisher=The Times of India|date=19 September 2012}}</ref> Following the success of Raaz 3, Vikram Bhatt's written Hindi horror movie [[1920: Evil Returns]] which has been directed by debutant Bhushan Patel topped the first weekend collection chart at the box office and the approximate collection was Rs 124.3&nbsp;million nett.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/box-office/2012/1920-evil-returns-lstck-weekend-collection-box-office-100908.html | title=1920 \u2013 Evil Returns, LSTCK weekend collection at Box Office | work=[[OneIndia Entertainment]] | date=5 November 2011 | accessdate=12 November 2011 | author=Shekhar}}</ref> The movie further collected approx Rs 37.5&nbsp;million nett in the second Weekend, taking the total to Rs 228.6&nbsp;million nett. The film has been declared a 'Hit'.<ref name=\"Taran Adarsh\">{{cite web|title=Midweek: '1920 \u2013 Evil Returns' & 'Student Of The Year' dominate|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/trade/top5/id/913/date/2012-11-12|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref> Soon after, Bhatt signed a deal with Bhushan Kumar's T-Series to produce 5 films of sci-fi, thriller and horror genre. Two of the films will be directed by Bhatt himself.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/vikram-bhatt-bhushan-kumar-sign-5-film-deal-295808 | title=Vikram Bhatt, Bhushan Kumar sign 5-film deal | work=[[NDTV Movies]] | date=22 November 2012  | accessdate=16 April 2013 | author=Press Trust of India}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Bhatt announced his upcoming projects, [[Creature 3D]], India's First 3D Monster Movie with Bipasha Basu in the lead role<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/13/jan/10-news-bipasha-basu-in-vikram-bhatts-next-creature-011304.asp | title=Bipasha Basu in Vikram Bhatt's next CREATURE | work=[[Glamsham.com]] | date=10 January 2013  | accessdate=16 April 2013 | author=Glamsham Editorial}}</ref> and 1920 London, third in the 1920 series.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/prachi-desai-to-play-princess-in-vikram-bhatts-next-1920/ | title=Prachi Desai to play princess in Vikram Bhatt's next '1920' | work=[[The Indian Express]] | date=20 February 2013  | accessdate=16 April 2013 }}</ref> Vikram Bhatt will mark his foray into Marathi cinema with 'Ek Doosrey Ke Liye', which will be directed by Ashwini Kumar Patil.\n\nStarting from 16 February 2014, he would be seen hosting the TV Show ''Ishq Kills'' based on Real Life Romances on [[Star Plus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikram Bhatt to host TV Show Ishq Kills on Star Plus|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/vikram-bhatt-to-host-tv-show-ishq-kills-on-star-plus/|work=IANS|publisher=Biharprabha News|accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Notable achievements==\nBhatt's movies, [[1920: Evil Returns]]'s social media promotion campaign was studied by [[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore]]. The management institute assessed Internet activities and campaigns; the team finally establish the connection between box office collections and promotions on social media. This case study is published by [[Harvard Business Publishing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hbr.org/product/1920-evil-returns-bollywood-and-social-media-marketing/an/IMB437-PDF-ENG |accessdate=25 December 2014|publisher=[[Harvard Business Publishing]] |title=1920 Evil Returns - Bollywood and Social Media Marketing |date=1 September 2013}}</ref> and is being used by students in the US, Canada, Norway, Slovenia and Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/on-campus/iimb-scripts-case-on-digital-promos-of-bollywood-film/article5627380.ece |accessdate=25 December 2014|publisher=[[The Hindu Business Line]] |title=IIM-B scripts case on digital promos of Bollywood film  |date=28 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iimb.ernet.in/research/news-events/iimb-case-study-bollywood-film-finds-its-way-harvard-business-publishing |accessdate=25 December 2014|publisher=[[IIM Bangalore]] |title=IIMB CASE STUDY ON A BOLLYWOOD FILM FINDS ITS WAY TO HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING}}</ref>\n\nBhatt's scripts for [[Khamoshiyan]], [[1920: Evil Returns]] and 1920 are set to turn into novels and release in January 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vikram Bhatt thrilled as scripts for 'Khamoshiyan', '1920 - Evil Returns' turn into novels |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/vikram-bhatt-thrilled-as-scripts-for-khamoshiyan-1920--evil-returns-turn-into-novels/519449-8-66.html |date=23 December 2014 |publisher=[[IBN Live]] |accessdate=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBhatt is married to his childhood sweetheart, Aditi Bhatt, and they have a daughter, Krishna Bhatt.<ref name=\"Gupta16204366\">{{cite news |last=Gupta |first=Priya |title=Vikram Bhatt's holiday with wife and daughter |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Vikram-Bhatts-holiday-with-wife-and-daughter/articleshow/16204366.cms |date=3 September 2012 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>  Later, Bhatt was reportedly dating [[Ameesha Patel]] for five years.<ref name=\"Gupta16296838\"/> Bhatt shares a great bond with his daughter and she has been assisting him on his sets.<ref>{{cite news |title=THE MOST HEARTWARMING FATHER-DAUGHTER STORY FOR VALENTINE\u2019S DAY!|url=http://www.thefilmstreetjournal.com/generalarticle.aspx?id=149 |date=February 2012 |publisher=TheFilmStreetJournal |accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n! Year\n! Film\n! Note\n|-\n| 1992\n|''[[Jaanam]]''\n| Inspired by  ''[[Bobby (1973 film)|Bobby]]''\n|-\n| 1994\n|''[[Madhosh (1994 film)|Madhosh]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n|''[[Gunehgar (1995 film)|Gunehgar]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[Fareb (1996 film)|Fareb]]''\n| Based on ''[[Unlawful Entry (film)|Unlawful Entry]]''\n|-\n| 1996\n|''Bambai guys''\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n|''[[Ghulam (film)|Ghulam]]''\n| Based on ''[[On the Waterfront]]'' and ''[[Kabzaa]]''\n|-\n| 2001\n|''[[Kasoor]]''\n| Based on ''[[Jagged Edge (film)|Jagged Edge]]''<br> Also rendered his voice for Aftab Shivdasani\n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Raaz (2002 film)|Raaz]]''\n| Based on ''[[What Lies Beneath]]''\n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Aap Mujhe Achche Lagne Lage]]''\n| \n|-\n| 2002\n|''[[Awara Paagal Deewana]]''\n| Based on ''[[The Whole Nine Yards (film)|The Whole Nine Yards]]''\n|-\n| 2003\n|''[[Inteha (2003 film)|Inteha]]''\n| Based on ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''\n|-\n| 2003\n|''[[Footpath (2003 film)|Footpath]]''\n| Based on ''[[State of Grace (1990 film)|State of Grace]]''\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Aetbaar]]''\n| Based on ''[[Fear (1996 film)|Fear]]''\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[Elaan (2005 film)|Elaan]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[Jurm (2005 film)|Jurm]]''\n| Based on ''[[Double Jeopardy (1999 film)|Double Jeopardy]]''\n|-\n| 2005\n|''[[Deewane Huye Pagal]]''\n| Based on ''[[There's Something About Mary]]''\n|-\n| 2006\n|''[[Ankahee (2006 film)|Ankahee]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Red: The Dark Side]]''\n|\